<1ST_LINE>r p PM-HometownCelebrity Bjt   03-10 0618</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hometown Celebrity, Bjt,610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Has Home-Turf Edge In Pair Of Upcoming Contests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In this city, Jesse Jackson is the well-known
social activist, a canny player in the back rooms of a world-class
political hotbed.
   In Greenville, S.C., he's the hometown celebrity who hasn't
forgotten his roots.
   Jackson hopes to cash in on both images and turn hometown
sentiment into votes in two contests in the next week.
   South Carolina holds Democratic caucuses on Saturday; the
Illinois primary is Tuesday.
   Arriving under chilly gray skies back in Chicago on Wednesday,
Jackson was triumphant, telling a rally of factory workers, `We get
stronger every day.''
   Here, he founded the social action organization People United To
Serve Humanity. Here he makes his home, in a large comfortable
house on a pleasant residential street, with his wife Jacqueline
and five children.
   Halfway across the nation is Jackson's other hometown. It was
Greenville where Jackson stopped last week as he launched his final
swing through the South on the road to the critical Super Tuesday
contests.
   Jackson came in first in the popular vote in those primaries and
caucuses, and second to Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis in the
delegate count.
   In Greenville, they remember Jackson as the youngster who went
off to be a college football quarterback, then launched a career as
a minister and civil rights activist who followed Dr. Martin Luther
King Jr.
   Jackson saw familiar faces when his motorcade pulled up to the
Springfield Baptist Church last week to address a convention of
ministers. It was this church, he told them, that he attended as a
boy while his mother sang in the choir.
   Greenville, a medium-sized city set among rolling hills with a
rural atmosphere, was a major textile center in those days. But it
fell on hard times as the mills began to close, Jackson says.
   Jackson took reporters to the projects where he lived as a boy.
He went into his old apartment, a spartan brick unit with plastic
flowers on display, the home today of a single mother of two who
earns minimum wage putting pleats on skirts.
   The project's residents came out to shake Jackson's hand as he
strolled through the streets, Secret Service agents and TV cameras
in tow.
   Today, Jackson's mother lives in a comfortable split-level home
_ walls covered with tastefully framed photo layouts depicting
Jackson's life _ in a far more affluent neighborhood of Greenville.
   There, a group of friends and family members celebrated
Jackson's night at home with a feast of sweet potatoes, corn bread,
turkey, dressing, cobblers and other home cooking the likes of
which is seldom seen on Jackson's breakneck campaign.
   The next morning there was more home cooking _ biscuits and
grits, this time with white farmers on a dairy farm near town.
   South Carolina farmers told Jackson how the nation's farm policy
has brought them hardship. But they were noncommittal about whether
they would vote for him.
   There is no such reticence when Jackson gets home to Chicago, a
big industrial city whose people hurry along skyscraper-lined
sidewalks, bundled up against the icy blasts that whistle along the
streets and beneath the elevated rail cars.
   Here the crowds that come to see him are his fans.
   At the General Electric plant rally, the crowd knew what they
wanted the candidate to do.
   ``Jesse, help us save our jobs,'' their signs read.
   ``I've been working here 23 years,'' said Mack Fundes, a truck
driver for GE's Hotpoint refrigerator plant that is scheduled to
close in a couple of years.
   ``Nothing has changed here. It's time for change. I believe
Jesse would make a change,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
