<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-88 0101EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Gephardt'sStruggle Bjt   03-10 0747</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gephardt's Struggle, Bjt,740</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gephardt Trudging On After Big Super Tuesday Setback</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE GLOVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FLORENCE, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Richard Gephardt grimaced a bit as he
stood in a pole barn on a soggy afternoon, pondering a question
from the tiny knot of Democrats.
   The question was: ``Do you really think you can beat Jesse
Jackson and Al Gore here?''
   After a pause, Gephardt said: ``We're going to try very hard.''
   Throughout Wednesday, the day after his disastrous Super Tuesday
performance, Gephardt doggedly trudged across rain-drenched South
Carolina, trying to explain his showing and pleading with Democrats
to give him a boost in Saturday's caucuses.
   ``Unless you're willing to stand up for change, it's not going
to happen,'' Gephardt said. ``If you will stand with me on
Saturday, we'll change those facts of life.''
   Only a month ago, Gephardt was riding high after a win in the
Iowa caucuses. From there, he went on to a second-place finish in
New Hampshire, and won South Dakota's primary a week later.
   But suddenly, he is fighting to keep his campaign alive.
   The difficulty facing Gephardt was summarized at the Jim Harwell
farm just outside this eastern South Carolina town.
   As the recorded strains of country singer Willie Nelson wailed
mournfully in the background, Gephardt mingled with a couple of
dozen party activists in what was billed as a farm rally for him to
push some basic campaign themes he hopes will sway farmers in this
heavily rural state.
   Gephardt insisted throughout the day that his problem during the
20-state round of voting earlier in the week was the sheer size of
the event. He said it prevented him from telling his story, leaving
him victorious only in his home state.
   ``When I get my message out to the voters, I win,'' Gephardt
said. ``They didn't hear what I had to say; that was the problem.''
   But when Gephardt sounded his familiar tough-talking trade
themes they got a lukewarm response.
   That was partly because the audience was tiny. Only a couple of
dozen people showed up at the farm. At an event earlier in the day
at a threatened textile plant, his audience was composed almost
entirely of elementary-school students bused in for the occasion.
An evening rally in Greenville found the room half empty.
   That's the price Gephardt paid for his showing on the campaign
season's biggest event, as attention focuses on other candidates
like Gore, Jackson and Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis who have
reaped big harvests of delegates.
   ``We did not have a good outcome yesterday,'' Gephardt said in a
significant understatement.
   But he spent a lot of his time insisting he's in the race for
the long haul.
   ``The race is on,'' Gephardt said. ``I'm not where I'd like to
be, but I think I have ample opportunity to make up lost ground and
get back in the middle of this race and win.''
   Gephardt and his aides conceded their campaign could badly use a
boost, and they busily drew up scenarios for keeping the effort
alive.
   ``It's going to be tough; it's an uphill battle,'' said deputy
campaign manager Joe Trippi. ``But that's what we're going to try
to do.''
   Throughout the Super Tuesday campaign, Gephardt was outspent by
both Gore and Dukakis, and campaign consultant Bob Shrum conceded
that a fourth-place showing won't make raising money any easier.
   ``It won't be as easy to raise money, but we'll raise money,''
Shrum said. ``We're not penniless.''
   Gephardt insisted his financial picture is not all that bleak.
His debts are modest, he says, and more federal matching funds are
on the way.
   ``We didn't borrow, as others did, to run on Super Tuesday,''
Gephardt said. ``Maybe in retrospect we should have.''
   But Gephardt faces big hurdles if he's to regain momentum.
   South Carolina is where Jackson was born, and Gephardt aide
concede that he best they can hope for Saturday is a second-place
finish.
   The Gephardt campaign has been downplaying next week's Illinois
primary, saying results will be muddled by home-state Sen. Paul
Simon's presence on the ballot.
   That leaves Gephardt with a long stretch before he's likely to
get any positive campaign news.
   He's pinning his hopes on Michigan, which holds caucuses March
26, as a key blue-collar state where he hopes his tough trade talk
will sell.
   It also drastically raises the stakes for Gephardt.
   ``We're going to do well in Michigan,'' he said. ``I need to do
well in Michigan.''
</TEXT>
