<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-Hefner-Palimony     03-10 0525</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Hefner-Palimony,0547</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Playboy Publisher Says Ex-Girlfriend's Suit Is Publicity Stunt</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN ROGERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Playboy publisher Hugh Hefner, standing
arm-in-arm with his new girlfriend, announced a countersuit against
his ex-lover, alleging she was unfaithful and her $35 million
``palimony'' lawsuit was a publicity stunt.
   But model Carrie Leigh's attorney says her action was brought to
stop Hefner from using and discarding young women.
   The 61-year-old Hefner, who filed the $1 million cross complaint
Wednesday, said Ms. Leigh filed her lawsuit to advance her own
career and that of her lawyer, Marvin Mitchelson.
   ``You're talking about the criminal misuse of the judicial
system,'' Hefner told reporters as he stood with his new
girlfriend, 24-year-old Kimberley Conrad, at the Playboy Mansion.
``I want to put a stop to that.''
   Ms. Leigh could not be reached for comment because her phone
number is unlisted.
   Mitchelson, on vacation in Paris, said from his hotel:
   ``This is my 32nd year as a lawyer, and I've never filed a
lawsuit in my life that didn't have merit.
   ``The palimony suit was really developed to remedy situations
involving people like Hugh Hefner,'' he continued. ``He has made a
lifelong practice of getting involved with teen-age girls, living
with them for a few years and then discarding them.''
   Ms. Leigh's suit filed last month claims Hefner reneged on
promises to marry her, father her child and support her.
   Hefner's attorney, Anthony Glassman, said he filed two legal
actions Wednesday in Superior Court.
   One was an answer to Ms. Leigh's palimony suit in which the
founder of Playboy magazine denied his former girlfriend's
allegations.
   The second was the cross complaint seeking $1 million plus court
costs, attorney fees and an amount of punitive damages to be
determined by the court.
   Glassman said the $1 million represents the value of cash,
jewelry, furs and other gifts Hefner gave to Ms. Leigh, now 24,
while the two were together from April 1983 to January.
   Hefner's complaint also accuses Ms. Leigh of fraudulently
telling Hefner she loved him and was faithful to him.
   ``On repeated occasions, Ms. Leigh was sexually unfaithful to
him,'' Glassman told reporters.
   Hefner said he bears no animosity toward Ms. Leigh, but believes
now that she had planned for years to eventually sue him for
palimony.
   ``I think what is happening now is something that was in her
mind from the beginning,'' he said.
   He added that friends, relatives and business associates tried
to warn him about her but he didn't listen to them.
   ``I just saw what I wanted to see,'' he said.
   Hefner, meanwhile, said he has not asked Ms. Conrad to sign any
legal papers absolving him of financial responsibility should their
relationship eventually disolve.
   He said he met the tall, blonde model, Playboy magazine's
January Playmate of the month, when she came to the mansion last
May to pose. He said the two didn't become involved until after Ms.
Leigh left the mansion.
   Ms. Conrad declined comment on Ms. Leigh.
   ``I'm just here to support Hef, and I came after Carrie Leigh,
so I really have no comment,'' she said.
</TEXT>
