<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FarmScene     03-10 0718</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Scene,710</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dogs, X-Rays To Screen Travelers For Illegal Plants, Food</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International travelers arriving at some major
U.S. airports this summer will be greeted by Agriculture Department
inspectors operating X-ray machines to see if their baggage harbors
illegal food or plants.
   The X-rays, in addition to sharp-nosed canine sniffers, will be
used to check arrivals at 11 U.S. international airports for
illegal sausages, mangoes and other contraband.
   ``Imported meats can carry exotic diseases that could devastate
American livestock,'' James W. Glosser, head of the department's
Animal and Plant Health Inspection Service, said Wednesday.
``Fruits and vegetable coming into the country can carry pests that
could seriously damage American crops.''
   Agency inspectors have used X-ray equipment in Puerto Rico and
Hawaii for departures for several years, with interceptions of
prohibited agricultural items doubling, he said.
   The new systems for arrivals were recently installed at
international airports in Miami; Honolulu; San Juan, Puerto Rico;
Houston; and Chicago.
   Additional equipment soon will be installed at international
airports in Atlanta; New York; Washington; Boston; Los Angeles; and
San Francisco.
   The USDA agency also is installing large signs at the 11
airports telling travelers that X-rays are being used to check
their baggage.
   ``Although most people willingly declare their agricultural
products, we do come across some intentional violators,'' Glosser
said. ``That's only natural, considering that we encountered an
estimated 43 million air travelers in 1987. Some ignore the
regulations and others are not even aware of them, despite all our
information efforts.''
   Glosser said the agency uses several methods to find smuggled
agricultural items, including trained beagles to sniff out the
errant braunschweiger here, the occasional mango or two there.
   ``Finally, we rely on the deterrent effect of penalties,'' he
said. ``We fine violators $25 to $50, payable on the spot. We
currently collect about $30,000 per month, and we have collected
nearly $1.8 million since 1984. Fines are deposited in the U.S.
Treasury.''
   Glosser said the travel industry plays an important role in
helping educate the traveling public, including the distribution of
booklets about agricultural items that may be brought into the
United States.
   A brochure also can be obtained by writing: Travelers Tips,
USDA-APHIS, G-187 Federal Building, Hyattsville, Md. 20782.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An absorbent called super slurper invented in
the 1970s is helping tiny worms kill destructive root weevils that
threaten citrus trees, according to an Agriculture Department
scientist.
   William J. Schroeder, an entomolgist in the department's
Agricultural Research Service, said Wednesday the super slurper
keeps soil moist so that the microscopic worms, or nematodes, can
survive and kill weevils that chew the tree roots.
   In tests, 60 percent of the weevils were killed, compared with
only 25 percent without the help of the worms. Schroeder said that
weevils can kill up to 30 percent of the trees in a grove if not
controlled.
   The nematodes haven't been used before as a natural weevil
control because they die quickly if soil dries out, Schroeder said.
   Other agency scientists are looking into the use of super
slurper and nematodes to see if they can control pests of corn and
vegetables.
   Agency scientists in Peoria, Ill., invented the cornstarch-based
super slurper 14 years ago. It has been successfully used in dozens
of commercial products, including body powder, medical dressings
and many other items.
   Schroeder, who works at the department's horticultural research
laboratory in Orlando, Fla., said he thought of super slurper in
1985 when he observed nematodes dying in dry soil.
   ``I realized that in order to use this biological control
(nematodes), we would have to keep the soil moist,'' Schroeder said.
   With its ability to hold up to 2,000 times its own weight in
water, superslurper provided the answer, Schroeder said..
   Companies could mass-rear nematodes and ``package billions of
them alive'' for sale to growers, who then could mix the worms with
super slurper for application on tree roots before planting, he
said.
   For citrus groves already inhabited by the beneficial nematodes,
Schroeder said he is looking into the possibility of injecting
super slurper into the soil with a nozzle.
   The tiny worms, which survive as long as the soil is kept moist,
penetrate the weevils and release lethal bacteria, which don't harm
plants or other organisms, Schroeder said.
</TEXT>
