<HEAD>Tracy Scoggins Labels Defendant's Story Unworthy of Comment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EL PASO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man accused of trying to sexually
assault Miss USA pageant co-host Tracy Scoggins contends she
invited him to her room, a claim the actress dismissed as absurd.
   ``Tracy Scoggins has turned some very serious charges into a
very cheap publicity stunt in a desperate attempt to benefit her
sagging career,'' said attorney Jose Montes Jr., who is
representing the man.
   Montes said Tuesday that Miss Scoggins met his client, Pedro
Concepcion Padilla, in traffic on Interstate 10 on Feb. 25 and
invited him to her hotel room. Montes declined to elaborate on the
highway encounter.
   The actress, best known for her role as Monica Colby in TV's
prime-time soap opera ``The Colbys,'' told police Padilla attacked
her that day in a hotel elevator.
   Padilla was arrested and gave police and a judge a false name
and address, authorities said. After posting $100 bail, he was
rearrested, and then released on $100,000 bail.
   Miss Scoggins, who was here for the pageant, described the
attack at a news conference on Feb. 26, and a first-person account
with her byline is in the latest edition of the National Enquirer.
   Miss Scoggins, in a statement released Tuesday by her publicist,
said she had never seen Padilla until he got on the elevator.
   ``The allegations made by Mr. Padilla's attorney are so
blatantly absurd they should not be dignified by comment. But I do
want to say, though, that it's a pity a woman has to be a victim
twice,'' she said.
