<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-88 0134EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NRCFine     03-10 0322</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-NRC Fine,0333</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NRC Fines Utility's North Anna Nuclear Power Plant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Nuclear Regulatory Commission has fined
the owner of the North Anna nuclear power plant $100,000 after
operators failed to respond promptly to a equipment malfunction,
officials said Wednesday.
   Monitoring instruments on two pipes carrying steam to the
plant's generators malfunctioned, and operators did not respond for
about 10 hours, according to the NRC, which imposed the penalty
against Virginia Power Co.
   Under NRC rules, operators must take action within an hour.
   The incident, which occurred Nov. 4 when the utility was
restarting North Anna Unit 2 after refueling, caused no injuries or
release of radiation.
   The NRC said that the violation, involving part of a non-nuclear
system, did not pose a direct safety hazard.
   However, the instruments provide information necessary to
reactor safety, and if steam is not moving correctly to generators,
the nuclear systems could overheat, utility and NRC officials said.
   The instruments could also be used in responding to steam-line
ruptures. In 1986, at Virginia Power's Surry nuclear plnat, four
workers were killed by scalding steam and water from a failed pipe.
   The commission said because similar incidents occurred
previously at North Anna, the fine was doubled from $50,000, the
typical amount for such violations.
   The utility said it would not contest the fine and it disputed
only the NRC's contention that previous violations were similar.
   Virginia Power has taken action to ensure a violation will not
happen again, including improved training of operators, said
utility spokesman James E. McDonald Jr. No workers were dismissed
or disciplined, he said.
   The North Anna nuclear unit has three main steam lines, and each
has two of the instruments. In the November incident, one
instrument failed on each of two lines.
   McDonald said operators initially were unaware the instruments
were malfunctioning.
   Virginia Power has been fined 13 times since it began operating
nuclear plants in 1972.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
