<HEAD>Female Impersonator Divine Died of Enlarged Heart</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An autopsy determined that heart disease
caused the death of Divine, the 375-pound female impersonator who
starred in the cult film classic ``Pink Flamingos,'' the coroner's
office says.
   ``There was no evidence of drugs or alcohol. He died in his
sleep of an enlarged heart, probably due to the obesity,'' Steve
Stewart, a Los Angeles County coroner's spokesman, said Wednesday
   The cause of death was listed as hypertrophic cardiomyopathy, or
enlarged heart, Stewart said. The coroner's report showed that
Divine, whose real name was Harris Glenn Milstead, weighed 375
pounds.
   The 42-year-old actor, who appears in the current release
``Hairspray,'' was found dead in his bed Monday at the Hollywood
Regency Plaza Hotel.
   Manager Bernard Jay said Milstead had a long-term weight
problem, but otherwise was found to be in excellent health during a
medical checkup Friday.
