<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-88 0143EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-DemocraticGridlock Bjt   03-10 0751</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Democratic Gridlock, Bjt,730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Odds Increasing for Brokered Presidential Convention</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD L. VERNACI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Democratic Party's losing presidential
candidates have found one bright spot in the darkness of their
defeat: The odds are that nobody will be able to claim victory by
the time the primaries are over in June.
   The big winners in this week's round of primaries and caucuses
dismiss that as wishful thinking.
   ``If you get within a decent distance, you're not going to be
stopped,'' said Rick Hutcheson, who oversees delegate selection for
Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr.'s campaign. ``I don't think there's
any doubt in the world that there are plenty of delegates out there
for a first-ballot nominee to develop.''
   True, there are enough delegates yet to be allotted that a clear
winner could emerge. But the odds certainly are growing longer that
any candidate can come up with the magic number needed to win on
the first ballot at the Democratic convention in Atlanta.
   ``Mathematically and politically this process is in gridlock,''
said Terry Michael, spokesman for Illinois Sen. Paul Simon, who
suffered a shutout in Tuesday's round of primaries and caucuses.
   Hutcheson, who worked in former President Jimmy Carter's 1976
presidential campaign, said the then-candidate Carter wound up the
primary season with about 85 percent of the delegates he needed to
win the Democratic presidential nomination. The remaining delegates
gravitated toward a winner, he said.
   ``I think that same scenario will develop here,'' Hutcheson said.
   Simon, who held just 35.5 delegates both before and after
Tuesday's balloting, is banking on nobody being able to gain the
2,082 delegates needed to win the Democratic presidential
nomination when the primaries conclude on June 7, with California
and New Jersey, two of the largest states with a total of 423
delegates at stake.
   ``The person or persons with the greatest potential to negotiate
his way to a first-ballot victory will be the candidate who is
hottest at the end,'' Michael said.
   The Democrats have yet to allocate 2,524 of their national
convention delegates, and another 258.65 delegates list themselves
as uncommitted. Thus the available pool of delegates to be won
between now and early June would be 2,782.65. Partial figures
result from party rules that divide up some votes at the convention.
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis, who was leading the field of
Democratic candidates with 456.5 delegates, needs to win another
1,625.5 to wrap up the presidential nomination. Or, put another
way, he has to win more than 58 percent of all the delegates that
are still left to be won _ roughly twice as well as he's done so
far.
   Dukakis was followed in the delegate count by Jesse Jackson with
395.55 and Gore with 346.8.
   The virtual three-way tie prompted Carter to observe that ``I
think it's accurate to say the chances are less likely that one of
the candidates will arrive in Atlanta with a clear majority.''
   New York Gov. Mario Cuomo, a non-candidate who nonetheless has
said he would consider stepping into the void at a deadlocked
convention, still says he wants to see his party hold a ``quiet
convention.'' But he concedes that it will be difficult for any of
the current candidates to secure a first-ballot victory based on
results of the primaries and caucuses.
   Michael said if no candidate holds a majority by the time the
primaries conclude, the rule of conscience that binds delegates to
the candidates will begin to bend and break.
   But Susan Brophy, an aide to Dukakis, called that assertion
``ridiculous.''
   ``These people get into the process because they believe, A, in
the process and, B, in the candidate _ and not necessarily in that
order.''
   And, Jude Barry, an aide to Missouri Rep. Richard Gephardt's
presidential campaign, agreed, saying, ``I think there's going to
be loyalty and commitment. We're prepared to protect what we have,
as I'm sure the other candidates will as well.''
   Gephardt, who had 143 delegates after Super Tuesday, is hoping
to hang on with a strong showing in the Michigan caucuses on March
26 and the congressional Democratic caucuses on April 19 and 20.
Gephardt also expects to win big when his House colleagues pick 210
of their own to be national convention delegates. Another 43
delegates will be picked by Senate Democrats.
   ``Our hand certainly will not be weak with that wild card,''
Barry said.
   Simon, meanwhile, is hoping to score a victory next Tuesday in
his home state of Illinois.
</TEXT>
