<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CitrusBan     03-10 0267</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Citrus Ban,0273</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Texas Files Suit Against USDA Over Florida Citrus</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BROWNSVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas on Wednesday sued to bar
shipments of Florida citrus in an attempt to protect its fruit
crops from citrus canker.
   U.S. District Judge Filemon Vela on Wednesday denied the state's
request for an emergency stay of a federal order Feb. 11 lifting a
3-year ban on shipments of fresh Florida citrus into Texas and
other citrus-producing areas.
   Vela scheduled a hearing for Monday on the suit, which accuses
the U.S. Agriculture Department of lifting the quarantine without
giving proper notice and an opportunity for a public hearing.
   Florida citrus was quarantined after an outbreak of citrus
canker in Florida in 1984. The bacterial disease can cause
defoliation, lesions that render the fruit unmarketable and
premature dropping of the fruit from the tree.
   On Feb. 15, four days after the quarantine was lifted, Texas
imposed an emergency 30-day ban on Florida citrus, but a federal
court in Austin on overturned the ban, ruling that federal action
takes precedence over state.
   Paul Martin, director of pest management for the Texas
Department of Agriculture, said Texas at least would like to keep
Florida fruit out of the lower Rio Grande Valley, where the state's
$65 million citrus industry is concentrated.
   ``The issue is, we're dealing with a real serious disease in
this case that is a threat to the industry,'' he said.
   Florida producers maintain that the canker presents a minimal
threat to the Texas citrus industry, and some growers there sued to
stop the Texas quarantine.
</TEXT>
