<1ST_LINE>r w PM-CleanAir     03-10 0247</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Clean Air,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Business Lobby Opposing Clean Air Legislation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A major business lobbying group is trying to
keep Congress from passing new nationwide clean air legislation,
claiming it will cost too much, reduce jobs and increase the trade
deficit.
   David M. Roderick, chairman of the environment committee of the
Business Roundtable, said Wednesday that any legislation should be
targeted only at areas with dirty air.
   However, he did not offer specific suggestions for such regional
measures, and said the decisions should be left to the
Environmental Protection Agency.
   Roderick commented as the business group released a report
claiming that clean air legislation passed by the Senate
Environment and Public Works Committee earlier this year would cost
the economy between $15 billion and $73 billion. It said the most
likely figure is $32 billion, and also claimed that the measure
would eliminate between 300,000 and 600,000 manufacturing jobs.
   Roderick, who is chairman of USX Corp., complained about acid
rain provisions in the bill. He said the government should wait for
the final report of the National Acid Precipitation Assessment
Program, a 10-year, 12-agency research effort that isn't due for
completion for another 18 months.
   He said complying with the committee-passed bill would cost his
own company's U.S. Steel Corp. subsidiary $1.5 billion to $2
billion.
   ``We would import more semi-finished product,'' worsening the
trade deficit, he said.
   Roderick said the business group also objects to tougher new
controls on toxic chemical and auto emissions.
</TEXT>
