<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ChanceReunion     03-10 0214</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chance Reunion,0219</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cousins Meet By Chance After 60 Years Apart</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMARAC, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When a nurse in a hospital waiting room
called the name Gnau, two cousins who hadn't seen each other in 60
years stood up.
   ``I looked at him and asked him his name,'' said 73-year-old
Elmer Gnau, a retired tool and dye maker. ``I knew if he said
Kenneth, he would be my cousin. Not many people are named Gnau.''
   Tuesday's chance meeting was an emotional experience for the two
soft-spoken men, who last saw each other when they were children in
Louisville, Ky. Elmer was 13 and Kenneth 3.
   ``I never thought I would have recognized him,'' said Kenneth
Gnau, 63. ``But I looked up, and my stomach came right up to my
throat. He has the face of my father. I almost cried.''
   Elmer Gnau, who lives in La Grange, Ky., said he was in Florida
to visit his son, Jerry Gnau, in North Lauderdale when the
after-effects of a bout with pneumonia sent him to the hospital.
   Kenneth Gnau, who retired to Margate with his wife, was waiting
for an X-ray of a shoulder injury.
   The cousins, whose fathers were brothers, planned to visit each
other later this week after Kenneth Gnau has shoulder surgery.
</TEXT>
