<DOCNO> AP880310-0023 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-88 0204EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Unions-Democrats     03-10 0884</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Unions-Democrats,860</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Super Tuesday Shows Labor Yet To Pick Its Candidate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Union members in the South have given the
heave-ho to one of the two Democratic presidential candidates who
courted them most actively and sent a strong signal to their once
reluctant leaders to play ball with the other.
   Jesse Jackson, shunned by the AFL-CI0 in 1984 in its failed
effort to help put Walter Mondale in the White House, received a 37
percent plurality of votes from union households in 12 Southern
Super Tuesday primaries, according to ABC-TV exit polls.
   Only 10 percent of union voters in the same primaries cast
ballots for Rep. Richard Gephardt of Missouri, point man the past
three years for organized labor's top priority in Congress _
retaliatory trade legislation.
   With Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis and Sen. Albert Gore of
Tennessee equally sharing the other half of the union vote Tuesday,
the AFL-CIO is no closer to making a Democratic presidential
endorsement than it was a year ago.
   Unlike 1984 when Mondale's challengers pinned a ``special
interest'' tag on labor after its early endorsement of him, union
leaders have proclaimed all of the still viable Democratic
candidates this year as acceptable to them.
   Consequently on Tuesday there were none of the union volunteers
and phone banks brought into action in the Southern primaries four
years ago to stop then-Sen. Gary Hart's threat of taking the
nomination away from Mondale.
   Also absent Tuesday was union rank-and-file worker turnout. Only
5 percent of those voting in the Democratic Southern primaries came
from union households, according to the exit polls.
   ``We have a problem of labor being with everyone, so nobody is
doing anything,'' said Joan Baggett, political director of the
Bricklayers Union who took her vacation the past three weeks to
work as a volunteer for Dukakis in the South.
   ``The up side is we haven't alienated any of our members by
endorsing,'' she said. ``The down side is that we haven't excited
them either. We're just not getting people to the polls.''
   Jackson's strong showing among those union members who did vote
Tuesday indicates he may be the exception. While blacks compose 14
percent of the U.S. population, they represent a larger 20 percent
share of 19 million unionized workers nationwide and an even
greater proportion in the South.
   Still, for Jackson to get 37 percent of the union vote, some of
the support had to come from white workers, whose cause Jackson has
championed on hundreds of picket lines over the past four years.
   ``He's been out there on the lines and in the strikes every time
labor has called on him and this is a healthy response to that,''
said Jerry Clark, political director for 1.1-million-member
American Federation of State, County and Municipal Employees.
   Loretta Bowen, who holds the same title for the Communications
Workers of America, said white members of her union were slated as
Jackson delegates in the South and have expressed a keen interest
in him in New York as well.
   ``As a spokesman for the gut issues that affect organized labor,
he's articulating them better than any of the candidates,'' she
said. ``And the fact there has been no endorsement has helped him a
lot.''
   But Ms. Bowen, who personally favors Dukakis, and other labor
political activists believe Jackson's plurality of support will
fade as the primaries move next week to Illinois and then on to
other rust belt states like Michigan, Pennsylvania and Ohio, where
unions are much stronger.
   ``The buzzword already is electibility, and I've never seen that
kind of November strategy ever emerge this early before in our
union,'' she said.
   Allen Zack of the United Food and Commerical Workers union,
noting Gore's increased use of TV spots emphasizing his pro-worker
record in Congress, said all of the Democratic candidates are now
going after the labor vote.
   ``Jesse's talking their language better,'' Zack said. ``He's not
trying to tell some laid off steel worker in Alabama about some
high-tech job in the future. He's talking about restoring their
standard of living today.''
   For that reason, Zack said he was surprised that Gephardt with
his emphasis on slashing trade imbalances through retaliatory
quotas against foreigners who restrict their imports of U.S. goods
got no better than 10 percent of the union vote Tuesday.
   ``Of course he didn't have the money to get on the air as
much,'' Zack said of Gephardt. ``If Super Tuesday confirms
anything, it's the power of TV advertising. It's quite obvious from
the turnout and the results that a parade hasn't formed yet for
labor leaders to rush out in front of.''
   Officials for the AFL-CIO said members of its affiliated unions
running on delegate slates for Jackson, Dukakis and Gore all won
seats Tuesday at the Democratic National Convention in July after
failing to get a single delegate in New Hampshire's primary three
weeks ago.
   ``We didn't do much with Gephardt because Gephardt didn't do
much,'' said Rex Hardesty, a spokesman for the federation.
   Keith Geiger, a vice president of the National Education
Assocation, the nation's largest union with more than 1.7 million
members and not a part of the AFL-CIO, said it also won convention
delegate seats for each of the three Democratic front-runners
Tuesday.
</TEXT>
