<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Civil rights pioneer Rosa L. Parks has received
a pacemaker, and is expected to leave the hospital in a few days, a
spokeswoman says.
   Mrs. Parks was in satisfactory condition Wednesday, a day after
the operation at Johns Hopkins Hospital, said hospital spokeswoman
Ghita Levine.
   The 75-year-old Detroit woman, who was admitted to the hospital
Sunday, was in Baltimore for medical tests and to help plan a
birthday tribute to her in June, Ms. Levine said.
   In 1955, Mrs. Parks was arrested for refusing to give up her
seat to a white man on a segregated bus in Montgomery, Ala. The
black community retaliated by boycotting the buses.
