<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-EgyptRelics     03-10 0299</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Egypt Relics,0306</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Earl Says Egyptian Antiquities Brought into England Legitimately</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Earl of Carnarvon said Egyptian relics found
in his family mansion were brought to Britain legitimately by his
grandfather and Howard Carter, the man who discovered the tomb of
Tutankhamen.
   Antiquities officials in Egypt have said they may try to recover
the trove of 300 objects discovered recently in Highclere Castle,
the ancestral home of the fifth earl of Carnarvon, grandfather of
the current earl.
   But they said they will take no action until more is known about
the find.
   The fifth earl, himself an Egyptologist, financed the expedition
led by Carter which found the almost intact and gold-filled tomb of
the pharaoh in Egypt in 1922.
   ``The records we have discovered show these items were brought
to England legitimately, with the knowledge of the Egyptian
government, by my grandfather and Howard Carter,'' said Lord
Carnarvon.
   He said he had informed the Egyptian ambassador in Britain of
the find ``but I don't expect any serious claim to be made by the
Egyptian government as this could involve the major part of my
grandfather's collection, which is in the Metropolitan Museum of
New York.''
   Ibrahim el-Nawawy, undersecretary of state for the Egyptian
Antiquities Organization, said in Cairo on Tuesday that he was
excited by the find but wants to determine what it includes before
taking action.
   ``It is difficult to say what steps we will take,'' he said.
``We will have to go back through our records to see if the items
were registered and legally taken out of Egypt.''
   The fifth earl died in 1923 from an infected mosquito bite,
nurturing a myth that the 19-year-old pharaoh who died in 1323 B.C.
had put a death curse on anyone who violated his tomb.
</TEXT>
