<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Shultz-Mideast     03-10 0564</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shultz-Mideast,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz Wins Support From House Committee Chairman</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz says he
will press efforts to revive the Middle East peace process because
he is ``absolutely convinced there is an answer out there.''
   Talking to reporters after meeting Wednesday with the House
Foreign Affairs Committee, Shultz said his plan for peace between
the Israelis and Palestinians is ``a pretty good and balanced
concept.''
   Shultz had just briefed the committee privately on his recent
mission to the Middle East.
   ``What we really need to have happen is to get started, get
started on negotiations,'' Shultz said. ``I'm absolutely convinced
that if we can ever get the key people talking and negotiating that
there's an answer out there.''
   Committee Chairman Dante Fascell, D-Fla., said afterward that
``there was tremendous support for what the secretary has
undertaken.''
   Fascell said stern Israeli action to quell persistent violence
in the occupied territories has convinced most members of Congress
of the urgent ``need to find a way into a peace process that will
provide security for all of the inhabitants of the Middle East.''
   ``If a vote had been taken in there it would have been unanimous
in support for what the secretary is trying to do,'' Fascell said.
   The vote of confidence in Shultz comes a week before the planned
visit here by Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, who on
Wednesday expressed astonishment at a letter from 30 senators who
said Israel should be willing to give up control of occupied land
in return for Middle East peace.
   Shamir has blocked attempts inside the Israeli Cabinet to force
a vote on the Shultz plan. The plan calls for an international
conference, to be followed by talks on self-administration for
Palestinians in the occupied territories and negotiations on the
final status of the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   ``Your letter came as a surprise, at a crucial moment in the
peace efforts,'' Shamir wrote in a three-page response. ``We were
astonished by the words of criticism you leveled at us on the
formula of `territory for peace.'''
   Shamir's letter was sent to Sens. Carl Levin, D-Mich., and Rudy
Boschwitz, R-Minn., said Levin administrative assistant Gordon
Kerr. Both senators, strong supporters of Israel, were out of town
and unavailable for comment Wednesday night.
   Twenty-three Democratic and seven Republican senators had sent a
letter to Shamir last week in which they noted that Israel in the
past had supported the idea of ``land for peace'' by returning the
Sinai Peninsula to Egypt.
   They noted that Shamir had rejected ``this expression of
territory for peace'' and expressed hope that the prime minister's
statement ``did not indicate that Israel is abandoning a policy
that offers the best hope for long-term peace.''
   Shamir, in his response, said Israel accepts the U.N. Security
Council resolution that provides for an Israeli withdrawal from
land captured in the 1967 war but he did not agree to Israel's
eventual withdrawal from the West Bank and Gaza.
   Shamir has opposed an international conference on the Middle
East on grounds it would put Israel at serious disadvantage.
   But Fascell suggested that it might be possible to hold an
international conference that would not disadvantage Israel,
especially if the ground rules for the meetings did not permit an
imposed solution or give participating countries veto power.
</TEXT>
