<1ST_LINE>r p PM-PoliticalAds     03-10 0580</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Ads,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dole Attacks Bush in Illinois TV Ad</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Bob Dole sounded the first negative note
of the TV campaigns leading up to next week's Illinois presidential
primary with an attack on Vice President George Bush's Iran-Contra
role.
   With his candidacy at stake in Illinois after losing all 17
Super Tuesday contests, the Kansas senator on Wednesday revived an
ad that says ``Bush approved selling arms to the Ayatollah'' at the
same time he chaired a terrorism task force that said America would
never sell arms for hostages.
   The ad says Bush has ``changed his story nine times'' and owes
voters ``an honest answer'' about his role in the affair.
   Bush was nearly two-thirds of the way to the GOP nomination
after sweeping the Super Tuesday states. He is hoping to ride TV
ads and local endorsements to an Illinois victory that would end
the Senate Republican leader's bid.
   Bush's initial TV ads in Illinois emphasized his connection with
President Reagan. In one ad he and Reagan are shown walking
together, arms around each other, projecting an old-pals image.
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis led the Democratic field
after Super Tuesday with victories in seven states. He and Sen.
Albert Gore Jr. of Tennessee said they would compete full-tilt in
Illinois despite the presence of favorite sons Jesse Jackson and
Sen. Paul Simon.
   Dukakis started two ads Tuesday night in Illinois. In one, a
Massachusetts official of the international bricklayers union says
Dukakis's economic policies ``put people to work.'' The other ad
highlights Dukakis' experience as a chief executive and says it is
unique to the Democratic field.
   Dukakis spokesman Steve Akey said Dukakis spent $1.5 million on
TV advertising for Super Tuesday. ``We haven't made the decision on
a total media buy for Illinois but we'll be on a significant
amount,'' Akey said.
   Gore spent close to $3 million on Super Tuesday media and won
six states. Spokesman Paul Risley said that ``we fully intend to
run a full (media) campaign up there'' in Illinois, but no spending
figure has been fixed.
   There was some possibility that Missouri Rep. Richard Gephardt
would buy Illinois television time, but spokesman Mark Johnson said
the congressman would save most of his resources for the March 26
caucuses in Michigan.
   ``We'll definitely do a full-scale (TV) effort in Michigan,''
Johnson said. As for Illinois, ``We're still considering that
option.''
   Gephardt suffered devastating losses on Super Tuesday, spending
$1.1 million on television ads but winning only his home state.
Part of his problem was being the target of negative ads by both
Dukakis and Gore.
   Akey said the Dukakis campaign went negative on Super Tuesday to
counter ``distorted Gephardt campaign ads.'' Asked if the campaign
is ready for a Gore offensive, he replied, ``We are always prepared
to respond.''
   Jackson and Simon said they planned little or no advertising in
their home state. ``I offer Illinois 30 years of service rather
than a 30-second commercial,'' said Simon, who skipped the Super
Tuesday contests.
   Jackson won five states on Super Tuesday with a minimal $100,000
media campaign and is expected to do well Saturday in South
Carolina, where he was born. His campaign is in debt but raised a
substantial amount of money in February and may buy more media time
in New York, California and other large states later in the
election season, according to campaign manager Gerald Austin.
</TEXT>
