<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CampaignMoney     03-10 0652</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Campaign Money,670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush, Dukakis Have The Cash As Well As Delegates</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush and Michael Dukakis both have
large cash reserves to protect their delegate leads as their rival
presidential hopefuls must refill campaign coffers depleted by the
Super Tuesday marathon.
   Dukakis, who leads the Democratic delegate chase, was sitting on
a cache of $2 million and anticipating $1 million more in matching
funds next week, said campaign finance chief Robert Farmer.
   It was not known exactly how much cash Bush has on hand as he
tries to follow up his sweep of 16 GOP primaries with a knock-out
punch against Sen. Bob Dole of Kansas in next Tuesday's Illinois
primary and beyond.
   But Bush's campaign has been better heeled and more frugal all
along than Dole's or Pat Robertson's.
   Bush had more than $9 million in the bank at the start of
February, the Bush campaign's director of operations, Ede Holiday,
said Wednesday. The bills are still coming in from the Super
Tuesday states, she said, but ``we clearly have plenty of money
left.''
   At Dole headquarters, spokeswoman Dale Tate said: ``We aren't in
the hole. We have cash on hand.'' She declined to say how much. The
Dole campaign was anticipating staff cutbacks.
   Thomas Rath, a senior Dole strategist, said in Chicago that the
campaign will have enough money to run commercials in Illinois. He
said the Kansas senator raised more than $240,000 last week.
   Robertson said Tuesday night: ``I do have resources left. We
have the largest donor base of any candidate and I can carry all
the way to New Orleans.''
   The former television evangelist had spent $17.6 million through
January, and ended that month with $5.5 million in cash but debts
of $6 million.
   What Jesse Jackson calls his ``poor campaign with a rich
message'' has raised $600,000 since the Iowa caucuses Feb. 8,
according to campaign manager Gerald Austin. That is more than the
civil rights leader has ever raised before in such a short time.
   Austin said the Jackson campaign has $250,000 in cash on hand
and anticipates $600,000 in federal matching funds in mid-March.
   Jackson said his wins in five Democratic primaries in the South
came despite being outspent 20- and 30-to-1 by Al Gore Jr. and
Dukakis on television ads. Jackson says he spent just $100,000 on
ads in the Super Tuesday states.
   Austin said Jackson will be buying more television time in large
states like New York and California, and he anticipates earmarking
$30,000 of his $200,000 Illinois budget for television.
   A Gore campaign spokesman, Paul Risley, said the Tennessee
senator spent ``somewhere close to $3 million'' on ads in the Super
Tuesday states. The Dukakis campaign said it spent $1.5 million,
while Rep. Richard Gephardt bought $1.1 million worth of air time.
   Gephardt blamed his meager returns on Super Tuesday _ he lost
everywhere but at home in Missouri _ on his inability to counter
the drumbeat of Gore and Dukakis ads.
   ``With 20 states and a million dollars, we just could not get
our message ... in front of the voters,'' Gephardt said. He claimed
they spent up to $7 million to defeat him.
   Gephardt's deputy campaign manager, Joe Trippi, said Gephardt
has $250,000 on hand and debts of only $75,000. Trippi said the
campaign hopes to raise $500,000 over the next two weeks.
   Illinois Sen. Paul Simon, who bowed out of the Super Tuesday
contests to make a low-budget stand at home, said of his campaign,
``It's kind of a hand-to-mouth operation.''
   The Simon campaign has missed one payroll and is in danger of
missing a second. But Simon raised $932,000 in February and soon
will get $364,000 in matching funds, spokesman Terry Michael said.
   Simon owes $145,000, but ``we are in much better financial
condition right now than either the Gore or the Gephardt
campaigns,'' claimed Michael.

</TEXT>
