<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-88 0244EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-NuclearTerrorism     03-10 0454</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nuclear Terrorism,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NRC Chief Defends Regulations To Protect Nuclear Plants From
Terrorists</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nuclear Regulatory Commission officials say
the agency's rules provide commercial reactors adequate safeguards
against terrorist attacks but its staff will additionally look at
the potential threat from truck bombs.
   NRC Chairman Lando W. Zech told a House subcommittee Wednesday
that the commission has confidence in the current safety rules, but
recently instructed its staff to draft a series of options related
to a truck-bomb threat ``as a prudent measure.''
   The disclosure came as NRC officials clashed with Rep. Sam
Gejdenson, D-Conn., chairman of the House Interior and Insular
Affairs subcommittee on general oversight and investigations, over
commission security requirements.
   Gejdenson urged the commission to beef up its security
standards, which require plant operators to protect against a
hypothetical threat of ``several'' terrorists armed with hand-held
automatic weapons and aided by an accomplice inside the plant.
   Fuel from traditional U.S. commercial reactor cannot be stolen
and used to make nuclear bombs. But Gejdenson said he feared
terrorists could break into a nuclear reactor, hold it and the
surrounding region hostage or trigger a nuclear meltdown that would
release deadly radiation into the atmosphere.
   Rep. Peter A. DeFazio, D-Ore., pointed to a threat last June
from state-run Tehran radio that said Iran could attack U.S.
reactors in retaliation against American forces in the Persian Gulf.
   ``You have people here who want to be martyrs,'' DeFazio said.
   Gejdenson said the regulations should protect against a car or
truck bursting through a plant's chain-link fence, attackers
invading from a boat, and truck bombs like the ones used in
terrorist attacks overseas.
   ``Simple prudence and common sense dictate that the NRC assume
that terrorist have cars and that licensees should be required to
protect against this level of threat,'' Gejdenson said. In an
interview last week, the congressman said ``the gang that couldn't
shoot straight could take any one of these facilities'' under the
current standards.
   Zech said the regulations are ``adequate and appropriate at this
time.'' And he said the NRC is in daily contact with U.S.
intelligence agencies monitoring any potential threats.
   But he added that the NRC told the staff last month to prepare
``a range of options'' regarding a truck-bomb threat for commission
consideration. Such recommendations could eventually become
regulations, said NRC spokesman Bob Newlin.
   Zech said the staff review stems from a December classified
report by the National Security Council, but Gejdenson contended
the move was a response to his investigation.
   Gejdenson said that the agency began working on a truck-bomb
regulation following the October 1983 bombing of the Marine
barracks in Lebanon, but that the commission never approved the
proposal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
