<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis     03-10 0538</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Stumps For Labor Votes in Rust Belt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential contender Michael
Dukakis, saying he's in an ``uphill battle'' in Ilinois, attacked
rival Sen. Albert Gore Jr. as a regional candidate who would have
little chance to win the general election in November.
   The Massachusetts governor is also touting himself as the
candidate who has the best track record on the economy.
   Dukakis began airing a television spot here in which a
bricklayers' union official tells voters that if they want to go
out for a beer they should call their buddy, but ``if you care
about your job, Mike Dukakis is your guy.''
   In Tuesday's Illinois primary, Illinois Sen. Paul Simon is
expected to garner favorite-son votes and the Chicago-based Jesse
Jackson is likely to tap black support in his hometown.
   That leaves Dukakis battling Gore for the remaining share. And
Dukakis suggested that he was a better choice to represent the
party as the nominee.
   ``I'm not so sure he's a major contender,'' Dukakis said of
Gore. ``A guy from Massachusetts beat him in Texas, beat him in
Florida. He wasn't willing to go into the early primaries. But I
still take everyone seriously.''
   Michael Bakalis, Dukakis' Illinois campaign chairman, said white
blue-collar voters in Chicago could form Dukakis' base in Illinois.
   ``Paul Simon in the 1984 Senate race did not do very well in
Chicago, particularly in the white, ethnic precincts,'' Bakalis
said.
   Those were precisely the precincts Dukakis targeted Wednesday in
his first full day of campaigning in Illinois in the week leading
up to the primary.
   He met over breakfast with laid-off steel workers and then
visited the Metron steel warehouse in Chicago, owned by one of
Dukakis' many Greek-American supporters, Andrew Athens.
   Illinois will send 173 delegates to the Democratic National
Convention in Atlanta. Of those, 113 will be decided next Tuesday.
The rest are held by various party and elected officials. Bakalis
said 74 of the 113 will come from the greater Chicago area.
   The Dukakis camp plans to wage a traditional campaign in
Illinois, with an appearance at tonight's Democratic party dinner,
a spot in Chicago's famous St. Patrick's Day parade and a message
geared toward working men and women, said Dukakis national
political coordinator Charles Baker.
   ``Win, lose or draw _ and we don't expect to win _ you want
people here to care about this race,'' Baker said.
   The Dukakis campaign remains the financial front-runner after
the media spending of Super Tuesday. Campaign finance chief Robert
Farmer said Dukakis is raising half a million dollars a week.
Coming out of Super Tuesday, he said, Dukakis has $2 million in the
bank and another $1 million on the way in federal matching funds.
   Bakalis said the governor has budgeted $300,000 to $350,000 for
the state leading up to next Tuesday. That amount could increase,
he said, if Dukakis decides to increase his media advertising.
   With two Illinois residents in the race, ``Obviously it's going
to be an uphill battle,'' Dukakis said.
   ``At this point I think that most people would think that third
place would be respectable,'' he said. ``But I want to do better
than that.''
</TEXT>
