<1ST_LINE>r w PM-AirportSecurity     03-10 0524</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Airport Security,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FAA Hit by Parent Agency for Airport Security Lapses</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Aviation Administration is coming
under criticism from its boss for not being aggressive enough in
issuing civil fines against airlines because of airport security
shortcomings.
   Transportation Secretary Jim Burnley says he is disturbed that
the FAA has not been complying with a directive issued last summer
and reiterated in October, calling for ``aggressive enforcement''
actions against airlines that allow mock weapons to go undetected
at an airport screening point.
   The FAA has been testing security at the nation's airports by
passing phony weapons through the checkpoints to see if they are
found. Last year a report concluded that as many as one in five
mock weapons in FAA tests go through undetected.
   The discovery prompted the Transportation Department to order
the FAA to get tough with airlines so that security is improved.
The airlines are responsible for airport security checkpoints,
although the stations are usually staffed through a contractor.
   Burnley said Wednesday that the department specifically told the
FAA to take enforcement actions, including a possible fine, when a
security checkpoint allows a mock weapon through without detection.
   Burnley aides released a sharply worded memorandum sent earlier
this week to FAA Administrator Allan McArtor. In it, the
transportation secretary said he was ``deeply disturbed'' that five
months after the crackdown was ordered, ``the FAA is only taking
action if carriers fail three out of five tests at a checkpoint and
is only issuing a fine for the third failure.''
   ``I am troubled by continuing reports of failure by the FAA to
fully implement these directed improvements and to strictly enforce
security requirements,'' he wrote.
   McArtor said in a statement, ``I absolutely share Secretary
Burnley's concern that FAA aggressively implement all security
recommendations. I have instructed FAA personnel that the rules
must be strictly enforced.''
   Agency officials had no further comment.
   The incident, however, is likely to further strain relations
between Burnley and McArtor.
   The Washington Post reported earlier this week that Burnley was
displeased with the FAA's top public affairs officer because some
regulatory action involving commuter airlines had been disclosed
prematurely just when Burnley wanted media attention focused on a
speech he was making at the National Press Club.
   Wendy DeMocker, who is Burnley's spokesman, denied that Burnley
had anything to do with the departure of Air Force Lt. Col. James
C. Jannette from the post. Jannett, who had been at the job only
three months and had been a personal choice of McArtor, was asked
by the Pentagon to return to his military duties, she said.
   Meanwhile, there have been differences between McArtor and
Burnley on other aviation matters. Last year McArtor told reporters
he planned by April to submit legislation to Congress on a national
policy to deal with noise problems at airports.
   Burnley said Wednesday no such plans are in the works and that
McArtor had changed his mind. Burnley often has said he believes
such legislation would be foolhardy because Congress has no desire
to tell local officials what to do about airport noise.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
