<1ST_LINE>u a AM-SmallPlaneCrash     03-10 0174</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Small Plane Crash,0179</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Small Plane Crashes Into Residential Area; At Least Three Killed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARREN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A twin-engine plane crashed into a
residential neighborhood shortly after takeoff early Thursday,
killing at least three people, authorities said.
   The plane took off from Detroit City Airport and struck one or
two houses about five miles to the northwest, said Tim Stayer, a
worker at Universal Macomb Ambulance Service Inc. of Warren.
   He said the plane was heading for Oakland-Pontiac Airport at the
time of the crash.
   It was not known how many passengers were aboard the plane or in
any of the homes involved, Stayer said.
   Officials said at least three people were killed.
   The crash occurred at 12:30 a.m., Warren police Sgt. Richard
Pytlak said.
   The plane had been in the air one-to-two minutes before it
crashed, said Barbara Gardner-Martin, air traffic manager for City
Airport. She said that type of aircraft normally is used to carry
freight, but she said she did not know what or who was aboard the
flight.
</TEXT>
