<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-88 0328EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bush     03-10 0523</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Begins Illinois Campaign Today</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: No prenoon lead; first event begins 1:30 p.m. EST</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush, with the support of Gov. Jim
Thompson and most Republican Party leaders, will stump his way
``through all corners'' of Illinois, his campaign says.
   After a one-day respite from campaign rigors, Bush was flying to
Chicago today to begin an intensive five days of vote-seeking as he
tries to pad his formidable lead in the race for nominating
convention delegates.
   Between now and next Tuesday, Bush will have criss-crossed the
state several times, with Thompson, a four-term governor, at his
side most of the way.
   He was beginning his campaign with a speech to the GOP Governors
Club Luncheon in Chicago, to be followed later in the day with
Lincoln Day dinner appearances in Champaign and Alton. Bush has the
endorsements of 93 of 102 county GOP chairmen in Illinois.
   The Bush campaign style will be similar to the one he used
successfully in New Hampshire, South Carolina and the Super Tuesday
states. He is scheduled to discuss agricultural issues Friday and
visit a methanol plant later that day.
   With Thompson at his side, Bush will enjoy the benefits of
having the support of the state's top office-holder.
   In advance of Bush's campaign foray, Thompson's press secretary,
David Fields, said the governor had virtually cleared his schedule
of any conflicting events.
   ``The governor and Bush will be together pretty much through the
whole five days,'' Fields said. ``We're talking about the length
and breadth of Illinois _ a pretty good cross-section.''
   Pete Teeley, Bush's chief spokesman, said of Thompson: ``He's a
terrific campaigner and we sure want him to be with us.''
   Bush campaign manager Lee Atwater said earlier this week that
the vice president, seeking to win the 82 convention delegates
Illinois offers, would ``go through all corners of the state,
campaign directly and forthrightly, discuss issues and get his
message out.''
   Bush, who has amassed 805 of the 1,139 delegates needed for
nomination, has refused to accept Sen. Bob Dole's demand that the
two meet in one-on-one campaign debates in Illinois.
   Rep. Lynn Martin, R-Ill., co-chairman of the Bush campaign, said
that while Bush would travel throughout the state, he would focus
on the stronghold of the state Republican Party, the ``collar
communities'' surrounding Chicago.
   She said that Dole ``has a right to say to the Illinois farming
communities, `I'm one of you' and George Bush can't do that.''
   But Martin also said that ``Illinois is not Iowa, and our
farming communities did not have the same difficulties.''
   Bush finished a distant third behind Dole and Pat Robertson in
Iowa, and a part of the reason was disenchantment there with Reagan
administration farm policy.
   Martin said: ``I don't think there's any question that Bush will
win the popularity vote, but Dole will do well in some districts.''
   Ken Wright, one of Bush's principal strategists in Florida,
said: ``I think, going to Illinois, we've got a great organization
up there. Gov. Thompson is enormously popular there, and I think
he'll do very well.''
</TEXT>
