<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Philippines 1stLd-Writethru a0481 03-10 0704</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0481,0725</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Aquino Criticizes Human Rights Charges; Won't Seek Second Term</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after lede and SUBS 7th graf pvs `On Wednesday
...' with 6 grafs to restore dropped material about Aquino not
seeking re-election. PICKS up 8th graf pvs bgng, `In its report
.... ADDS byline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT H. REID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Corazon Aquino today called
``one-sided'' a report by Amnesty International alleging widespread
human rights abuse in the Philippines during her two years in
office.
   Also today, Mrs. Aquino said she had no plans to run for
re-election when her term expires in June 1992. It was the clearest
statement of her political intentions to date.
   Mrs. Aquino said there have been delays in punishing human
rights violators because the Philippines respects the rights of the
accused to due process.
   On Wednesday, the London-based human rights organization alleged
that Mrs. Aquino's government had used torture, murder and illegal
arrests in fighting the country's 19-year communist rebellion.
   Amnesty International called on the government to end killings
by military and paramilitary forces, saying they represented the
country's most serious human rights problem since mid-1987.
   ``I think the Amnesty International report was very one-sided,''
Mrs. Aquino told Filipino reporters. She said the organization had
relied only on social activist groups, such as the church-backed
Task Force-Detainees, in compiling its report.
   The president urged such groups to cooperate with the
government's Commission on Human Rights in providing documented
evidence to help find and punish human rights violators.
   On Wednesday, Task Force-Detainees said its investigation showed
that 7,444 Filipino civilians were arrested illegally in 1987,
eclipsing the 5,967 arrests in 1985, when Ferdinand Marcos was
president.
   Mrs. Aquino came to power when Marcos' authoritarian regime
collapsed in February 1986. There has been speculation Mrs. Aquino
would seek a second term, using a technicality in the new
constitution.
   ``I don't think so,'' she told Filipino reporters. She added:
``I have never had political ambitions.''
   The constitution, drafted by an Aquino-appointed commission and
approved in a plebiscite last year, limits the president and vice
president to one six-year term.
   But ``transitory provisions'' in the constitution, temporary
measures designed to ease the transition of power, also state that
the first regular elections for president under the new charter
will be held on the second Monday of May 1992.
   Some political observers and Aquino supporters have interpreted
the wording of the transitory provision to mean Mrs. Aquino is not
bound by the one-term limit.
   In its report, Amnesty International praised the Aquino
government for ``some very real progress'' in human rights,
particularly in restoring legal safeguards and in greatly reducing
the use of torture.
   But it called on the government to reaffirm publicly its
commitment to protect human rights. The report said Amnesty
International knew of no cases where soldiers had been punished for
human rights violations.
   It cited the February 1987 killing of 17 civilians in Lupao. The
military said the killings took place after a lieutenant was killed
by a communist sniper during a patrol in Lupao.
   ``With regards to no soldier being convicted, in fact charges
have been filed against the soldiers involved or implicated in the
Lupao massacre,'' Mrs. Aquino said.
   ``We are living in a democracy. While it is true there is
evidence ... everyone is entitled to due process of law. Even those
who are accused should have their day in court.''
   Mary Concepcion Bautista, chairwoman of the Commission on Human
Rights, also criticized the Amnesty International report as
``exaggerated.''
   She said the government was investigating about 200 cases of
human rights abuse, claiming ``there is a serious effort to clean
up.''
   Mrs. Bautista said investigations of human rights abuses against
the military were often not publicized to avoid demoralizing
soldiers who are fighting the rebels.
   ``The insurgents don't follow the rules,'' she said. ``Soldiers
complain that when they fight the insurgents, they have one hand
tied behind their back.''
   Last year about 150 police and soldiers were fatally shot on
Manila streets. Communist rebels claimed responsibility for about
half the killings.
   An average of 10 soldiers, civilians or police officers are
killed daily in clashes between government and rebel forces.
</TEXT>
