<HEAD>Swiss Concert Promoter Sues British Orchestra</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Swiss concert promoter filed suit against the
Royal Philharmonic Orchestra for reneging on an agreement to play
12 concerts in Jerusalem in May, officials said.
   An orchestra spokesman on Wednesday confirmed that the orchestra
had pulled out of the concerts, but said the suit would be
``vigorously defended.''
   ``We pulled out because we had to review our undertaking to 125
musicians because contractual payments had not been honored,'' said
the spokesman, who confirmed the suit had been received and who
spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Robin Shaw, the lawyer for the Geneva-based Opera on Original
Sites Inc., said in a statement the firm was suing for damages from
the canceled booking.
   The statement, released Wednesday, said the action was brought
because the orchestra failed to honor a contract to play the
concerts May 15-29.
   The orchestra was scheduled to play in performances of Verdi's
opera ``Nabucco'' as part of Israel's 40th anniversary
celebrations, it said.
</TEXT>
