<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--China-Colleges     03-10 0122</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--China-Colleges,0124</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China To Reduce Growth In College Enrollment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chinese universities will sharply cut the rate of
growth in enrollment to cope with problems of overcrowding and
inadequate facilities, an official newspaper said today.
   College enrollment increases will be held to between 2 percent
and 5 percent annually from this year through 1990, compared to a
growth rate of 17 percent in the 1981-85 period, the China Daily
said.
   It said college administrators attending a national conference
agreed that the current goal of 750,000 undergraduates in 1990 is
not practical, and opted for a figure of 680,000.
   They said junior colleges, correspondence schools and other
programs will help satisfy the great demand among young Chinese for
higher education.
</TEXT>
