<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Italy-Scandal,0191</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Ex-Ministers Under Investigation in Scandal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three former government ministers are being
investigated by a parliamentary committee about a scandal over
prison construction contracts.
   Italian media reported that Franco Nicolazzi, who resigned as
secretary of the tiny Social Democrat party February 29, and two
Christian Democrats, Clelio Darida and Vittorino Colombo, were
served notice Wednesday about the probe to clarify what, if any,
links they have to the scandal.
   The scandal, nicknamed the ``Golden Prisons'' case, involves
alleged bribes to obtain public works contracts.
   Nicolazzi was Public Works minister in several governments from
1980 through last June and secretary from October 1985 of a party
that won 3.4 percent of the vote in the June 1987 elections to the
Chamber of Deputies.
   Sen. Antonio Cariglia was elected in his place Wednesday evening
by the central committee of the party.
   Darida served as justice minister and subsequently government
participations minister from 1981 to March 1987.
   Colombo last held a Cabinet post in 1980 as post and
telecommunications minister. From 1979 to 1982, he was
vice-secretary of Christian Democrats, Italy's largest vote-getter.
</TEXT>
