<1ST_LINE>r i PM-NATO-Missiles     03-10 0580</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-NATO-Missiles,0595</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Adjust Missile Force After Superpower Treaty, NATO Chief
Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CASTEAU, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Although the superpower missile treaty
has not been ratified yet, the Soviet Union is already adjusting
its nuclear missile force to regain firepower lost through the
accord, NATO's top commander said.
   The commander, U.S. Gen. John R. Galvin, said on Wednesday that
the moves were expected and were not in violation of the treaty
signed last December to eliminate the superpowers' medium- and
shorter-range nuclear missiles worldwide. Missiles covered by the
treaty have ranges from 300 to 3,000 miles.
   ``They are restructuring their missile force,'' Galvin said in
an interview with The Associated Press in his spartan office at
Supreme Headquarters Allied Powers Europe. Galvin likened the
Soviet moves to reshaping a wall from which some stones have been
removed.
   ``I don't want to get too specific ... but I get some
indications that the Soviets are readjusting the stones on the
wall,'' he said, adding that the Western allies would do this, too.
   Galvin added: ``(The Soviets) will retarget other warheads into
Western Europe'' to cover military targets previously assigned to
the hundreds of SS-20 rockets to be dismantled under terms of the
superpower accord.
   He said it was not yet clear how the Soviets would accomplish
this. ``They may have to take ... warheads that were aimed in
another direction and aim them toward Western Europe,'' Galvin said.
   The net result, he said, is likely to be that the Soviets will
partially offset the loss of their SS-20s, which are triple-warhead
ballistic missiles capable of striking all of Western Europe.
   ``The overall capabilities of the Soviets would still be
somewhat lower _ a small amount lower _ because of the treaty,''
Galvin said. ``But the adjustments ... will to some degree cover
that.''
   The North Atlantic Treaty Organization also is seeking to adjust
and modernize its remaining nuclear forces in Europe to partially
compensate for the loss of the U.S. cruise and Pershing 2 missiles.
But there is disagreement in NATO over how and when to do this.
   According to Galvin, it was important for NATO eventually to
replace its aging Lance short-range nuclear missiles, which are not
covered by the treaty, with a more modern version of longer reach.
But he said a final decision on replacing the Lance missiles in
West Germany was not needed before 1990.
   He said NATO arms modernization is necessary to help defeat one
of Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev's chief aims: to rid Europe
of all nuclear weapons.
   Despite Gorbachev's recent pronouncements about seeking a more
peaceful relationship with the West, Galvin said, the Kremlin
leader has not abandoned the long-standing Soviet aim of dominating
Western Europe.
   ``He's moving in exactly the same direction,'' he said.
   Galvin said many Westerners are responding to Gorbachev's softer
stance in the same way a hostage feels kindly toward his captor
after being released.
   ``Maybe we're seeing a little bit of that psychology where we
have felt ourselves under the pressure of the powerful military
forces of the Soviet Union and the Warsaw Pact for so many decades
... that when we get some indication of a friendly nod in our
direction we respond enormously because it's such a change,'' he
said.
   According to Galvin, Western governments should not move too
quickly to encourage Gorbachev's efforts to modernize the Soviet
economy, since a stronger economy could make Moscow a more
formidable enemy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
