<1ST_LINE>r a PM-LaRouche-NBC     03-10 0422</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-LaRouche-NBC,0434</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NBC Loses Appeal Of Decision In LaRouche Case</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-LaRouche Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NBC must surrender to a judge outtakes from an
interview with a former Lyndon LaRouche consultant who said an aide
to the political extremist discussed a plot to assassinate Henry
Kissinger, a federal appeals court ruled.
   The decision Wednesday by the 1st U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
upheld a lower court order that videotape of the entire interview
must be surrendered for possible use at the conspiracy and fraud
trial of LaRouche, six aides and five political organizations.
   The court also upheld a contempt citation against the network.
   NBC had contended that surrendering portions of the interview
that were not broadcast violated its First Amendment right against
judicial intrusion into news gathering and editorial decisions.
   U.S. District Judge Robert E. Keeton ruled that the rights of
the defendants to have access to the interview with Forrest Lee
Fick outweighed those of the network.
   ``At stake in the defendants' side of the equation are their
constitutional rights to a fair trial under the Fifth Amendment,''
the appeals court wrote in concurring with Keeton, whose original
order called for him to review the entire interview and determine
its relevance to the case.
   NBC attorney Floyd Abrams said the network would decide within a
few days whether to appeal to the U.S. Supreme Court.
   ``It is an opinion which we believe does not sufficiently
recognize the First Amendment rights of broadcasters,'' Abrams said.
   Keeton had issued a similar order requiring CBS to surrender
outtakes of an interview it conducted with another LaRouche aide.
CBS complied.
   NBC interviewed Fick for 100 minutes and in April 1986 broadcast
a one-minute portion of the interview in which Fick said he and
LaRouche aide Paul Goldstein discussed a plot to assassinate
Kissinger, the former secretary of state.
   Fick, of Reading, Pa., worked as a LaRouche security consultant
with another Reading man, Roy Frankhauser. Frankhauser was
convicted in December of conspiring to obstruct a federal grand
jury investigation of alleged credit card and loan fraud by
LaRouche followers during his 1984 presidential campaign.
   Fick was a prosecution witness against Frankhauser. Both are
expected to be called as witnesses at the trial of LaRouche and
aides including Goldstein.
   Defense lawyers contend the entire NBC interview will help show
Fick and Frankhauser were among scores of operatives planted in
LaRouche organizations by the FBI and CIA to gather information and
ultimately to ruin LaRouche and cripple his fund-raising operation.
</TEXT>
