<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     03-10 0327</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After a long, hard day of fighting crime
on the streets of Los Angeles, police detective Norman Nelson gets
his kicks by climbing onto the back of a 2,000-pound Brahma bull.
   ``Bull riding's a high,'' explains Nelson, 44, a three-time LAPD
bull-riding champion. ``You can't imagine it if you haven't
experienced it. But once you know that thrill, you don't want to
give it up.''
   And there's more than just kicks.
   Since taking up the sport in 1983, Nelson has been hooked,
horned, stepped on and knocked senseless. But he says there's a big
difference between busting crooks and riding Brahmas in a rodeo.
   ``With the bull, the danger comes from something you respect,''
Nelson said. ``You respect its strength, its power, its ability.
The bull doesn't care whether it kills you or not. It's a clean
contest between you and the bull.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MURPHY, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 25 percent increase in attendance at the
Democratic caucus here was cause for rejoicing among party
stalwarts in Owyhee County, population 8,272.
   It meant they'd have a quorum. Murphy, a tiny community in
Idaho's southwestern corner, is reputed to be the smallest county
seat in the nation, consisting of the Owyhee County Courthouse and
several mobile homes.
   Sheriff Tim Nettleton, was one of four Democrats who attended
the caucus at the courthouse, locally famous as the site of
Murphy's one parking meter.
   When a man in a cowboy hat walked into the meeting room, his
arrival was seen as increasing attendance by 25 percent. ``I knew
there was something I liked about you,'' Nettleton said. ``You must
be a Democrat.''
   ``No,'' he replied. ``I just wanted to see the sheriff for a
minute.''
   Eventually, however, the Democrats rounded up a quorum.
   That put them one up on Democrats in heavily Republican Custer
County in central Idaho. They had a caucus scheduled Tuesday night,
but nobody came.
</TEXT>
