<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WashingtonInBrief     03-10 0555</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington In Brief,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Navy Defends Seawolf Attack Sub Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Seawolf, the Pentagon's newest nuclear
attack submarine scheduled to begin production later this year,
will help the United States dominate the Soviet Union at sea long
into the next century, the Navy says.
   The SSN-21 will have double the fire power and be faster,
quieter and more survivable than the SSN-688 Los Angeles class sub,
which the Seawolf is expected to replace as the nation's chief
attack submarine, Vice Adm. Bruce DeMars, assistant chief of naval
operations for undersea warfare, told a House panel Wednesday.
   The Seawolf, which has been in the research and design stage for
six years, has been criticized by some lawmakers who fear the sub
is not advanced enough for the Soviet's planned successor to their
Akula attack sub.
   But DeMars dismissed that notion, telling the House Armed
Services sea power subcommittee that the Seawolf is ``the
foundation for far-term submarine superiority.''
   Last year, a House subcommittee tried to delay funds for the
project, but Congress restored the money. Navy officials have
warned that such a delay could severely damage the Seawolf program
and cause massive cost overruns.
   DeMars said the project now is on schedule and on budget.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Pacifier Holder Recalled Because of Choking Hazard</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Early models of the Baby Buddy clip-on
pacifier holder are being recalled by the Consumer Product Safety
Commission because of a potential choking hazard.
   About 9,000 of the holders were distributed nationwide in 1986
and 1987, officials said. They sold for about $3.95 each.
   While no injuries have been reported involving the holders,
parents were urged to return them to the store where purchased for
a free replacement. When tested, the small bear figure separated
from the holder and thus could pose a choking hazard, officials
said.
   New model holders can be distinguished by the two round holes in
the back of the clip. There are no holes in the clip of the holders
being recalled.
   Recalled pacifier holders include those with a pink ribbon and
white bear, blue ribbon and bear, yellow ribbon and brown bear, red
ribbon and white bear and red ribbon and brown bear.
   Persons needing more information can contact Baby Buddies Inc.,
615 Jasmine Avenue North, Suite I, Tarpon Springs, Fla., at
1-813-934-3359 or the Safety Commission at 1-800-638-2772.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Government To Appeal Judge's Ruling On Confession</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department has filed notice hat it
will appeal a federal judge's decision to suppress the confession
of a former Lebanese Shiite Amal militiaman accused of leading an
airline hijacking.
   The government's move Wednesday to appeal the ruling by U.S.
District Judge Barrington D. Parker stays the March 22 trial of
Fawaz Younis pending a ruling by the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
here.
   Parker ruled last month that the FBI illegally obtained a
confession from Younis when he was arrested and interrogated for
four days aboard a Navy munitions ship in the Mediterranean after
being lured into an FBI-chartered yacht.
   The judge ruled that prosecutors could not use the confession as
evidence that Younis led four other hijackers who seized a Royal
Jordanian airliner on June 11, 1985 at Beirut International Airport.
   The plane was destroyed a day later after the passengers and
crew were taken off the aircraft.
