<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Clancy-Publisher     03-10 0207</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Clancy-Publisher,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Best-Selling Author, Publisher In Dispute Over Rights To Character
Jack Ryan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Author Tom Clancy hopes to learn in June
whether he or the Naval Institute Press of Annapolis, Md., calls
the shots for CIA operative Jack Ryan.
   The Washington Post reported today that Clancy and the Naval
institute are in a dispute over the rights to Ryan, a character in
Clancy's best-selling books ``The Hunt for Red October'' and
``Patriot Games.''
   The small institute had never before published an original work
of fiction when it brought out ``Red October'' in 1984 and
copyrighted the work in its own name. Clancy later signed a
three-book, $3 million contract with Putnam, a New York publishing
firm.
   The institute now is challenging Putnam's publication of ``The
Cardinal of the Kremlin,'' a new novel by Clancy with the Ryan
character. It also is seeking payment for use of the Ryan character
in last year's ``Patriot Games'' and wants a percentage of any
earnings from a proposed television mini-series of that novel, the
Post said.
   Clancy refused to comment on the advice of his lawyers, the
newspaper said. He took the case to the American Arbitration
Association last month, with a binding decision expected in June.
</TEXT>
