<1ST_LINE>u i PM-UN-Cuba     03-10 0552</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UN-Cuba,0569</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cuba Invites U.N. Delegates To Check Human Rights Allegations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For the first time, the Cuban government has
invited delegates of the U.N. Human Rights Commission to visit Cuba
to investigate the human rights situation on the island nation.
   One United States delegate called the offer a ``diversionary
tactic,'' while another questioned the way it was brought before
the commission.
   The chief Cuban representative to the 43-nation commission, Raul
Roa Kouri, said on Wednesday that six members could go to Cuba ``in
order to see ... the situation prevailing there in human rights and
to inform the commission.''
   Roa, who is also a deputy foreign minister, said the commission
members allowed to visit would be the chairman, Alioune Sene of
Senegal, and five other delegates, one from each of the regional
groups.
   Reading what he said was a letter to Sene from his government,
Roa indicated that the Cuban government would arrange ``the
necessary contacts and interviews with the officials and competent
authorities of our country who would answer all their questions.''
   He also said the representatives would be given access to
``penitentiary establishments,'' but did not elaborate. Roa did not
give a date for the planned visit.
   Roa's remarks in Spanish were translated into English by an
interpreter. U.S. delegate Daniel Pipes said the Cuban invitation
was made to draw attention away from a U.S.-proposed resolution,
which calls for the U.N. secretary-general to investigate charges
of human rights abuses in Cuba and for Cuba to allow the
International Red Cross to visit Cuban prisons.
   ``They're afraid of the vote'' on that resolution, Pipes told
The Associated Press.
   Another U.S. delegate, Lewis Anselem, told the commission the
Cuban invitation was ``the first time that the Cuban government has
shown a willingness to have a United Nations organ look into the
human rights situation in that country and into the allegations
about that situation.''
   But Anselem said some of the procedures used to bring it before
the commission were ``highly irregular.''
   The proposed visit was introduced in the commission meeting by
Colombia, reportedly with the support of Argentina, Mexico and
Peru, all members of the commission. Cuba is an observer this year.
   Anselem said the United States would not accept the proposed
visit as a substitute for its own resolution.
   The United States for the second year in a row is pursuing its
goal of having the commission examine alleged human rights abuses
in Cuba. This year the U.S. government appointed a former Cuban
political prisoner, Armando Valladares, to head the U.S. delegation.
   The Cuban government has attacked the appointment of Valladares,
a poet who wrote a book about torture and degrading treatment he
said he suffered during 22 years in Cuban prisons.
   Valladares has said the United States, in pressing the Cuba
issue, is trying to fight a ``selective sensitivity'' in the
commission, which routinely condemns human rights violations in the
Israeli-occupied territories, Chile and South Africa.
   The United States maintains that human rights abuses in Cuba
include torture, clandestine executions and religious and political
persecution.
   The U.S.-sponsored resolution cites allegations of human rights
abuses in Cuba made by other international groups, including
Amnesty International and the Organization of American States.
   The resolution is to be voted on before the commission ends its
annual meeting on Friday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
