<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Briefs,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Speaker To Democratic Candidates: Tone Down Negative Ads</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, says he's
sent telegrams congratulating all the Democratic candidates who won
delegates on Super Tuesday and asking them to eschew negative ads
from now on in the campaign.
   ``Candidates with viable ideas and strong ideals do not need to
rely on negative campaigning which only tarnishes and muddles the
processes of democracy,'' Wright said.
   Wright said the use of negative ads had become a ``vogue,''
intensified by the short time between the New Hampshire primaries
and Tuesday's 20-state extravaganza.
   Super Tuesday, the brainchild of moderate and conservative
Democrats, Wright said, ``put a great premium on having an enormous
amount of money to spend in little quickie TV spots'' and denied
candidates the chance to be evaluated by voters on the merits of
their ideas.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The rush left ``no time to make a sensible ... appeal,'' Wright
said, and led candidates to ``succumb to the wicked blandishments
of those in the advertising fraternity'' who specialize in attack
ads.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Pat Robertson 4th in Poll of Evangelicals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former television evangelist Pat Robertson
finished fourth among Republican presidential candidates in a
preference poll of board members at the National Association of
Evangelicals' annual convention.
   Vice President George Bush received 40 percent of the vote
Wednesday. Kansas Sen. Robert Dole received 32 percent, New York
Rep. Jack Kemp 17 percent and Robertson 12 percent.
   The results ``confounded conventional wisdom that he would be
the near-unanimous choice of evangelical leaders,'' said Richard
Cizik, research director for the NAE in Washington.
   Among Democrats, Missouri Rep. Richard Gephardt was supported by
37 percent of the board members. Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore
received 33 percent of the vote, Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis
16 percent, Illinois Sen. Paul Simon 11 percent and the Rev. Jesse
Jackson 5 percent.
   Wednesday's voting, conducted without discussion, was by
denominational presidents, organizational executives and lay
leaders from across the country.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
