<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0599</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Strong, Gusty Winds in Southwest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   High winds howled through sections of the West today after gusts
up to 70 mph felled trees and damaged cars in southern Nevada as
snow moved into parts of the Rockies and rain continued falling in
the Southeast.
   A tree knocked down by wind late Wednesday injured one person in
the Las Vegas, Nev., area and did major damage to a trailer and
some parked cars. The winds also caused numerous power outages.
   In southwest Utah, the wind reached 58 mph in St. George and a
brief, heavy snow hit the area Wednesday night. Two inches fell in
Cedar City between 8 p.m. and 10 p.m.
   Light snow fell in other parts of Utah and in western Wyoming.
Two inches fell in West Yellowstone, Mont., in six hours overnight.
   Winds gusting to 50 mph were recorded in California's Tehachapi
Mountains near Bakersfield and in foothill communities along the
north side of the San Fernando Valley.
   A high wind warning or wind advisories were in effect today in
Southern California and southern Nevada.
   A heavy snow warning was issued for the Colorado mountains,
where a foot or more was expected. Advisories for snow or blowing
snow were up in western Colorado and the mountains of Utah and
southwest Wyoming.
   Winter storm watches were in effect through tonight for
northeast Colorado, eastern Wyoming and western sections of South
Dakota and Nebraska, and were expected to be issued tonight in
central parts of South Dakota and Nebraska.
   Scattered light rain extended from the Mid-Atlantic States to
New England, with some wet snow in northern Maine. Light rain fell
in parts of Tennessee, Kentucky and West Virginia.
   Vermont experienced its first snow melt problems of the season
Wednesday night, when water ran over roads in two parts of Westford
due to frozen culverts and rising streams.
   Today's forecast called for snow from northern Arizona and Utah
to the northern and central Rockies and the northern High Plains;
scattered rain and snow in eastern sections of the Dakotas and
parts of Minnesota; a few flurries over northern Maine; rain
showers from the Mid-Atlantic States to the Carolinas and Georgia
and thundershowers in southern Florida.
   High temperatures were expected to be in the 30s and 40s from
New England across the Great Lakes and the northern Plains to the
Rockies; 70s or lower 80s in southern Florida and the southern
Plains; 70s through the desert Southwest and Southern California
and the 50s or 60s in the rest of the nation.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 18
degrees at Marquette, Mich., to 77 degrees at Key West Naval Air
Station, Fla.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 47 partly cloudy; Boston 47 cloudy; Buffalo 30
partly cloudy; Charleston, S.C. 62 rain; Cincinnati 35 cloudy;
Cleveland 33 cloudy; Detroit 33 cloudy; Miami 74 fair; New York 49
cloudy; Philadelphia 50 cloudy; Pittsburgh 33 drizzle; Portland,
Maine 37 foggy; Washington 52 cloudy.
   _Central: Bismarck 40 cloudy; Chicago 29 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth
43 fair; Denver 40 fair; Des Moines 30 fair; Indianapolis 33
cloudy; Kansas City 35 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 33 cloudy;
Nashville 40 drizzle; New Orleans 50 fair; St. Louis 38 cloudy.
   _West: Albuquerque 38 fair; Anchorage 34 snow; Las Vegas 48
fair; Los Angeles 58 fair; Phoenix 64 fair; Salt Lake City 32
cloudy; San Diego 55 partly cloudy; San Francisco 47 fair; Seattle
36 partly cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal 32 cloudy; Toronto 28 fair.
</TEXT>
