<HEAD>Quotes From Presidential Candidates</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are some comments Wednesday from
candidates for the presidency;
   
   JACK KEMP, who is expected to announce today his withdrawal from
the GOP race: ``There were rumors we would withdraw after Iowa. But
I'm not a quitter. I'm an ex-quarterback, and I don't enter a
contest lightly.''
   
   BOB DOLE, on the importance of next Tuesday's Illinois primary
to the viability of his campaign after his total defeat in the
Super Tuesday Republican primaries and caucuses: ``I've got to win
in Illinois. I feel like I've just taken the finals, and I didn't
flunk but I didn't do too well either.''
   
   GEORGE BUSH, in a telegram to Dole after Super Tuesday's
primaries and caucuses gave him two-thirds of the delegates
necessary to win the GOP nomination: ``I believe it is now time to
look ahead to the issues which distinguish us from the Democrats.''
   
   PAUL SIMON, on why his cash-poor campaign would not run
television advertisements before next week's Illinois primary: ``I
offer Illinois 30 years of service rather than a 30-second
commercial.''
   
   JESSE JACKSON, who captured five states and the most popular
votes in the Super Tuesday Democratic primaries and caucuses: ``We
get stronger every day.''
   
   ALBERT GORE, on his electability: ``I'm not going to say that
any of our candidates are unelectable. But I have the best chance.''
   
   MICHAEL DUKAKIS, on Gore as his primary rival: ``I'm not so sure
he's a major contender. A guy from Massachusetts beat him in Texas,
beat him in Florida.''
   
   PAT ROBERTSON, who had said he would win the South but won only
the Washington state caucuses in the 20-state Super Tuesday
contests: ``It isn't over yet.''
</TEXT>
