<1ST_LINE>u i PM-India-Tibet     03-10 0376</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-India-Tibet,0388</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tibetans Clash With Police, 16 Injured</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DILIP GANGULY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Wtiter</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police clashed today with 200 Tibetan
refugees who tried to march to the Chinese Embassy in New Delhi,
and seven Tibetans and nine policemen were injured, authorities
said.
   The refugees gathered near the Parliament House and chanted
``China, stop killing Tibetans'' in a rally commemorating the 29th
anniversary of the abortive uprising against Chinese rule in Lhasa,
Tibet's capital.
   Police intervened when the crowd surged toward a police
barricade to attempt a march to the Chinese Embassy.
   ``We were not only stopped, but badly beaten,'' said Tashi
Namgyal, secretary-general of the Tibetan Youth Congress. ``The
policemen poked bamboo sticks and hit us on our heads.''
   It was on March 10, 1959, that Tibetans rose in revolt against
the Chinese Red Army that invaded Tibet in 1949. China claims the
region was part of China since the 13th century. Tibetans dispute
that claim.
   After the uprising, the Dalai Lama, spiritual and temporal
leader of the Tibetans, and 100,000 of his followers fled to India.
The Tibetan god-king has since maintained exile headquarters in
Dharmasala in northern India.
   In a statement issued today from Dharamsala, the Dalai Lama
called on Tibetans to ``honor the courage of our brethren in Tibet
who have taken to the streets to draw attention to their suffering
under Chinese colonial rule.''
   ``It is indeed a sad reflection of the state of the world that
violence seems to be required for the international community to
pay attention.''
   He was referring to a clash in Lhasa last Saturday which left as
many as five Tibetans and three police dead.
   The rally site in New Delhi was strewn with stones, shoes,
sandals and sticks after the clash with police. The Chinese Embassy
in the nearby diplomatic district was cordoned off.
   Police accused the Tibetans of starting trouble.
   ``For no reason the Tibetans became violent and started hurling
rocks at us,'' said police officer Shanti Kumar Jain. ``We had to
stop them.''
   It was the second rally by Tibetans in New Delhi this week. On
Monday, hundreds of Tibetans held a demonstration and chanted ``We
shall overcome.'' They were prevented Monday from marching on the
Chinese Embassy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
