<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ArmsTreaty 1stLd-Writethru a0514 03-10 0308</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Arms Treaty, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0514,280</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 2nd graf to take out extraneous material; ADDS headline.</NOTE>
<HEAD>Arms Agency Reports US Could Verify Soviet INF Compliance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Without knowing the exact size of the Soviet
arsenal, the U.S. intelligence community could effectively verify
Soviet compliance with the Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces
treaty, according to a classified report by the Arms Control and
Disarmament Agency.
   The Washington Post reported today that the ACDA study, which
was sent Tuesday to members of the Senate Foreign Relations
Committee said, the pact's ``verification measures posed
significant risks for the Soviets of U.S. detection'' even though
``U.S. intelligence cannot achieve a total count'' of Soviet
medium-range and shorter-range nuclear-armed missiles and lauchers
that are to be eliminated under the agreement.
   The Post said the ACDA report seemed to answer criticisms by
Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., and others who maintain that Soviet
compliance with the INF treaty cannot be verified because the U.S.
intelligence community is uncertain about how many SS20
medium-range missiles the Soviets have.
   The report also said that U.S. officials have assumed ``Soviet
declarations for total numbers, locations, and characteristics of
their treaty-limited items could be false'' so they would not be
used to verify Soviet compliance.
   The Soviets said last year they planned to destroy 650 deployed
or stored SS20s but analysts at the Defense Intelligence Agency, an
arm of the Defense Department, have said the Soviets have at least
165 additional SS20s. Helms said this was an indication the Soviets
may have hidden some of the missiles for potential use against U.S.
European alllies.
   The report acknowledge that Soviet retentions of some missiles
couldn't be ruled out but noted that the United States would
scrutinize the destruction of ``all launch-critical equipment'' and
that all test flights would be barred six months after the treaty
takes affect.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880310-0068 </DOCNO>
