<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Stronger, Gold Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar steadied at higher levels against
nearly all major currencies in light European trading early today.
Gold bullion prices were higher.
   Dealers said the dollar was mostly higher on a technical rebound
and they expected it to remain stable through the day.
   The British pound, which surged earlier this week, eased amid
fears of profit-taking and more pound sales by the Bank of England
to stop sterling rising too sharply.
   In Tokyo, the dollar closed at 128.20 Japanese yen, up from
128.08 at Wednesday's close. Later, in London, the dollar traded at
128.05 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Wednesday:
   _1.6708 West German marks, up from 1.6685
   _1.3805 Swiss francs, up from 1.3785
   _5.6622 French francs, up from 5.6485
   _1.8764 Dutch guilders, up from 1.8750
   _1,234.75 Italian lire, up from 1,231.50
   _1.2585 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2532
   In London, the pound fell to $1.8420 from $1.8460 late Wednesday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $436 a troy ounce, down
from $436.50 late Wednesday, but rose in later trading. At
midmorning today, the city's five major bullion dealers set a
recommended price of $437.25.
   In Zurich, the noon bid gold price was $437.20, up from $437
late Wednesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold closed at $438.42 bid, up from
Wednesday's $438.01.
   Silver was quoted in London at $6.33 bid an ounce, up from $6.31
late Wednesday.
