<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WritersStrike     03-10 0309</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Writers Strike,0319</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Bargaining Session Begins</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Talks scheduled to resume at 2 p.m. EST</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Striking scriptwriters agreed to resume
negotiations today with both sides under a gag order not to
disclose details of the talks, while producers of the Oscar
ceremonies vowed the show must go on.
   The Writers Guild of America went on strike Sunday after
rejecting the latest offer by the Alliance of Motion Picture and
Television Producers. The dispute centered on artistic control of
scripts and money received from reruns.
   Commissioner Leonard Farrell of the Federal Mediation and
Conciliation Service imposed a gag order on negotiators for both
sides Tuesday, blocking any disclosures about the bargaining.
   ``It's a mediation session and that's all I can say,'' guild
spokeswoman Cheryl Rhoden said after the gag order was imposed.
   ``It's not an unusual situation in a strike,'' she said. ``It's
important that those topics on the table be kept there, rather than
be aired in the media.''
   Writers working on the Academy Awards show slated for April 11
said they left its script half written when they walked out. But
producer Samuel Goldwyn Jr. said: ``The show must go on, and it
will.''
   The academy was denied a guild waiver to let writers finish the
show.
   About 125 East Coast scriptwriters picketed outside the MGM
building in New York City on Wednesday. It was the first protest by
the eastern arm of the guild.
   In the Manhattan protest, three writers of ``Late Night with
David Letterman,'' wearing jackets bearing the show's logo, walked
the picket line.
   William Peter Blatty, who wrote ``The Exorcist,'' joined
pickets, as did Screen Actors Guild member Barbara Feldon of ``Get
Smart'' fame.
   ``The union is only as strong as its ability to strike,'' said
marcher John Patrick Shanley, a best original screenplay Oscar
nominee for ``Moonstruck.''
</TEXT>
