<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NorthwestAirline     03-10 0429</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Northwest Airline,0441</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Northwest Says It Will Impose Contract With Flight Attendants</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA WILKINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EAGAN, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Northwest Airline's decision to impose a
contract on its 6,700 flight attendants has put the airline and the
union on a ``collision course,'' says a Teamsters official.
   The contract that the airline said it will impose April 1 is
substantially the same as the proposal that negotiators fashioned
in talks before the Feb. 26 strike deadline passed, Northwest said
Wednesday.
   ``We're not asking them to accept this. They've already rejected
it. We're putting it into place,'' said Terry Erskine, the
airline's vice president of law and labor relations.
   Erskine said the airline has not talked with the union about its
plan to impose the contract, but he said if attendants decide to
strike, the airline is prepared to hire permanent replacements.
   ``They're on a collision course, and everybody's going to get
hurt,'' William Genoese, director of the Teamsters airline division
and the flight attendants' chief negotiator, told WCCO-TV Wednesday.
   When asked what the chances of a strike next week are, Genoese
said: ``I would say they're pretty close to 100 percent. I would
say unless somebody gets the people to the bargaining table ... the
company's the one that's going to hurt itself.''
   Teamsters have called a strategy meeting Monday in Washington,
D.C., for local union officers and strike captains at Northwest, he
said.
   The main obstacle to reaching a settlement between the airline
and the flight attendants has been disagreement over how to raise
lower-paid B-scale attendants to higher paid A-scale wages.
   Northwest has proposed extending the B-scale from five years to
eight years, meaning lower-wage flight attendants would have to
wait an additional three years before earning top-scale wages,
Erskine said.
   B-scale flight attendants have said the airline is trying to
break a promise that they would earn A-scale wages after five years.
   The union also has objected to two-tier wage agreements, saying
they pit junior workers against senior workers.
   The issue has intensified since Northwest acquired Republic
Airlines in 1986. Roughly one-third of the 2,600 former Republic
attendants work for B-scale wages and the other two-thirds have
said they wouldn't get enough out of Northwest's latest wage offer.
   Under the contract proposal that will be implemented, the
entry-level wage will go from more than $13,000 a year to $15,000 a
year, and the top base wage will go from the current $32,000 up to
$35,000 a year, Erskine said.
   ``Our door, of course, will always be open for further
collective bargaining,'' Erskine said.
</TEXT>
