<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Cambodia-Guerrillas     03-10 0225</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cambodia-Guerrillas,0233</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cambodian Guerrilla Leaders Dismissed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four Cambodian guerrilla leaders
accused of human rights abuses have been dismissed from their
military posts, a spokesman for the resistance group said today.
   Son Sann, president of the Khmer People's National Liberation
Front, ordered the dismissals of Chea Chhut, Liv Ne, Gen. Dien Del
and Gen. Hing Kunthon in early February, said the spokesman, who
spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The front is one of three major resistance groups fighting
Vietnamese forces in Cambodia. It operates from bases along the
Thai-Cambodian border.
   ``We want to let the people investigate the alleged human rights
abuses, what was done,'' he said in a telephone interview.
   ``Another reason (for the dismissals) is we want to reorganize
and clear up the climate at the border,'' he said. The spokesman
did not specify the alleged abuses.
   In recent years, international aid workers and organizations
like the U.S. Lawyers Committee for Human Rights have accused some
Khmer People's National Liberation Front commanders of dispensing
justice arbitrarily and allowing abuses against Cambodian civilians
and local Thais.
   Some front soldiers also have been arrested by the Thais for
banditry.
   The four officials have been moved to inactive posts and were
replaced by their assistants, the spokesman said. Asked about their
whereabouts, the spokesman said: ``They are surely not at the
border.''
</TEXT>
