<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-88 0811EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CrashHearing     03-10 0479</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Crash Hearing,0492</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vortex Unlikely As Crash Cause, Witnesses Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBBIE NEWBY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GOLDEN, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Experts testifying about possible causes of
a Continental airliner crash did not rule out disturbance from a
plane landing on an adjacent runway, but said winds could have
swept away any such effect.
   ``Turbulent winds lead to the early demise of vortex,'' said
James Hallock, who has studied the air currents caused by plane
landings for the Department of Transportation.
   Hallock testified Wednesday during the second day of a National
Transportation Safety Board hearing into the Nov. 15 crash of
Continental Flight 1713, which killed 28 people and injured 54 at
Denver's Stapleton International Airport.
   George Greene of the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration's Langley Research Center, who also has studied
vortex, agreed that winds generally diminish the effect of such
turbulence.
   Federal Aviation Administration officials tried to elicit from
Greene a definite statement on whether vortex caused the Stapleton
crash. But NTSB board member Joseph T. Nall, chairman of the
inquiry, would not allow him to answer.
   Nall said conclusions about what caused the crash must be made
by the NTSB when it completes its investigation. A final report is
not expected until later this year.
   Continental spokesman Bruce Hicks said the witnesses' testimony
did not mean vortex should be ruled out as a possible cause.
``Nobody shot down anything today,'' he said.
   Earlier Wednesday, an airplane engineer testified that enough
snow fell during the 24 minutes that Continental 1713 awaited
takeoff for ice buildup on the wings to have been a possible factor
in the crash.
   Continental officials said they believe wing icing can be ruled
out as a factor because the plane exceeded the speed at which it
likely would have stalled from ice.
   Ralph Brumby, manager of aerodynamics and acoustics for
McDonnell Douglas Corp., which manufactured the DC-9, said 0.032
inches of precipitation, or about one-third of an inch of snow,
fell in the 24 minutes between de-icing and takeoff.
   If all that snow turned to ice on the wings, the DC-9 could have
stalled after takeoff, Brumby said. Ice can change the shape of a
wing, affecting lift.
   Brumby, under questioning by Continental officials, said that
the amount of precipitation that fell between the time the plane
was de-iced and takeoff was enough to cause the plane to stall at
about 150 knots, or a little more than 170 mph.
   But he said it was impossible to draw a definite conclusion that
ice on the wing was a factor based on the theory that all the snow
had turned to ice.
   ``There are so many open parameters,'' he said. ``We don't know
the amount of roughness generated by the water collection.''
   He also said officials do not know how long the de-icing fluid
was able to prevent buildup before the plane took off.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880310-0075 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-88 0812EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-India-Punjab     03-10 0379</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-India-Punjab,0393</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government's Conciliatory Efforts Fail To Stem Sikh Violence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least 19 people were reported killed
in Punjab state today and Wednesday despite government efforts to
give militant Sikhs a freer hand in trying to resolve the region's
problems.
   Sikh gunmen killed three Sikh policemen standing guard outside a
high school where examinations were under way today in the village
of Dari Wala, Amritsar district police chief Mohammed Izhar Alam
said.
   He said the four gunmen, who used Chinese-made AK-47 assault
rifles, arrived and fled on a tractor.
   Two people were killed in the village of Mehsampura early today
when Sikh gunmen sprayed the sleeping village with gunfire, the
United News of India reported. The identity of the victims was not
immediately available.
   Dari Wala and Mehsampura are near the town of Mehta, about 25
miles east of Amritsar.
   On Wednesday, seven people were killed by Sikh extremists in the
Amritsar district. Seven other deaths were reported in the state,
including police slayings of two suspected extremists in shootouts.
   The deaths came as militant Sikhs on Wednesday installed Jasbir
Singh Rode as chief priest at the Golden Temple in Amritsar,
Sikhism's holiest shrine.
   On Friday, the government released Rode, who had been held since
1985 on accusations of sedition but never tried. On Sunday, the
government said it was dissolving the Punjab state assembly, which
had been controlled by a moderate Sikh party.
   Both moves were seen as an effort by Prime Minister Rajiv
Gandhi's administration to try to involve militant leaders in
bringing an end to the increasing violence in Punjab state.
   The latest killings raised to at least 417 the number of people
killed in attacks blamed on Sikh extremists since the start of the
year.
   Last year, more than 1,000 people died in Sikh attacks in the
state.
   Most of the victims have been Hindus or moderate Sikhs.
   Sikhs, whose religion was founded about 500 years ago as an
alternative to Hinduism and Islam, claim they are discriminated
against by India's majority Hindus. Sikhs make up less than 2
percent of India's population, but are a majority in Punjab. Hindus
are more than 80 percent.
   Sikh extremists have been agitating for more political autonomy
or an independent state since 1982.
</TEXT>
