<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Obit-Franceschi     03-10 0209</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Franceschi,0214</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Security Minister Dies At 64</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joseph Franceschi, a Socialist deputy in the
National Assembly and former secretary of state for public
security, died today after a long illness, the Socialist Federation
announced. He was 64.
   Franceschi, a close friend of President Francois Mitterrand,
died about 7 a.m. at his home in Alfortville southeast of Paris. He
had been hospitalized for the past month. The federation said he
died after a ``long and cruel illness,'' without adding further
details.
   Franceschi held three Cabinet posts under Mitterrand.
   The first was as secretary of state for the elderly. In August
1982, he was named secretary of state for public security. After
two years, he returned to the post of secretary of state for
retired persons and the elderly, which he held until the Socialists
lost power in March 1986.
   Franceschi was born Jan. 15, 1924 in Tunis, Tunisia and had a
degree in letters and a doctorate in political science. He became
mayor of Alfortville in 1965 and was elected a deputy in the
National Assembly on the Socialist ticket in 1973, serving as a
vice president of the Assembly in 1977-78.
   The funeral was scheduled for Saturday at the Notre Dame church
in Alfortville.
</TEXT>
