<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Malaysia-Detainee     03-10 0338</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Malaysia-Detainee,0350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opposition Leader Arrested Again After Release</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARI S. MANIAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A political opposition leader who
was ordered freed after four months in prison was arrested again as
he was headed home, his wife and police said today.
   Karpal Singh was released Wednesday after a court ruled that one
of the charges used in his original arrest was erroneous. Singh is
vice president of the opposition Democratic Action Party and a
member of Parliament.
   The party condemned the rearrest ``in the strongest terms
possible.''
   A statement issued by party Deputy Secretary General Lee Lam
Thye said the action shows the disregard the executive arm of the
government has for the judiciary.
   Karpal and his wife, Gurmit Kaur, were traveling home from Ipoh
after his release when police stopped their car at a roadblock and
arrested Karpal, Kaur said.
   She said they were stopped near Nibong Tebal, a village near
Karpal's hometown of Penang. Penang is 180 miles northwest of Kuala
Lumpur.
   ``Later at the Penang police station I was told that he was
being detained under the Internal Security Act,'' Kaur said in a
telephone interview.
   A police spokesman at the Federal Police Headquarters today
confirmed the arrest.
   Karpal originally was arrested under the Internal Security Act
on Oct. 27, together with the leader of the opposition in
Parliament, Lim Kit Siang, and others. The act allows imprisonment
without trial.
   The National News Agency Bernama said the regional High Court in
Ipoh, 120 miles north of Kuala Lumpur, found earlier Wednesday that
the detention order was made without care, caution and a proper
sense of responsibility.
   Karpal was one of 119 people detained under the Internal
Security Act between October and December, government officials
said. The act allows imprisonment without trial.
   Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad has said the arrests were
necessary to prevent Malay-Chinese racial clashes.
   On Tuesday, Deputy Home Affairs Minister Megat Junid Megat Ayub
told Parliament that 86 people were still being held under the act.
</TEXT>
