<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Meese-Pipeline 1stLd-Writethru a0502 03-10 0669</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Meese-Pipeline, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0502,620</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDs: TOPS with 11 grafs new material; picks up 2nd graf, McKay
and; REMOVES last two grafs pvs.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The author of a letter from Democrats on the
House Judiciary Committee calling for the temporary resignation of
Attorney General Edwin Meese III said today there is ``considerable
sentiment'' for even harsher action against Meese.
   A Republican on the committee, however, called the letter ``an
outrageous political move,'' and a Meese spokesman said the
attorney general would not comply.
   Meanwhile, Swiss oilman Bruce Rappaport has testified under oath
before independent counsel James McKay in the criminal
investigation involving Meese and a proposed $1 billion Iraqi
pipeline project, according to sources familiar with the probe.
   Eleven Democrats on the Judiciary Committee called Wednesday for
Meese to step down until that and other independent counsel
investigations into Meese's conduct are completed.
   Rep. Edward Feighan of Ohio, who was introduced as the letter's
author on ``CBS This Morning'', said the committee members did not
specifically consider impeachment of Meese, but ``there was
considerable sentiment for even harsher action than the letter we
sent.'' He did not say what other steps might be taken.
   Feighan said that although no Republicans on the committee
signed the letter, Meese had become a ``major embarrassment'' to
his party. He also said morale was low in the Justice Department
which Meese heads.
   Rep. William McCollum, R-Fla., also interviewed on CBS, noted
that Meese has been cleared every time he has been investigated.
   ``This is an outrageous political move on the part of some
Democrats in a political year,'' he said. McCollum denied that
morale was low in the Justice Department.
   ``The pervasive perception that you have allowed personal
considerations to encroach on your constitutional responsibilities
threatens to breed contempt for your office, your administration
and the rule of law itself,'' the letter said.
   Justice Department spokesman Terry Eastland said the letter
proposed ``a politically partisan idea and a thoroughly bad idea.''
   He said Meese ``has every intention of serving to the end of
this term. He has spent some time with his lawyers on the
investigation, but there has been no serious subtraction of his
time or effort from leadership of the Department of Justice.''
   McKay and his deputy, Carole Bruce, took the statements from
Rappaport in London on Tuesday, said the sources, speaking on
condition of anonymity. McKay has granted immunity from prosecution
to Rappaport.
   Meese's former chief of staff, John Richardson, who left the
Justice Department several months ago, also testified separately
Tuesday afternoon before the federal grand jury in Washington which
is receiving evidence from McKay's office.
   Richardson, who has joined a Richmond, Va., law firm, declined
on Wednesday to discuss his testimony.
   The independent counsel is investigating whether Meese may have
violated the Foreign Corrupt Practices Act which prohibits paying
bribes to foreign officials by U.S. companies and authorizes the
attorney general to intervene to block them.
   The investigation stems from a 1985 memo to the attorney general
from his longtime friend, E. Robert Wallach, who had been hired as
legal counsel by Rappaport to help secure U.S. support on the
pipeline project.
   Wallach's memo says that payments were planned to the Israeli
Labor Party in connection with the pipeline. Rappaport, a partner
in the proposed pipeline, has denied that any such payments to the
Labor Party were contemplated.
   Meese has said he doesn't recall reading the portion of the memo
mentioning planned payments to the Labor Party.
   Rappaport was brought into the project because of his close ties
to then-Israeli Prime Minister Shimon Peres to aid in getting
assurances for the Iraqi government that Israel would not attack
the pipeline.
   The pipeline was never built but was to have been constructed by
the San Francisco-based Bechtel Group Inc.
   McKay's investigation of Meese which began last May 11, has
delved into Meese's involvement with scandal-plagued Wedtech Corp.
and the regional Bell telephone companies as well as with the
pipeline project.
</TEXT>
