<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-Lemmon     03-10 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Lemmon,0278</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jack Lemmon Credits Luck and Fear For Much of His Success</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jack Lemmon, who will be honored
tonight by the American Film Institute with a Life Achievement
Award, says luck helped him win good parts and fear helped bring
out his best performances.
   Lemmon, 63, landed starring roles in his debut appearances on
stage, in film, and on television.
   ``There's a tremendous boost in playing a lead, especially in a
first job,'' Lemmon said, ``because slips of confidence are built
into an actor's life. You go from thinking you will never work
again to thinking you're the greatest young actor in America.''
   After graduating from Harvard College, Lemmon started in
television in ``The Arrival of Kitty.'' From there, his lead role
in a Broadway revival of ``Room Service'' led to his starring
performance in the film ``It Should Happen To You.'' He was only 29.
   Lemmon, talking in his Beverly Hills office this week as he
prepared his acceptance speech for the AFI award, said a successful
acting career depends on making the most of every opportunity.
   ``The very reason we are sitting here talking is that I was able
to deliver,'' the two-time Oscar winner said. ``But first the doors
had to open. I had to get the part.''
   After the luck of the draw decides casting, fear takes over,
Lemmon said.
   ``I think you do better work if you're afraid,'' he said.
   Lemmon won Academy Awards in 1955 and 1973. He was honored first
for Best Supporting Actor in ``Mister Roberts,'' then received a
Best Actor Oscar for ``Save the Tiger.''
</TEXT>
