<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AlcatrazCasino     03-10 0384</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Alcatraz Casino,0393</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Alcatraz Casino Plan Put on San Francisco Ballot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A measure designed to put a gambling casino
on Alcatraz Island, once the site of a federal prison that housed
some of the nation's most notorious criminals, has been approved
for the city ballot.
   ``I'd never turn my back on something that would bring money to
the city legally,'' said Supervisor Wendy Nelder, one of six city
supervisors who voted Wednesday to put the advisory measure on the
June 7 ballot.
   The measure asks whether the city should encourage changes in
state and federal law to allow a gambling resort on Alcatraz, for
29 years a prison for for 1,576 criminals who included Al Capone
and George ``Machine Gun'' Kelly.
   The prison that was dubbed ``The Rock'' was closed in 1963 when
Attorney General Robert Kennedy called the facility inhumane.
   It isn't the first time a casino has been suggested for the
island.
   In 1969, more than 300 recommendations were submitted to Mayor
Joseph Alioto about the future of the island in San Francisco Bay.
   Suggestions included a casino, a home for hippies and a site for
a replica of the Eiffel Tower. Alioto favored a giant monument
symbolizing ``Justice'' on the outcropping a mile off Fisherman's
Wharf that would be a West Coast counterpart to the Statue of
Liberty in the New York harbor.
   The latest casino plan stemmed from a luncheon meeting Tuesday
of labor leaders, city supervisors and Warren Hinckle, a San
Francisco Examiner columnist who made an unsuccesful bid for mayor.
   The casino complex could bring in at least $150 million a year
to help San Francisco solve a projected budget deficit, said
Hinckle, whose plan would include a tunnel under the bay to the
casinos.
   The state constitution would need to be changed by voters to
exempt the island from state laws that forbid gambling, Hinckle
said.
   The federal government would also have to be petitioned to
remove Alcatraz from the Golden Gate Recreation Area, which covers
vast stretches of federal open space on both sides of the Golden
Gate Bridge. Federal officials would then have to sell the island
to San Francisco.
   Hundreds of tourists visit Alcatraz each year for a guided tour
of the island that is conducted by park rangers.
</TEXT>
