<2ND_LINE>PM-Couple Charged,0317</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Foster Parents Charged in Death of Boy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man with a criminal record that would have
barred him as a foster parent and his wife were ordered held
without bail today on charges of shaking their 2-year-old foster
son to death, authorities said.
   Walter ``Sonny'' Hairston, 26, and his wife, Maryanne, 33, were
arraigned early this morning on charges of murder and involuntary
manslaughter in connection with the death of Joey Huot, said bail
commissioner Garnita Selby.
   Hairston also was charged with providing false background
information on foster placement applications, Ms. Selby said.
   Hairston pleaded guilty in 1981 to charges of rape, aggravated
assault and burglary in Washington County, but social workers did
not know of his record when Joey was placed with the couple,
authorities said.
   The boy was placed in the couple's home by Catholic Social
Services under a contract with Philadelphia's Department of Human
Services.
   Since January 1987, 18 children who had been under the care of
the city department have died of suspected abuse or neglect.
   The alleged falsifications on Hairston's foster-parent
applications prevented caseworkers from identifying him as a former
criminal, a source in the state's child welfare system told The
Philadelphia Inquirer. The source said Catholic Social Services had
checked with state police and the state's registry of reported
child abusers, as required, but Hairston was cleared.
   Catholic Social Services spokeswoman Ursula O'Reilly declined to
comment on the agency's background checks because of the legal
proceedings.
   Joey died on Jan. 27 at The Children's Hospital of Philadelphia
after he was declared brain-dead and his mother gave doctors
permission to take him off a respirator.
   The Hairstons were arrested at their home Wednesday morning,
police said.
   Police said the Hairstons told them Joey was injured when he
fell from a couch during an apparent epileptic seizure.
</TEXT>
