<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Iran-Iraq 3rdLd-Writethru a0556 03-10 0690</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-Iraq, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0556,0710</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraq Offers to End Missile Duel After Firing 50th Into Tehran</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with statement from Hussein
offering to end missile duel. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq fired its 50th long-range missile
into Tehran today and then Iraqi President Saddam Hussein offered
to halt the deadly missile duel if Iran did the same.
   But he warned in a Baghdad Radio broadcast, monitored in
Nicosia, that Iraq will go on pounding Iranian cities with missiles
if Iran continues to hit population centers, launch ground
offensives or attack ``any Arab city.''
   Iran said some civilians were killed in the latest attacks. Iraq
fired two long-range missiles into the Iranian capital, raising to
50 the number it claims to have shot into Tehran in 11 days.
   Iran claims to have fired 25 missiles into Baghdad and other
Iraqi cities in the same period.
   The latest Iraqi bombardment was in retaliation for an overnight
Iranian artillery attack on the southern Iraqi cities of Basra and
Qurna, Baghdad's official Iraqi News Agency reported.
   The agency, monitored in Nicosia, said ``a number of civilians''
were killed in Basra and Qurna, which is 40 miles north of Basra.
   Hussein's statement, read by an unidentified military spokesman,
followed a joint meeting in Baghdad of the ruling Revolutionary
Command Council and the regional command of the Arab Baath
Socialist Party, at which Saddam presided.
   It said the Iraqi bombardment of Tehran and other Iranian cities
would halt at 4 p.m. Friday if the Iranians stop firing.
   The statement charged that Tehran triggered the latest flare-up
in the ``war of the cities'' by hitting Baghdad with two missiles
Feb.29.
   ``So the last bombardment should be Iraq's before the cease-fire
goes into effect,'' the statement said.
   There was no immediate response from Tehran, which has appealed
to the United Nations and other world bodies to force Iraq to halt
the bombardment.
   Hundreds of civilians on both sides have been killed or wounded
in the missile duel, the first time Tehran has been hit by
long-range surface-to-surface weapons since the Iran-Iraq war broke
out in September 1980.
   ``If the enemy Iranian regime attacks any of our cities with
missiles, warplanes or artillery in retaliation for the last Iraqi
bombardment, we will continue attacking and teach the rulers of
Tehran the appropriate lessons,'' the Iraqi statement said.
   It said that if the Iranians launched any new ground assaults,
``we shall retaliate ... by attacking all Iranian cities ... with
all means.''
   The Iraqis have been braced for weeks for a major Iranian
offensive in the southern sector of the battlefront, where Tehran
has been massing troops.
   The Iranians have also been attacking in the mountainous
northern sector for several weeks.
   The Iraqi statement called on the U.N. Security Council to
impose sanctions, including an arms embargo, on Iran for failing to
comply with the council's July 20 cease-fire resolution.
   Earlier, Tehran Radio reported that Iraqi warplanes bombed the
central city of Isfahan, former capital of ancient Persia, hitting
a mosque and a school and killing or wounding some children.
   The radio reported other air raids on Hamadan, Arak, Dezful,
Shustar, Shahr-e Kord and Burujerd in western Iran. It claimed one
Iraqi jet was shot down by anti-aircraft fire over Arak. Baghdad
denied losing any planes.
   The official Islamic Republic News Agency said the Iraqi
missiles hit residential areas of Tehran. It said a number of
civilians were killed or wounded, but it gave no figures.
   IRNA also said Iranian fighter-bombers attacked Iraqi military
positions and economic targets in Basra and Al-Amarah, further
north, in three raids today. It said Iran inficted ``heavy
casualties and damage.''
   Iranian authorities say at least 157 civilians have been killed
and more than 420 wounded in missile attacks on Tehran alone in the
past 11 days.
   Iraq has not given any casualty figures.
   In Basra, women vowed to have more babies to help their
country's war effort, the Iraqi News Agency said. It said the women
promised Hussein to ``increase reproduction'' in response to his
call for bigger families last November.
</TEXT>
