<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SouthAfrica     03-10 0505</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Africa,0517</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Leader of Police Unit Says He was Drunk At Time Of Killings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A police squad leader accused
by fellow officers of ordering the execution of a black youth
testified that he was drunk at the time and had assaulted the
victim.
   Warrant Officer Leon De Villers, 36, concluded his testimony
Wednesday after six days on the stand during a trial that began in
October.
   The trial is unusual because it focuses on testimony by
policemen against their fellow officers. Five members of the
all-white, 10-member unit have alleged that De Villiers and his
codefendant, Constable David Goosen, were responsible for the
execution and a fatal stabbing that occurred a few hours earlier.
De Villiers and Goosen are charged with murder in both deaths.
   According to the five officers, Goosen stabbed one black man,
Andile Plaatjie, 45, during an unauthorized foot patrol and later
shot 18-year-old Mlungisi Stuurman in the head after being told by
De Villiers that the badly beaten youth should be ``taken out.''
   De Villiers and Goosen contended that Stuurman was shot
accidentally after being taken to a riverside to wash off blood
from injuries inflicted when officers assaulted him.
   De Villiers testified that he had drunk most of a bottle of
brandy shortly before his unit's two forays into the black section
of the Cape Province town of Cradock in July 26, 1986. Other
members of the unit also drank heavily, according to testimony, and
engaged in a blood-oath ceremony in which they swore to keep
secrets.
   De Villiers said he was too drunk to accompany his men during
the predawn foot patrol, when the stabbing allegedly occurred.
   During the second foray, De Villiers said, he lost his temper
because Stuurman refused to answer questions, hit the youth and
then stood by as other members of the unit beat and kicked him.
   De Villiers said he decided not to report the subsequent
shooting of Stuurman because he was ``shocked'' and under the
influence of alcohol.
   He said he could not explain why, if the shooting was
accidental, five members of the unit alleged it was deliberate.
   In separate developments:
   _ The New Nation, a black-oriented weekly newspaper, reported
Thursday that a black activist was abducted from his home near
Johannesburg by eight white soldiers last month, taken to a
cemetery, and interrogated while lying on a grave with a gun
pressed to his neck. Police and military spokesmen said the
allegation was under investigation.
   _ A Johannesburg police sergeant on trial for murder testified
Wednesday that he was ordered by his co-defendant, a police
captain, to kill three men last year. Two of the men were shot dead
and one was injured.
   Sgt. Robert van der Merwe said he carried out the assignment
after Capt. Jack la Grange told him the three targets were working
for the outlawed African National Congress guerrilla movement.
Testimony in the trial has indicated the murders were related to
drug smuggling and had no connection to the ANC.
</TEXT>
