<1ST_LINE>r w PM-DeafSchoolPresident 1stLd-Writethru a0467 03-10 0651</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Deaf School President, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0467,610</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: New material, editing thruout</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gallaudet University's new president, told by
an influential congressman she may have no choice but to step down,
said today she will meet with instructors and students who oppose
her appointment as the head of the nation's only university for the
deaf.
   The congressman, Rep. David Bonior, D-Mich., said he told Dr.
Elisabeth Zinser, the school's new president, on Wednesday that
federal aid for the school may be jeopardized if she refuses to
leave the post.
   ``There's a variety of scenarios and that's one,'' Bonior told
The Washington Post afterward. ``I prefer that she make the
decision through a period of meeting with students and faculty and
arrive at a decision that's best for the university.''
   Zinser later acknowledged to an interviewer that ``a very strong
signal is being sent to me to resign, but I'm not sure that's
uniform.''
   Her selection has been opposed by students, instructors and
alumni who contend it is time for Gallaudet to have a deaf
president. Zinser hears normally and does not know sign language.
   Interviewed today on ABC-TV's ``Good Morning America,'' Zinser
said ``my deepest concern is to see the university continue its
good work and get back to educating students and carrying out its
research mission.''
   ``Today is the day in which I'm going to attempt to establish
the communication that is needed with the students and the faculty.
... My concern at this stage is that as president of the
university, that I exercise the leadership to get the university
back to business and engaged in the good work that it is doing.''
   But such talks are doomed, said the president of the National
Association for the Deaf.
   Gary Olsen, himself a graduate of Gallaudet, said on the ABC-TV
program that ``there's no way there will be an open dialogue
amongst the faculty, staff and students with her. ... If she wants
business to continue, then she should really be honest about it and
back down.''
   The appointment of Zinser, who has been chanceollor of the
University of North Carolina at Greensboro, was announced Sunday
night. Protests closed the university Monday; boycotts left
classrooms empty Tuesday and Wednesday.
   Protest leaders had said they were considering a mass student
withdrawal today. But one leader, Tim Rarus, said this morning,
``''We've decided not to do that. We would lose our leverage.''
   One deaf student said the protests recall the classic civil
rights demonstrations of the 1960s.
   ``This is the Selma of the deaf,'' Gallaudet graduate student
Kathy Karcher said at a rally Wednesday, referring to the Alabama
city where civil rights demonstrators were bloodied by
club-wielding police 23 years ago. ``This is a very important
moment.''
   Protest leaders say demonstrations will continue until Zinser is
replaced. They are also demanding the replacement of Jane Bassett
Spilman, the chairwoman of the board of trustees, and the
implementation of a plan to make deaf people a majority on the
school's 20-member board of trustees. The board has just four deaf
members.
   The Gallaudet protesters have encountered none of the violence
of the Selma demonstrators, but they say their struggle is akin to
the trials endured by blacks in their fight for equality.
   On Wednesday, more than half of Gallaudet's 274-member faculty
attended a meeting and voted overwhelmingly to ask the school's
board of trustees to oust Spilman. The faculty group also endorsed
the students' demands.
   ``Those are the people I think who are really deaf,'' deaf
actress Marlee Matlin said on ``Nightline,'' referring to
Gallaudet's board of trustees. Matlin won a 1986 Academy Award for
her performance as a dropout from a school for the deaf in
``Children of a Lesser God.''
   Gallaudet was founded by an act of Congress in 1864, and
receives three-quarters of its $76 million annual budget in federal
funds.
</TEXT>
