<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BrawleyCase     03-10 0511</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Brawley Case,0523</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Events Still Obscure Despite New Details</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investigators in the Tawana Brawley case have
uncovered new details about events during the four days she claims
she was abducted and sexually abused, but they are still uncertain
exactly what happened, according to a report published today.
   In a related development, child protection officials are
investigating whether Miss Brawley's welfare has been endangered
since she was whisked into seclusion by the Rev. Al Sharpton,
according to another report.
   Miss Brawley, who was 15 at the time she disappeared for four
days starting last Nov. 24, has said she was held in a wooded area
and sexually abused by at least two and as many as six white men,
one of whom flashed a police-type badge. She was found in a plastic
bag with racial slurs scrawled on her body and smeared with animal
feces.
   Gov. Mario Cuomo appointed Robert Abrams, state attorney
general, as special prosecutor. But Sharpton and Miss Brawley's
attorneys, C. Vernon Mason and Alton Maddox, have withheld her
cooperation from the investigators.
   Today's New York Times reported that interviews with witnesses
indicated that:
   _ Miss Brawley made an abrupt decision to get off a bus near her
home in Wappingers Falls, which apparently ruled out the
possibility that someone deliberately ambushed her.
   _ Investigators found traces of marijuana and hashish in an
apartment near where she was found and that her family had recently
been evicted from. The denim jacket she was wearing when she
disappeared was also found there and had traces of the drugs in it.
But tests performed on Miss Brawley showed no signs of drug use.
   _ Just before she was found, her mother went into the apartment
to look for her. Although she found no one, she said she suspected
someone had been there because the heat was turned on. A local
investigator who entered the apartment described it as
``blisteringly hot.''
   _ A charcoal substance that might have been used to write racial
slurs on Miss Brawley's body was found on leather gloves underneath
the garbage bag.
   _ Dog feces were found inside and outside her clothing,
suggesting to investigators that she might have been naked when
they got on her. The yard of the apartment was littered with such
feces.
   In addition, more evidence has surfaced indicating that Miss
Brawley spent at least part of the four days around the apartment,
according to the Times.
   On Wednesday, child protection officials began investigating
whether Miss Brawley has suffered ``emotional and educational''
neglect, insufficient psychiatric and medical care and inadequate
supervision, according to a report in today's Daily News.
   A ``possible neglect'' complaint was filed last week by
79-year-old Conrad Lynn, chief counsel of the Mid-Hudson region of
the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People.
Wappingers Falls is 50 miles north of New York City.
   But Matthew Strong, Miss Brawley's uncle and legal guardian,
said Miss Brawley is receiving the care she needs.
   ``She's going to school and she's in therapy,'' said the
Monticello police officer.
</TEXT>
