<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MoneyBags     03-10 0492</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Money Bags,0505</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Money From Armored Truck Returned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE CARPENTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who apparently was part of a crowd
that grabbed more than $700,000 that fell from an armored truck has
had a change of heart and turned in $28,000, police said.
   ``She said she picked up the money and then got kind of scared,
so she decided to turn it in,'' Sgt. William Herndon said late
Wednesday.
   The woman, identified only as a 30-year-old postal worker, gave
police two clear plastic bags containing a total of $28,000
Wednesday, more than 24 hours after a crate filled with money fell
from the back of a Loomis Armored Inc. truck.
   However, most of the estimated $771,000 that was in the crate is
still missing, and police warned opportunists they could face
felony theft charges if they don't return the cash.
   The woman, who may have been the one seen throwing money bags
into her car and driving away, could be charged with failure to
return property to its lawful owner, a misdemeanor, Herndon said.
She was interviewed by police.
   Since talking with the woman, police think more people than they
originally believed were involved snatched the estimated 20 bags
still missing. On Tuesday, they thought only three to five people
took advantage of Loomis' misfortune.
   ``She did say ... there were so many people picking up sacks
that she didn't believe it,'' Herndon said. ``It makes sense,
because when we interviewed people at the scene, no one knew
anything.''
   One man at the scene, television repairman Luis Lopez, managed
to save two bags containing $20,050 each and took them straight to
Loomis' nearby offices.
   Investigators were working to trace license plate numbers and
vehicle descriptions reported by witnesses and trying to compile a
list of the lost bills' serial numbers.
   A spokesman for Oakland-based Loomis declined comment on the
incident.
   The armored truck, carrying more than $1.7 million collected
from 20 banks in the San Francisco Bay area, was headed for Loomis'
offices from downtown.
   Lt. Barry Johnson said the driver claimed the rear door had been
locked, but that a dolly containing a crate of bills slammed
against the door and forced it open.
   The driver, whose name was not disclosed, did not learn of the
mishap until a honking motorist pointed it out two blocks away.
Police described him as ``white as a ghost and real upset.''
   Before the driver could return, a crowd gathered around the
fallen bags. Some people put money back into the crate but others
hung onto it, including one man who witnesses said tossed numerous
bags into his pickup truck and drove off.
   Police declined to be specific Wednesday about the amount
involved, saying only that it was more than $500,000. The San
Francisco Examiner reported that $771,000 in $10, $20 and $50 bills
fell out of the truck while close to $1 million remained inside.
</TEXT>
