<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SupercarrierSeries     03-10 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Supercarrier Series,0375</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Navy Withdraws Support From ``Supercarrier'' Series</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Navy has pulled the plug on helping
production of the ABC-TV ``Supercarrier'' series, saying the show
inaccurately portrays the lives of the crew and officers on a
fictional aircraft carrier.
   ``After lengthy deliberations the Navy determined that the
scripts for `Supercarrier' did not accurately portray the Navy and
its people; therefore cooperation was withdrawn,'' a Navy spokesman
said.
   Navy officials declined to comment on specific plot summaries
that prompted concern, but one reportedly involved a tale about
gun-running military action in Central America.
   Navy spokesman Capt. Michael Sherman said ABC could regain the
Navy's support if future scripts are in line with Navy interests.
   Show producer Charles Fries said, ``I think they're in a
wait-and-see mode.''
   The show, likened to the movie ``Top Gun'' with its hard rock
sound track and F-14 jet fighters, premiered Sunday with a
90-minute movie and took a 13.0 rating and 19 percent audience
share. It will be broadcast at 8 p.m. Sundays over the next seven
weeks.
   Fries said the show at first was planned to focus on the lives
of the men and women aboard the carrier, but then shifted to
action-adventure.
   ``From that point on, the Navy became more and more disenchanted
because essentially they're concerned about their perception (by
the public,)'' he said.
   ``Right now, the Navy is in a peacetime mode ... but to do an
action-adventure show we had to get off the carrier and bring in
some conflict and jeopardy.''
   Two episodes remain to be shot, and Fries said he had ample
shipboard footage left to continue production without Navy help.
   The Navy charged Fries' company $50,000 for the use of Navy
personnel, planes and facilities for the scenes that have been shot
so far.
   The show is loosely based on the best-selling non-fiction book
of the same name by George Wilson, a Washington Post reporter.
   ``I was kind of distressed that they didn't get it a little more
realistic in terms of what really goes on out there,'' said Wilson,
who said one admiral told him: ``You ought to sue ABC for not
plagiarizing your book.''
</TEXT>
