<HEAD>Former Girlfriend of Leader of The Order Testifies
^Eds: Subs 4th graf, `Craig said ...,' with 4 grafs to UPDATE with
other meetings. Picks up in 5th graf, `Miller, who ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT SMITH, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former girlfriend of the leader of
the right-wing group The Order testified that she helped him
distribute $2 million of $3.6 million stolen in an armored car
robbery in California in June 1984.
   Zillah Craig said Wednesday that she also helped Robert Mathews,
killed in a December 1984 shootout with FBI agents on Whidbey
Island near Seattle, pass counterfeit bills.
   Craig testified Wednesday in the sedition-conspiracy trial of 14
men. Ten of them are charged with sedition, five are accused of
conspiring to kill a federal judge and an FBI agent, and two are
accused of interstate transportation of stolen money.
   Craig said that in August 1984 she and Mathews traveled to
Cohoctah, Mich., where they spent the night with defendant Robert
Miles, head of the Mountain Church. She said Mathews took a
briefcase with him to a meeting with Miles that lasted several
hours.
   Craig said she and Mathews also met in Arlington, Va., with
William Pierce, head of the National Alliance, a reputed white
supremacist organization.
   Pierce is the author of ``The Turner Diaries,'' a book that
government witnesses have testified formed the basis for The
Order's plans to overthrow the government and establish an
all-white nation in the Northwest.
   Miles gave Mathews a letter of introduction to Glenn Miller,
head of the White Patriots Party in North Carolina, she said. She
and Mathews visited Miller at his home and gave him about $25,000
to $30,000, she testified.
   Miller, who recently agreed to appear at the trial as a
prosecution witness, is to testify this week.
   Craig testified that she gave birth to Mathews' baby, a girl,
about two months before Mathews was killed in the shootout with FBI
agents. Shortly after Mathews' death, she said, Miles began sending
her money with the notation ``Widows and children aid fund.''
   She also testified that after visiting defendant Richard Scutari
in federal prison at Memphis in October 1986, she relayed to Miles
a message from Scutari that he feared James Ellison would cooperate
with federal agents.
   Ellison, former leader of the Arkansas-based survivalist group,
the Covenent, the Sword and the Arm of the Lord, did testify for
three days two weeks ago. He's considered the prosecution's star
witness in the case.
   In other developments, defendant Bruce Pierce said Wednesday he
had changed his mind about his statement Tuesday that he would
plead guilty to conspiring to overthrow the government.
   U.S. District Judge Morris Arnold ruled Tuesday that Pierce had
voluntarily confessed to FBI agents shortly after his March 1985
arrest in Georgia; that statement prompted Pierce to announce his
guilty plea.
   Pierce contended that he was coerced into confessing, claiming
that authorities told him that his wife would be arrested and his
three children placed in foster homes in he did not talk to the FBI.
   Pierce, 34, is serving 100 years for racketeering and 150 years
for violating the civil rights of outspoken Jewish radio talk show
host Alan Berg, who was shot to death in Denver.
