<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PhonyInvoices     03-10 0435</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Phony Invoices,0448</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rabbis Sentenced In $130 Million Tax Scheme</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONALD POWERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge says he sentenced two rabbis and the
wife of one of the men to prison because they ``reaped millions''
as part of a $130 million garment industry tax fraud in which more
than 200 companies participated.
   But U.S. District Judge John M. Walker said Wednesday he took
into account a lengthy appeal for leniency by lawyers for the three
defendants, all members of the ultra-religious Lubavitch sect of
Judaism and active in their Brooklyn community.
   The three were convicted Dec. 4 of one count of conspiracy and
44 counts of aiding and assisting the filing of false federal tax
returns.
   Rabbi Schnejer Zalman Gurary, 76, who Walker called the
``kingpin'' of the scheme, was sentenced to three years in prison
and five years on probation, and was fined $2 million.
   ``You reaped millions,'' Walker told him. The sentence would
have been stiffer, but for Gurary's failing health and a thick file
of letters attesting to Gurary's good community deeds, Walker said.
   Gurary's son-in-law, Nochum Sternberg, 43, was sentenced to 18
months in prison and five years on probation. His wife, Esther
Sternberg, 43, Gurary's daughter, was sentenced to 120 days in jail
and five years on probation.
   The Sternbergs also were fined $1 million.
   They faced up to five years on the conspiracy count and three
years in prison on each of the 44 aiding and assisting counts.
   The Sternbergs have 11 children, four of whom still live at
home, and Walker said Sternberg was not to begin serving his prison
sentence until his wife had completed hers.
   The judge also accommodated the woman's strong religious beliefs
by allowing her to leave jail each week for the Jewish Sabbath.
   During the six-week trial, the government said the scheme
involved phony invoices from a group of 36 companies known
collectively as the ``Zalga companies.''
   The defendants sold phony Zalga invoices, primarily to companies
in the garment center, indicating that goods had been purchased
when in fact no goods were involved.
   The garment company would then issue a check to the Zalga
company issuing the phony invoice. The defendants then returned
cash to the company, keeping 10 percent to 15 percent of the amount
of the check as a commission.
   Representatives of the other companies, a number of whom
testified against the three, were sentenced earlier on various tax
fraud charges.
   According to trial testimony, the defendants issued more than
$130 million in fraudulent invoices to more than 200 companies
between 1979 and 1986.
</TEXT>
