<HEAD>LaRouche Supporter Elected Demo Chief In Houston</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, `Jones, an ...,' with 1 graf to add vote tally.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Lyndon LaRouche associate says he will assume
the traditional duties of Harris County Democratic Party chairman,
the office he won in an upset.
   Party leaders, meanwhile, said Wednesday they are taking steps
to thwart Claude Jones' influence.
   Jones, an associate of the political extremist, threw the
Democratic party into turmoil Tuesday when he narrowly defeated
incumbent Larry Veselka in the primary. Jones received 54,394
votes, or 51.46 percent, to Veselka's 51,318 votes, or 48.55
percent.
   The result shocked party leaders who face working under a
chairman associated since 1975 with a fringe presidential candidate
strongly opposed by the national and state party.
   Members of the party's steering committee met Wednesday night to
consider a plan by which the party executive committee would
empower the party secretary to run the party rather than Jones, who
takes office May 2. The 664-member executive committee is made up
of elected precinct chairmen.
   Former county party chairman Barbara Stanley, who attended the
meeting, said state law places most of the party's power with the
committee rather than the chairman, who has no inherent power.
   Party leaders won't challenge Jones' right to hold the office,
she said, adding she presumes they will not try to stop him from
conducting three legally required county party executive committee
meetings during his term.
   Jones said he desires to work with the party, help register
voters and defeat the Republicans, particularly George Bush, whom
he described as the likely nominee.
   LaRouche associate Harley Schlanger, appearing with Jones,
asked, ``Do the leaders of the Democratic Party have a right to
tell the voters who their party chairman will be?''
   Jones dismissed as ``a silly question'' an inquiry about
analysts' views that Jones' common name and the obscurity of the
race accounted for his win.
   He won, he said, because he has ``been working hard pushing
LaRouche's issues, and those issues finally hit a nerve.''
   Democratic National Committee member Billie Carr of Houston said
Jones was elected because the voters didn't know of his association
with LaRouche. She said she doesn't blame Veselka, who didn't
campaign for re-election and was out of the city in the weeks
before the campaign.
   Jones, who was defeated by Veselka in 1986, said his sole
occupation is working for LaRouche. He said he staffs solicitation
booths the LaRouche organization sponsors at airports and other
public places.
   Jones said he will back the Democratic presidential nominee
although he supports LaRouche.
   LaRouche has accused Queen Elizabeth of drug trafficking and
espouses a quarantine of AIDS patients.
   One person happy about the flap was Texas Republican Chairman
George Strake.
   ``I wish them (the Democrats) every success under their new
leadership,'' he said Wednesday.
</TEXT>
