<1ST_LINE>r a PM-LaRoucheTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0503 03-10 0823</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-LaRouche Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0503,0841</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Declassified Documents Indicate CIA, FBI Infiltrated LaRouche
Groups</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 5 grafs after 4th graf, `A federal ...,' to UPDATE
with appellate ruling about NBC, from a0505. Picks up in 5th graf,
`The prosecutor ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three intelligence operatives said FBI and CIA
officials asked them to infiltrate the political organizations of
extremist Lyndon LaRouche, a declassified document shows.
   The document was made available Wednesday to defense lawyers in
the fraud and conspiracy trial of LaRouche, six aides and five of
his political groups.
   The defense, which claims the criminal charges emerged from a
White House-directed plot to ruin LaRouche, won a delay in the
trial as a result of the document and a previously disclosed memo
indicating two key players in the Iran-Contra scandal discussed
collecting evidence against LaRouche.
   A federal judge ordered the prosecutor to search government
files for any additional evidence that should be surrendered to
defense lawyers.
   In a separate decision, a federal appeals court ruled Wednesday
that NBC must surrender to a judge outtakes from a 100-minute
interview with a former LaRouche consultant who said an aide to the
political extremist discussed a plot to assassinate Henry
Kissinger. The network broadcast a one-minute excerpt of the
interview in April 1986.
   The decision Wednesday by the 1st U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
upheld a lower court order that videotape of the entire interview
must be surrendered for possible use at the conspiracy and fraud
trial.
   The court also upheld a contempt citation against the network.
   NBC had contended that surrendering portions of the interview
that were not broadcast violated its First Amendment right against
judicial intrusion into news gathering and editorial decisions.
   However, U.S. District Judge Robert E. Keeton ruled that the
rights of the defendants to have access to the 100-minute interview
with Forrest Lee Fick outweighed those of the network.
   The prosecutor, Assistant U.S. Attorney John Markham, has at
times ridiculed defense claims that LaRouche was a target of
infiltration by the FBI and the CIA, which is prohibited by law
from spying domestically. The defense claims Marine Lt. Col. Oliver
North, the former National Security Council aide fired for his role
in the Iran-Contra affair, directed the infiltration because
LaRouche refused to support the Nicaraguan rebels.
   Defense attorneys are seeking dismissal of charges on the ground
that prosecutors deliberately withheld evidence that the defense
later learned of through Freedom of Information Act requests.
   The FBI document declassified Wednesday refers to Gary Howard
and Ron Tucker, founders of a private, now-defunct Dallas company,
Peregrine International Associates.
   Peregrine reportedly was involved in an aborted attempt to sell
arms to Iranians who planned to assassinate their nation's leader,
Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini, and helped train Contra forces and
elite military units in El Salvador, Honduras and Peru.
   The document also refers to retired Sgt. Maj. Fred Lewis, who
defense lawyers in the LaRouche case say also worked for Peregrine.
   ``When asked about their possible ties to LaRouche, they
(Howard, Tucker and Lewis) claimed they had previously been
requested by the FBI and CIA to penetrate the LaRouche
organization,'' said the document.
   Lewis, a former member of the Army's elite special operations
Delta Force, was said by the FBI document to be an employee of
Rhyolite Management Systems of Dallas. Rhyolite is the name of a
spy satellite, the government acknowledged several years ago.
   A memo to North from retired Air Force Maj. Gen. Richard Secord,
one of North's main operatives in the private network to aid the
Contras, said ``our man here claims Lewis has collected information
against LaRouche.''
   The defense lawyers said they have been informed by the
government that the ``our man'' reference is to Oliver Revell, an
FBI assistant director involved in counterintelligence.
   FBI spokesman Ray McElhaney said the agency would not comment on
the memo during the trial.
   ``This was an activity that was headed up by Oliver North and
Mr. Secord in a political attempt to stop the LaRouche people,''
defense attorney Michael Reilly said Wednesday.
   Tucker, a former Texas Department of Public Safety Narcotics
Agent, and Howard, a former border patrol agent, claim in a lawsuit
filed last summer against the Customs Service that they have been
government informants since 1979. Tucker and Howard are seeking
$1.4 million for their expenses in a sting operation that led to
the arrest of a man allegedly buying arms for Iran.
   They say the government backed off the case because it would
have revealed the Reagan administration's arms shipments to Iran
and the diversion of profits to the Contras.
   The FBI document also said that during interviews with FBI
agents in San Antonio and El Paso, Tucker and Howard said they had
approached family and friends of Soviet dissidents Andrei Sakharov
and his wife, Yelena Bonner, and told the family they could free
the couple from the Soviet Union for $2 million.
</TEXT>
