<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Walesa     03-10 0193</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Walesa,0198</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Walesa Says Passport's Denial Violates Union Rights</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa today
accused the Polish government of violating union rights for denying
him a passport to attend an international labor meeting in
Australia.
   The leader of the outlawed federation of labor unions said the
government had so far ignored his request to attend the meeting
March 14-18, according to Solidarity spokesman Janusz Onyszkiewicz.
Walesa said he was convinced his request was being denied, given
recent political statements by the government.
   Government spokesman Jerzy Urban said two weeks ago that
Solidarity shouldn't be allowed to send delegations abroad because
it has been outlawed.
   Walesa, who won the Nobel Peace Prize in 1983, had asked to go
to the meeting of the International Confederation of Free Trade
Unions in Melbourne with three aides.
   He said today that some Solidarity representatives would attend
the congress despite the government's action, but he did not
elaborate. Solidarity operates an external office in Belgium.
   The passport's denial has drawn criticism from Australian Prime
Minister Bob Hawke and prompted trade unionists briefly to block
mail delivery and garbage removal at the Polish embassy.
</TEXT>
