<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Kerrey     03-10 0318</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Kerrey,0327</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Governor Enters Senate Race in Nebraska</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL ZUEGNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Bob Kerrey officially entered the
race for the U.S. Senate today, telling 300 supporters he expected
a tougher campaign than six years ago when he was elected governor
in his first try for public office.
   ``I would like to be your next senator,'' Kerrey said in
starting a two-day swing through the state. ``I can promise you I
will never betray you. And I will never dishonor the respect I have
for you.''
   Kerrey, 44, ended months of speculation last November when he
said he would run for the Senate. He has been criss-crossing
Nebraska since then, saying his main issues are trade policy, the
federal budget, education and agriculture.
   ``A great and glorious future will not happen unless we do the
unglamorous work today,'' he said.
   No other Democrat has filed for the nomination. Sen. David
Karnes, appointed to succeed the late Democratic Sen. Edward
Zorinsky, and Rep. Hal Daub are seeking the GOP nomination.
   Kerrey was a political unknown when he began his campaign for
governor in December 1981; he upset incumbent Republican Charles
Thone in 1982.
   A Medal of Honor winner who lost part of his right leg while
serving with the Navy in the Vietnam War, Kerrey was a popular
governor in mostly Republican Nebraska. He made headlines for his
romance with actress Debra Winger, who visited Nebraska frequently
but later married actor Timothy Hutton.
   Kerrey's announcement in October 1985 that he wouldn't seek a
second term shocked many Nebraskans, but Kerrey said it was ``time
to move on.''
   Since leaving office, he has been involved in various business
ventures, including a restaurant chain and an investment banking
firm.
   He also taught a class on the Vietnam War at the University of
California at Santa Barbara and high school government classes in
Omaha.
</TEXT>
