<HEAD>Japan's Trade Surplus Declines In February</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: A version on financial wires.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan's unadjusted trade surplus fell in February
from a year ago, the Finance Ministry reported today.
   The ministry said foreign sales exceeded foreign purchases by
$5.24 billion last month, compared with a surplus of $7.13 billion
in February 1987.
   The February surplus was up $3.08 billion from January, but the
ministry said trade usually dwindles in January because of the long
new year holiday.
   Imports shot up 48 percent from a year ago to a record $14.96
billion in February, while exports rose 17.2 percent to $20.2
billion. The previous high for imports was $14.76 billion in
December 1987.
   Japan's surplus in trade with the United States fell to $3.40
billion from $3.97 billion in February 1987. Exports rose 9.7
percent to $6.81 billion dollars, while U.S. imports soared by 51.9
percent to a record $3.41 billion.
   U.S. aircraft purchases accounted for a large portion in the
imports, totaling $477.86 million, up 194.2 percent from a year
earlier.
   The previous monthly high for U.S. imports was $3.12 billion set
in June 1986.
</TEXT>
