<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Waldheim 1stLd-Writethru   03-10 0739</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Waldheim, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0581,0760</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: For Release 2:15 p.m. EST - time set by source</NOTE>
<HEAD>Waldheim Apologizes For Nazi Crimes, Ignores Wartime Past</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS graf after 7th graf pvs: ``Austria was ...,'' to ADD
that Austrians approved Anschluss in vote. Pick up 8th graf pvs:
`Austria's Nazi...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROLAND PRINZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Kurt Waldheim, commemorating
Austria's annexation by Germany 50 years ago, today apologized for
the crimes committed by Austrian Nazis but ignored his own
controversial wartime past.
   ``We must not forget that many of the worst Nazi hangmen were
Austrians,'' Waldheim said in a televised speech. ``There were
Austrians who were victims and others who were perpetrators.
   ``Obviously, there is no collective guilt'' for the war crimes
committed by Austrians, the president declared. ``Nevertheless, as
head of state of the Republic of Austria, I wish to apologize for
Nazi crimes committed by Austrians.''
   It was the first time that Waldheim has used such language in
public to acknowledge Austria's share in World War II and the
Holocaust.
   Waldheim did not acknowledge until two years ago that he served
in World War II in a German army unit implicated in wartime
atrocities, and he has resisted pressure to resign since it became
known.
   In his speech, the president insisted that ``as a state, Austria
was Hitler's first victim. That is indisputable.''
   Austria was wiped off the map when Nazi troops invaded on March
11, 1938. Adolf Hitler then returned in triumph to Austria, his
native land, cheered by hundreds of thousands of countrymen.
   In April 1938, the Nazis said 99 percent of Austrians approved
the Anschluss in a nationwide vote. More than half a million
Austrians joined the Nazi party, and many of the brutal guards in
the concentration camps were Austrians.
   Austria's Nazi past _ largely suppressed here over the past four
decades _ has dogged this neutral country since the disclosure in
March 1986 of Waldheim's wartime service.
   Vienna's Socialist mayor, Helmut Zilk, opening an exhibition
looking back at the Nazi era in Austria, sharply criticized the
government for reneging on a promise to help fund the display.
   Zilk charged the coalition government of Socialists and
conservatives had behaved ``like a dog that shakes off fleas'' by
shrugging off the exhibit.
   He speculated aid was withheld because the conservatives
objected to descriptions of the prewar rightist regime called
``Austrofascism'' by liberals and Socialists.
   In his speech, Waldheim left unmentioned his wartime years in
Yugoslavia and Greece and the furor triggered last month by a
historians' report questioning Waldheim's integrity during the war.
   The report did not furnish evidence to clearly back allegations
Waldheim participated in war crimes, but it said he was ``in close
proximity'' to war crimes and did nothing to prevent them.
   Public pressure after the report's release forced Waldheim to
drop plans to speak at a solemn remembrance of the Nazi annexation
on Friday.
   Waldheim recalled the Anschluss, as the Nazi annexation of
Austria is known, as an event that ``triggered an avalanche of
suffering.''
   ``It was an avalanche of suffering that buried those who thought
differently and, in a terrible racial mania, buried our Jewish
fellow citizens,'' Waldheim declared. ``Millions of Jewish people
were annihilated in the concentration camps.
   ``Nothing can explain or excuse those crimes,'' said the
president. ``I bow in deep respect to those victims who must always
serve as a reminder and a duty'' for Austria.
   The controversy over Waldheim has divided Austria and tarnished
the country's image. The U.S. Justice Department last year barred
Waldheim from the country as an undesirable alien.
   Waldheim asked foreign critics ``to see Austria not only in the
light of the horrors of the past but in the light of standing the
test'' of the present.
   Turning to his domestic critics, Waldheim said, ``I ask you to
refrain from blanket charges and from unqualified accusations'' and
instead to see Austria as a country looking into the future ``open
to the world, ready to assist and self-assured.''
   He appealed to Austrians to ``wrestle with the shadows of the
past'' and, repeating earlier statements, called for
``reconciliation.''
   Waldheim also outlined what he called a program of discussion
with politicians of all parties to reform public life and do away
with a wave of corruption and other scandals that have hit
headlines in recent months.
   The moral standards of all who work in public life should
improve, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
