<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Panama Bjt   03-10 0757</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Panama, Bjt,0778</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Banks Say They Can't Open, Despite Government Go-Ahead</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with banks saying they're still
unable to do business, bishops appealing to military to allow
civilian rule, new quotes. No pickup.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By REID G. MILLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most banks said today they didn't
have the cash to open despite a government go-ahead to resume
limited transactions. Roman Catholic bishops urged the military to
bow to civilian rule.
   The National Banking Association, representing 97 of the
approximately 120 banks doing business in Panama, said its members
``are not in condition to renew services'' and will remain ``closed
temporarily.''
   According to the statement, banks reiterated to their depositors
``the security of the funds entrusted to them and their inalterable
decision to find the conditions that might permit the most prompt
return to normality of the banking system.''
   It was the eighth straight day of a nationwide bank closure,
which came a few days after the ouster of President Eric Arturo
Delvalle by supporters of military strongman Gen. Manuel Antonio
Noriega.
   On Wednesday, the nation's Roman Catholic bishops appealed to
the military to subordinate itself to civilian rule.
   In a statement distributed by Archbishop Marcos McGrath, the
religious leaders also urged fellow Panamanians to put personal and
party interests aside in finding a solution to the crisis.
   It said the bishops believe necessary ``the strict observance of
constitutional standards, the full and effective subordination of
military forces to civilian authority, the search for conditions
and structure that make possible national elections that deserve
the credibility of all the voters, the restoration of the exercise
of all human and civil rights and ... the reopening of the
communications media.''
   Also Wednesday, the nephew of the late Omar Torrijos, Panama's
previous strongman, disclosed that he had broken with the Noriega
government. Santiago Torrijos said he left his post as chief of
Panama's consulate in Los Angeles and was joining forces loyal to
Delvalle.
   Diplomatic sources in Washington, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said Torrijos' defection was significant because of the
close identification of his relatives with the Defense Forces.
   The government's National Banking Commission told local and
international financial institutions late Wednesday they could
reopen but only to accept deposits and transfer funds among
themselves and other banks around the world.
   None did.
   The cash shortage was caused by the freezing of millions of
dollars in Panamanian funds in U.S. banks. The United States
continues to recognize Delvalle as the leader of Panama and has
called for the resignation of Noriega, under indictment in Florida
on drug trafficking charges.
   Rufina Escobar, a 55-year-old schoolteacher, said she had enough
food on hand at home to make it through the week. ``But if the
banks don't open next week, I'll have to ask friends for a few
dollars just to eat.''
   Arial Simons, 17, complained that his mother had cut off his
weekly $10 allowance.
   ``I guess I won't be going to the movies or any parties this
weekend,'' he said. ``I don't even have the money to buy a beer.''
   Clerks at Sarah's, one of Panama City's most fashionable
department stores, spent their time dusting shelves, chatting among
themselves and waiting on an occasional customer.
   ``People aren't buying anything unessential,'' said one young
clerk, whose name tag identified him as Esteban. ``They're being
very cautious with their money. Business is way, way down.''
   The young man declined to give his last name ``because I don't
want any trouble.''
   People everywhere were hoarding their cash, which was the only
thing most businesses were accepting because they couldn't process
checks or credit card transactions.
   A lone customer at Sarah's cosmetics department was buying
lipstick, occupying the attention of only one of five bored
saleswomen. The customer explained her purchase almost defensively
as she left the store.
   ``I work in an office and I have to look nice,'' she said. Then
she dug into her purse, pulled out an empty tube of lipstick and
declared: ``Look, this was all I had left. I just had to buy more.
But something like new shoes, that's out.''
   The woman, whose husband admonished her with a wagging finger
not to give her name, said she hadn't bought anything else except
household essentials since the banks closed last week.
   ``I bought large bags of beans and rice, a lot of milk for the
kids and things like that,'' she said. ``But we're being careful,
too, because we don't know how long this thing will last.''
</TEXT>
