<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Kemp 3rdLd-Writethru a0603 03-10 0695</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Kemp, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0603,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kemp Drops White House Bid</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with new material on vice presidential issue in top
four grafs, picking up in 5th graf pvs, Kemp departed</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Jack Kemp quit the race for the
Republican presidential nomination today after a string of poor
performances in the early primaries and caucuses, but vowed to
``carry the flag high'' for his conservative causes.
   ``We have not failed because our ideas are winning,'' the New
York congressman said at a Capitol Hill news conference where he
clearly signaled his interest in the 1988 vice presidential
nomination.
   Flanked by members of his family and House members who supported
his White House bid, Kemp said he would not seek re-election to a
10th term in the House from his district in upstate New York, and
had no plans to run for the Senate.
   Asked about the No. 2 spot on this year's ticket, he said,
``Obviously you don't make plans to run for vice president.'' Asked
again, he called the idea ``a very flattering and awesome thought.
... Would I think about it, the answer is yes.''
   Kemp departed the race with a pledge to campaign for the
Republican nominee _ and a blast at the Democrats.
   ``We must never compromise with the liberal Democratic
Congress,'' he said to applause. ``We must replace the liberal
Democratic Congress.''
   Kemp made his exit after failing in his bid to emerge as the
true heir to the Reagan Revolution and the conservative alternative
to GOP front-runner George Bush and Sen. Bob Dole of Kansas.
   His efforts were thrwarted by former television evangelist Pat
Robertson, whose surprise second-place finish in the lead-off Iowa
caucuses was a blow from which the congressman never recovered.
   Even so, he claimed success for his efforts, noting Bush's
statement that he opposes tax increases to cut the deficit and
Dole's support for the Nicaraguan Contra rebels and the Star Wars
initiative pushed by President Reagan.
   Kemp bowed out two days after winning just four delegates from
712 at stake in 17 Super Tuesday contests. His best finish in the
17 GOP contests was a dismal 7 percent showing in the Massachusetts
primary.
   Kemp had 35 committed delegates _ but most of those were handed
to him by Bush in a Michigan compromise designed to prevent
Robertson from claiming a victory.
   Campaign spokesman John Buckley said Kemp spent $15 million on
his effort, and departs with debts of less than $100,000.
   Some aides to Kemp had urged him to get out even before the
Super Tuesday voting across the South and elsewhere, following his
fourth-place finish in South Carolina's primary.
   As recently as Monday Kemp insisted he would press on, but he
acknowledged he had to reassess his candidacy after the Tuesday
voting.
   ``There were rumors we would withdraw after Iowa,'' he said.
``But I'm not a quitter. I'm an ex-quarterback, and I don't enter a
contest lightly.''
   Kemp, a former professional football player, campaigned as a
candidate of ideas and claimed to be heir to President Reagan's
conservative legacy.
   But his emphasis on economic opportunity and talk of returning
to something like a gold standard didn't excite many conservatives
who were concerned about more emotional issues. Despite years of
work for his White House aspirations, Kemp was never able to light
a spark outside his small group of loyalists.
   His problem was summed up last year by Angela Jackson, who tried
to persuade her brother, conservative commentator Patrick J.
Buchanan, to enter the presidential race.
   ``Jack Kemp's been out there for two years,'' she said. ``He's
gone from 7 percent to 7 percent.''
   Kemp, 51, formally entered the GOP race on April 6, 1987.
   He was a strong proponent of deploying the Strategic Defense
Initiative, Reagan's space-based missile defense system, and a
tough opponent of any tax increase.
   He blasted both Bush and Dole in a debate in Dallas in February,
saying they were identical tax raisers whose election would signal
the end of the ``Reagan revolution.'' His rivals countered that in
his zeal, Kemp was ignoring the danger of huge budget deficits.
</TEXT>
