<DOCNO> AP880310-0116 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-88 1221EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p BC-KempText     03-10 1144</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Kemp Text,1,150</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is the text of New York Rep. Jack Kemp's
statement Thursday on his withdrawal from the Republican
presidential race:
   Last April, when I was explaining to my family about our race
for the presidency, we had a moment of family time. Jeffrey was
there at the time, as well as Jimmy and Judith and Jennifer, and
Joanne of course. And I quoted the book of Ecclesiastes. I'd like
to share it with you today. It tells us that in everything there is
a season and a time for every purpose under heaven. There's a time
to fight, a time to do battle.
   Well, ladies and gentlemen, we've fought the good fight. We've
fought long and hard and well. I want to thank from the bottom of
my heart my family, my colleagues and comrades-in-arms, the large
family of Kemp supporters across the country. I want to tell each
and every one of you that you can hold your heads high. We've waged
an honorable, spirited, a principled campaign on issues and ideas,
and frankly, in many ways, that's the most important victory of all.
   But then there's a time to refrain, a time to not fight, a time
to accept defeat in one battle, so we can move on to fight again. I
want to salute my fellow candidates: George Bush, Bob Dole, Pat
Robertson, and Pete du Pont and Alexander Haig as well. And Joanne
and I particularly want to congratulate today George and Barbara
Bush for their great victory across the South on Super Tuesday.
Today, I'm withdrawing from the race for president. I'm folding up
my tent, but I want you to know I'm going to continue to carry the
flag high now and in the future.
   Far more important than personal success in an election is the
cause in which we believe. I ran for the presidency to ensure that
the torch that we lit in 1980 in Detroit, Michigan, when we
nominated Ronald Reagan and revolutionized the Republican Party,
would burn even brighter and help light the way into the 1990s.
   We may have suffered a political defeat, but our principles have
not been defeated. We have not failed because our ideas are
winning. We know our ideas are winning when George Bush says we
must not reduce the deficit by raising taxes, that we need to cut
the capital gains tax, that we need to enact free enterprise zones
to unleash the talent of the inner city and to create more jobs,
and when he says that we need to strengthen free and open trade
throughout the world.
   We know our ideas are winning when Bob Dole pledges to support
the freedom fighters and deploy the Strategic Defense Initiative.
We know our ideas are winning when every single Republican
candidate says that he supports the inalienable right to life for
the born and the unborn, and pledges to fight for a pro-family, and
a drug-free future for America. I want you to know, I'll be proud
to campaign for any Republican nominee who carries that banner, and
I will fight at his side as long and as far as he carries that
banner on the field of friendly strife.
   To my fellow Republicans, I would say that in politics as in the
marketplace, winning means staying ahead of your competitors. It
means not only having better ideas, but carrying them through to
completion. Our party must never drift back to mindless austerity.
We must never close our eyes to economic and moral challege. We
must never break faith with the family or with senior citizens, or
ignore the threat from a dangerous enemy that remains at war with
freedom and democracy throughout the world.
   Let the liberal Democrats try to raise the burden of taxes on
the workers and the families of America. Let liberal Democrats turn
their backs on the freedom fighters around the globe. Let liberal
Democrats raise tariffs on our allies and friends while they shirk
the responsibility to preserve peace through strength. The American
people will reject such a party, just as roundly and overwhelmingly
in 1988 as they did in 1980 and 1984.
   Ladies and gentlemen, we must not compromise with the liberal
Democratic Congress. We must replace the liberal Democratic
Congress with a free-enterprise Congress. Ours is a greater cause.
Our ideas can move America and the whole world forward, but like
the Good Shepherd, we can't leave anyone behind.
   We can't rest until our economy is so strong that there's a job
for every man and woman in America who wants to work, until our
dollar once again is as good as gold and the budget is in balance.
We can't rest until we've helped freedom fighters to victory and
until we've researched, tested, developed, deployed, and built a
strategic defense for the United States of America and our allies
in Europe and Israel. We can't rest until all of us, black and
white, Christian and Jew, rich or poor, are living in an America
that is more prosperous but more tolerant, more decent and more
generous, an America bound together as the founder of our party,
Abraham Lincoln, envisioned the Republican Party _ as a people
party, as a freedom party, as an emancipation party, to help make
America one nation under God with liberty and justice and equality
of opportunity for all.
   I want to close, if I can, my remarks by pulling from my pocket
something I've carried around with me since Super Tuesday. Joanne
and I went to bed Tuesday night and found a little note on our
pillow from one of our children. It was from our daughter Jennifer,
and she told us that she loved us and that she was proud of us. And
then, as a typical Kemp child, she ended by quoting Winston
Churchill. And it wasn't because they all went to Winston Churchill
High School; it's because all the Kemps love Churchill, as
freedom-loving men and women do throughout the world.
   Jennifer ended her little letter by saying, ``Finally, Dad, as
Winston Churchill said, `Success is never final, failure is never
fatal, it's courage that counts.' And you're the most courageous
people I know.'' Well, I want you all to know that no father, no
candidate, no human being could ask for more than to have a
courageous family, courageous comrades-in-arms, and courageous men
and women around this country who believe in the ideas upon which
America was built in the past, and upon which, alone, we can build
a great victory for America and the world in the future.
   Thank you, Jennifer. Thank you to my family. Thank you to each
and every one of you. And may God continue to bless America. Thank
you very, very, very much.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>END OF TEXT</HEAD>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
