<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Afghanistan 1stLd-Writethru a0469 03-10 0490</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Afghanistan, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0469,0499</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Say Troop Withdrawal Doesn't Mean End to Afghan Aid</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with Soviets saying agreement to
withdraw troops doesn't mean end to Afghan aid. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union said today that an agreement on
the withdrawal of its troops from Afghanistan is not a commitment
to end military aid to the Kabul government.
   Soviet ambassador Nikolay Kozyrev said the question of a halt to
Soviet assistance has ``not arisen'' in the almost 6-year-old
U.N.-sponsored Afghanistan peace talks.
   He said the draft agreement would not bar any kind of Soviet
aid, except the sending of new troops into Afghanistan, where the
Soviets intervened in 1979. An estimated 115,000 Soviet troops are
helping the Marxist government fight U.S.-backed Moslem insurgents.
   Kozyrev rejected the U.S. demand for a ``symmetrical cessation''
of military aid to both sides in the war. Kozyrev said it was an
attempt to interfere in the internal affairs of Afghanistan and in
the bilateral relationship between Kabul and Moscow.
   He said the demand would be tantamount to Moscow calling for an
end to U.S. military aid for Pakistan.
   Kozyrev also warned that if a Geneva settlement were not signed,
a ``new flare-up of bloodshed and fratricidal war cannot be
excluded.''
   Kozyrev, a specialist on Asian affairs, came to Geneva as head
of a Soviet team of experts to follow the peace talks. His remarks
followed a statement by Afghan foreign minister Abdul Wakil, who
said Wednesday that Moscow had helped Afghanistan for years and
would continue to do so after the troop withdrawal.
   Wakil has said earlier that the draft agreements provided only
for a halt to arms shipments to the guerrillas fighting the Kabul
government. The United States is considered the insurgents' main
supplier, with deliveries totaling a reported $700 million last
year.
   Kozyrev said the peace talks have ``bogged down'' because of
Pakistan's insistence on having a settlement linked to the
formation of a transitional government in Kabul to oversee the
withdrawal of the Red Army troops.
   Pakistan, which represents Afghan rebels in the peace talks,
says that a government to replace the present Soviet-backed one
would ensure stability and the safe return of more than 5 million
Afghan refugees.
   Kozyrev sidestepped a question on whether negotiations could
continue after next Tuesday, a target date set by Moscow. Soviet
leader Mikhail Gorbachev said last month that the troops would
leave Afghanistan starting May 15 if an agreement were reached
March 15.
   ``I can only hope that the other side (Pakistan) will show
enough common sense and responsibility,'' he said, adding later,
``It is too early to say what will happen after that date.''
   Wakil and the Pakistani delegations have both made plain that
they do not consider March 15 a deadline and that a settlement at a
later date would just put off the start of the withdrawal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
