<DOCNO> AP880310-0121 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-88 1233EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dole 1stLd-Writethru a0468 03-10 0741</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dole, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0468,730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dole Says He's Stronger Candidate Than Bush</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with Dole comment on Bush in top 5 grafs, picking up
in 2nd graf pvs, ``Well we</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY MASSEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican presidential candidate Bob Dole sought
today to sow doubts about the party's front-runner, saying Vice
President George Bush will face a ``tough, tough race'' in November
if he is the GOP nominee.
   ``I would be a much stronger candidate,'' Dole said as he
campaigned in the Chicago area. ``That's the message we're going to
try to make in the next couple of days.''
   Dole planned to concentrate today on suburban Chicago before
heading downstate for a swing Friday through farm country where the
Kansas senator considers his support the strongest.
   He started the day with a tour of the Rehabilitation Hospital of
Chicago, which is near another hospital where Dole underwent
surgery 40 years ago for injuries he received in World War II.
   ``This is going to be the political recovery state just as it
was the personal recovery state 40 years ago,'' Dole said on
Wednesday. ``That may be more symbolism than anything, but to me it
is an indication that it can be done.''
   On Wednesday, one day after Dole's Super Tuesday drubbing, a
senior campaign adviser was quizzed whether the results had
triggered a ``meltdown'' in the Kansas Republican's presidential
candidacy.
   ``Well, we might have started evacuating around the reactor,''
quipped the aide, Thomas Rath.
   His reply reflected the perilous situation as Dole's campaign
works toward the March 15 Illinois primary, which even the
candidate openly acknowledges is a do-or-die contest if he is to
have any chance of beating Vice President George Bush for the GOP
presidential nomination.
   Dole, campaigning in the Chicago area on Wednesday, said he must
win at least 65 percent of all remaining delegates nationwide as
well as those who are uncommitted if he is to emerge victorious.
His first objective is Illinois, a state where Bush has the backing
of Gov. James Thompson and 93 of the state's 102 GOP county
chairmen.
   ``I've got to win Illinois,'' Dole said bluntly at one campaign
stop. Later, speaking to Northwestern University law school
students, Dole made it even more clear that his political survival
was at stake. He renewed a challenge to Bush to participate in a
series of freewheeling one-one-one debates.
   ``I just appeal to George Bush. Here's a chance, George, to
finish me off right here in Illinois,'' Dole said. The debate
challenge is mentioned at every campaign stop and is a key part of
Dole's strategy to try to draw Bush into a discussion of issues and
break his link to President Reagan. Dole attributes Bush's sweep of
the 17 Super Tuesday primaries and caucuses to Reagan's popularity.
   ``George Bush is running like Ronald Reagan,'' said Dole. ``It's
tough to beat Ronald Reagan. I can't beat him. I can beat Bush, but
beating Ronald Reagan is impossible. Bush has wrapped himself
around Reagan and it's been very effective.''
   Dole never misses an opportunity to chip away at Bush's record
and to raise questions about the vice president's ability to defeat
a Democrat in the November general election.
   ``I don't have any real quarrel with George Bush except I think
I'm a stronger person. I think I know more about the issues. I
think I'm a better leader,'' Bush told a group of lawyers at a
downtown Chicago reception.
   Already, the Dole campaign is airing television advertising in
Illinois that touts Dole's leadership in the Senate and focuses on
what the Kansan says are nine different answers by Bush to his role
in the Iran-Contra arms-for-hostages affair. Similar ads were used
to no avail against Bush in the South.
   But increasingly, Dole is highlighting the ``electability''
question in his attempts to revive his campaign _ even though he
concedes ``it's hard to make that an issue.''
   ``I think there is one person between me and the White House and
that is George Bush,'' Dole quipped at the lawyers' reception. ``I
think there are a couple of people between him and the White
House.''
   Dole told supporters ``if I can turn it around in Illinois ...
then the momentum changes.''
   ``The Republicans, I think, will take a deep breath and
reconsider the choice before them,'' he said. ``And that's why I
take heart that I'm sort of back in the heartland.''
</TEXT>
