<1ST_LINE>r i BC-Waldheim-TextExcerpts     03-10 0679</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Waldheim-Text Excerpts,0697</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Excerpts from Waldheim's Speech</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For Release at 2:15 p.m. EST _ Times Set By Source</NOTE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are excerpts of a televised speech
Thursday by President Kurt Waldheim as Austria remembers the Nazi
annexation of March 1938. The text was translated from German by
The Associated Press.
   
   In these days, we are remembering the events which 50 years ago
led us into the darkest epoch of our recent history.
   ... There were also hundreds of thousands of Austrians, who
welcomed the Anschluss, who feted Hitler and the invasion and
pinned many false hopes on it.
   It was a mass psychosis of a kind that only totalitarian regimes
can create. Today we know that one should resist the very
beginnings of intolerance and instigation. Today we know where the
fanning of fanaticism, hate and violence lead.
   Today we know that, with March 11, 1938, an avalanche of
suffering was triggered.
   It was an avalanche of suffering that buried those who thought
differently and, in a terrible racial mania, buried our Jewish
fellow citizens. The Holocaust is one of the greatest tragedies of
world history. Millions of Jewish people were annihilated in the
concentration camps. Nothing can explain or excuse those crimes. I
bow in deep respect before these victims, who must always be a
reminder and a duty for us.
   The avalanche of suffering also caught up countless men and
women of the resistance, who had to give their life for the freedom
of Austria.
   We must not forget that many of the worst Nazi hangmen were
Austrians. There were Austrians who were victims and others who
were perpetrators. Let us not give rise to the impression that we
had nothing to do with this. Obviously there is no collective
guilt. Nevertheless, as head of state of the Republic of Austria, I
wish to apologize for Nazi crimes committed by Austrians.
   But as a state, Austria was Hitler's first victim. That is
indisputable. Though it resisted Hitler's political and economic
pressure for years, it went under. The international community of
states gave us no help against the aggression.
   Our country is open to criticism. As the head of state of our
republic, however, I would ask the critics to be fair and
objective. I would ask them not only to see Austria in the light of
the horrors of the past, but in the light of how it has stood the
test in the present.
   I ask you to refrain from blanket charges and from unqualified
accusations and to look at Austria as it stands in the late 1980s:
secure and open to dialogue, open to the world, ready to assist,
self-assured and pointed toward the future.
   But as your elected president, I also appeal to you, my dear
countrywomen and countrymen, to wrestle with the shadows of the
past. The meaning of these days lies in reflection, not in dispute.
... The meaning of these days can be only one thing: reconciliation.
   The ugly storm of scandals which has confronted us in the last
years underlies the necessity of a basic reform of public life ...
of an improvement of moral standards for all who have to act and
work in the public interest. In the coming months, I will use the
authority of this office to discuss the perspectives and contours
of such a reform with representatives of all political institutions
in Austria.
   The moral renewal of our republic is an undertaking which can
only have the desired success if it is supported and carried by all
those responsible.
   Let us assume resonsibility for our mistakes in a way that would
encourage avoiding mistakes in the future. Let us love our country
without false shame and arrogant pride so that Austria also finds a
place in the hearts of youth:
   _ as a country that has come to terms with itself,
   _ as a country which has learned from history,
   _ as a country that despite some mistakes deserves affection,
   _ as our common ``much tested, much loved'' Austria.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880310-0123 </DOCNO>
