<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Nancy-Skin     03-10 0241</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nancy-Skin,240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Non-Cancerous Patch Of Skin Removed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A dermatologist removed a small patch of skin
from Nancy Reagan's upper lip and tests show it to be
non-cancerous, her spokeswoman said Thursday.
   ``It was from too much sun,'' Mrs. Reagan's press secretary,
Elaine Crispen, said.
   The first lady ``had a little scraping'' done to remove the skin
patch and no stiches were required, Mrs. Crispen said. She was
informed of the results of the tests on Monday, the spokeswoman
added.
   The procedure was performed at the White House over the weekend
by Adm. William Narva, a U.S. Naval dermatologist who is the
attending physician to Congress, the spokeswoman said.
   The first lady wore a small adhesive bandage for two days but is
no longer wearing one, Mrs. Crispen said.
   The procedure marked the second time the first lady has had a
growth removed from the area. In 1982, a growth was removed that
was diagnosed as a basal cell carcinoma.
   Last August, President Reagan had a skin cancer identified as a
basal cell epithelioma removed from the tip of his nose. It was his
third procedure in three years dealing with skin cancer.
   In their younger days and as residents of California, Reagan and
his wife spent many hours in the sun. Since their bouts with skin
cancer, they have changed their habits, wearing sunblock and hats
when they venture outdoors and advising others to do the same.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
