<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-88 1242EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-RobinHood Bjt   03-10 0627</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Robin Hood, Bjt,0643</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Not All is Merry in Nottingham as City Debunks Robin Hood</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCUS ELIASON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fans of Robin Hood are up in arms and the city of
Nottingham has been accused of shooting itself in the wallet by
putting out a tourism brochure debunking the legend of the medieval
outlaw.
   The glossy color brochure takes a skeptical academic line on
Robin Hood, his love affair with Maid Marian, the existence of his
faithful lieutenant Friar Tuck and that he robbed the rich to give
to the poor.
   ``We are not debunking anything. We are putting Robin Hood in
historical context,'' insisted City Council spokesman Tim Jones.
   ``The city fathers have done a disservice to their own city,''
countered Malcolm Barker of the Robin Hood Society, who took up the
cudgels on the outlaw's behalf.
   Barker doesn't claim that the story, as handed down by
Hollywood, is true. He simply objects to tinkering with a beautiful
legend that also is a major tourist attraction.
   ``If Mickey Mouse can bring a fortune into Florida, why
shouldn't Robin Hood bring a fortune in to the people of
Nottingham?'' he said in a British radio interview.
   The affair came to light Thursday in London's Daily Telegraph in
a report headlined ``Robin Hood is robbed of myth and romance.''
   The brochure undermines many of the popular notions about Robin
Hood and his band of merry men, not to mention his favorite woman.
   Maid Marian, it says, comes from a 13th century French poem,
while chubby Friar Tuck is probably an amalgam of two characters
from different parts of England.
   As for Robin himself, the brochure notes that in the earliest
tales, he was a highwayman who robbed travelers in neighboring
Yorkshire and was in business strictly for himself.
   Graham Black, curator of Nottingham Castle Museum and a
historian whose work contributed to the brochure, was quoted by the
Telegraph as saying: ``One of the problems about Robin Hood is that
the legend is 700 years old, a story handed on by word of mouth,
and it was 200 years before people became literate.''
   His philanthropy was ``the fashionable academic interpretation
of the 1950s,'' Black said. ``But there is no evidence for this.''
   Jones said in an interview that the legend took its present form
under the 19th century Victorians.
   It remains a potent one. When Raisa Gorbachev, wife of the
Soviet leader, visited Nottingham in 1984, city officials said she
asked about Robin Hood, apparently regarding him as a socialist who
believed in the redistribution of wealth.
   Barker, the outlaw's defender, said: ``Does it really matter?
... It's an adman's dream. We've got something here that is
wonderful. Visitors come from all over the world that know about
Robin Hood and Maid Marian, and I think that the city fathers have
done a disservice to their own city.''
   Nottingham, a city of 290,000 people in central England, can
hardly be accused of neglecting the legend. Its main beltway is
called Maid Marian Way, and two rival consortiums are planning
Robin Hood exhibition centers for the city.
   Hordes of tourists visit the Sherwood Forest Center where they
can see displays of medieval lifestyles and gaze at the oak tree
where the merry men may or may not have relaxed after a hard day's
archery.
   Brian Marshal, chairman of the city tourism council that
produced the brochure, says the debate about Maid Marian is largely
irrelevant. People are more interested in Robin Hood versus the
Sheriff of Nottingham, he said, ``because it's always the good guy
against the bad guy, isn't it.''
   ``I think people will feel what they feel. If they want to
believe in Maid Marian then they'll do that,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880310-0125 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-88 1246EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Toshiba-Submarines     03-10 0471</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Toshiba-Submarines,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pentagon Can't Assess Damage From Toshiba Submarine Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon doesn't know whether the sale of
Japanese machine milling equipment helped the Soviet Union build
quieter submarines, according to a top Defense Department official.
   The Soviet Union was building quiet propellers for its subs
three years before the Toshiba equipment was exported between 1983
and 1985, said Richard Armitage, assistant secretary of defense for
international security affairs.
   Armitage's assessment was contained in a letter outlining the
Pentagon's opposition to congressional proposals which would limit
or ban the sale of Toshiba products in the United States.
   Toshiba officials admitted last year that a subsidiary company
had sold the Soviet Union machine tools for making quiet submarine
propellers.
   Navy officials have said in the past that Soviet subs were
noisier than their American counterparts, making it easier for the
United States to keep track of the Soviet subs. Both sides are
continually seeking to develop quieter submarines.
   Armitage's views were outlined in a letter to Rep. Les Aspin,
D-Wis., chairman of the House Armed Services Committee. The letter
was released Thursday.
   ``The indignation felt in the United States is understandable,''
Armitage said. He added that ``Perhaps some Americans don't fully
realize that many Japanese feel a similar indignation complemented
by acute embarrassment.''
   ``The actual damage done from the Toshiba Machinery diversions
is difficult to assess,'' Armitage said.
   ``Despite allegations of tens of even $100 billion in damages,
our Navy cannot determine the direct costs of this diversion to
U.S. national security because the Soviets had quiet propellers
three years before the first diversion and we had already planned
programs to deal with this development,'' he said.
   A conference committee of 20 House members and seven senators is
trying to work out House-Senate differences on an omnibus trade
bill, and one of the unresolved issues involves Toshiba.
   The House bill contains no sanctions against the company, while
the Senate version would ban the sale of any Toshiba products in
the United States for two years to five years. Toshiba has annual
U.S. sales of $3 billion to $4 billion.
   ``Actions by the U.S. government against Toshiba would be
interpreted in Japan as motivated by trade imbalances, rather than
by national security concerns,'' Armitage said.
   He predicted that Japanese efforts to protect sensitive
technology ``will greatly improve as a result of what has happened,
but only if we don't undercut the post-Toshiba actions'' by the
Japanese government, which he described as ``unprecedented.''
   The Pentagon is considering whether to sell the Japanese navy
four Aegis ship defense systems, costing $1 billion each. The
system contains the Navy's most sophisticated anti-aircraft
electronic gear, and some critics in Congress have questioned
whether the Aegis sale is a good idea in the wake of the Toshiba
case.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880310-0126 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-88 1302EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-US-Panama 2ndLd-Writethru a0635 03-10 0784</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Panama, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0635,760</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: First 3 grafs new with vote, picking up 3rd graf pvs, ``Now
is</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House today overwhelmingly demanded the
ouster of Panamanian strongman Manuel Antonio Noriega and urged
President Reagan to impose strong sanctions to encourage
restoration of civilian rule in Panama.
   Before the 367-2 roll call vote on an anti-Noriega resolution,
the Panamanian military ruler was denounced during floor debate as
``a gunrunning thug'' and ``one of the most ruthless tyrants of our
time.''
   Voting against the resolution were representatives George W.
Crockett Jr., D-Mich., and Henry B. Gonzalez, D-Texas.
   ``Now is the time for Gen. Noriega to step down and open the
door for true democracy in Panama,'' said Rep. Benjamin Gilman,
R-N.Y.
   Said Rep. Dan Mica, D-Fla.: ``Noriega must leave, and he must
leave quickly.''
   The resolution, sponsored chiefly by Mica, said the House ``is
deeply concerned about the deterioration of United
States-Panamanian relations'' and calls on Noriega to comply with
President Eric Arturo Delvalle's order dismissing him as commander
of the Panamanian defense forces.
   The resolution also ``calls on the president to consider
seriously the range of additional economic and political sanctions
available to the United States that could be used to encourage the
re-establishment of civilian authority in Panama.'''
   The House action came as the Reagan administration studied tough
new sanctions against Panama, and two prominent Panamanian
diplomats deserted the Noriega government.
   Santiago Torrijos, nephew of former Panamanian leader Omar
Torrijos, abandoned his post as consul general in Los Angeles and
flew to Washington to join forces with allies of the ousted
Delvalle.
   Torrijos' late uncle was widely esteemed in Panama for
negotiating with President Carter for the treaty under which the
Panama Canal will revert to Panama by the year 2000. The former
consul general accused the Noriega regime of plunging Panama into a
political crisis.
   Panamanian Ambassador Juan B. Sosa, who supports Delvalle, said
Wednesday that Santiago Torrijos' decision to break with Noriega
will have a major impact on Panama because of the close
identification of the Torrijos family with Panama's Defense Forces.
Torrijos is believed to be the first member of the Torrijos family
to break ranks with Noriega.
   Omar Torrijos dominated Panama's political life from 1968 until
his death in a plane crash in 1981. In a typewritten statement made
public Wednesday night, his nephew said a ``political, financial,
moral and social crisis'' exists in Panama and must be resolved.
   He said that a ``small political-military circle'' has betrayed
the pledge of Omar Torrijos to return Panama to constitutional rule.
   Meanwhile, the Panamanian Embassy made public a copy of a letter
by Panama's Ambassador to Mexico, Emilia Arosemena Vallarino, in
which she announced her resignation because she was ``in
disagreement with political events'' in her country. She had served
in Mexico for 18 years and was dean of the diplomatic corps there.
   At issue are the circumstances under which Panama's new
government took power two weeks ago. Delvalle attempted to fire
Noriega but was fired himself hours later.
   The Reagan administration, along with a number of Panamanian
diplomats and consular officers, have refused to recognize the
successor government, regarding Delvalle as the constitutional
authority. He has remained in hiding for almost two weeks.
   Today, high-level meetings were scheduled at which
administration officials were considering a series of economic
sanctions against Panama.
   U.S. officials, who asked not to be identified, said that it is
almost certain that the United States will withhold a $6.5 million
payment due to Panama on March 15 for canal-related operations.
   Also being considered are measures that would have the effect of
making some Panamanian products less competitive in U.S. markets.
State Department figures show that Panama's U.S. exports totaled
$342 million last year, but Commerce Department statistics list
that category at $388 million.
   The officials said Panama may lose its right to participate in
the Caribbean Basin Initiative, under which some products are
allowed duty-free access to the United States.
   To be eligible to take part, nations of Central America and the
Caribbean must cooperate in combatting drug smuggling to the United
States.
   The Reagan administration has concluded that Panama has not been
cooperating, and two federal grand juries have handed down
indictments accusing Noriega of being a key figure in an
international drug trafficking operation.
   But White House chief of staff Howard Baker denied Wednesday
that the United States is planning an invasion of Panama, saying
American troops there are merely holding regularly scheduled
training exercises.
   Jorge Abadia, Panama's foreign minister, this week accused the
United States of conducting ``the prelude of an armed invasion'' by
staging military exercises along the Panama Canal.
</TEXT>
