<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Mecham 1stLd-Writethru a0490 03-10 0693</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mecham, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0490,0714</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Top Aide Contradicts Governor</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Rewrites throughout to UPDATE with today's testimony, edit.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE ASSEO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Evan Mecham's former chief of staff
testified today at the governor's impeachment trial that he would
not have directed the state's public safety director to stonewall
an investigation, as the governor is accused of doing.
   Mecham, who faces removal from office by the state Senate, is
accused of trying to thwart an investigation into an alleged death
threat by then-state prison construction chief Lee Watkins against
a former Mecham aide, Donna Carlson. The threat allegedly was made
as Ms. Carlson was about to appear before a grand jury
investigating Mecham's campaign finances. Watkins has denied
threatening Ms. Carlson.
   Mecham also is accused of concealing a $350,000 campaign loan
and misusing $80,000 from the governor's protocol fund by loaning
it to his auto dealership.
   Richard Burke, the governor's first defense witness, was
cross-examined by prosecutor William French in his second day on
the stand.
   He acknowledged that he would not have made the statements that
Mecham is accused of making Nov. 15 to Department of Public Safety
Director Ralph Milstead.
   French quoted from statements Milstead has testified Mecham made
regarding plans for Officer Frank Martinez and Lt. Beau Johnson to
give statements to the attorney general's office about the alleged
threat.
   ``Would you under any circumstances, Mr. Burke, tell Mr.
Milstead `I don't want Frank or Beau giving any statements to the
attorney general.' Would you say that?'' French asked.
   ``No,'' Burke replied.
   ``Would you say this: `Don't tell the attorney general
anything,''' French said.
   ``No,'' Burke answered.
   Burke, a former law school dean and federal prosecutor who came
out of retirement last November to serve as Mecham's chief of
staff, said he believed Mecham understood that a serious threat may
have been made against Carlson, although Burke was not certain
whether it was specified that it was an alleged death threat.
   ``I think all of us assumed that it was a crime, or a potential
crime, or it wouldn't have been reported to us,'' Burke said.
   French asked whether it was Milstead's job to report the alleged
crime ``and the governor would not have the authority to stop it.''
   ``My impression of law enforcement, certainly that would be
true,'' Burke said.
   Burke said, however, that he agreed with Mecham's contention in
a television interview several days after he was told about the
alleged threat that he knew little about it.
   During House impeachment hearings in January, Mecham insisted
that the report to the Department of Public Safety violated an
unwritten rule against disclosing things that happen in the
governor's office.
   The prosecution rested its case Wednesday on the death threat
allegation, the first of the three major charges against Mecham.
   ``No man is above the law,'' prosecutor Paul Eckstein said in
his closing argument. ``The evidence that has been put before you
cries out ... for a conviction.''
   Defense lawyer Fred Craft argued that prosecutors had not proven
Mecham tried to obstruct an investigation because ``nobody told the
governor that there was indeed an attorney general's investigation
that he could possibly obstruct.''
   Mecham, 63, who ran an auto dealership before he was elected
governor in a three-way race, has contended he handled the matter
properly by having Watkins' boss, then-Department of Administration
Director Max Hawkins, investigate.
   A two-thirds vote of the 30-member Senate is required to convict
Mecham and remove the first-term Republican from office.
   The governor also faces an April 21 criminal trial on charges of
hiding the $350,000 loan, and a May 17 recall election.
   Maricopa County Superior Court Judge Michael Ryan said Wednesday
he was ``reluctantly'' granting a prosecution motion to delay the
criminal trial, which had been scheduled to start March 22. The
judge said more time was needed to decide pretrial motions and
gather a large pool of potential jurors.
   Mecham, the first U.S. governor to be impeached in six decades,
has not attended the impeachment trial, but senators Wednesday were
shown a Nov. 16 TV interview in which he denied knowledge of the
alleged death threat.
</TEXT>
