<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Iditarod 2ndLd-Writethru a0561 03-10 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iditarod, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0561,0373</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Redington Into Cripple At Front Of Pack
^Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to UPDATE standings, picking up 6th graf
pvs, `Several racers ....'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede McGRATH, Alaska</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CRIPPLE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 70-year-old man known as the ``Father
of the Iditarod' pocketed $2,500 in silver ingots today for being
the first to reach the half-way point of the 1,100-mile Iditarod
Trail Sled Dog Race.
   Joe Redington of Knik reached the Cripple checkpoint at 5:40
a.m. His nearest competitor, Herbie Nayokpuk of Shishmaref, checked
into Ophir, 55 miles behind Redington, at 11:10 p.m. Wednesday.
   Redington, a founder of the mushing marathon from Anchorage to
Nome, now heads for the Sulatna Crossing and then to Ruby on the
Yukon River. He has raced in all but two of the 16 Iditarods,
finishing three times in fifth place.
   Four-time champion Rick Swenson of Two Rivers was running third.
He checked out of Takotna at 8:37 p.m. Wednesday. He was followed
by Joe Garnie of Teller, Jan Masek of Anchorage and DeeDee Jonrowe
of Bethel.
   Defending champion Susan Butcher of Manley was seventh.
   Several racers said that despite Redington's lead, Nayokpuk is
now the musher to beat because of his strong dog team.
   ``I think it's going to take us quite a while to gain that kind
of time back, unless he runs into some kind of situation up
ahead,'' Swenson said.
   A blizzard pounding Alaska's southwestern coast threatened to
turn into complicate things on the Iditarod trail for the racers.
If the gale-driven snow reaches inland to the Iditarod Trail, the
going could turn slow.
   At the back of the pack, 290 miles behind the leaders, the
oldest Iditarod musher announced that he was dropping out of the
race. Norman Vaughan, 82, said three of his dogs were in heat and
he had whiteout conditions ahead.
   Another musher, Ray Dronenburg of Trapper Creek, also scratched
Wednesday, saying several of his dogs were weak with a virus. That
leaves 50 mushers in the race, which started Saturday.
   A $30,000 first prize awaits the winner, who is expected to
reach Nome sometime next week. The next 19 finishers will split the
rest of the $150,000 purse.
</TEXT>
