<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-SouthKorea     03-10 0248</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-South Korea,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz Sees `Political Miracle' In South Korea</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz said
Thursday that South Korea has accomplished a ``political miracle''
in its peaceful transition to civilian rule.
   ``I think the Korean situation is one we've all watched very
closely and worked on hard,'' he told members of the House foreign
operations appropriations subcommittee. ``And in (South) Korea they
have managed to put a political miracle alongside their economic
miracle.''
   However, Shultz said later that it would be bold to predict when
U.S. troops could be withdrawn.
   He said President Chun Doo-Hwan ``engineered this change and
takes considerable pride in being the first leader of Korea to pass
the leadership to somebody else in a peaceful transition of power.
So it's a major and important event.''
   He promised U.S. support to the new government,
   Shultz was asked about reports that the 40,000 U.S. troops could
be withdrawn by 1990. He replied that he thought no date could be
set.
   The United States would like to see more stability in the Korean
peninsula, he said.
   ``But there is a very militaristic North Korea, whose
performance has been terrible,'' he went on.
   Shultz said there was ``quite compelling'' evidence that North
Korean intelligence was responsible for blowing up an airliner.
   Progress is most likely by taking small steps such as exchanging
family members, he said, adding that the holding of the Olympic
games in Korea will also be a positive element.
</TEXT>
