<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-88 1348EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Gephardt     03-10 0566</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gephardt,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gephardt Opens ``Full Force'' Michigan Drive</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE GLOVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LANSING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Richard Gephardt opened a ``full force''
drive in Michigan Thursday, two days after finishing a poor fourth
among Democrats on Super Tuesday, and said, ``If we don't do well
here obviously we aren't going to be able to continue in this
race.''
   Most of the other Democratic presidential candidates were in
Illinois campaigning for that state's primary, which is next
Tuesday. And Gephardt, too, was joining the others in Chicago
Thursday night at a dinner and town meeting.
   But he said as he arrived for a rally on the Michigan Statehouse
steps, ``Our real thrust, our real force is going to be in
Michigan.''
   Michigan's Democratic caucus is March 26.
   ``We have a long road to go,'' Gephardt said. ``Let's go the
next step. I think Michigan is going to be a real test of every
campaign. We're going to do well in Michigan and when we do we'll
be right back in the middle of this.''
   Gerphardt, fighting against talk that his campaign may be
nearing an end, held up a copy of Thursday's Wall Street Journal
which said he had failed the test of a successful candidate.
   ``I think The Wall Street Journal is dead wrong,'' he declared.
   He met with legislators and local Democratic officials in a
state where he said his message will be well received.
   Earlier in the day, he campaigned in South Carolina, which holds
caucuses on Saturday.
   While the other Democratic presidential hopefuls have spent most
of the week focusing on delegate-rich Illinois, Gephardt is trying
to portray Michigan's voting as the next major test of the
Democratic campaign.
   ``We're going to be there in full force,'' Gephardt said.
``After that, we'll see where we are and where we go.''
   In Michigan, said deputy campaign manager Joe Trippi, ``we need
to win it or at least come in second to Jesse,'' a reference to
Jesse Jackson.
   Trippi said as many as 70 paid staffers would be sent to
Michigan by next week, compared to roughly 20 staffers in Illinois.
   ``We'll take virtually every organizer we have,'' he said.
   ``We had our bad day on Super Tuesday, but now we're back and
we're still in the middle of this race,'' Gephardt said.
   Gephardt rejected any comparisons with New York Rep. Jack Kemp,
who dropped from the Republican presidential race earlier Thursday.
   He pointed to his strong showings in several early contests,
including victories in Iowa and South Dakota, and said he has the
backing of 80 members of Congress, most of whom will be delegates
to the Democratic National Convention this summer.
   ``Unlike Jack Kemp, I have been in the middle of this race from
the beginning,'' Gephardt said. ``I have a delegate count that is
within striking distance of being back in the leadership.''
   Throughout the day on Thursday, Gephardt continued to hammer at
the central theme of his campaign, talking tough on trade. That's
designed to appeal in South Carolina, where the textile industry
has been damaged by foreign competition, as well as in Michigan
with its auto industry.
   The United Auto Workers Union, a major force in Michigan
Democratic politics, is remaining neutral, but Gephardt aides said
they anticipated getting support from union locals and
rank-and-file members because of his trade and economic positions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
