<DOCNO> AP880310-0134 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-88 1350EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Berlin-Escape     03-10 0455</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Berlin-Escape,0473</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three East Germans in Truck Smash Border Barriers at ``Bridge of
Spies''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRIEDER REIMOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three East Germans crashed a flatbed truck through
steel barriers and roared over Glienicker Bridge into West Berlin
on Thursday in the first escape of its kind over the famed ``Bridge
of Spies,'' officials said.
   Bernd Puhlmann, who drove the truck in the high-speed escape to
the West, said a Soviet soldier on the East German side of the
bridge took aim at the vehicle but did not fire.
   Pulhmann said he thought that empty propane tanks that had been
loaded onto the truck may have accounted for the soldier's
reluctance.
   ``Because the soldier didn't know what was in the tanks, he
probably did not dare to shoot,'' the 37-year-old Puhlmann told
reporters.
   Puhlmann said he and his two friends decided while drinking beer
about midnight to make the escape.
   Two hours later, the 7{-ton truck plowed through two East German
metal gates and a chainlink fence before racing onto the Glienicker
Bridge, which has been made famous by numerous East-West spy
exchanges.
   The truck sped across the bridge, smashing through another East
German-built chainlink fence and tearing off a steel control gate
in West Berlin before coming to a halt, police said.
   With the truck demolished, the three escapees got out uninjured
and called West Berlin authorities, said a West Berlin police
spokesman who asked not to be further identified.
   ``This is the first time that anyone has broken through those
barriers,'' said another police officer.
   Glienicker Bridge connects Potsdam, East Germany with West
Berlin. Potsdam is on Berlin's southwest outskirts.
   The truck's impact tore the 4-foot-high steel gate on the West
Berlin side of the bridge off its foundation and twisted the
barrier into a half-circle.
   Wrecked barriers could be seen on the East German side of the
bridge as well.
   Metal, glass, plastic and motor oil from the truck were strewn
across the area.
   The demolished truck sat with its engine compartment smashed and
bumpers dangling.
   Puhlmann said he, Gotthard Ihden, 37, and Werner Jaeger, 28, all
of Potsdam, decided to try the escape because they were
dissatisfied with political conditions in communist East Germany.
   West Berlin officials said the three may face charges of
destroying property and driving dangerously.
   Among the most famous spy swaps on the bridge was the Feb. 10,
1962 exchange by the United States of convicted Soviet KGB master
spy Col. Rudolph Abel for Francis Gary Powers, whose U-2
surveillance plane was shot down over the Soviet Union.
   Many refugees fled over the bridge to West Berlin after the East
German workers' uprising in 1953, but the barriers there had never
been breached.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
