<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-88 1401EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Jesse-BlackMachine Bjt   03-10 0709</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jesse-Black Machine, Bjt,710</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Supporters Mobilizing Black Vote in Illinois</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. HIDLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Illinois blacks will deliver their primary vote
almost exclusively to favorite son Jesse Jackson next Tuesday, but
black leaders credit the monolithic vote to Jackson's charisma and
not a Daley-style political machine.
   Jackson, who has had his differences with the black hierarchy in
his adopted hometown of Chicago, doesn't need a machine to ensure
the black vote, observers say.
   ``This is a movement vote that is bigger than the capabilities
of any ward committeeman or political organizer,'' said Don Rose, a
longtime Chicago political consultant who predicts Jackson will win
up to 95 percent of the black vote in the Illinois primary.
   But Jackson's supporters are working hard to mobilize that vote
and _ more importantly _ to make sure supporters realize the
necessity of also voting for Jackson's slated convention delegates
in Illinois.
   Illinois' beauty pageant primary is separate from the election
of 173 delegates to the Democratic National Convention.
   Jackson is fielding full delegate slates in only 17 of the
state's 22 congressional districts. He is one delegate short in
four other districts and has no slate in the nearly all-white
suburbs on Chicago's northwest side.
   The black vote alone won't be enough to give Jackson a victory
in the Illinois primary _ and may not be enough to lock up second
place, Rose said.
   He predicted the black vote would amount to between 23 percent
and 25 percent of the entire Democratic vote in Illinois. ``If he
gets 10 percent of the white vote, that would give him 30 percent
and make it unlikely for him to carry the state,'' Rose said.
   ``Right now, there is a tremendous fervor in the community for
Jesse after the outcome of Super Tuesday,'' said Chicago Alderman
Danny Davis, a black leader and Jackson supporter. ``I've heard
people ... talking about how it was the second coming.''
   Jackson returned in triumph Wednesday to Chicago, his political
base for nearly two decades, reminding voters, ``I am a charter
member of the underclass, the son of a teen-age mother who was the
daughter of a teen-age mother. I was able to break the shackles.''
   Jackson rose to national prominence from Chicago's predominantly
black South Side where he started a civil rights group called
Operation PUSH in the early 1970s.
   He owns a home in a middle-class Chicago neighborhood and
regularly returns to PUSH headquarters to speak at the group's
weekly Saturday meetings, which often take on the flavor of a
church revival meeting.
   Davis and other political observers predicted that Jackson's
Chicago political base would help him win about 95 percent of the
black vote in Illinois and up to 10 percent of the white vote _
roughly the proportions he won in the Super Tuesday primaries.
   But they say he'll carry the black vote without relying on the
type of ward-boss political machine that has permeated Chicago
history, most recently under the late Mayor Richard Daley.
   ``There is not a black political machine in the formal sense,''
said Rose, who worked for the late Mayor Harold Washington, the
city's first black mayor.
   ``There is a mobilized black vote _ the product of the Harold
Washington years,'' Rose said Wednesday. ``Jesse is able to pull it
together and he will deliver an overwhelming black vote of 90
percent to 95 percent.
   ``But that's not the product of anybody's machine,'' Rose said.
``That's a product of Jesse's charisma and popularity among black
voters.''
   Jackson had the support of Washington in 1984 and of current
Mayor Eugene Sawyer this year. But he and Washington were largely
allies of political convenience, and Jackson actively backed
another black alderman over Sawyer in the political fighting that
followed Washington's death last November.
   East St. Louis Mayor Carl Officer, a longtime Jackson supporter,
will deliver the Democratic contender the bulk of the black vote in
that Southern Illinois city, said several Jackson supporters.
   Jackson also will be counting on the black church, long a
political base for him, to help mobilize voters, Chicago Alderman
Tim Evans said. On Sunday, he said, black ministers throughout the
city likely will preach to their parishioners to vote for Jackson.
</TEXT>
