<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Kenya     03-10 0197</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Kenya,0204</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Question Kenyan Editor Who Criticized Elections</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Security police on Thursday questioned the
editor of a church-sponsored magazine after he charged that some
voters were intimidated by the government in recent primary
elections, a colleague said.
   During the Feb. 22 elections, voters were required to line up at
polling places behind their candidate or someone representing him.
   Chief Editor Bedan Mbugua called the system ``a mockery of
democracy'' in Monday's edition of Beyond magazine, which is
sponsored by the National Council of Churches of Kenya. He charged
that some voters were intimidated by administration officials into
voting for certain candidates.
   Ibrahim Omondi, associate editor of Beyond, said Mbugua reported
to security police, but no details of the investigation were
available.
   The general secretary of the Kenya African Nation Union, the
country's sole legal political party, acknowledged mistakes during
the primary, but he accused Beyond of sloppy and unfair reporting.
   ``It is one-sided and self-serving,'' Burudi Nabwera said at a
news conference. ``It is difficult to understand how the magazine
could have drawn conclusions after looking partially at only five
constituencies.''
   General elections on March 21 will be by secret ballot.
</TEXT>
