<1ST_LINE>u a PM-ThrillKilling 3rdLd-Writethru a0672-674-s 03-10 0662</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Thrill Killing, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0672-674-677,0679</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Teen-Ager Convicted In Beating Death Of Classmate</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Combines pvs.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DEDHAM, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 15-year-old boy was convicted of
second-degree murder and sentenced to life in prison today for
beating a classmate to death with a baseball bat so he could see
what it was like to kill someone.
   Rod Matthews showed no reaction when the verdict was announced
and his sentence immediately imposed. The verdict, issued at 2:10
p.m., followed nearly 10 hours of deliberation over two days.
   The victim's mother sobbed as the verdict was announced, and
Matthews' mother sat silently with lowered head.
   Matthews' mental state was the focus of closing arguments
Wednesday in Norfolk Superior Court.
   The jurors began their work after Judge Roger J. Donahue
explained again the various possible convictions available and
outlining the basis for acquittal by reason of insanity.
   Prosecutors, who were seeking a first-degree murder conviction
for the Nov. 20, 1986, slaying, depicted Matthews as a
dispassionate murderer who plotted for weeks to lure 14-year-old
Shaun Ouillette to a secluded area ``to find out what it was like
to kill somebody.''
   Defense attorney John Philip White, calling for acquittal by
reason of insanity, called Matthews an irrational, ``diseased
intellect'' who appealed for help before the killing but was
ignored by a teacher and friends.
   Matthews, tried as an adult, had faced a mandatory sentence of
life imprisonment without parole if convicted of first-degree
murder. If found guilty of second-degree murder, the maximum
penalty is life imprisonment with a chance of parole in 15 years.
   If Matthews had been found innocent by reason of insanity, he
would have been evaluated by the state Department of Mental Health,
White said.
   District Attorney Peter Casey portrayed Matthews as a troubled
youth who was prompted to kill by his own desires, not by mental
illness.
   ``He did that because he doesn't care about anybody,'' said
Casey, who repeatedly jabbed an accusatory finger at Matthews
during closing arguments. ``What did it feel like? It was
deliberate. ... He really wound up and hit him about the head.''
   Matthews chose Ouillette as the victim after rejecting two other
classmates as targets because two of his friends objected, Casey
said.
   Ouillette, who moved to Canton with his family about two years
before the slaying, was selected because Matthews felt he would not
be missed, according to testimony during the week-long trial.
   Matthews said he had plotted the killing for a month to
experience what killing someone was like, according to testimony
from two classmates who were shown the body by Matthews before a
pre-Thanksgiving pep rally.
   Ouillette's body was discovered in December 1986 after one of
the youths sent police an anonymous letter. None of the teen-agers
who knew of the slaying faces prosecution.
   White depicted Matthews as a highly unstable youth whose use of
Ritalin, a drug used mainly to control hyperactivity in children,
may have exacerbated his already unstable state.
   That contention is a smoke screen, Casey said, citing medical
experts' testimony that Ritalin does not permanently alter behavior
or trigger violence or hallucinations in normal doses.
   White also said Matthews unsuccessfully sought help prior to the
slaying in a letter to a teacher in which Matthews described his
desire to kill and light fires.
   ``Had they said, `No, don't kill Shaun Ouillette,' in all
likelihood Shaun Ouillette would not have been harmed,'' said White.
   The trial was attended each day by the victim's and defendant's
families and dozens of residents of Canton, a middle-class
community of 17,000 people about 15 miles south of Boston.
   The case has been compared to the 1982 trial of Anthony
Broussard, then 18, and sentenced 25 years to life in San Jose,
Calif., for killing his girlfriend the year before.
   Broussard, who was tried as an adult, took at least 13
schoolmates to see the victim's body. The movie ``The River's
Edge'' was based on that case.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880310-0144 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-88 1456EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Cuba-Prisons     03-10 0654</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cuba-Prisons,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cuban Penal System Has Positive, Negative Aspects, Group Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA </BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Cuban prison system is generally
constructive and humane for cooperative inmates but metes out
``harsh and cruel'' treatment to those who reject rehabilitation
programs, according to a report released Thursday.
   The report was prepared by the Institute for Policy Studies, a
liberal research group based in Washington which sponsored a visit
by a six-member delegation to Cuba from Feb. 26 to March 5.
   The delegation, which visited six prisons at various locations
around the island and conducted more than 120 ``confidential''
interviews, said it found a number of ``constructive aspects'' to
the Cuban system:
   _The great majority of prisoners work a regular work week at
productive jobs under conditions similar to those of ordinary
workers. Many acquire practical skills during confinement and have
opportunities to advance their education.
   _Almost all the prisoners who work are paid, receiving the same
rate as civilians except for certain discounts to cover cost of
living.
   _The regular prison facilities were all clean and hygenic, there
were no complaints of the use of ``instruments of torture'' and a
system of conjugal visits was well established.
   But the report also found that prisoners who resist re-education
or violate prison discipline are confined for extended periods, at
times in ``extremely harsh punishment cells _ bare, tiny, dark,
cold (or hot, depending on the season) _ sometimes with not enough
food.''
   One delegation member, Aryeh Neier, said the cells were five
feet by seven, had no bedding, only a primitive sanitary system and
housed three prisoners each.
   The delegation said it had heard reports of a few prisoners who
wore no clothes or only undershorts and shoes.
   Some prisoners who refuse to work are allowed sun only once a
week for an hour or two and are confined to iron cages too small to
take walks, the report said.
   Until recently, uncooperative prisoners were allowed visits only
once every six months but the delegation said new rules have
reduced this to once every 60 days, the report said.
   But a Cuban exile, Reinaldo Lopez Lima, who said he spent 23
years in Cuban prisons, told Neier during the news conference that
he spent eight of those years without a family visit. He described
prison conditions as ``terrible'' and said he knew of a dozen
prisoners who were killed early last year shortly before his
release.
   Under questioning, Neier said he was satisfied that the
delegation got an ``unfettered look'' at the Cuban prison system.
He said it would have been difficult for Cuban authorities to
restrict the delegation to ``showcase'' areas reserved for foreign
visitors because he had maps drawn for the delegation by former
prisoners.
   The visit came at a time when the Reagan administration is
making a concerted effort at the U.N. Human Rights Commission in
Geneva to make Cuba an agenda item at the 1989 commission session.
   In a speech to the commission on Tuesday, the U.S. ambassador to
the United Nations, Vernon Walters, said that Cuba has more than
200 prisons and labor camps and that there may be between 10,000 to
15,000 political prisoners.
   He said that a group of long-term political prisoners who have
refused rehabilitation began a hunger strike a week ago ``to
protest Havana's attempts to misinform the world about prison
conditions, torture and other mistreatment.''
   Neier noted that Amnesty International, a London-based human
rights group, claims to have the names of 600 political prisoners
and said he believes the actual number in that category is only
somewhat higher.
   The report said that the delegation interviewed at least 50
political prisoners, most of whom the group had selected in advance.
   The visit was undertaken at the suggestion of the Institute for
Policy Studies. In exchange, IPC agreed to seek similar access to
U.S. prisons by a delegation of Cuban legal experts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
