<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Contras-Talks     03-10 0443</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Contras-Talks,0459</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Contras Drop Demand Blocking Peace Talks, Blast U.S.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Nicaraguan Contras on Thursday dropped a demand
that had blocked peace talks with their homeland's Marxist
government, agreeing to the open agenda proposed by the Sandinistas.
   The rebel group made the announcement at a news conference here
where its leaders bitterly criticized the United States for cutting
off Contra aid.
   ``The United States has once again abandoned an ally,'' said
Adolfo Calero, one of six directors of the Nicaraguan Resistance.
``But we have been abandoned before. We will continue our efforts.''
   Calero said the rebels will now accept the proposed open agenda
for talks in Sapoa, Nicaragua, and suggested the talks begin March
16.
   ``We are ready to go to Sapoa,'' said Calero, who will head the
delegation.
   He said the Nicaraguan Resistance, as the Contras are formally
known, would no longer insist that the agenda include a program
hammered out during talks mediated by Nicaraguan Cardinal Miguel
Obando y Bravo in Guatemala last month. That included a 30-day
truce, political amnesty, press freedoms, an end to the draft, and
a dialogue with the opposition.
   The Contras proposed instead that the Sandinistas allow the
``internal opposition'' to attend the talks, but stopped short of
saying they would insist on that condition.
   The change in the Contras' position came one week after a Reagan
administration proposal to continue funding the rebels lost in a
close vote in the U.S. House of Representatives on March 3.
   Calero called the United States ``an inconsistent and
impermanent'' friend, in contrast to the Soviets, who support the
Sandinistas.
   He and fellow director Aristides Sanchez said the aid cutoff
might eventually hurt troops in the field, but insisted their
morale was still high.
   ``We will never surrender,'' said Calero.
   The Sandinistas have previously accepted Contra demands that
Obando y Bravo, whom the Nicaraguan government dropped as mediator,
attend the Sapoa talks as a witness.
   The Contras, in turn, accepted Organization of American States
head Javier Baena Soares as a second witness.
   Calero said Thursday that in previous communications the
Sandinistas have ``given every guarantee'' of the Contra
delegation's safety inside Nicaragua.
   Nicaraguan President Daniel Ortega had proposed the Sapoa talks
begin March 9, but the Contras begged off, saying they were only
notified the night of March 7.
   Last week, they asked instead for a meeting in Costa Rica to
discuss details of the talks, but Thursday's proposal made no
mention of a preliminary meeting.
   Calero said he had kept the United States _ which he referred to
as ``our ally, in quotes'' _ informed of the talks.
</TEXT>
