<HEAD>Singer Andy Gibb Dies</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 7th graf, `Gibbs' hit...' to CORRECT song title.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pop singer Andy Gibb, younger brother of the three
members of the Bee Gees rock group, died today in an Oxford
hospital after developing stomach pains, his record company said.
He was 30.
   A spokesman for Island Records Ltd. who spoke on condition he
not be identified said he could not release the cause of death.
   ``He was 30 years old. He was taken ill with stomach pains on
Monday and was admitted to hospital for observation and then he
died this morning,'' the record company said in a statement. ``The
reason for death has yet to be announced.''
   A spokesman for John Radcliffe Hospital in Oxford, 52 miles
northwest of London, confirmed Gibb died there at 8:45 a.m.
   ``I can't give you any further information than that,'' said
Colin Weston, the hospital's duty administrator.
   The record company spokesman said the Australian-born Gibb,
younger brother of Robin, Maurice and Barry who make up the Bee
Gees, signed a contract with Island Records two months ago and was
due to work on a new album this spring.
   Gibb's hit songs include ``I Just Want To Be Your Everything,''
in 1977, ``Shadow Dancing'' and ``An Everlasting Love'' in 1978 and
``(Our Love) Don't Throw It All Away'' in 1979.
   Gibb's manager, Robert Stigwood, said in New York he was ``very
sad and deeply distressed, and sorry. I have been in touch with his
parents and brothers. I will miss him.''
   Gibb's Miami lawyer, John Kozyak, said he received word of
Gibb's death from the Miami manager of the Bee Gees.
   ``This is really a shock,'' Kozyak said. The last time I saw
him, he looked perfectly healthy to me. He was playing tennis.''
   Dick Ashby, the Bee Gees' representative in Miami, said Gibb's
mother, Barbara Gibb, was with him when he died.
   Gibb lived in a penthouse apartment at Venetia on Biscayne Bay
in Miami.
   Last October, court papers filed in connection with Gibb's
bankruptcy proceedings in Miami showed Gibb earned only $7,755 in
1986 and lived rent-free while playing guitars loaned him by his
brothers.
   Kozyak said an investigation was under way into Gibb's death.
   ``The doctor was going to talk to him this morning and arrange
more tests, and he simply died,'' he said.
   Gibb, who co-hosted TV's ``Solid Gold'' in 1981 and 1982, had
six hit records in the late 1970s.
   He was born in Australia but had lived in the Miami area for
several years.
   Gibb got the Venetia apartment in exchange for promoting the
plush condominium complex. He had appeared at various celebrity
charity events around south Florida, including pro-celebrity tennis
matches in Miami and Fort Lauderdale.
   But he suffered financial setbacks in recent years and filed for
bankruptcy last September. At that time he estimated his debts at
more than $1 million and his assets at less than $50,000.
   Gibb had been in London about a month. Kozyak said Gibb's
bankruptcy was discharged from Miami federal court in January and
all of Gibb's debts were settled.
   Since then, Gibb ``was back on his feet and in good spirits and
trying to put together a record contract,'' he said.
</TEXT>
