<HEAD>Seventh-Graders Disciplined for Bringing Bombs To School</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADISON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A seventh-grader was expelled and a
classmate was suspended for 30 days for making at least three
``homemade bombs'' and bringing them to school, allegedly to get
back at a teacher, officials said Thursday.
   The Boone County Board of Education took the action against the
unidentified boys following hearings March 1 and 2, school
officials said. A third youth had been suspended for 10 days but is
back at the Madison Middle School.
   Two bombs were found hidden in a restroom ceiling, and testimony
at the hearings indicated the third was detonated somewhere outside
school, Principal Joe Tagliente said Thursday.
   The containers found hidden in the ceiling contained some kind
of fuel mixed with gun powder, Tagliente said.
   ``According to the testimony, one of the boys had a problem with
a teacher and was mad at him, and the student brought the bombs to
school to blow up his car,'' Tagliente said. ``The student denies
saying it.''
   Superintendent Kenneth Mabe said one youth was expelled for the
rest of the school year and banned from school property. The second
was suspended for 30 days and placed on probation the rest of the
school year, he said. Both were required to seek counseling.
   Both were accused of manufacturing the devices, Tagliente said.
   The third student was not accused of making the bomb but was
allegedly involved in the plot, he said.
   No criminal charges have been filed against the youths.
