<HEAD>Anti-Mafia Sweep Yields 96 Arrests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALERMO, Sicily (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A nationwide sweep of Mafia suspects has
led to 96 arrests, authorities said Thursday.
   More than 1,000 members of various agencies were trying to
execute 160 arrest warrants for suspects in cities from Palermo in
Sicily to Milan in northern Italy, authorities said.
   Prosecutors in Palermo said Thursday they began the
investigation in April based on statements by Antonio Calderone,
who was arrested at that time in an investigation of the so-called
Alleruzzo gang of Mafiosi that operated near Mount Etna in Sicily.
Magistrates were also acting on statements made by other Mafia
informants, the prosecutors said.
   The Italian news agency ANSA said the crimes cited by Calderone
included the killing of police Col. Giuseppe Russo and ambush of
Gen. Carlo Alberto dalla Chiesa, the prefect of Palermo and Italy's
top Mafia fighter. His 1982 murder prompted an investigation that
led to a 1985 anti-Mafia sweep with 200 arrests.
   ANSA said Calderone also told authorities about the role of
small crime families that operate on the flanks of the large Mafia
groups in the cities.
   Italian news agencies said an unspecified number of people named
in the latest arrest warrants were already in prison for other
crimes.
