<DOCNO> AP880310-0152 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-88 1534EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-VolunteerGraduation     03-10 0452</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Volunteer Graduation,0465</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Volunteer To Graduate Bill Meeting Resistance In Michigan
Legislature</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MALCOLM JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LANSING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Many people would like to see students
perform community services, and a bill in the Legislature would
require all Michigan high school students to do that to graduate.
   Critics of the measure say students should concentrate on
academics, such service should be voluntary, and the state
shouldn't intrude on local control of education.
   The bill introduced Wednesday by Sen. Jerome Hart would require
students to perform 40 hours of community service over the last
three years of high school. It also would let them earn at least
one-half course credit if they performed an additional 50 hours of
service.
   Rhett Johnston, an aide to Hart, said about 5 percent of the
schools nationwide require community service as a condition of
graduation. About 28 percent of the nation's 74,000 public high
schools offer elective course credit for volunteer work.
   ``Community service offers our young people the chance to
discover, develop and display talents and skills they rarely use in
school and it also provides hard-pressed community social agencies
a corps of hard-working, dedicated and compassionate volunteers,''
Hart said.
   ``It's pretty widespread,'' said Barbara Gomez, director of
school-sanctioned youth community service programs for the
Washington-based Council of Chief State School Officers, which
represents state school superintendents.
   ``It's a grass-roots effort that's filtering up to the state
level. There seems to be a big movement on voluntary service. ... I
don't think it's something that is going to go away.
   ``Our stance is that it's another way of learning. ... What goes
on in the classroom is not the only way a child can learn,'' Gomez
said.
   Two school districts in Michigan _ Detroit and Bloomfield Hills
_ require community service to graduate. Paid part-time jobs
satisfy the requirement in Detroit.
   ``You require what you value. We think this is a valuable
experience,'' said Gary Doyle, deputy superintendent for the
affluent Bloomfield Hills school district. ``Reaching out and
helping others gives students a better sense of self.''
   But some education officials don't like the idea.
   ``It should be determined locally. If it's going to be a
mandate, we would probably oppose it,'' said Don Elliott, executive
director of the Michigan Association of School Administrators.
   ``It may well be a good idea, but it should be something that
each school district should consider on its own,'' said Justin
King, executive director of the Michigan Association of School
Boards.
   ``Our position is any graduation requirement should be (a matter
of) local control,'' said Carl Cohen, president of the Michigan
PTA. ``We think that community service should be something that
everybody should want to do.''
