<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corporate sponsors have rebuffed Elizabeth Taylor's
gala to raise money for AIDS care and research, making it unlikely
the benefit will reach its $3 million goal, organizers said.
   ``We would have liked to have had a major corporate donor shake
Elizabeth Taylor's hand and present her with a large check, but I
couldn't get anybody,'' said Jane Fincher, who is in charge of
obtaining corporate donations for the Sunday event ending at the
Fontainbleau Hilton hotel on Miami Beach.
   But only three corporations have given $60,000, said Al Evans,
chairman of the Community Alliance Against AIDS, a fund-raising arm
of the University of Miami School of Medicine and co-sponsor of the
event.
   ``We were led to believe that (the corporations) cared,'' Evans
said. ``But they're still not brave enough.''
   More than $1.5 million has been raised through pledges and
donations, he said.
   On Sunday, celebrities will be co-hosts at 15 $2,500-a-plate
dinners in south Florida. Proceeds will be split between the
University of Miami School of Medicine and the American Foundation
for AIDS Research, led by Miss Taylor.
   Committed guests for Sunday include Miss Taylor, model Cheryl
Tiegs and actors Zsa Zsa Gabor, Marlee Matlin and Ed Asner.
