<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0765</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At first, Louisiana's chief financial
officer was amused by a phony memo bearing his name that told state
employees to limit their restroom time or face some surprising
reminders.
   In the March 1 memo, a ``Restroom Trip Policy'' is outlined ``to
provide a consistent method of accounting for each employee's
restroom time and ensuring equal treatment of all state employees.''
   ``All restroom stalls are being equipped with timed paper roll
retractors,'' the memo said. ``If the stall is occupied for more
than three minutes, an alarm will sound. Thirty seconds after the
alarm sounds, the roll of paper in the stall will retract, the
toilet will flush and the stall door will open.''
   But after his initial amusement, Brian Kendrick, the state's
commissioner of administration, started thinking about how the memo
was being spread, and whether that meant the state could economize
on some office machinery.
   ``If we can find out where those copies are starting, we'll go
in and take out some copiers,'' he said.
   ``If I had a dollar for every copy that's been made, I could
have probably solved the state's money problems,'' Kendrick said
Wednesday. Louisiana faces a budget deficit projected as high as
$200 million.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lee Trevino hopes golfers and
non-golfers alike will remember his name when they vote for their
next congressman, but he hopes they look at the issues because his
golf game is not too hot.
   This Lee Trevino is an insurance executive. It's the other Lee
Trevino who's a famous professional golfer.
   Trevino, 42, won the Republican primary Tuesday, but doesn't
think his name helped.
   ``It's a big joke _ Lee Trevino, the golfer. Everybody laughs
about it, but it's in good humor,'' Trevino said Wednesday.
   ``No one has been critical, nobody has asked, `Did I change my
name?' or `Was I trying to get in with the name?' I don't think the
name is going to be an issue in the race,'' he said.
   And in any event, his real first name is Loreto, and Lee is a
nickname given to him 16 years ago by a supervisor when Trevino
introduced himself.
   ``He said, `How about Lee?' I said, `No, my name is Loreto.' He
said, `Well, I'll just call you Lee,' and it stuck,'' Trevino said.
   ``I was angry with him for doing it. I had a hard time getting
adjusted to it, but I love it now,'' Trevino said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   You might expect the guests of honor at a
luncheon at Sardi's, the posh restaurant, to be compatible,
well-mannered and fashionable, but what do you do if one guest is a
working stiff who tries for a smooch?
   The Dog Fanciers Club organized the event Wednesday to honor the
nation's top show dog and the city's top police dog.
   The show dog, Champion Great Elms Prince Charming II, a fluffy
little Pomeranian, arrived in an elegant, padded carrying case. The
dog was named best in show at the prestigious Westminister Kennel
Club Show in Madison Square Garden last month.
   The other guest of honor was Nero, a big, amiable bruiser of a
German shepherd, a specialist in sniffing out bombs and narcotics.
Nero, who arrived at the end of a leash, has helped the Police
Department make hundreds of arrests.
   Prince, long used to being coddled and primped, seemed oblivious
to all the attention and photographers.
   But then Nero grew bold enough to prod the smaller dog on the
chin, and Prince blinked and drew back.
   ``He's a very friendly dog,'' said Nero's master, Officer Joseph
Faraguna. ``In all the arrests I've made with him, he's only bitten
four times.''
