<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AIDS-Disclosure     03-10 0464</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS-Disclosure,0474</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bill Would Set Guidelines On AIDS Information Disclosure</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL STASHENKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The drug-taking and sexual partners of
AIDS-infected people would be told they're at risk of catching the
deadly disease under a bill introduced in the New York Legislature.
   The measure says doctors should have the power, without threat
of legal penalty, to inform people in danger even over the
objection of those infected with AIDS. The bill doesn't
specifically allow doctors to use the names of the AIDS-infected
people when informing intimates, but it does give physicians the
right to use their discretion.
   The legislation, unveiled Wednesday, also would require that
counseling and education services be made available to people being
tested for AIDS and for those close to them who are at risk of
catching the disease.
   Also under the bill, blood testing for exposure the HIV virus,
which causes acquired immune deficiency syndrome, would be limited
to people who voluntarily agree and give written authorization to
be tested.
   According to sponsors, the legislation would restrict release of
the results of AIDS tests without a person's consent to the
individuals being tested and to professionals directly involved in
the medical care of that person. Some information could be
exchanged by public health and social services agencies, sponsors
said.
   ``The bill protects confidentiality, protects the information,
except to deal with an identified and legitimate health concern and
treatment necessity,'' said state Assemblyman Richard Gottfried,
chairman of the Assembly's health committee. ``You would not notify
everybody in the neighborhood (of the presence of AIDS). You would
not notify somebody's fellow workers.''
   Sponsors say the bill would limit discrimination against people
with AIDS, the HIV virus or with AIDS-related complex in
employment, housing, credit transactions and other areas.
   A violation of the disclosure rules would carry a misdemeanor
criminal penalty of up to one year in jail under the bill, which
also would establish improper disclosure as grounds of a civil
lawsuit.
   Current state laws require physicians to inform people when they
are at risk of getting certain sexually transmitted diseases such
as syphilis. The legislation proposed Wednesday would make AIDS
notification optional for doctors, and it would also give doctors
the right to ask public health officials to do the notifying
instead.
   Tim Sweeney, deputy director for policy of the New York
City-based Gay Men's Health Crisis, said that a ``strong
confidentiality bill can enhance public health and civil
liberties.''
   New York state, with 14,000 AIDS cases, has the nation's highest
incidence of the disease. AIDS is caused by a virus that damages
the body's immune system. It is spread most often through sexual
contact, needles or syringes shared by drug abusers, infected blood
or blood products, and from pregnant women to their offspring.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
