<2ND_LINE>AM-Handgun Ban,0279</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oak Park Sued by Man Twice Aquitted of Violating Handgun Ban</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who was twice acquitted of charges he
violated Oak Park's handgun ban has sued the community and several
of its officials for $2.5 million.
   In the lawsuit filed Wednesday in U.S. District Court, Don
Bennett accuses the suburban village, several officials and police
officers of conspiring to harass him and violate his constitutional
rights to free speech, due process and equal protection under the
law.
   Bennett, 45, a resident of the nearby Hanover Park, formerly
owned a gas station and minimarket in Oak Park.
   Bennett's attorney, Michael D. Johnson, said Bennett sold his
business in July after he was harassed by the village and its
officials because of his outspoken opposition to the ban on
handguns.
   The Oak Park attorney, Raymond Heise, said he had not received a
copy of the lawsuit, but he denied the allegations.
   ``If Mr. Bennett interpreted that enforcement as harassment,
that's his interpretation,'' he said. ``I don't know any day that
he wasn't free to operate his business.''
   On March 26, 1986, Bennett was charged with violating the
handgun ban after he chased and shot at two people who robbed his
gas station. Bennett was acquitted that fall.
   The lawsuit contends a police officer told Bennett the following
day to stop talking with the news media about his case, Johnson
said.
   Bennett was charged with a second violation of the handgun ban
on Feb. 23, 1987, accused of brandishing a firearm while dealing
with an unruly customer. He was later acquitted of that charge,
too, Johnson said.
</TEXT>
