<HEAD>Store Owner Killed, Suspect Held</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILLICAN, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The sole resident of this unincorporated
town has been fatally shot in the country store he tended for 42
years, and a man paroled from prison three weeks ago has been
charged with his murder.
   William Mellin, 70, was shot in the back of the head Tuesday
night, officials said.
   David Ray Wareham, 41, who had worked at the store since his
parole Feb. 18, was arrested an hour after the shooting and is
being held without bail on murder charges, officials said. He also
was charged with the attempted murder of a witness to the shooting,
whom police refused to identify.
   Wareham apparently went to work at the stide 25 percent of the funds
for the giant atom
smasher.
   Herrington said that should the United States fail to build the
physics research center, there could be a ``brain drain'' of
mammoth proportions, as U.S. scientists go abroad to work on the
best equipment.
   He urged Congress to help the United States take the lead in
high-energy physics ``and let the brain drain happen in other
countries.''
   The subcommittee's chairman, Rep. Tom Bevill, D-Ala., pressed
Herrington to get financial commitments from foreign nations before
Congress votes further money for the project.
   ``Unless we can get allocated another billion dollars pretty
soon and start it ... we could not possibly initiate the funding,''
Bevill said. ``But if we had assurance 50 percent or 75 percent
would be contributed by other countries, it would be a whole new
game.''
   Herrington, however, said it was up to the United States to act
first in order to draw foreign participation.
   Rep. Carl Pursell, R-Mich., said he was worried that depending
on some foreign nations, such as Japan, for funds would endanger
U.S. commercial and security interests.
   The project ``may be pure physics in itself, but there are
results that will translate into the industrial and strategic
area,'' said Pursell, whose district contains one of seven proposed
sites for the super-collider.
   President Reagan has proposed $363 million for super-collider
construction in 1989, but critics in Congress oppose such high
spending on grounds it would divert money from other important
research projects.
   The research center would include a 53-mile-around atom smasher
to study the effects of high-speed collisions of subatomic
particles.
   Backers of the project contend it would produce practical
technological benefits into the next century.
   Bevill, however, said $6 billion in large, federally backed
research projects have been discontinued the past five years.
   ``That isn't a good track record,'' he said. ``When you make
mistakes on a small research project, that is one thing, but when
we look at the size of this, it shocks us.''
   Besides Michigan, six other states have sites that remain in
competition for the project, which will produce 3,000 jobs and have
an annual operating budget of $279 million.
   The states are Arizona, Colorado, Illinois, North Carolina,
Tennessee and Texas.
