<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Nicaragua-American     03-10 0303</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-American,0312</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Contras Free American Peace Group Member</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Contra rebels freed a U.S. peace
activist they had held for nine days, turning him over to members
of his Witness for Peace organization, the group's local director
said Thursday.
   Edward Griffin, the head of Witness for Peace here, said
activist Richard Boren was released Wednesday night near the
isolated town of Quilali, 187 miles north of Managua.
   In a telephone interview, Griffin said Boren, 30, a volunteer
from Elkin, N.C., ``had a cold and was very tired, but otherwise
was fine.'' He said he got news of Boren's release by radio from
other volunteers working in the area.
   No definite time was set for his arrival in Managua.
   Boren was seized along with 12 Nicaraguans March 1 when ``Contra
troops forced him out of a private home at gunpoint,'' said Witness
for Peace, an organization based in Durham, N.C.
   The group is made up of American volunteers opposed to the Regan
administration's continued support of the Contra rebels in their
6-year-old fight to overthrow Nicaragua's leftist Sandinista
government.
   On Tuesday, the government filed a diplomatic note of protest
with the U.S. Embassy against the Contra abductions. The
Sandinistas claimed 12 men were taken by the Contras, Witness for
Peace said there were 13.
   Boren was the second American Witness for Peace member seized by
the Contras. The first was Paul Fishcer, who was abducted in
October in central Chontales province and held for two weeks.
   Witness for Peace officials in North Carolina and Washington
also announced Boren's release.
   On Monday, a spokesman for the U.S. State Department said Contra
leaders in Washington and Florida had agreed to release Boren as
soon as the rebels could do so safely in front of reliable
witnesses.
</TEXT>
