<DOCNO> AP880310-0164 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-88 1555EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Unions-GOP     03-10 0679</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Unions-GOP,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Republican Union Members Like Dole But Leaders Don't</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican union members, against the wishes
of their leaders, appear to be embracing the presidential candidacy
of Kansas Sen. Bob Dole despite his poor record on labor issues.
   Democrats far outnumber Republicans in organized labor. And
Democratic union members, like Democrats in general, have yet to
unite behind any of their party's candidates.
   But Dole, despite having what has been called one of the 20
worst voting records in the Senate on labor issues, is the clear
favorite of union members who say they are Republicans _ about
about one-fourth of the 19 million union members in the nation.
   Dole, for example, garnered 53 percent of the Republican union
vote in Tuesday's 12 Southern primaries, according to exit polls.
   But with only 1 percent of the Republican vote in the Southern
primaries coming from union households, their support for Dole was
no more than a drop in the bucket as Vice President George Bush
swept the region.
   Bush received 28 percent of the Republican union vote in the
Super Tuesday primaries, followed by former television evangelist
Pat Robertson with 22 percent and Rep. Jack Kemp of New York with 6
percent.
   Labor political strategists see primarily two phenomena at work
in the strong support for Dole and in Bush's weak showing among
their Republican members.
   ``Dole is perceived incorrectly as less elitist, more moderate
and more of a regular guy,'' said Jerry Clark, political director
of the 1 million-member American Federation of State, County and
Municipal Employees.
   ``Except on a few things like food stamps that affect
agriculture, his voting record on our issues is terrible,'' Clark
said.
   The other factor is Bush's identification with President Reagan,
who despite the AFL-CIO's vehement opposition, received about 45
percent of union members' votes in the 1984 general election.
   Rex Hardesty, a spokesman for the federation, contended Dole's
strong showing this year represents an anti-Reagan vote.
   ``The drumbeat of union publications that Reaganomics and
Reagan's conservative views should hold no appeal to trade
unionists is getting through,'' he said.
   Reagan had support from just two unions in 1980 _ the Teamsters
and the Professional Air Traffic Controllers Organization. Within a
year of his election, he fired 11,000 PATCO members for going on
strike and destroyed their union.
   The Teamsters endorsed Reagan again in 1984, but with much less
enthusiasm than in 1980. Later, the administration indicted their
president, Jackie Presser, on charges of embezzlement and launched
a legal effort to seize control of the union through a government
trusteeship, contending that it is dominated by racketeers.
   In reaction to the takeover attempt, the Teamsters sought refuge
in the AFL-CIO, rejoining the federation after a 30-year absence
and promising to not disrupt its political goal of putting a
Democrat in the White House.
   Although they are now unlikely to make a Democratic endorsement
before the party's convention next July, labor leaders have agreed
to unite behind whoever is the party's nominee.
   Joan Baggett, political director for the Bricklayers Union and a
Democratic Party activist, said labor leaders clearly prefer to run
against Bush, believing fewer of their members will cross over to
support him than did Reagan.
   ``Bush is now clearly linked with Reagan, and our members have
come to realize that Reagan has not been particularly good for
their interests,'' Ms. Baggett said.
   ``We don't want to run against Dole,'' she added. ``He has a
long voting record against our members' interests, but they don't
know that. It's partly because, that with our lower political
profile this year, we haven't told them.''
   Not everyone agrees.
   Dole drew fewer negative responses than any other candidate in
either party in a poll of members of the United Food and Commercial
Workers Union.
   ``If our members have a preference as far as Republicans are
concerned, they would much rather have Dole,'' said Allen Zack, a
UFCW spokesman. ``He's developed a reputation as being at least a
person you can deal with.''
</TEXT>
