<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Darden Bjt   03-10 0661</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Darden, Bjt,0682</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Human Rights Group To Ask Governor For Mercy In Death Case</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto staffing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANA SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amnesty International officials accused
Gov. Bob Martinez on Thursday of trying to rush the execution of
convicted killer Willie Jasper Darden, Florida's most-often
condemned man who is under his seventh death warrant.
   Officials of Amnesty International and other groups planned to
go to the state Capitol on Friday to ask Martinez to meet with
Darden's attorneys and listen to new evidence that they say could
clear the inmate of the murder of a Lakeland furniture store owner
in a $15 robbery.
   Supporters say Darden, who is black, was the victim of racial
prejudice in his trial.
   Darden's is the most-litigated case involving a death row
inmate, with nearly 100 judges involved in decisions. It has been
before the U.S. Supreme Court four times.
   The latest time before the Supreme Court was Monday, when the
court turned down his claim that he received an unfair trial.
   The next day, the governor signed a seventh death warrant for
Darden and set his execution for March 15. That gave the inmate's
attorneys less than a week to prepare his case. Usually, at least
30 days are allowed.
   ``I think the governor is looking for some kind of ritualistic
sacrifice that he can go through to prove he's tough on crime,''
said Magdaleno Rose-Avila, national director of Amnesty
International's campaign to abolish the death penalty. He noted
that the governor's popularity rating has been low in recent polls.
   The governor's spokesman said politics had nothing to do it,
since Martinez always has strongly supported the death penalty.
   ``The issues have been debated and resolved by the courts. There
was no reason not to sign the warrant,'' said press secretary Jon
Peck.
   Peck said Martinez had instituted a new policy recently to
schedule executions on subsequent warrants in 20 days, rather than
30 days, which he said would have put the execution near the Good
Friday and Easter holidays.
   ``It seemed like kind of an inappropriate time,'' Peck said.
   Joe Spicola, the governor's general counsel, said Darden had
exhausted all possible appeals. ``He is not going to abuse the
process any further,'' he said.
   Attorney Mark Olive said he did not know when he would be able
to file a last-ditch appeal on Darden's behalf.
   Amnesty International planned to organize supporters in Florida
and European countries to call or cable the governor's office
Friday to protest the execution.
   ``I think there will be public outrage like they've never seen
if they execute Willie Darden,'' Rose-Avila said.
   No other Florida inmate has survived as many death warrants, few
have been as celebrated and only one other inmate has been on
Florida's death row longer.
   When Martinez signed Darden's sixth death warrant earlier this
year, Soviet dissident Andrei Sakharov, American actress Margot
Kidder and British rock star Peter Gabriel urged clemency. Sakharov
won the 1975 Nobel Peace prize for his defense of human rights in
the Soviet Union.
   Darden, 54, has been on death row since Jan. 29, 1974. A
prolific writer, he has been called the ``poet of death row.''
   Darden's supporters cite sworn statements from a minister and
another Lakeland resident saying he could not have been at the
furniture store when owner James Turman was killed.
   The Rev. Sam Sparks said Turman's wife had told him that all
blacks looked alike to her and that her identification of Darden
was unimportant because lawyers had told her Darden committed the
crime. Helen Baum, formerly Helen Turman, recently denied having
made that statement to Sparks and reaffirmed her identification of
Darden.
   Christine F. Bass, a Lakeland secretary, said Darden's car had
broken down near her home and he waited for a tow truck from 4 p.m.
to 5:35 p.m. on Sept. 8, 1973. Her house was eight miles from the
furniture store. Prosecutors say the crime occurred about 6 p.m.
</TEXT>
