<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ScrollandKey     03-10 0227</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Scroll and Key,0233</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Yale Group To Admit Women</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of seven secret undergraduate
societies at Yale University has decided to admit women in 1989,
according to published reports.
   The move by the Scroll and Key will leave two secret clubs
off-limits to women, including Skull and Bones, whose alumni roster
includes Vice President George Bush and conservative columnist
William F. Buckley Jr.
   A group called Wolf's Head also does not admit women.
   Among Scroll and Key's alumni is A. Bartlett Giamatti, the
president of major-league baseball's National League and former
president of Yale, the New Haven Register reported Thursday. The
decision to admit women was reported by The New York Times and the
Register.
   The secret societies are exclusive social clubs that select
children of former members and other selected students for
membership in their senior year. The clubs meet in privately owned
buildings on or near campus and have individual initiation rites
and rituals.
   The societies have come under criticism; similar clubs at
Harvard and Princeton have been the targets of lawsuits.
   ``It creates a whole system of shooting people straight to the
top,'' said Byrony Romer, a sophomore and co-coordinator of the
Yale Women's Center. ``It is such a strong power base.''
   Scroll and Key, which was founded in 1842, is the second-oldest
of the Yale secret societies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880310-0170 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-88 1602EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-MeeseProbe     03-10 0641</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Meese Probe,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Documents Show Pipeline Payment Benefited Meese's Finances</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A $150,000 payment to a friend of Attorney
General Edwin Meese III for work on an Iraqi pipeline project ended
up in a stock-trading account that was apparently used to benefit
Meese's finances, a published report said Thursday.
   The money, a legal fee intended for attorney E. Robert Wallach,
went through two accounts before being deposited in October 1985 in
a pooled account used to trade stocks on behalf of Wallach, Meese
and others, docments obtained by the Los Angeles Times showed.
   The discovery indicates the fees Wallach received for lobbying
the White House, with Meese's help, on the pipeline project were
later used to Meese's financial advantage, despite vigorous denials
by lawyers for both Meese and Wallach, the paper said.
   Meese played a key role in securing U.S. government support for
the Iraqi pipeline when he arranged a White House meeting between
pipeline promoters and former National Security adviser Robert C.
McFarlane and discussed the project with former Israeli Prime
Minister Shimon Peres.
   Meese's lawyers denied Meese knew anything about the payment to
Wallach and said he had no way of knowing of any possible benefits
he might have received from the money.
   And George G. Walker, Wallach's attorney, told the Times, ``We
will categorically deny that any monies Mr. Wallach received ever
went into Mr. Meese's account or were used for his benefit.''
   But highly unusual stock-trading practices by W. Franklyn Chinn,
the financial adviser who managed both Meese's and Wallach's money,
suggest that Meese did benefit from trades made with the Wallach
fee, the newspaper said.
   A Swiss financier, Bruce Rappaport, who was the pipeline's chief
promoter said he deposited the $150,000 with Chinn, who controlled
accounts for Wallach and Meese at the time. Rappaport has said he
hired Wallach because of his Washington contacts, including Meese.
   The payment to Chinn was made less than two months after Meese
helped Wallach arrange a meeting between Rappaport and McFarlane on
June 24, 1985. McFarlane assigned a National Security Council aide
to find a way to insure the pipeline so that it could be financed
and built. The pipeline was never constructed.
   Chinn was able to pool the $150,000 with other funds and use the
money to buy blocks of stock. He then could allocate the most
profitable trades to Meese's account after learning how the deals
came out, according to a recent report by the Democratic staff of
the Senate Governmental Affairs oversight subcommittee.
   The Senate staff report concludes that nearly a third of the
stock purchases allocated by Chinn to Meese's account, called Meese
Partners, required more money than his account contained at the
time they were made.
   Over an 18-month period, Chinn was able to turn about $50,000
into about $95,000 through investments for Meese _ a return of
better than 80 percent.
   Last week in Geneva, Rappaport said the $150,000 was transferred
to Chinn's business account at the Bank of America in San Francisco
in August 1985 on instructions from Wallach.
   A government investigator who reviewed the financial records of
Meese, Wallach and Chinn said that on Aug. 15, 1985, Chinn
transferred $150,000 from his Bank of America business account to
the stock trading account he maintained for his business at the San
Francisco office of Bear, Stearns & Co., a brokerage house.
   Chinn maintained several trading accounts for clients at Bear,
Stearns, including the one for Meese.
   Independent counsel James C. McKay is investigating Meese,
chiefly because of his role in the pipeline affair. Key to this
aspect of the inquiry is a 1985 memo to Meese in which Wallach
cited a proposal to make payments to the Israeli Labor Party in
return for Israel's guarantee not to interfere with the pipeline to
be built by Iraq, its longtime enemy.

</TEXT>
