<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Gore     03-10 0395</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gore,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gore Says Voters Won't Buy Dukakis Appoach</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Albert Gore Jr. said Thursday the Democratic
Party is bound for another election-year disaster if front-runner
Michael Dukakis wins its presidential nomination.
   ``We have tried a Mike Dukakis approach time and time and time
again and people of this country are just not buying it,'' Gore
said during a visit to Children's Memorial Hospital.
   ``The people want a president who understands it's necessary to
fight for working men and women, not a technocratic manager,'' the
Tennessean said.
   ``For those who want another election blowout and see the
Democratic Party losing 49 of 50 states, vote for Mike Dukakis.''
   In two days of campaigning for Illinois' March 15 primary, Gore
has portrayed the Massachusetts governor as too liberal for the
American electorate.
   He has mostly ignored the state's favorite sons _ Sen. Paul
Simon and Jesse Jackson _ except to acknowledge they have a
home-field advantage.
   Gore is staying at the Palmer House, one of the city's grand old
hotels, and he began his day a few yards away, shaking the hands of
rush-hour commuters as they left the elevated trains that circle
downtown.
   Later, he and his wife, Tipper, took a private tour of the
hospital on the city's North Side.
   In the lobby, the Gores met about a dozen young patients and
their parents who were surprised by the glare of the television
lights.
   ``Is this a nice place?'' Gore asked Sam Goad, 8.
   ``No,'' the boy replied. ``After a while it gets boring.''
   In remarks to hospital workers and patients, Gore said he would
overhaul federal Medicaid and Medicare programs and other health
services, preferably without a tax increase.
   ``I'm not proposing additional taxes,'' he said. ``I believe
that by changing priorities, eliminating wasteful spending in areas
that have been intentionally overlooked by the Reagan
administration ... it is possible to avoid a tax increase.
   ``I have indicated that it can't be completely ruled out.''
   Gore touted his 12 years in Congress, saying he sponsored
legislation to protect consumers of infant formulas and to make it
easier for children to get organ transplants.
   He planned to campaign in central Illinois on Friday before
moving on to South Carolina and Washington. Aides said he would
return to Illinois on Sunday.
