<1ST_LINE>r w AM-HanfordClean-Up     03-10 0487</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hanford Clean-Up,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Administration Officials Say Clean-Up Legislation Unneeded</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LES BLUMENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Proposed legislation to ensure the federal
government complies with its own environmental laws is
unconstitutional, unneeded and could undercut efforts to clean up
such facilities as the Hanford nuclear reservation, Reagan
administration officials said Thursday.
   Members of a House subcommittee insisted, however, that the
Department of Energy and other agencies have ``thumbed their
noses'' at efforts by the Environmental Protection Agency to
enforce federal environmental laws at federal facilities.
   Lawmakers also said that EPA has been less than forceful in its
efforts to force compliance with the laws, while the Department of
Justice has obstructed those efforts.
   ``It's a shame that some in the federal government have taken
the position they are above the law,'' said Rep. Thomas Luken,
D-Ohio, chairman of the transportation, tourism and hazardous
materials subcommittee of the House Energy and Commerce Committee.
   The subcommittee's hearing focused on five bills that were
introduced late last year amid mounting criticism that the Energy
Department and other federal agencies are dragging their feet over
cleaning up federal facilities, including the Hanford reservation
in central Washington.
   The General Accounting Office has said there may be over 1,000
hazardous waste sites at Hanford, the legacy of 40 years of
plutonium production for nuclear weapons. The waste is both highly
radioactive and chemically toxic.
   ``The scope and the complexity precludes quick solutions,''
Joseph Salgado, a DOE undersecretary, said of the clean-up at
Hanford and other facilities.
   Salgado said that a compliance agreement with EPA and the state
of Washington covering clean-up of Hanford was a top priority of
DOE.
   But Rep. Ron Wyden, D-Ore., said after the hearing that DOE
promised almost a year ago to come up with an agreement and a plan
for Hanford.
   ``We still don't have a program, a schedule or anything,'' said
Wyden, adding that a new Justice Department interpretation of some
environmental laws might even preclude states from getting involved
in enforcement efforts.
   ``This is just another message that the administration isn't
serious about Hanford clean-up and is just throwing up more
obstacles,'' said Wyden.
   Wyden and Rep. Al Swift, D-Wash., are among the sponsors of the
package of bills that would establish a special environmental
counsel to enforce the laws, broaden the authority of the EPA and
the states in environmental matters at federal facilities and
create a special DOE department to handle environmental issues.
   Salgado said that the five proposed bills were unneeded and that
his department acknowledged their responsibility to comply with
federal environmental regulations.
   ``The Department of Energy's critical national security mission
must not be jeopardized by an environmental protection and safety
program too weak to assure excellence, or by one so rigid and
oppressive that these missions cannot be accomplished,'' he said.
   Salgado said DOE believes that the present framework of state
and federal laws are ``adequate and appropriate.''
</TEXT>
