<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BrownProtest     03-10 0216</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brown Protest,0222</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Elitism Protest At Brown Causes $15,000 In Damage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vandals protesting alleged elitism at
Brown University damaged 10 oil portraits of early school
supporters.
   ``It appears to be a protest against the white elitist male
orientation of the founders of the university,'' Eric Broudy,
spokesman for the school, said Wednesday.
   The vandals spray-painted the message ``Elite? Who us?'' across
the paintings in the Manning Chapel, Broudy said.
   A group calling itself ``the Coalition for Creative Subversion''
claimed responsibility and called on the school to ``diversify
itself,'' Broudy said.
   The vandalism occurred Feb. 17, one day before a seminar on
class and elitism was held in the room, said Eric Widmer, the dean
of student life.
   Widmer said it will cost more than $15,000 to restore the
portraits, which are more than a century old. ``I don't know that a
value could be placed on the paintings, but they're certainly part
of the history of Brown,'' he said.
   The group's letter, sent to the campus newspaper and distributed
around campus, contended that incidents from Brown's history show
that the school is racist, sexist and biased against certain
religions.
   ``Another way Brown perpetuates these discourses is by choosing
to hang paintings of wealthy white men on its walls,'' the
statement said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
