<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CandidatesAnnounce     03-10 0358</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Candidates Announce,0369</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nebraska's Kerrey, Vermont's Sanders Declare Candidacies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Nebraska Gov. Bob Kerrey officially entered the race for
the U.S. Senate on Thursday, while maverick Mayor Bernard Sanders
launched his campaign for Vermont's sole congressional seat.
   ``I would like to be your next senator,'' Kerrey, a 44-year-old
Democrat, told 300 supporters in Omaha before starting a two-day
swing through the state.
   No other Democrat has declared for the nomination. Sen. David
Karnes, appointed to fill the term of the late Edward Zorinsky, and
Rep. Haul Daub are seeking the GOP nomination.
   ``I can promise you I will never betray you. And I will never
dishonor the respect I have for you,'' said Kerrey.
   Despite high popularity ratings, Kerrey declined to run for
re-election as governor in 1986 because he said it was ``time to
move on.''
   Kerrey ended months of speculation last November when he said he
would run for the Senate. Since then he has been criss-crossing the
state, saying his main issues are trade policy, the federal budget,
education and agriculture.
   ``A great and glorious future will not happen unless we do the
unglamorous work today,'' he said Thursday.
   Sanders, four-term mayor of Burlington, Vermont's largest city,
and a longtime critic of the concentration of wealth in America,
said he would fight for national health care, disarmament, tough
environmental laws, affordable day care and higher taxes on the
wealthy and corporations.
   Although Sanders, 46, has long claimed socialist leanings, he
said he would run as an independent candidate.
   Four Democrats and one Republican have declared their intentions
to run for the seat being vacated by Republican James Jeffords, who
in turn is seeking to fill the seat of retiring Republican Sen.
Robert Stafford.
   Sanders said Thursday he wanted to take his
tax-the-rich-and-feed-the-poor message to Washington.
   ``If a hotshot student can graduate law school and start work at
$70,000 a year for a big-name law firm, surely we can pay child
care workers more than $12,000 a year and teachers more than
$16,000 a year, and nursing home workers more than the minimum
wage,'' Sanders said in Montpelier, the state's capital.
</TEXT>
