<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NewBedfordRape     03-10 0526</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-New Bedford Rape,0538</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>High Court Upholds Convictions in Big Dan's Gang Rape Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER B. DALY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state's highest court on Thursday rejected
claims of an unfair trial and left standing the convictions of four
men in the 1983 gang rape of a woman on a tavern pool table.
   In a pair of unanimous rulings, the Massachusetts Supreme Court
rejected defense objections to the prosecutor's handling of
evidence, to the trial judge's decision to keep television cameras
turned away from the victim and to other matters.
   Bristol County District Attorney Ronald Pina welcomed the
ruling, saying he hoped it would end the lingering controversy over
the case and encourage women everywhere to prosecute rapes.
   Defense attorney David H. Waxler said he was reviewing the
opinion for possible grounds for further appeal.
   ``The unfortunate aspect of this sort of decision is that future
prosecutors rest more comfortbaly in the knowledge that they need
not turn over exculpatory evidence, and that's unfortunate,'' he
said. ``It's the old saying: tough cases make bad law.''
   The dramatic account of the rape given by the victim, a young
mother, and the lengthy televised trial in Superior Court in 1984
drew unwanted national attention to the working-class neighborhoods
of New Bedford and sparked an intense debate over rape. It also
brought agony to the Portuguese-American community in the fishing
city 60 miles south of Boston.
   Six young men of Portugese descent were charged in the case;
four were convicted of aggravated rape.
   Daniel Silvia was sentenced to nine to 12 years; Joseph Vieira,
six to eight years; and John Cordeiro and Victor Raposo, nine to 12
years each.
   The victim, also of Portuguese ancestry, left New Bedford and
was killed in a single-car crash outside Miami in 1986 at age 25.
   According to court records, the woman entered Big Dan's tavern
on March 6, 1983, to buy cigarettes. She ordered a drink and spoke
briefly with another woman, and they watched a game of pool. When
she declined an offer of a ride from Cordeiro and Raposo, the court
said, she was knocked down, dragged to thje pool table and raped,
the judges said.
   ``Eventually, clothed only in a shirt and one shoe, the victim
escaped and ran into the street, where she flagged down a passing
truck.''
   On appeal, Vieira and Silvia claimed the prosecutor failed to
make a timely disclosure of certain evidence that might have helped
the defense, depriving them of their rights to due process. They
also argued that the district attorney suppressed until after trial
a witness's recorded account of the victim's condition and
statements shortly after the rape.
   And they argued that Young prejudiced the defense theory that
the victim consented to the sex. They also complained about the
exclusion of an allegedly false prior complaint of rape by the
woman.
   In their separate appeal, Cordeiro and Raposo argued that
Young's order keeping courtroom cameras away from the woman
prejudiced their right to a fair trial. They also claimed that
Young erred in refusing to instruct the jury on consensual rape.
   The high court dismissed each claim.
</TEXT>
