<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Angolan-Ambassador     03-10 0393</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Angolan-Ambassador,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Angolan Official Says Luanda Against Any Role For Savimbi</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Angolan official said Thursday his
government would never agree to giving rebel leader Jonas Savimbi a
role in running the country if an end to the civil war is
successfully negotiated.
   Manuel Pedro Pacavira, Angola's new ambassador to the United
Nations, indicated that Savimbi would have to leave before there
could be any reconciliation between officials of his Marxist
government and UNITA, Savimbi's organization.
   ``Some elements of UNITA could deserve different treatment ...
but not Savimbi,'' Pacavira told reporters at a luncheon. ``He is a
crook, incoherent ... doesn't care about consequences.''
   Savimbi's group _ the National Union for the Total Independence
of Angola, or UNITA _ receives financial aid from the United States
and South Africa.
   Before peace is achieved, Pacavira said, South Africa must cease
its help to UNITA and there must be an ``understanding'' that the
United States will end its assistance.
   A major stumbling block to ending the 12-year civil war is the
presence of 40,000 Cuban troops in Angola. State Department
officials say the Angolans have agreed in principle to withdrawal
of the troops.
   Pacavira said Angola is prepared to remove the troops ``within
limits'' once outside aid to UNITA stops and South Africa grants
independence to Namibia under a United Nations plan.
   The Angolans have not provided a timetable for any troop
withdrawal, but Pacavira said he expects another ``ministerial
meeting'' between officials of Luanda and Washington in March or
April.
   Assistant Secretary of State Chester Crocker, who has tried for
seven years to negotiate a solution in Angola, held discussions
with Angolans in January. The State Department said it is awaiting
new proposals from Angola.
   Pacavira said the United States can continue to play a role as
mediator, but Angola is also ready to hold discussions with
officials of white-ruled South Africa. The Cubans would have to be
included in the talks, he said.
   Pacavira dismissed a statement made by South African Defense
Minister Magnus Malan who suggested that Pretoria is willing to
deal directly with the Soviet Union on Angola.
   ``His statement has nothing concrete and constructive,''
Pacavira said. ``It is just an exercise to distract public
opinion.''
   Pacavira served as his country's ambassador to Cuba before being
assigned to the United Nations.
</TEXT>
