<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0717 03-10 0731</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0717,730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush: `Tired' of Scandal in High Office</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with Bush saying not criticizing Reagan, subbing 5
grafs for grafs 7-8 pvs, Bush did ... of ethics.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush said Thursday he is ``tired of being
embarrassed'' by scandals surrounding public officials and
unethical behavior by high government officials. He pledged he
would create a special White House ethics panel if elected
president.
   Bush, arriving in Illinois on the heels of his stunning Super
Tuesday victory, also promised he would set up a budget deficit
summit with congressional leaders on ``day one'' of his
administration _ an echo of a stand taken by GOP presidential rival
Bob Dole.
   Bush told the Governor's Club luncheon at the Chicago Hilton
said that in such a summit scenario, ``I am personally going to
head the executive branch negotiating effort.''
   ``We're going to meet. We're going to talk. Maybe, even, we'll
shout, but we're going to solve this problem,'' he said.
   Bush has said on several occasions that he would seek to bring
people into government ``who want to serve, not to profit'' but he
has steadfastly refused to criticize any Reagan administration
officials, including Attorney General Edwin Meese, who is under
investigation by several grand juries.
   Former top White House aides Michael K. Deaver and Lyn Nofziger
have been convicted in court cases involving their lobbying
activities after leaving the administration.
   At a news conference shortly after his speech, Bush was asked
whether his call for a special White House panel on ethics was a
criticism of the way things had been done during the Reagan
administration.
   ``No, because I was asked this in an interview ... and I said I
don't know of anybody who has a higher standard of personal ethics
than the president, always above any possible conflict of
interest,'' he replied. ``Certainly, nobody should imply criticism.
I'm just saying what my priorities would be in the future.''
   Asked to name public officials who had caused him embarrassment,
Bush said, ``I'm not going to be specific in terms of names. I'm
going to be generic.''
   Bush said, ``I'm just saying how I would do it.''
   He said in his speech, ``I am personally disturbed at the
breaches of ethics I have seen in the past few years in government.
Once elected, I'd appoint an ethics panel to work right there in
the White House. I'd have them draft a new and specific code of
ethics.''
   ``When a congressman goes bad or someone in the executive branch
violates the public trust, it hurts,'' he said. ``I'm tired of
being embarrassed. I'm tired of seeing our children seeing things
that should embarrass us all. People at all levels of government
should come to serve, not to profit.''
   ``Clearly, I have big plans,'' he told the audience of
Republican boosters, who sat silently through the speech.
   At the outset of his talk, Bush told his audience ``there's no
complacency'' in his campaign in the wake of his near sweep of the
Super Tuesday competition.
   Bush's announcement that he would personally oversee
deficit-reduction negotiations also seemed an implied criticism of
Reagan.
   In the aftermath of the Wall Street crash last Oct. 19, Reagan
set up a negotiating team to work out a deficit-reduction
compromise with Capitol Hill leaders.
   But with the exception of some meetings in the White House with
congressional figures, Reagan left the actual bargaining to chief
of staff Howard Baker, Treasury Secretary James Baker and budget
director James Miller.
   Those negotiations produced a two-year, $76 billion budget
reduction plan, which included $23 billion in new taxes.
   Bush, from the start of the campaign, has said that he would not
try to win the GOP nomination by ``jumping away'' from Reagan or by
criticizing the president.
   ``I'm not going to try to move up the ladder by knocking someone
else down,'' the vice president has said.
   And in Thursday's speech, there was plenty of praise for the
president.
   ``I am proud to have been part of a m ajor change in public
policy,'' he said. ``They call it the Reagan revolution because it
was revolutionary. ... You know the results. Greatest peacetime
economic growth in our history, strengthened defense, the Soviets
come to the bargaining table.
   ``But it's not a complete triumph. It's only a beginning,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
