<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Simon-Money     03-10 0425</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Simon-Money,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Simon Looks To Home State to Regain Matching Fund Status</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Paul Simon is counting on a strong
showing in his home state of Illinois next Tuesday to restore his
eligibility for federal matching funds before a cutoff is
triggered, a campaign spokesman said Thursday.
   Simon became ineligible for matching funds by winning less than
10 percent of the vote in two successive primaries, but election
law stays the cutoff for 30 days.
   The matching funds can continue to flow during the 30 days, and
eligibility is restored when a candidate receives at least 20
percent of the vote in another state primary.
   ``We are not in jeopardy,'' said Simon's press secretary Terry
Michael. ``There is zero chance that we won't get 20 percent next
Tuesday.'' In fact, he said, Simon is counting on cleaning up in
all but three of the state's 22 congressional districts.
   Michael conceded those three Chicago districts to the state's
other native son, Jesse Jackson, who expects he will win much more
than that.
   Federal Election Commission spokesman Fred Eiland said that
after Simon fell below the 10 percent threshhold in South Dakota
and Vermont, he would have had to get 20 percent in one of the
Super Tuesday states this week.
   Since he did not campaign for Super Tuesday and failed to do
achieive the threshhold, his ineligibility for matching funds will
be effective March 31 unless he does well in Illinois, Eiland said.
   Rep. Jack Kemp, R-New York, also has fallen below the threshhold
but since he dropped out of the race on Thursday, he will be
allowed to receive matching funds to pay off any leftover debts.
However, he could not use those funds to resume campaigning.
   The same is true of former Colorado Sen. Gary Hart, if he drops
out of the race Friday as aides have said he would do.
   The matching funds are provided from the taxypayer-supported
fund. Every donation of $250 or less that a candidate raises is
matched by the public fund. To qualify, a candidate must raise at
least $100,000 across 20 states in contributions of $250 or less.
   Michael said Simon has whittled down his loan debt, which stood
at more than $500,000 at the beginning of February, to about
$45,000, and has some $100,000 in cash on hand.
   The campaign raised $932,000 during February through events and
direct mail and got $364,000 in matching funds.
   Simon has received a total $2.2 million in matching funds so far.
</TEXT>
