<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-88 2013EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TeenSuicides     03-10 0641</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Teen Suicides,0662</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Town Tries to Forget One Year After Four Teen Suicides</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HENRY STERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERGENFIELD, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One year has passed since four
teen-agers made a suicide pact and died together in a locked garage
here, but local officials say the worst thing they could do is
commemorate the deaths.
   ``All psychiatrists tell us don't memorialize it in any way,''
said school Superintendent John Habeeb. ``It could only cause
trauma. It will be business as usual on Friday.''
   Last March 11, Thomas Olton, 19, Thomas Rizzo, 18, and sisters
Cheryl and Lisa Burress, ages 17 and 16, were found dead of carbon
monoxide poisoning in Olton's idling car.
   Reporters descended upon the school and officials worried that
other troubled youths seeking glorification might try to imitate
the four.
   ``Our fear was that the blitz could trigger some students that
were already unstable,'' Habeeb said. ``After all, it's very
romantic to get your name in the paper.''
   Charlotte P. Ross, president and executive director of the Youth
Suicide National Center in Washington, D.C., said studies in the
past year tend to discount any ``copycat'' theory of adolescent
suicides.
   ``There's an enormous amount of suicidal behavior among young
people,'' Ms. Ross said. ``Since Bergenfield, studies have cast
shadows and a lot of doubt that suicide is like the measles. You
can't catch it.''
   Even so, Bergenfield has worked hard to avoid any repeat of the
tragedy.
   In the past year, Bergenfield High School has given a part-time
drug and alcohol counselor full-time status _ authorities found
traces of cocaine in the blood of all four of the dead youngsters,
and two had been drinking.
   The school also hired a psychiatrist for grades 7-12, and hired
two outreach workers for its community response team. The response
team, comprised of mental health professionals, clergy, teachers
and police officers, began immediately after the suicides.
   ``It's an example of an outstanding response,'' Ms. Ross said.
``They've worked very hard. We don't know how many suicides came
close and were prevented.''
   Bergenfield's strategy will be part of a manual on adolescent
suicide due for release in the spring by the federal Centers for
Disease Control and will play a part in guidelines being assembled
in California for municipalities there, she said.
   Bergenfield has done such a good job that the federal government
denied two grant applications for the community, saying other
municipalities needed the money more, Habeeb said.
   He said the school's programs have cost about $80,000, and New
Jersey has sent a $35,000 state grant for substance abuse programs
in town.
   Robert J. Gallione Jr., the recently elected mayor of this
community of 26,000 residents and a job counselor at Columbia
University, says the money is well spent.
   The focus of the past year has been on reaching out to youths
and identifying teen-agers who feel alienated. Special attention is
paid to dropouts, since three of the four suicide victims had left
school.
   Habeeb said Bergenfield's low drop-out rate of 1.5 percent can
lead to dropouts being stigmatized.
   Gallione added that a Mayor's Advisory Committee on Youth gives
teen-agers a chance to suggest ideas that might not naturally occur
to adults.
   One recent suggestion was a town-sponsored battle of teen rock
bands. Gallione called that a good approach to disaffected youths,
who often find a safe haven in music.
   While school officials work on prevention, others in town want
to forget.
   Four 15-year-old sophomore girls, who didn't want to give a
reporter their names, said the suicides are not talked about much
anymore.
   The mayor said such an attitude is not a bad thing.
   ``There was a lot of negative focus but it's been offest by
other things we do in the community,'' Gallione said. ``People have
to come to see another side of us _ just a traditional community.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
