<1ST_LINE>u w AM-MinimumWage     03-10 0601</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Minimum Wage,610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Committee Approves Increase In Minimum Wage To $5.05 Over 4
Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM SEPPY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An increase in the federal minimum wage from
$3.35 to $5.05 an hour was tentatively approved Thursday by the
House Education and Labor Committee.
   The original bill before the committee called for an increase of
50 cents in 1989, 40 cents in 1990 and 40 cents in 1991 to $4.65.
   The committee adopted, on a vote of 18-14, an amendment by Rep.
Carl C. Perkins, D-Ky., which added a 40-cent increase in the
fourth year, on Dec. 31, 1991.
   The full committee was unable to take action on all the pending
amendments and will continue debate on the bill next week.
   The Senate has a companion bill, sponsored by Edward M. Kennedy,
D-Mass., chairman of the Labor and Human Resources Committee, which
would raise the minimum wage to $4.65 over a three-year period.
   The Perkins amendment was approved essentially along party lines
except that two Democrats, Reps. Austin J. Murphy of Pennsylvania
and Timothy J. Penny of Minnesota, joined the Republicans in
opposing the proposal.
   Murphy is chairman of the House labor standards subcommittee,
which had approved an increase to $4.65. He said that legislation
was ``crafted so that it will be accepted by the full House and the
executive branch. If we accept this (Perkins) proposal, it will not
be accepted.''
   Rep. Stephen J. Solarz, D-N.Y., read from a letter written by
Labor Secretary Ann McLaughlin, who said senior White House
advisers would recommend to President Reagan that he veto any
legislation increasing the minimum wage.
   ``So it doesn't matter what we do, the executive will be against
it,'' Solarz said.
   The House committee also voted 20-13 on an amendment by Rep.
Tommy F. Robinson, D-Ark., to increase the ``tip credit'' for
restaurant workers.
   Current law allows employers of workers who regularly receive
tips _ such as waiters and waitresses _ to count the tips as earned
wages equivalent to 40 percent of the minimum wage. Thus, a
restaurant owner could pay a worker $2.01 an hour, with the
remaining $1.34 - 40 percent of today's $3.35-an-hour minimum wage
_ coming from tips.
   Under the Robinson amendment, the tip minimum would be raised to
50 percent of the minimum. Thus, if the minimum wage were increased
to $5.05 an hour, an employer could pay a $2.52 hourly wage, with
the other $2.52 coming from tips.
   The biggest argument of the session came over the amendment by
Perkins who said his proposal ``does not go far enough, but it is a
start.''
   ``It gives the American worker some level of decency,'' Perkins
said.
   He said his amendment would still not bring workers up to what
is described by the federal government as the ``poverty level,'' a
family of three earning approximately $9,500.
   Rep. Dick Armey, R-Tex., who opposes any increase in the minimum
wage because he said he would destroy jobs, proposed an amendment
to raise the base to $20 an hour.
   ``I don't think we ought to be pikers,'' he said. ``It would put
minimum wage workers on the par with members of Congress.''
   Rep. Augustus F. Hawkins, D-Calif., the committee chairman,
called the proposal ``absurd.'' Armey said he thought the entire
discussion was absurd because the committee refused to discuss the
number of jobs that would be lost because of the minimum wage
increase.
   Armey, an economist, said different studies show anywhere from
300,000 to 800,000 job opportunities would be lost because of the
increase. Hawkins said there was not support for such projections.
</TEXT>
