<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SeditionTrial     03-10 0329</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sedition Trial,0337</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Leader of White Supremacist Group Testifies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT SMITH, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former leader of a white supremacist
group testified Thursday that the founder of the right-wing group
The Order gave him $75,000 in stolen money in 1984 to fund his
organization.
   Glenn Miller, 47, former leader of the White Patriots Party in
North Carolina, said Robert Mathews, killed in a shootout with the
FBI near Seattle in December 1984, gave him the money on a visit in
August 1984.
   ``He explained that it was stolen from banks and armored cars,''
Miller said.
   Miller said Mathews told him that his group was ``sitting on
$3.5 million. He said that they were working on an inside job that
would net them $50 million.''
   Zillah Craig, Mathews' girlfriend, testified Wednesday that she
traveled around the country with Mathews and helped him distribute
$2 million, part of $3.6 million stolen from an armored car in June
1984 at Ukiah, Calif.
   Both Miller and Ms. Craig testified in the sedition trial of 14
men. Ten defendants are charged with sedition, five are charged
with conspiring to kill a federal judge and an FBI agent, and two
are charged with interstate transportation of stolen money.
   Miller said Robert Miles, one of the 14 defendants, once told
him that he could receive more money for his organization.
   Miller said Mathews told him several leaders of the white
supremacist movement had received money, among them defendant Louis
Ray Beam. Miller said Mathews also claimed to have given money to
William Pierce, head of a reputed white supremacist group called
the National Alliance.
   Pierce also wrote a book of fiction called ``The Turner
Diaries,'' which government witnesses have testified formed the
basis for The Order's plan to overthrow the government and
establish an all-white nation in the Northwest.
   Miller, who was captured at Ozark, Mo., by the FBI, has pleaded
guilty to a firearms charge and sending a threat through the mail.
</TEXT>
