<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Afghanistan     03-10 0629</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan,0646</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Feel Free To Continue Military Aid, Reject U.S. Stand</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Single name Najib is cq</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED AFTAB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union said Thursday it feels free to
keep sending military aid to the Kabul government even after it
withdraws its troops from Afghanistan.
   It rejected a U.S. demand that foreign military aid to both
sides in the Afghanistan war cease simultaneously once a peace
settlement is reached. The United States aids the Afghan rebels.
   Nikolay Kozyrev, a senior Soviet specialist in Asian affairs,
said that except for sending new troops to Afghanistan, the Soviet
Union was not committed to halt any kind of assistance to Kabul. He
noted that the two countries had contractual ties now for seven
decades.
   Kozyrev, introduced as an ambassador-at-large, came to Geneva as
head of a small Soviet delegation assigned to follow the indirect
peace talks between Pakistan and Afghanistan. U.N. Undersecretary
General Diego Cordovez is mediating the talks.
   Kozyrev's appearance at a news conference organized by the
Soviet mission to the U.N. office in Geneva marked the first time a
Soviet official took a public stand on the negotiations since the
talks started almost six years ago.
   He said the question of a cutoff of Soviet aid never was a
subject of the U.N.-sponsored peace talks. He termed the U.S.
demand for a ``symmetrical cessation'' of military aid, spelled out
at a State Department briefing last Friday, ``an attempt to
interfere with the internal affairs of Afghanistan and with the
bilateral relationship'' between Kabul and Moscow.
   Kozyrev said the U.S. demand would be tantamount to Moscow
calling for a cut-off of U.S. military aid to Pakistan.
   A U.S. mission spokesman, Chris Henze, said there would be no
immediate comment from Robert Peck, the assistant deputy secretary
of state who is in Geneva to follow the talks. Kozyrev said he was
in touch with Peck.
   The chief Afghan negotiator, Foreign Minister Abdul Wakil, said
last week draft documents of the settlement provided for U.S. aid
to the Islamic guerrillas to cease simultaneously with the start of
the withdrawal of the estimated 115,000 Soviet troops.
   The United States is the main supplier of arms to the guerrillas
fighting the Marxist Kabul government, with shipments reported
worth about $700 million last year and including shoulder-fired
Stinger missiles.
   Kozyrev told reporters that after agreement was reached on all
main elements of the projected peace package, negotiations bogged
down because of Pakistan's insistence on the settlement's being
accompanied by formation of a broad-based transitional government
in Kabul.
   Pakistan argues that only such a government, replacing the
Soviet-backed one headed by President Najib, would be able to
oversee implementation of the agreements and ensure a safe return
of more than 5 million refugees from Pakistan and Iran.
   Kozyrev sidestepped a question on whether negotiations could
continue after next Tuesday's target date set by Moscow. Soviet
leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev has said Moscow will bring home its
troops starting May 15 provided the settlement is signed by March
15.
   Pakistan, which adjoins Afghanistan, supports the guerrillas and
acts as their spokesman at the Geneva talks.
   Cordovez met separately with the two delegations Thursday for a
total of five hours. He said there would be no formal negotiation
session Friday, but he would meet privately with the two sides.
   Cordovez said earlier that final agreement was not imminent.
   Also on Thursday, the 43-nation U.N. Human Rights Commission
adopted by a 29-7 vote a Western-sponsored resolution expressing
concern at what it said were continued widespread violations of
human rights by Afghan authorities, despite some improvement. Six
nations abstained and Mozambique was absent.
   The Soviet Union intervened militarily in neighboring
Afghanistan in late 1979 and its troops stayed on to fight
anti-Marxist guerrillas.
</TEXT>
