<1ST_LINE>u a AM-CDC--InjuryGoals     03-10 0598</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CDC--Injury Goals,0610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Many Of Feds' 1990 Goals For Injury Death Prevention Likely To Be
Met</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release 6:30 p.m. EST</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nine years ago, federal health officials set nine
goals for reducing fatalities from injuries in the United States by
1990. Thursday, officials predicted at least six of those goals
will be met.
   The fatality rates from many types of injuries _ such as car
accidents, house fires and drownings _ have dropped since 1979,
when the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services announced its
1990 goals, the Centers for Disease control reported Thursday.
   But in some cases, the rates have not fallen as far as the
government had hoped, the CDC said. While authorities expect to
meet the goals on reducing deaths from car crashes, childhood
household accidents, house fires and gun accidents, the goals for
reducing deaths from falls and drownings won't be met.
   ``Achieving the 1990 objectives ... will require the coordinated
efforts of federal, state and local agencies, ... academic
institutions, professional associations and private entities,'' the
Atlanta-based CDC said in its weekly report.
   Here, from the CDC report, are the nation's 1990 goals for
reducing deaths from injuries, and the progress being made:
   _ Reducing the nation's annual motor vehicle fatality rate, from
23.6 such deaths per 100,000 Americans in 1978 to 18 per 100,000 in
1990: By 1984, the rate had fallen to 19.6, and the goal is
projected to be met, in part because of a reduction in
alcohol-related fatalities.
   _ Reducing the motor vehicle fatality rate for children under
15, from 9 per 100,000 in 1978 to 5.5: By 1984, the rate had fallen
to 6.6, and the goal is projected to be met.
   _ Reducing the death rate from falls from 6.2 per 100,000 in
1978 to 2.0: The rate had fallen only to 5.1 by 1984, and the goal
is not expected to be reached. People over 65 continue to have high
death rates from falls _ for example, in 1984, 10.2 such deaths per
100,000 people age 65-74, and 147 per 100,000 people over 84.
   _ Reducing the death rate for children under 15 in home injuries
from 6 per 100,000 in 1978 to 5: The 1984 rate was 4.9, already
meeting the objective.
   _ Reducing the drowning rate from 3.2 per 100,000 in 1978 to
1.5: The rate had fallen only to 2.3 in '84, and the goal is not
expected to be met.
   _ Reducing the number of deaths in residential fires from 5,401
in 1978 to 4,500: The objective was reached in 1984, when 4,466
Americans died in such fires.
   _ Reducing the number of deaths in firearm accidents from 1,806
in 1978 to 1,700: The goal was met in 1984, when 1,668 such deaths
were reported.
   _ Reducing the suicide rate among 15-24-year-olds from 12.1 per
100,000 in 1978 to 11: The rate is going up, not down. It was 12.2
per 100,000 in 1984, up slightly from 1978 and up about 200 percent
from 1950. The CDC noted that various suicide prevention approaches
have been tried in communities, but the effectiveness is not known.
   _ Reducing the homicide rate among black males aged 15-24 from
70.7 per 100,000 in 1978 to 60: This goal will probably be met,
according to CDC researcher Dr. Richard Sattin. The rate had fallen
in 1984 to 61.5. This goal was set recognizing the high homicide
rate among young black men, Sattin said, noting that the national
homicide rate in 1984 was 8.4 per 100,000 Americans.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
