<DOCNO> AP880310-0194 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-88 1718EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-SoCarolinaDems     03-10 0575</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SoCarolina Dems,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>In South Carolina, Jackson Should Fulfill Chant</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID REED</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson is the favorite son and
front-runner in South Carolina's Democratic caucuses Saturday,
leaving the division of the remaining delegates among the other
presidential candidates as the only question mark.
   Jackson was born and raised in South Carolina, one of two states
he won in his 1984 presidential race.
   Jackson, who plans a homecoming campaign trip Friday, has the
overwhelming support of the state's black voters, who make up more
than one-third of the electorate, and got an average of 10 percent
of the white vote in other Southern states on Super Tuesday.
   Between a quarter and a half of South Carolina Democrats
traditionally remain uncommitted at the caucus meetings to give
themselves more maneuvering room through the nominating process.
They usually choose a candidate at the county or state convention.
   That leaves few delegates for the rest of the field. But in a
tight national race in which no candidate appears to be able to
capture the majority of delegates, every one helps.
   ``This certainly increases the importance of South Carolina
because the delegate count is so close,'' said Kevin Gray, state
coordinator for Jackson.
   The candidates are relying on grass-roots organizing, telephone
banks and direct mail to lure Democrats to the caucus; none is
buying television advertisements.
   Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr., who plans to campaign in the
state on Friday, has the largest organization in the state and the
most endorsements from elected officials, who wield strong
influence at the caucuses.
   Gore also has the momentum from his strong showing across the
South Tuesday, which lessened the perception among some South
Carolinians that he's not electable.
   Missouri Rep. Richard Gephardt, who traveled across the state
Wednesday and Thursday, has a skeletal organization. But his few
endorsements are the biggest _ former Govs. Dick Riley and Robert
McNair and all of the South Carolina Democratic congressmen who
have chosen sides.
   Dukakis has an even smaller local organization.
   All of the competing state campaigns except Gore's has conceded
that Jackson will win the lion's share of the 44 delegates at stake.
   ``I don't think there is any doubt that Jesse Jackson will
win,'' said Bill Prince, Gephardt's state coordinator.
   House Speaker Robert Sheheen, Gore's state chairman, said
``there's really no way of knowing'' whether the Tennessee senator
can upset Jackson. ``We're not conceding anything to anybody.''
   Gore, who is the only candidate with an outside chance of
upsetting Jackson, is promoting his strong ties to the South and a
strong defense, which plays will in the Palmetto State.
   Gephardt is hoping to use his trade policy to gain votes in the
state, which has seen its largest industry _ textiles _ severely
weakened by cheap foreign imports.
   But most political scientists and campaign officials agree that
because the Democratic field is so large and so close together and
because a large number of delegates probably will remain
uncommitted, the results Saturday will be inconclusive.
   Take Riley's assessment Thursday, for example: ``Jackson will do
very well. Gore is well organized. Dukakis will get a piece of the
vote and Gephardt will get his share.''
   South Carolina's Democratic leaders decided against following
the crowd on Super Tuesday, when all of the other Southern states
held primaries.
   ``They decided to nestle in the days of old,'' Clemson
University political science professor Steve Wainscott said
Thursday.
</TEXT>
