<1ST_LINE>r w AM-China-PeaceCorps     03-10 0542</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Peace Corps,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Applicants Eager To Work In China Start Phoning Agency</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HENRY GOTTLIEB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Applicants started phoning a few hours after
China announced it would accept the Peace Corps for the first time
and the agency said Thursday it is eager for negotiations with the
Chinese to set the terms of the program.
   Though the concentration is likely to be on English teachers,
China still must decide what special skills it wants the volunteers
to have, where they will serve and how large the Peace Corps
program would be.
   The agency also will have to put volunteers for the program
through a rigorous testing program that rejects four out of five
applicants, said Arlen Erdahl, director of recruiting for the Peace
Corps.
   ``We'll be just as careful as we always are,'' Erdahl told a
news conference.
   The United States, in a drive for better relations with China,
had been giving Chinese officials information about Peace Corps
programs for years and began discussions of the issue in 1984.
   On Wednesday, Foreign Minister Wu Xueqian announced during an
appearance at the National Press Club that China had agreed to
accept volunteers and would work out the details with U.S.
officials.
   A few hours later, Karl and Katherine Brandt of Lexington, S.C.,
heard a radio news report about it and phoned the regional Peace
Corps office in Atlanta to volunteer.
   ``We've always wanted to do something like this; we visited some
Peace Corps people in Grenada once and when we heard about China we
decided this might be a neat idea,'' Brandt said in a telephone
interview.
   The 55-year-old chemist said he and his wife, a nurse, have
never lived outside the United States but ``we'd be interested in
going to China.''
   The Peace Corps has been sending American teachers, technicians,
professionals and community workers to foreign cities and villages
since 1961, when President Kennedy started the agency to improve
America's overseas image.
   The biggest country to accept volunteers had been India, which
had Peace Corps programs between 1962 and 1976, but China is the
most populated country and Erdahl said America's ``fascination''
with that nation is likely to spur applications for the corps.
   He noted, however, that while applicants for the Peace Corps are
asked to state their preferred assignments, they are not guaranteed
being sent to a specific country.
   There are currently 64 countries with Peace Corps programs. The
process of establishing the agency's relationship with China will
be the same as it was for the others. It could take between two
months and two years.
   ``This is just the starting gong,'' said John Scales, the
agency's general counsel.
   After a series of meetings, China will make a formal request for
a Peace Corps presence, a team of agency officials will visit the
country and the two sides will hammer out an agreement on numbers
of volunteers, where they will do their work and what they will do.
   Erdahl and several other Peace Corps officials who appeared at
the news conference suggested that they expected China to be most
interested in Peace Corps English teachers. The agency has become a
specialist in teaching English as a second language and runs such
programs in 33 countries.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
