<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-88 2030EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-MotherhoodJudgeship     03-10 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Motherhood Judgeship,0373</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Backlash Propels Bramblett Past McKellips</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EL PASO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge who suggested during his
re-election campaign that his opponent should stay home with her
young children has been turned out of office in a landslide.
   State District Judge John McKellips' ex-wife and six children
had endorsed his opponent, assistant county attorney Mary Anne
Bramblett, in Tuesday's Democratic primary.
   Ms. Bramblett outpolled McKellips 32,412 to 10,752 and she is
assured of taking office because there is no Republican on the
November ballot.
   Ms. Bramblett, a political newcomer, attributed her victory to a
negative image that may have started with McKellips' bitter divorce
in 1985. Lillian McKellips sued for divorce, claiming McKellips was
having an affair with his 1984 campaign manager, Margaret Randle.
   McKellips married Ms. Randle two months after the divorce was
granted. He gained publicity again last summer, when police were
summoned to the courthouse to quell a quarrel between him and his
new wife.
   Last month, Lillian McKellips and the couple's six children
endorsed Ms. Bramblett, citing McKellips' treatment of them. A
couple of weeks later, in an address at a sheriff's deputies'
meeting, McKellips questioned Ms. Bramblett's qualifications,
partly because she is a mother.
   ``She had to take some time out for maternity leave to have two
small children, so I don't know how much time she's actually spent
working as an attorney,'' he told the deputies.
   While attacking his opponent for taking time off to care for her
newborns, McKellips criticized working mothers by linking absent
mothers to overcrowded prisons.
   The next day, the judge amended his comments, saying ``it would
have been more correct to have used the term `parent' rather than
`mother.''
   Ms. Bramblett, whose children are 3 and 4 years old, said at the
time: ``Everybody got the clear message that (McKellips believes) I
am not qualified to be a judge because I'm a woman and a mother.''
   County Judge Luther Jones, who recruited Ms. Bramblett to run,
said the victory was ``truly an epochal event in El Paso's legal
history. The image of both the attorneys and the entire judiciary
have suffered immeasurable harm during the McKellips tenure on the
bench.''
</TEXT>
