<HEAD>Chita Rivera's Dancing Despite Shattered Leg</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to CORRECT that tour under way, ADDS 8 grafs to
UPDATE with lawsuit by Rockettes. 1st 5 grafs for release 6 p.m.
EST.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chita Rivera, whose left leg has been held
together by 12 screws since a car accident two years ago, says she
never doubted she'd be dancing again one day.
   Now, the longtime Broadway star, who is touring the country in a
revival of ``Can-Can,'' has asked the producers to add more dancing
to her new role, she said in an interview with Parade magazine.
   ``I'm not a Pollyanna; it hurts to dance,'' said Rivera, 55.
``But you don't keep telling yourself that.''
   She sometimes felt like quitting during physical therapy, when
``I would feel like I was going to hit the ceiling.'' But her
positive side prevailed.
   ``There are some people whose spirits are so high, their
determination so great, that you practically have to shoot them to
get them down,'' she says. ``I guess I'm one of those people. The
spirit is the strongest thing there is.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>End material embargoed for release at 6 p.m. EST.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Meanwhile, five Rockettes are suing Radio City Music Hall and
the producers of the touring show, charging them with false
advertising and violating the agreement with the dancers' union.
   The touring company advertisements say that 14 Rockettes are
dancing with Rivera in the production, according to Bernard B.
Cohen, attorney for the five. However, he said, only four real
Rockettes are in the 39-city tour, which started Jan. 29.
   ``Instead of dancing with Chita Rivera, the real Rockettes are
doing a tap dance on the unemployment line,'' he said.
   The contract between Radio City and the dancers' union, the
American Guild of Variety Artists, specifies that only Rockettes on
the official roster be hired for productions featuring the
Rockettes, Cohen said.
   The five dancers are seeking $2 million in damages.
   Radio City has maintained that the five could not handle the
dance routine and that the ``imposters'' are new Rockettes.
   The producers of the show are Kan Kan National Co., the Troika
Company Inc. and Trice Talent Payment Inc.
