<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-88 2055EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Kissinger-Israel     03-10 0338</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kissinger-Israel,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kissinger Says Israel Should Hold Elections, Reject Peace
Conference</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Secretary of State Henry A. Kissinger
said Thursday that Israel should hold early elections in order to
resolve an ``intolerable'' political problem.
   In a television interview taped for broadcast this weekend on
the syndicated ``One on One'' interview program, Kissinger also
reiterated his position that Israel should give Jordan the occupied
Gaza Strip and densely populated parts of the West Bank.
   Gaza was under Egyptian control before Israel captured it in the
1967 Mideast war, but Kissinger said it should now be given to
Jordan. He did not explain.
   Kissinger said Israel and the United States should stay away
from an international peace conference proposed by Secretary of
State George P. Shultz.
   ``I think there should be elections in Israel. It's desirable.
You have a prime minister and a foreign minister who are cutting
each other up,'' he said.
   Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, head of the right-wing
Likud bloc, and Foreign Minister Shimon Peres, who leads the Labor
Party, have both considered moving the elections up from November.
   ``Each side is trying to line up the United States and other
foreign countries in their support. It's an intolerable situation.
So the earlier they have an election and get unified, the more
important it is,'' Kissinger said.
   Kissinger, who mediated Israeli agreements with the Arabs in the
mid-1970s, said he would prefer that the United States help
negotiate peace between the sides without interference from the
other four permanent members of the U.N. Security Council _ the
Soviet Union, China, England and France.
   ``I'd prefer Shultz to do it alone,'' he said.
   All the other countries will press for Israeli withdrawal to its
1967 borders, he said. ``I think those will guarantee the
destruction of Israel,'' Kissinger said.
   He said a formula must be found under which Israel would give
back some of those territories but retain sufficient lands to
guarantee it a defensible buffer zone.
</TEXT>
