<1ST_LINE>r a AM-JohnnySpain     03-10 0515</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Johnny Spain,0529</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>San Quentin Six Member Freed From Prison</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE GEISSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VACAVILLE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Black Panther convicted of
murdering two guards in a bloody 1971 San Quentin escape attempt
walked out of prison on bail Thursday, almost two years after a
judge ordered that he get a new trial.
   ``I feel great. ... I'm just very happy,'' Johnny Spain told
reporters at the front gate of the state prison at Vacaville, 50
miles east of San Francisco.
   ``I won't let anyone down who has supported me and there have
been many who supported me,'' he said, adding he was prepared to
deal with the challenges of living on the outside after 21 years
behind bars.
   Spain was hugged and congratulated by attorneys and
investigators who worked on his case, and members of their families.
   Attorney Dennis Riordan said Spain had promised to attend a play
in San Francisco on Thursday night with the 10-year-old daughter of
one of his supporters. Riordan said Spain would remain in the San
Francisco area until at least Wednesday for court appearances, then
planned to visit Los Angeles to see his wife and children.
   Some $100,000 of Spain's bail has been posted but $250,000 in
property must be guaranteed by Wednesday, Riordan said, adding that
he anticipated no problems.
   U.S. District Judge Thelton Henderson, who had previously
granted Spain a new trial in the ``San Quentin Six'' case, a state
lawyer's request Wednesday to delay bail until the state parole
board reconsiders his case.
   Spain, 38, has been behind bars since December 1966, when he was
arrested for a murder and robbery in Los Angeles.
   He later became the only prisoner convicted of murder in a 1971
uprising in which George Jackson, widely known for his book of
prison writings, ``Soledad Brother,'' was killed, along with two
other prisoners and three guards.
   Authorities said Spain, seen running from a maximum-security
unit with Jackson, conspired with him in an escape attempt that led
to the killings.
   Henderson reversed Spain's convictions in 1986, saying he had
been denied a fair trial by being required to wear heavy shackles
for every court appearance during the five years of proceedings.
   The state's appeal of the ruling is to be argued Monday before
the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals.
   On Tuesday, Los Angeles Superior Court Judge Kathleen Parker
ordered Spain paroled immediately from the sentence he has been
serving for the 1966 murder, a sentence that had kept Henderson
from granting bail earlier.
   She found that the parole board had improperly lengthened his
sentence nearly six years by applying regulations passed in 1976 to
disciplinary violations committed in 1970 and 1971.
   Riordan said Spain had spent twice as long in prison as the
average sentence for a similar crime.
   Lawyers said Spain would be living in San Francisco and working
as an electrician while his case is on appeal. Henderson's order
allows him to travel within the state and visit his wife, whom he
married while in prison, and two young sons in Los Angeles.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880310-0204 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-88 1955EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Pentagon-Gulf     03-10 0487</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pentagon-Gulf,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran Said Building Silkworm Platforms in New Area of Gulf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran has begun constructing crude launch pads
for Silkworm missiles on the island of Abu Musa in the Persian
Gulf, potentially expanding the area within which it can menace
shipping, U.S. military sources said Thursday.
   The defense officials, who agreed to discuss the matter only if
not identified, stressed that American intelligence agencies so far
had failed to detect any effort by Iran to actually send Silkworm
missiles over to the small island.
   Iran has built similar launch pads at other sites on its main
coastline without ever deploying any actual missiles, one source
noted.
   ``But it's still significant because it would really extend the
coverage of these missiles ... if they deployed Silkworms there,''
another official said.
   The Silkworm is a Chinese-built variant of an old Russian
missile that can be fired from mobile launchers on land against
ships. The missiles have a range of about 50 miles and while not
particularly accurate, they carry a large warhead packed with
conventional explosives.
   According to U.S. sources, Iran has acquired more than 100
Silkworms and stored the majority of them at a large naval base at
Bandar Abbas near the Strait of Hormuz, the sole entrance to the
Persian Gulf.
   Although concrete launch pads aren't essential for the Silkworm
truck launchers to operate, the Iranians nonetheless have
constructed such pads at several sites along the coastline
overlooking the strait. As a result, American warships escorting
tankers in and out of the gulf normally go to battle stations for
the passage and Navy jets provide air cover just in case a missile
attack is mounted.
   Abu Musa is a small, Iranian-controlled island inside the Strait
of Hormuz, roughly 50 miles into the gulf and almost in the middle
of the waterway. It long has been used by Iran as a base for
gunboats that have attacked commercial shipping.
   If Iran were to deploy Silkworms on Abu Musa, ``it would be
doubling the arc (of space) that it can threaten,'' one source said
Thursday.
   ``It definitely would extend our area of vulnerability up into
the gulf,'' another official agreed.
   ``We'd have to get pretty serious about (watching) that
island,'' added a third source.
   All the officials stressed that construction on the island had
begun only recently and was proceeding slowly.
   ``But it is assessed to be Silkworm firing platforms,'' said one.
   The United States has been escorting reflagged Kuwaiti tankers
in the gulf since last July. Kuwait, a key ally of Iraq in the
Iran-Iraq war, requested the protection after Iran began singling
out its ships for attack.
   The 16th convoy operation of 1988 and the 38th overall began
Tuesday night and was said to be proceeding uneventfully on
Thursday, with two tankers steaming southbound from Kuwait toward
the Strait of Hormuz along with a Navy frigate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880310-0205 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-88 2056EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Drugs-Aid     03-10 0506</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drugs-Aid,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Legislator Would Halt Aid to Five Latin Drug Countries OKed by
Reagan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Larry Smith on Thursday introduced
resolutions that would deny foreign aid and trade privileges to
Mexico, the Bahamas, Peru, Bolivia and Paraguay for alleged failure
to cooperate with U.S. anti-drug efforts.
   Smith, chairman of the House Foreign Affairs Committee's task
force on international narcotics control, said the five countries
were wrongly certified by President Reagan on March 1 as
cooperating with drug enforcement programs.
   ``Some of these `cooperative' countries have even actively
frustrated our efforts to stop the production of drugs and their
trafficking into the United States,'' Smith, D-Fla., told
reporters. ``It's time the president stands up and does more than
just saying no.''
   Smith and Reps. Benjamin Gilman, R-N.Y., and Dante Fascell,
D-Fla., chairman of the House Foreign Affairs Committee, said the
purpose of the resolutions was not necessarily to cut off aid to
the five countries but to focus public attention on the
certification process and determine whether it can be improved.
   Under comprehensive anti-drug legislation enacted in 1986, the
president must certify annually that major drug-producing and
shipment countries have ``fully cooperated'' with the United
States, or they face loss of a year's worth of military and
economic development aid and U.S. support for international
development bank loans.
   Countries that are ``decertified'' also may suffer a wide range
of trade sanctions at the president's discretion. These include a
50 percent boost in import tariffs, abrogation of airline
agreements, loss of U.S. sugar quotas and a halt in preferred U.S.
customs treatment.
   Reagan recently certified all the 24 major drug countries as
fully cooperating with U.S. anti-drug efforts except for Panama,
Afghanistan, Syria and Iran, which were decertified, and for
Lebanon, Laos and Paraguay, which were certified for ``national
interests.''
   Under the law, Congress has 45 business days _ until May 13 _ to
overrule any of Reagan's recent aid certifications and 30 days _
until April 19 _ to disapprove of further trade privileges for any
countries the president certified as fully cooperating.
   Smith said Mexico should be penalized because it is the primary
source of heroin and marijuana entering the United States, and the
smuggling route for one-third of the cocaine destined for U.S.
consumption.
   He said opium production has increased at least 30 percent and
eradication has fallen by one-third since 1984. Smith said
laundering of illicit drug profits is extensive and that Mexico
provides safe haven for hundreds of drug traffickers indicted in
the United States.
   Smith criticized drug enforcement efforts by the other four
countries, especially the Bahamas, which he said is the major
transit point for half the cocaine and marijuana entering the
United States.
   At a hearing that Smith headed Thursday, Assistant Secretary of
State Elliott Abrams said that ``while we believe that Mexico is
capable of even greater effort against narcotics trafficking, we
also believe that Mexican cooperation ... is substantial and
justifies the president's decision to certify Mexico.''
</TEXT>
