<2ND_LINE>AM-Bolivia,0277</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Striking Oil Workers Return To Jobs Under Dismissal Threat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LA PAZ, Bolivia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil workers returned to work Thursday
after the government began firing strikers, whose walkout paralyzed
oil and gasoline refineries for two days, the government-owned
State Petroleum Co. said.
   The strike began Tuesday, hitting hard at public transportation
and at factories that depend on oil or gasoline to operate.
   About half of State Petroleum's 7,000 workers were estimated to
have gone out on strike.
   Brazil's conservative government gave strikers until Thursday to
return to work or be fired. In previous strikes, the government
carried out similar threats.
   How many strikers were dismissed this time was not disclosed,
nor did the government say whether anyone would be reinstated.
   The government deployed troops to take over refineries and
gasoline stations Tuesday and arrested labor leaders.
   It rationed gasoline and motorists lined up for hours. Many
buses and taxis in major cities went out of service.
   The Federation of Petroleum Workers had rejected a 30 percent
wage increase which the government offered on condition that there
would be no strike for one year. The average petroleum worker earns
$350 a month, compared to $100 a month for other government
employees.
   Saul Soliz, leader of the union, said the no-strike condition
was a government maneuver designed ``to divide the labor movement
against the interests of workers.''
   The union said that the government planned to finance the wage
increase by firing 1,500 workers.
   The government conceded that there would be some dismissals to
finance the pay increase, but said they would not exceed 500.
</TEXT>
