<HEAD>Bolton To Head Civil Division</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John R. Bolton, the Justice Department's
liaison with Congress, will become the assistant attorney general
directing the department's civil division, Attorney General Edwin
Meese III announced Thursday.
   Bolton, who has been assistant attorney general for legislative
affairs since December 1985, will be taking charge of the largest
litigating division in the Justice Department.
   Bolton, 39, succeeds Richard Willard, who left the department in
February to join a Washington law firm.
   The civil division, directly responsible for 20,000 pending
cases, represents the government in constitutional litigation
involving federal statutes, torts, contract claims and federal
regulatory matters.
