<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HeroinStash     03-10 0351</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Heroin Stash,0361</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rival Drug Suspect Squeals On Competition To Police</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY HELEN GILLESPIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Increasing competition within the city's
drug trade prompted a suspected dealer to lead police to a rival's
secret stash of heroin, authorities said Thursday.
   No arrests were made, but 443 small bags of heroin were
confiscated Wednesday, police said. The bags were worth $20 each
for a total street value of $9,000, said Detective William
Gallagher.
   The tipster cooperated with police because of growing
competition among dealers in the North Camden neighborhood, the
worst drug area in the city, Gallagher said.
   ``We couldn't lock him up even though we know this guy is a drug
dealer because he didn't have any on him. We got the stash, said,
`Thank you, very much,' and he split,'' Gallagher said.
   The owner of the drugs was not at the scene when officers
William Durham and Michael Comuso uncovered the stash 10 feet under
a loose brick in the archway of a vacant house, Gallagher said.
   Durham and Comuso had looked for the drugs for about a week,
combing through piles of trash and vacant and abandoned houses,
which Gallagher described as the favored hiding places for drugs.
   The tipster decided to help the officers after his rival began
cutting into his territory, Gallagher said.
   ``There's some conflict of interest up there,'' he said, adding
that drug dealers from Colombia and the Dominican Republic are
trying to take over a neighborhood where black and other Hispanic
dealers have traditionally worked.
   ``North Camden is the hot spot right now. The traffic just flows
through there, especially on Thursday and Friday after payday,'' he
said.
   He declined to release the name of the tipster, saying such
action might make the man a target for retaliation from his rivals.
   In a way, the new spirit of cooperation is an asset for law
enforcement officials who spend hours each day patrolling the
blighted area, he said.
   ``But I also foresee where somebody's going to get hurt up
there,'' he said. ``They'll shoot you in a heartbeat.''
</TEXT>
