<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Mideast     03-10 0664</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Mideast,640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz Calls Mideast Peace Plan `Only Game in Town'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George Shultz said Thursday
his plan for bringing Arabs and Israelis to the negotiating table
is ``the only game in town'' and outlined details for the first
time in public.
   Shultz, testifying on Capitol Hill, also indicated that the
United States would continue to push the plan even if Israeli Prime
Minister Yitzhak Shamir rejects it when he holds talks in
Washington next week.
   ``People have looked at our ideas, and while nobody is saying
yes, nobody wants to say no, because it's the only game in town,''
Shultz said.
   ``People will probably _ would even dodge and object and so on,
but we're going to keep working and see if we can't bring something
out of this,'' he added.
   Shamir has opposed the Shultz plan because it sets a timetable
for negotiations between Israel and the Arabs on the future of the
Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   President Reagan, meanwhile, said in an interview Thursday that
``a great element'' of Israel's coalition government supports the
peace plan and that he will try to persuade Shamir to drop his
objections to the proposal.
   ``I believe that peace is inevitable,'' Reagan said. ``We may
have some differences there as to how to achieve it but I don't
think anyone believes that we can go on just with a constant state
of warfare and unrest (in the Middle East).''
   Shultz, in testimony to the House Appropriations foreign
operations subcommittee, said the United States feels ``time is
awasting'' and wants talks between Israel and Arab countries to
begin by May 1. The talks would be under the auspices of the five
permanent members of the U.N. Security Council _ the United States,
the Soviet Union, China, England and France.
   ``It is essential, particularly from the standpoint of the Arab
side, that there be an auspices for these negotiations, something
that gives them legitimacy,'' he said.
   ``We proposed that this conference initiate these bilateral
negotiations, that it be a body that can receive reports from the
parties on the status of their negotiations, but that ... the
conference will not be able to impose solutions or veto agreements
reached.''
   In what appeared a slight shift, Shultz did not insist as he has
in the past that the Soviets could only participate if they resumed
the diplomatic tiesthey broke with Israel in 1967.
   ``However, I have told the Soviets ... that whether they come to
a conference or not, they cannot expect to play a genuinely
involved role in Middle East affairs'' until they re-establish
official relations with Israel and ease their restrictions on
Jewish emigration, he said.
   In the plan he presented to Israeli and Arab leaders last week,
Shultz stipulated that all the participants must recognize U.N.
resolution 242 and 338, which call for Israel to return lands it
captured from the Arabs in the 1967 Mideast war. In return, the
Arab states would have to recognize the Jewish state's right to
exist.
   Shultz did not speak directly of the three months of
Israeli-Palestinian clashes in which more than 80 Arabs have been
killed. But he referred to it, saying that ``people's minds are a
little more open now than they've been in some time, and we should
take advantage of that.''
   Under the plan, the Palestinians would be represented by a joint
delegation with Jordan, Shultz said.
   The initial negotiations would address ``transitional
arrangements'' for three years of Palestinian self-rule, he said.
The United States would present a draft proposal as a preliminary
working paper.
   Such negotiations could be concluded within six months because
much of the preparatory work has been completed, he said.
   The transitional arrangement could be put into place within
three months after the end of the negotiations. Immediately
following the six-month negotiations, the sides would begin
yearlong talks on the final status of the territories, he said.
</TEXT>
