<2ND_LINE>AM-Dole,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dole Says Bush is Hiding</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY MASSEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican presidential candidate Bob Dole jabbed
at Vice President George Bush on Thursday, saying his rival for the
GOP nomination was ``hiding from America.''
   Dole, after touring a rehabilitation hospital, stepped up his
attacks on the vice president for not agreeing to one-on-one
debates before next Tuesday's Illinois primary.
   ``I don't think he wants to stand up without notes and talk
about issues,'' Dole said. ``It's not a strength of his. His
strength is to run these TV ads that distort somebody's record.''
   Dole apparently was referring to television spots that the Bush
campaign has used to raise questions about the Kansas senator's
position on taxes. Dole blames his campaign's failure to
effectively counter the ads for his loss in New Hampshire.
   ``I think he's going to play it safe,'' Dole said of Bush.
``He's not going to debate Bob Dole. He wouldn't dare debate Bob
Dole for two hours without notes, without Roger Ailes.''
   Ailes is a media consultant.
   At nearly every campaign stop since he arrived in Illinois on
Tuesday, Dole has hammered away at Bush and challenged him to speak
out on the issues.
   ``It's almost impossible to separate Bush from (President)
Reagan because he's been standing next to him for seven years,''
Dole said. ``Unfortunately, I didn't have time to stand there. I
had to get Reagan's program passed.''
   Dole also is questioning Bush's ``electability,'' saying he
would be a stronger candidate for the party to field against
Democrats in November.
   ``My view is it's going to be a very tough, tough race for
George Bush,'' said Dole. ``He does not attract Democrats or
independents.''
   Dole said he would seek out supporters of Rep. Jack Kemp now
that the New York Republican has pulled out of the presidential
race. He expects to soon receive the endorsement of Rep. Henry
Hyde, R-Ill., a key Kemp backer in the state.
   Dole said he faces a ``steep hill to climb'' to defeat Bush.
   ``I have to do very well in this state,'' Dole said.
   ``Does that mean winning? That means doing very well.''
   Dole seemed to be backing off slightly from statements on
Wednesday that Illinois was a must-win state for his struggling
candidacy, but he dismissed questions from reporters on whether he
was scaling down his expectations in the state.
   Dole's first stop on Thursday was to the Rehabilitation
Institute of Chicago, where he toured the hospital and greeted
patients, many of whom were confined to wheelchairs.
   The medical center is just a short distance away from another
hospital where Dole underwent surgery 40 years ago for wounds he
suffered in World War II.
   One woman patient told Dole, ``You're not going to get
Bushwhacked in the Midwest.''
   Dole gave words of encouragement to some of the patients and
told them how it was difficult for him to regain the use of one of
his arms which had been paralyzed.
   ``I don't give up easy. I'm like everybody in this building,''
Dole said after his tour. ``You wouldn't walk out of here if you
gave up easy. So I'm a fighter.''
</TEXT>
