<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-Japan-Nuclear 1stLd-Writethru a0747 03-10 0738</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Japan-Nuclear, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0747,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congressional Opponents of US-Japan Pact May Try To Kill it Next
Week</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Ledes with 13 grafs to UPDATE with details of GAO report and
defense of accord; DELETES 15th graf pvs, The source, as now
outdated; picks up 8th graf pvs, In December</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pact allowing Japan to retrieve plutonium
from U.S. nuclear wastes would leave the United States without
``effective control'' over reprocessing of the hazardous material,
the General Accounting Office has concluded.
   The GAO, the investigative arm of Congress, also found fault
with the agreement's provisions to guard against proliferation of
plutonium, the principal element in nuclear weapons, and said it
deprived Congress of its ``oversight function.''
   Opponents of the accord said they had failed to work out a
compromise with the State Department and may move to kill the
agreement next week.
   The accord, signed last November, gives Japan advance permission
for 30 years to recover plutonium from the fuel the United States
supplies for its nuclear power plants after it is used.
   Congressional opponents wanted the United States to have the
right to review the use of plutonium in any future Japanese
facilities on a ``case-by-case'' basis, and to be able to suspend
the agreement in a terrorism threat or other national security
situations.
   The congressional foes also sought to have the agreement
reviewed every five years.
   These changes would require renegotiating the terms with Japan,
which the State Department declined to do, said a congressional
source, speaking only on condition of anonymity.
   A leading opponent, Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif., said ``it is
extremely unfortunate the State Department has rejected a
compromise agreement. It is a bad agreement. It has serious flaws.''
   Cranston, chairman of the Senate Asia subcommittee, called on
the Reagan administration to withdraw the accord. ``Otherwise,'' he
said, ``it faces growing opposition'' in Congress.
   The GAO report was written by Milton Socolar, a special
assistant to the U.S. Comptroller General, and was dated Feb. 29.
It was obtained Thursday.
   The report said the agreement does not meet various requirements
of the Atomic Energy Act. It said giving ``blanket approval'' to
Japan for reprocessing plutonium ``would leave the United States
with no effective control over the life of the proposed agreement.''
   A U.S. official involved in the negotiations said, however, the
``safeguard concepts'' in the pact are adequate and that the
agreement could be suspended in the event of proliferation or a
terrorist threat.
   The official, speaking only if not named, said the agreement
``makes sure terrorists cannot get into the facilities.''
   In December, the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, in an
unusual move, voted 15-3 to return the pact to President Reagan and
asked that it be renegotiated. Opponents argued it sets a precedent
to encourage potentially hazardous trade in plutonium, which is a
potent cancer-causing agent.
   Opponents also complained the plutonium would be shipped over
Alaska and possibly other areas of the United States.
   On Tuesday, the State Department said the plutonium would be
shipped ``in accordance with rigorous physical protection and
safety requirements.''
   A statement issued by the Non-Proliferation Office said planes
carrying the plutonium soon will be able to fly non-stop from
Europe to Japan, taking a polar route. This would avoid overflights
of the United States, Canada or any other country.
   ``The administration is, therefore, prepared to rule out air
shipments of plutonium under the agreement from overflying or
landing in the United States, except in the case of aircraft
emergency,'' the statement said.
   Under the agreement, Japan would ship the spent nuclear fuel to
reprocessing plants in Britain or France, which would separate
plutonium from the waste. The plutonium then would be shipped back
to Japan by air.
   The congressional source said the statement was designed to ease
the concerns of Sen. Frank H. Murkowski, R-Alaska, but did not
basically alter the flaws in the agreement.
   Also, the source said, Richard N. Perle and Frank Gaffney,
former Defense Department officials, wrote members of Congress
urging rejection of the agreement as ``seriously flawed'' and
complaining that the Pentagon was not permitted to play a
meaningful role in the negotiations with Japan.
   Forty-five tons of plutonium could be airlifted from Europe to
Japan by the year 2000 under the pact. It takes 15 pounds to make a
bomb.
   Congress has until April 25 to block the agreement with Japan or
it takes effect.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880310-0215 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-88 2101EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ForeignAid     03-10 0490</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Foreign Aid,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz Says US Aid `Embarrassing' Compared with Europe's</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz on
Thursday called U.S. foreign aid embarrassingly low compared with
the effort made by Western European countries.
   He was challenging Rep. David R. Obey, D-Wis., who chaired a
hearing at which Shultz testified.
   ``Mr. Chairman, you talked about burden sharing, but if we
compared our effort in that regard with our European friends, I
think we would see a somewhat embarrassing picture,'' Shultz said.
   He was immediately supported by the member who had been
questioning him, Rep. John Edward Porter, R-Ill.
   ``It's shameful, Mr. Secretary, it's absolutely shameful,''
Porter said. ``I certainly agree with you.''
   Shultz was apparently referring to figures for 1986, compiled by
the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development, which
show that total U.S. development aid is high _ $9.56 billion for
1986 _ but low as a proportion of U.S. wealth.
   The OECD calculates that U.S. aid amounted to 0.23 percent of
the country's total production. By that measure Norway was at the
top of the list with 1.2 percent of its production, an effort more
than five times greater. The United States was close to the bottom
of the list. Only Austria was lower, with 0.21 percent.
   Shultz also made a comparison with the Soviet Union.
   ``The fact of the matter is ... the Soviets are spending
considerably more than we are in what we classify as as economic
and security assistance,'' he said. ``And their economy is half the
size of ours. So that our effort is relatively small.''
   According to the U.S. Agency for International Development, the
Soviets spent $3.68 billion on economic aid in 1986, equal to 0.33
percent of their national production.
   Obey had begun the hearing with an explanation of why Congress
provided smaller amounts for aid than had been requested by the
administration for countries where the United States has military
bases.
   ``We felt that the United States is getting the shaft from our
allies in terms of burden sharing around the world,'' he said.
   ``And we feel it's the obligation of our European allies to
carry a greater share of the load in supporting common defense
efforts. ... So it's not that we have any policy dislike for Spain
or for Portugal or for Greece or for any of the other countries
involved,'' he said.
   ``It's simply that when the U.S. taxpayer spends $1,100 on
average to support military and foreign expenditures, and the
(West) German taxpayer spends $450 and the Spanish taxpayer spends
$113 and the average for Europe is $318, we feel those are not good
conditions under which we ought to be making large commitments of
expenditures,'' he said.
   Obey, who chairs the foreign operations subcommittee of the
House Appropriations Committee, also complained of administration
proposals to lower spending on some domestic programs for education
and low-cost housing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880310-0216 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-88 2103EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-PublicBroadcasting     03-10 0337</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Public Broadcasting,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Public Broadcasting Corporation Needs $200 Million For New
Satellite</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Corporation for Public Broadcasting told
Congress on Thursday it needs $200 million to replace an aging
satellite system that is due to expire in 1991.
   Donald Ledwig, CPB president, told a House Energy and Commerce
subcommittee that unless the satellite system is replaced, the
skies will go dark for public radio and television stations that
rely on it to receive programming from the Public Broadcasting
Service.
   ``Without funding for the satellite, there would be no way to
replace it unless we pulled it out of our budget,'' which would
leave little money for anything else, Ledwig said.
   CPB is asking Congress to authorize $395 million for CPB's
general operations for the year beginning Oct. 1, 1991. The board
also proposes its federal support be increased to $411 million in
fiscal year 1992 and to $427 million in fiscal year 1993. The $200
million for a new satellite system would be additional.
   The Reagan administration in its recent budget proposal asked
Congress to freeze CPB's funding at its current level of $214
million for fiscal years 1989 through 1991 and did not include any
funds for a new satellite system. Congress previously had
authorized CPB to receive $228 million in 1989 and $233 in fiscal
1990.
   Rep. Edward Markey, D-Mass., chairman of the telecommunications
subcommittee, has introduced legislation that would split the
difference between what CPB wants and what the administration is
proposing.
   Some on the subcommittee, however, said that at a time of
soaring budget deficits, public broadcasters cannot count on
increasing their federal support.
   Rep. Michael G. Oxley, R-Ohio, said public broadcasters should
consider limited advertising between programs an a way to fill
their budget gaps.
   ``I am troubled by the intransigence of the (public
broadcasting) system on this important question,'' Oxley said.
   The Public Broadcasting Act prohibits advertising on public
radio and TV stations, but Oxley said this raises constitutional
free-speech questions.
</TEXT>
