<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-88 2105EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-HumanRights-Cuba     03-10 0546</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Human Rights-Cuba,0562</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UN Rights Commission Will Send Delegation to Cuba</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA WATSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.N. Human Rights Commission accepted Fidel
Castro's invitation Thursday to send its first delegation to Cuba
to investigate allegations of human rights abuses.
   The 43-nation body approved without a vote the decision drafted
by four Latin American countries to accept the invitation Cuba
extended Wednesday.
   Plans are for a six-member delegation, including the chairman of
the U.N. commission, to visit the Caribbean island this year and
report to the 1989 meeting.
   Before the decision, the United States and Latin American
countries led by Argentina, Colombia, Mexico and Peru, spent a day
negotiating acceptable conditions for a visit.
   In another action Thursday, the commission condemned Chile's
military government for violations including murder, kidnapping and
torture by security forces, continued curbs on basic civil rights
and intimidation by authorities.
   A resolution passed 34-0 cited ``acts of extreme violence from
all sources in Chile which have exacerbated the climate of
insecurity.'' Seven countries abstained, including the United
States, Japan and Brazil, and two did not vote.
   Armando Valladares, a former Cuban political prisoner who heads
the U.S. delegation to the rights commission, told a news
conference the two-year U.S. effort to have the commission examine
Cuba had forced Castro's hand.
   ``This visit has not been a voluntary gesture by Cuba,'' he
said, speaking in Spanish with simultaneous translation.
   A day of negotiations produced ``conditions and guarantees'' for
an impartial visit that did not exist when Cuba extended the
invitation Wednesday, said Valladares, who was released from 22
years in a Cuban prison six years ago. He called the commission
decision ``a triumph for human rights.''
   An official of the U.N. Center for Human Rights, K.F. Nyamekye,
said it was understood that the six members _ commission Chairman
Alioune Sene of Senegal and five others to be chosen geographically
_ would meet in Geneva for a week in May or June to plan their work.
   Cuba has been cited for such human rights violations as torture
and mistreatment of political prisoners by the United States and
international organizations, including Amnesty International.
   Castro's government denies the charges and fought the U.S.
effort to put its human rights situation on the agenda of the
commission, which meets every year for six weeks. Debate
intensified this year when Valladares, who wrote a book about
mistreatment and torture in prison, was chosen to lead the U.S.
delegation.
   After Thursday's decision, the United States withdrew a
resolution calling for the U.N. secretary-general to examine the
human rights situation in Cuba and report to the commission.
   Valladares said the plan adopted ``goes far beyond what we had
originally asked for. It is very important.'
   A member of the Cuban delegation said it would not have a
statement Thursday.
   The document approved is brief and does not give conditions of
the visit, saying only that a six-member team ``should visit Cuba
in order to observe the human rights situation'' and prepare a
report.
   Sene told the organization the investigating team would have
unrestricted access to information while in Cuba.
   They will visit Cuba for ``about five days'' in July or August,
then reconvene in Geneva in January to consider and adopt their
report, said Nyamekye.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880310-0219 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-88 1849EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-DartmouthUnrest     03-10 0599</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dartmouth Unrest,0622</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dartmouth Disciplines 4 Students For Harassing Black Professor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BETSY HENDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dartmouth College suspended two members of
a conservative student newspaper for two years Thursday and another
for two terms for harassing a black professor in his classroom.
   A fourth student staffer for the independent Dartmouth Review
was placed on disciplinary probation for one year for disorderly
conduct.
   The four white students had faced possible expulsion over a Feb.
25 confrontation with music Professor William Cole over a Review
article criticizing his class and his teaching ability.
   The article and the confrontation had drawn allegations of
racism against the Review and prompted demonstrations by black
students at the Ivy League school.
   The penalties imposed by the student-faculty Dartmouth Committee
on Standards take effect Wednesday, the end of the current academic
term.
   Christopher Baldwin of Hinsdale, Ill., John Quilhot of Fort
Wayne, Ind., John Sutter of St. Louis, and Sean Nolan of Lexington,
Mass., were charged with harassment, disorderly conduct and
invasion of privacy.
   Baldwin, a junior who is the Review editor, and Sutter, a senior
who is its executive editor, were suspended until the fall of 1989,
or six terms.
   Quilhot, a sophomore photographer, was suspended for two terms.
Nolan, a freshman contributor to the paper, was placed on
probation. Dartmouth operates on a three-term college year.
   Baldwin said the students will appeal.
   ``I knew we were going to get a sentence like that when we
walked into the hearing,'' Baldwin said. ``The hearing was
conducted in a lynch-mob hysteria.''
   ``They did what was politically expedient, not what was right,''
he said.
   The disciplinary panel found all four guilty of disorderly
conduct for failure to leave Cole's classroom after being asked
repeatedly to leave.
   Baldwin was guilty of harassment for initiating and persisting
in a ``vexatious oral exchange'' with Cole, and Sutter was guilty
of repeated ``aggressive, confrontational and particularly
vexatious'' behavior, the committee said.
   Cole, a specialist in African-American music and author of books
on jazz musicians John Coltrane and Miles Davis, sued the Review
for libel five years ago over an article questioning his competence
and saying he ``looks like a used Brillo pad.'' Cole later dropped
the suit.
   During nearly 16 hours of hearings last weekend, the four
students proclaimed their innocence and denied any racial
motivation.
   Founded in 1980 with support from such conservatives as Patrick
Buchanan and William F. Buckley, the Review repeatedly has been
accused of insensitivity to blacks, women and homosexuals.
   Baldwin led the group that approached Cole in a recital hall
after the professor finished a class.
   Baldwin said the Review wanted to give Cole another chance to
respond to an article in the Review several days earlier. In that
article the Review printed remarks, including profanities, that
Cole made in a telephone interview.
   Witnesses who testified before the committee last weekend agreed
that Cole became agitated and yelled and cursed when the four
approached him. Cole testified that he felt harassed and provoked,
and he accused the Review of bigotry.
   The invasion of privacy charge arose because Cole was
photographed and tape-recorded without permission.
   One witness, Luzmila Johnson, head of the Afro-American Society
at Dartmouth, testified that Sutter uttered a racial slur as he
left the recital hall. Sutter vehemently denied the charge.
   Two years ago, 12 people, most of them Review members, mounted a
sledgehammer attack on symbolic anti-apartheid shanties on the
college green.
   Three of the students were suspended. Seven others received
community-service sentences, including Baldwin.
   Dartmouth has nearly 4,100 undergraduates, nearly 7 percent of
them black.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880310-0220 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-88 1849EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p PuertoRico-Republicans     03-10 0344</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>Puerto Rico-Republicans,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GOP Leaders Considering Canceling Primary To Give Delegates To
Bush</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican Party officials said
Thursday they intend to award Puerto Rico's 14 GOP national
convention votes to Vice President George Bush and are considering
calling off the primary to do it.
   ``We haven't canceled the primary, but we are considering every
way possible not to have one,'' GOP vice chairman and local Bush
campaign manager Jose Dapena Thompson said. ``The reason is simple:
the nomination of George Bush has been practically assured.''
   However, the underlying issues at stake turn more on statehood
for the U.S. commonwealth than on presidential politics.
   The Republican primary is scheduled for March 20, when voters
are to cast ballots for slates committed to Bush; his main rival,
Sen. Bob Dole, R-Kan.; or any other Republican candidate as a
write-in.
   Bush needs 1,139 votes to win the GOP presidential nomination.
His total Thursday was 705.
   Dole's campaign chairman in Puerto Rico, Alejandro Cruz, agreed
with Dapena Thompson, but he, too, was unsure whether it was
possible to cancel the primary, or somehow to require Dole's 14
delegates to vote instead for Bush.
   The Republican Party will meet Saturday to review its
alternatives.
   A Democratic primary also is set for March 20, at which 51
Puerto Rico's national elegates are at stake.
   The main issue for both parties is the political status of the
commonwealth, whose citizens enjoy most every right and obligation
as other Americans with the exception that they cannot vote for
president or Congress, and pay no federal taxes.
   The Popular Democratic Party of Gov. Rafael Hernandez Colon
favors a continuation of commonwealth or limited autonomy. The
opposition New Progressive Party, which has strong ties with the
national Republican Party, wants Puerto Rico to be the 51st state.
   ``Our first goal is statehood and we have to be united to fight
for that,'' said Dapena Thompson, the mayor of the south coast city
of Ponce and the New Progressive Party's vice chairman.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880310-0221 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-88 2105EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Gallaudet-Candidates     03-10 0402</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gallaudet-Candidates,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Presidential Candidates Side with Gallaudet Protesters</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Deaf School President Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four presidential candidates _ two Republicans
and two Democrats _ have sided with deaf students at Gallaudet
University who want a hearing-impaired person to head their school.
   Sen. Bob Dole, R-Kan., was the first to support the idea with a
letter on Feb. 18, before the selection of Elisabeth Ann Zinser was
made. Zinser, who was named the school's president on Sunday, is
not deaf and does not know sign language.
   In his letter, Dole noted the accomplishments of Gallaudet,
which is the nation's only school for the deaf, and asked, ``Isn't
it time for the university to once again lead the way, instead of
following it, and place a deaf individual in a position of public
responsibility?''
   Vice President George Bush's support came next, in a letter
March 1 to the committee searching for a new school president.
   ``As an entity funded by the federal government, Gallaudet has a
responsibility to set an example and thus to appoint a president
who is not only highly qualified, but who is also deaf,'' he wrote.
   The March 6 appointment of Zinser, an administrator at the
University of North Carolina at Greensboro, set off demonstrations
by students, alumni and faculty at Gallaudet that have virtually
paralyzed the campus.
   The protests drew support from two Democratic presidential
hopefuls.
   Democrat Jesse Jackson on Wednesday issued a statement
supporting the demonstrations and saying, ``The problem is not that
the students do not hear. The problem is that the hearing world
does not listen.''
   Illinois Sen. Paul Simon, also running for the Democratic
nomination, on Thursday called for Zinser's resignation.
   Simon, a longtime member of the Senate Labor and Human Resources
subcommittee on the handicapped, which has jurisdiction over
funding for Gallaudet, said Zinser's appointment was a ``slap in
the face to the entire purpose of the university.''
   Simon, who wears two hearing aids to compensate for a hearing
impairment, cited the job listing placed by the school's
presidential search committee, which said, in part:
   ``Broad and deep knowledge of deafness and the variety of issues
important to the higher education of hearing impaired persons is
necessary.''
   ``Even if Elisabeth Zinser were deaf,'' Simon said, ``the fact
that she doesn't meet this qualification demonstrates that she is
not the best candidate for the job.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880310-0222 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-88 1855EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dole-Campaign 1stAdd a0814 03-10 0280</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dole-Campaign, 1st Add, a0814</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON: paid for.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Tate said more than half the campaign's 300 staffers were being
laid off.
   She declined to say who among the national staff was being let
go, saying workers were still being notified Thursday evening.
   ``It is significant _ it ranges from the top to the bottom in
every department,'' she said of the layoffs.
   Some of the layoffs had been planned for the period following
Super Tuesday, regardless of its outcome, she said.
   But Dole's campaign was reeling from its complete, 17-state loss
on that day. Vice President Bush won in 16 of the states and took a
giant step toward the GOP nomination.
   ``You have a much different campaign staff when you're trying to
compete in 17 states at once'' rather than one at a time, she said.
   She said the key members of Dole's traveling staff would be
unaffected by the cutbacks, naming press secretary Mari Maseng,
adviser Thomas Rath, campaign chairman William Brock and consultant
Kim Wells.
   She said the campaign would keep ``a full complement'' of staff
in Illinois.
   The news of the cutbacks came as Dole continued to campaign in
Illinois _ a state he said on Wednesday that he had to win.
   On Thursday, he appeared to back off on that contention, saying
instead he had to ``do very well'' in the state. He dismissed
questions from reporters on whether he was scaling down his
expectations in the state.
   At one point, however, he addressed the possibility of dropping
out, saying: ``I've been in this business long enough to know that
there comes a time you have to say, well, maybe it would happen.''
</TEXT>
