<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-88 1915EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     03-10 0517</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0533</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Storm Dumps Heavy Snow on Utah, Colorado, Wyoming</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A storm dumped heavy snow in Utah, Colorado and Wyoming,
covering some mountain areas with up to 28 inches, shutting down
highways and abruptly ending spring-like weather in the region.
   The storm also generated high winds in the central and southern
Rockies and the central and southern Plains, creating blizzard
conditions in some areas.
   Winter storm advisories, watches and warnings were posted in the
Rockies and northern Plains through Friday. Up to 16 inches of snow
were expected in Colorado's mountains overnight.
   In Utah's mountains, 28 inches of snow blanketed Brian Head by
Thursday morning. Elsewhere in the state, Little Cottonwood Canyon
got 18 inches, and Big Cottonwood Canyon and Solitude 8 inches.
   Snow was heavy in parts of western Wyoming, with a foot of new
snow at Casper Mountain and Rock Springs, and wind gusts to 50 mph
created blizzard conditions.
   More than 200 miles of Interstate 80 were shut down in southern
Wyoming between Laramie and Rock Springs, and numerous roads in
Wyoming were closed.
   About 4,000 state employess left work early in Cheyenne and
Caspar, and many schools closed early.
   Snow also fell over parts of western and central Montana and
South Dakota.
   As the storm moved eastward, the temperature fell dramatically.
Rapid City, S.D., had a high in the low 70s on Wednesday, but
readings climbed only into the mid-30s early Thursday afternoon.
   Temperatures elsewhere in the northern high Plains were 20 to 30
degrees lower than readings on Wednesday.
   Gusty winds also buffeted western Kansas, the Nebraska Panhandle
and southern New Mexico, where Ruidoso had winds up to 63 mph.
   Rainshowers were scattered across the Carolinas into northern
Georgia as a storm system slowly moved into the Atlantic Ocean.
   Heavier rainfall during the six hours ending at 1 p.m. EST
included 1.20 inches at Fayetteville, N.C., 0.91 inch at Charlotte,
N.C., 0.86 inch at Florence, S.C., 0.82 inch at Key West, Fla., and
0.67 inch at Hickory, N.C.
   Temperatures at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 21 degrees at Yellowstone
Park, Wyo., to 89 degrees at Cotulla, Texas. The morning low was 3
degrees at Gunnison, Colo.
   Friday's forecast called for snow from the plains of Wyoming and
northern Colorado through the upper Mississippi Valley, showers and
a few thunderstorms scattered across the central Plains and lower
Missouri Valley, from much of Kansas and western Missouri into
central Iowa and southern Wisconsin, and mostly sunny or partly
cloudy skies elsewhere.
   High temperatures were expected to reach the 40s, 50s or 60s
across much of the nation, with readings in the 20s from Wyoming to
the northern Great Lakes and across northern New England, in the
30s from the northern Rockies through the central Intermountain
region, the central high Plains into central Wisconsin and northern
Michigan as well as central New England, in the 70s across the
southern California coast and from the upper Rio Grande Valley
through northern Texas, the lower Mississippi Valley and Gulf Coast
into much of Florida, and in the 80s across southern Texas.
</TEXT>
