<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-AfricaFamine     03-10 0430</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Africa Famine,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>African Governments Blamed for Famines</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   African governments more than nature now cause
the famines that threaten millions of lives, a Reagan
administration official told Congress Thursday.
   ``Although natural factors are still present and important in
each of these countries, man-made factors predominate and drive the
seemingly intractable emergency situations and ever-escalating
needs,'' said Charles L. Gladson, assistant administrator for
Africa of the Agency for International Development.
   He listed as the ``most obvious'' factors:
   _internal strife and civil wars.
   _policies that fail to give incentives to farmers to grow enough
food.
   _poorly developed infrastructure, such as roads and railroads.
   _governments incapable of coordinating relief.
   Gladson's testimony was prepared for a hearing by the House
Select Committee on Hunger and the Foreign Affairs subcommittee
that deals with Africa. The hearing dealt with the crisis in
Angola, Mozambique, Ethiopia and Sudan.
   ``Even in the best of times, Ethiopia cannot feed itself with
its current policies,'' said Roy Stacy, deputy assistant secretary
of state for Africa.
   ``The U.S. government alone spent over $600 million for
emergency aid to save lives, but without incentive farming policies
such assistance does not result in recovery and provides little
resistance to the next drought,'' he said.
   According to the hunger committee, a drought in Ethiopia has
again resulted in crop failures and a food deficit of 1.3 million
metric tons, with 5.2 million to 8 million people at risk. It said
the U.S. government has provided more than $100 million in aid in
the current crisis.
   The administration view was endorsed by Rep. Tony Roth, R-Wis.
   ``Ethiopia, Mozambique and Angola _ is there some reason that
Mother Nature has singled out these three countries by chance? I
don't think so,'' he said.
   ``All of these countries share one other common trait: their
disastrous agricultural yields can be directly attributed to the
failures of collectivized farming and to a patent disegard for
human life,'' he said.
   All three have communist governments.
   He complained that a proposed resolution on famine relief,
introduced by Rep. Tony P. Hall, D-Ohio, and Mickey Leland,
D-Texas, contained no condemnation of the Ethiopian government of
Mengistu Haile-Mariam for withholding food as a means of combatting
rebel forces.
   He also criticized the proposed resolution for suggesting that
the U.S. government prevent refugees from crossing borders or going
into relief camps.
   ``It seems to me altogether inappropriate for it to to be a
policy of the U.S. government to prevent people from voting with
their feet and escaping from a brutal dictatorship,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
