<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-88 2107EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SuffocatedBoy     03-10 0390</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Suffocated Boy,0401</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Teens Found Guilty in Boy's Death</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DAYTON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two 13-year-old girls were found guilty of
involuntary manslaughter Thursday in the slaying of a 12-year-old
boy who was forced to drink lighter fluid and suffocated with a
plastic bag over his head.
   Police said the girls Feb. 8 helped two teen-agers get into the
victim's apartment, where the boys attacked Antonio R. Cooley for
not letting them use a videotape recorder.
   The 15-year-old boys sprayed Cooley with insecticide and forced
him to drink charcoal lighter fluid while he screamed for his life,
authorities said. A deputy coroner said Cooley was suffocated with
a bag.
   As Judge Arthur O. Fisher of Juvenile Court read the verdict in
the non-jury trial, the two girls sat almost motionless, and one
mouthed a curse. The other clutched a stuffed bear and sobbed
lightly as she was led away.
   They were also found guilty of grand theft for helping steal
Cooley's stereo and videotape recorder.
   The girls, whose identities were not released because of their
age, were being held in a youth detention center.
   The judge could order them held for a year, and state officials
then could decide whether to hold them until age 21, siad assistant
prosecutor Debra Armanini. No sentencing date was set.
   The judge said the girls helped the two boys get into Cooley's
apartment while his father was at work, knowing the boys intended
to beat Cooley and steal several electronic items.
   Prosecutors are seeking to have the two 15-year-olds tried as
adults on charges including aggravated murder and aggravated
robbery.
   Defense attorneys argued the girls did not know Cooley was to
die. But the judge said even if the girls had warned Cooley, as
they testified, they still were guilty for not trying to prevent
the attack.
   A 13-year-old accomplice has pleaded guilty to involuntary
manslaughter and theft and awaits sentencing. The defense at the
girls' trial contended the 13-year-old kept the girls in a back
room while the older boys did the killing.
   ``I think the verdict sends a message across this city that the
courts are not going to permit anyone, no matter what their age, to
take part in a scheme or plan to snuff out another life,'' said
assistant prosecutor Mathias Heck Jr.
</TEXT>
