<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Radio-Drugs     03-10 0339</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Radio-Drugs,0349</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Radio Personality Subject of Drug Probe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Howard Stern, a radio personality known for his
outrageous, innuendo-laced broadcasts, is the target of a federal
investigation begun after he bragged on the air about getting drugs
for someone, according to a published report.
   The New York Daily News on Wednesday said it learned of the
investigation from a letter to the newspaper from Michael Levine, a
Drug Enforcement Administration agent.
   Levine said Stern, who has come under fire from the Federal
Communications Commission for his broadcasts, bragged on his
morning radio show Monday of getting drugs for an unidentified
guest on his cable TV special ``Howard Stern's Underpants and
Negligee Party,'' shown Feb. 27.
   ``Maybe somebody should have warned him (Stern) that he was
admitting to the commission of a federal and state felony,'' Levine
said.
   The Daily News, citing unidentified sources, said that DEA
agents had taken the unusual step of clearing the investigation
with the U.S. attorney's office. Because of Stern's habit of making
outrageous statements on radio, investigators wanted to know if the
office would press charges, the newspaper said.
   Robert Stutman, head of the New York DEA office, said Levine's
letter was written without his office's knowledge. He declined
comment on any investigation.
   Stern, whose morning radio program is heard on WXRK-FM in New
York and on WYSP-FM in Philadelphia, could not be reached for
comment. A message left at the New York station was not immediately
returned Thursday.
   Stern's radio broadcasts are filled with veiled and obvious
references to sex and other bodily functions. He testified at an
FCC hearing in April, and the commission warned him to avoid
certain sexual innuendoes and double entenderes.
   The FCC said Stern's broadcasts ``dwelt on sexual and excretory
matters in a pandering and titillating fashion that was patently
offensive as measured by contemporary community standards.''
   But because the FCC's own standards for decency may have been
unclear, the commission said it was forced to limit its sanction
against Stern to a warning.
</TEXT>
