<1ST_LINE>u a AM-ThrillKilling 1stLd-Writethru a0738 03-10 0799</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Thrill Killing, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0738,0817</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>15-Year-Old Sentenced to Life Imprisonment for Killing Classmate</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to ADD prison official saying Matthews
becomes youngest state prisoner, quote from mother. PICKS UP 8th
graf pvs, `Defense attorney ...'</NOTE>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DEDHAM, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 15-year-old boy who beat a classmate to
death with a baseball bat to find out what it was like to kill
someone was convicted of second-degree murder Thursday and
sentenced to life in prison.
   Rod Matthews, who was 14 when he lured Shaun Ouillette into the
woods with a promise of fireworks, showed no emotion when the
verdict was announced. He had been expressionless throughout the
weeklong trial, sitting with his eyes downcast.
   Matthews will be eligible for parole in 15 years.
   Carrying a portrait of her son and choking back tears, Jeanne
Quinn, the victim's mother, said she had hoped Matthews would not
be eligible for parole, which would have been the case if he had
been convicted of first-degree murder.
   ``He planned this. I'm sorry. Fifteen years. No, I'm sorry,
that's wrong,'' said Mrs. Quinn. ``Shaun is not coming home in 15
years, is he? He's not ever coming home.''
   The trial in this suburb 15 miles south of Boston was
highlighted by graphic descriptions of the slaying and testimony
from two young people who described how Matthews plotted the
killing and then took them to see the bludgeoned body in the woods
in Canton.
   Matthews' family, including two sisters and a brother, was
escorted out of court by officers shielding them from journalists.
Kenneth Matthews, the father, said he felt his son belonged in a
treatment facility rather than in prison.
   Matthews becomes the youngest of more than 6,500 inmates in the
state's prisons, possibly the youngest ever, said Correction
Department spokeswoman Mary McGeown.
   ``It's terrible,'' said Matthews' mother, Janice. ``A child
shouldn't be persecuted and forced to go through something like
this. They're children. God only knows how much worse it's going to
make his condition.''
   Defense attorney John Philip White had argued that Matthews
should be acquitted by reason of insanity. He portrayed him as a
mentally unstable child whose pleas for help were ignored by
teachers and friends, and as someone adversely affected by taking
the drug Ritalin to control hyeractivity.
   White said after the verdict that he was concerned about
Matthews' safety at the adult prison at Walpole and about ``the
suicidal ideation he has shown.''
   Norfolk County Superior Court Judge Roger J. Donahue said
defense attorneys could appeal the verdict within 30 days. Donahue
rejected a defense motion to reconsider the sentence and classify
Matthews as a juvenile.
   The jurors had deliberated for nearly 10 hours over two days
before making their decision.
   Norfolk County Assistant District Attorney Peter Casey called
the decision an ``appropriate, well-counseled verdict.''
   The widely publicized case was compared to the trial of Anthony
Broussard, 18, sentenced to 25 years to life in 1982 in San Jose,
Calif., for killing his girlfriend. Broussard took at least 13
schoolmates to see the victim's body and the movie ``The River's
Edge'' was based on that case.
   Two child behavior specialists testified that Matthews did not
experience classic symptoms of psychosis and that continued use of
Ritalin could not have triggered violent behavior.
   But a doctor said Monday that Matthews' irrational conduct may
have been exacerbated by the drug, which Matthews had been taking
since the third grade.
   Two friends of Matthews', Rob Peterson and Jonathan Cash,
testified earlier this week that Matthews told them of his desire
to kill in the fall of 1986. They said two potential victims were
mentioned and rejected before Matthews decided on Ouillette.
   No charges were filed against Peterson and Cash.
   Matthews chose Ouillette because he felt he would not be missed,
the teen-agers said. Ouillette, 14, was relatively new to Canton,
his family having moved there two years before the slaying.
   Witnesses said Matthews befriended Ouillette before he lured him
to the wooded area after school on Nov. 20, 1986. He hit Ouillette
on the head with a baseball bat at least three times. Matthews
recalled Ouillette cried for help, the friends testified.
   Matthews took Peterson to see the body several hours after the
slaying and they hid a knife Matthews planned to use to cut off
Ouillette's arms and legs.
   Several days later, Peterson and Cash went with Matthews to see
the body after a pre-Thanksgiving pep rally at Canton High School.
   Police found the body on Dec. 15, 1986, after receiving an
anonymous letter sent by Cash.
   Matthews told a psychiatric counselor after the slaying that he
first decided to kill someone after viewing the videotape ``Faces
of Death,'' which depicts animal and human deaths.
</TEXT>
