<2ND_LINE>AM-Deaf Protest,0349</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Deaf Students Show Their Solidarity With Gallaudet Protest</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Deaf President, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH PICHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HENRIETTA, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 200 students from the National
Technical Institute for the Deaf rallied Thursday in support of
demands by students at Washington's Gallaudet University for a
hearing-impaired president.
   ``We will keep the spirit. The spirit shall never die,'' said
Scot Atkins, a spokesman for the NTID students. ``It's time for a
deaf president at Gallaudet.''
   The protests came in response to the appointment of Elisabeth
Ann Zinser, who can hear, as president of Gallaudet. The nation's
only liberal arts college for the deaf has not had a
hearing-impaired president in its its 124-year history.
   Gallaudet students have said Zinser is not welcome on campus,
and they have called for the resignation of Jane Bassett Spilman,
chairwoman of the school's board of trustees.
   At NTID, students carried signs with slogans such as ``It Ain't
Over Till the Hearing Ladies Quit'' and ``Deaf People Have Been
Ready To Function Forever,'' and chanted, signed and waved their
arms over their heads.
   ``Deaf people can be president. We can do anything we want. And
the idea that we can't is just nonsense,'' said student Linda
Whitmore, through an interpreter. ``I plan to work with hearing
people when I graduate.''
   NTID, with an enrollment of 1,250, is a part of Rochester
Institute of Technology and offers two-year programs in such fields
as business, computers, engineering and architecture.
   Some of the students go on to Gallaudet or to RIT, said NTID
spokesman Vince Dollard.
   Two busloads of students and numerous cars with a total of about
150 people were scheduled to leave the campus at midnight for a
rally Friday in Washington.
   Atkins said Thursday's rally and the support for Gallaudet's
students has nothing to do with NTID, whose director and president
both can hear.
   ``They've been very good to us and we've been very good to them
and we have no problem with the way things are here,'' he said.
</TEXT>
