<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Seagram-Beatrice     03-10 0357</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Seagram-Beatrice,0369</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Screwdriver Connection: Seagram Buying Tropicana</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seagram Co. said Thursday it is buying the makers
of Tropicana orange juice in a $1.2 billion transaction dubbed the
``screwdriver deal.''
   ``We have already broadened our base with Seagram's (wine)
coolers, and Tropicana is another step in this direction,''
Chairman Edgar M. Bronfman said in announcing the purchase of
Tropicana Products from Beatrice U.S. Food Corp.
   The deal will be financed initially with a combination of bank
loans and short-term borrowings, said the Canadian liquor and
beverage giant.
   Market watchers jokingly called the sale the ``screwdriver
deal'' in a reference to the popular cocktail made of vodka and
orange juice.
   Montreal-based Seagram is best known for its distilled spirits
and wines but in recent years has moved into the manufacturing of
wine coolers and sells cocktail mixers such as tonic, seltzer and
ginger ale under the Seagram's name.
   Seagram is also acquiring French cognac producer Martell & Co.
   Securities analysts said the move into the orange juice business
was a logical step for Seagram.
   ``They understand the business, and it's growing, unlike most of
their liquor products,'' said Ian Osler, an analyst with
Prudential-Bache Securities in Toronto.
   However, the New York credit-rating firm Standard & Poor's Corp.
said the pending sale had negative debt implications for both
Seagram and Beatrice.
   S&P said the deal would reduce Seagram's dependence on distilled
spirits but increase the company's debt load, raising questions
about Seagram's ability to absorb both Tropicana and Martell.
   Tropicana, with headquarters in Bradenton, Fla., had sales of
about $750 million in its last fiscal year, which ended Feb. 29,
said Marcelline Thomson, a Seagram spokeswoman.
   Seagram earned nearly $423.5 billion on sales of $3.3 billion in
the fiscal year ending Jan. 31, 1987, and reported a profit of more
than $402.4 million on sales of $2.6 billion for the nine months
ending Oct. 31, Ms. Thomson said.
   Beatrice U.S. Food Corp., based in Chicago, is a division of
Beatrice Co., whose holdings include Hunt's tomato products, Wesson
oil, Swift-Ekrich Inc. meats, Peter Pan peanut butter and Orville
Redenbacher popcorn.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
