<2ND_LINE>AM-Mecham, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0735,0749</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ex-Staffer Says He Would Have Handled Threat Differently</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS two grafs after 13th graf pvs, `Mecham has ...' with
secretary's testimony.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto covering</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Evan Mecham's last chief of staff
testified Thursday that he would not have responded as the governor
did to reports that another official threatened a former Mecham
aide who was a grand jury witness.
   But Richard Burke, a former U.S. attorney and Justice Deparment
official who was the first defense witness at Mecham's impeachment
trial, refused to say whether he thought the governor obstructed
the investigation of the alleged threat.
   ``I don't think I should comment on that,'' Burke said, as
members of the Arizona Senate pressed him for a legal opinion. ``I
think the governor would have a very different view of that than I
would.''
   Mecham, 63, is accused of obstructing justice by telling the
state's top police official not to give the attorney general
information about the alleged threat.
   He also is accused of concealing a $350,000 campaign loan and
misusing $80,000 from a state fund, but the Senate is hearing
testimony on the obstruction charge first.
   Mecham, who has not appeared at the impeachment trial since it
began Feb. 29, also faces a criminal trial April 21 on felony
charges of concealing the $350,000 and a recall election May 17.
   The first-term Republican is the first U.S. governor to be
impeached in six decades.
   Burke, who tried to reorganize the chaotic Mecham offices in the
two months before the governor's impeachment, said he believed that
the reported threat was serious and that Mecham should have fired
the accused aide, Lee Watkins, much earlier than he did.
   ``I certainly took it as a serious threat,'' said Burke. ``It
wasn't a threat of tiddlywinks. I think all of us assumed it was a
crime or a potential crime or it wouldn't have been reported to
us.''
   According to testimony in the impeachment trial, Mecham first
was told Nov. 13 that Watkins threatened former Mecham adviser
Donna Carlson, saying she might go ``on a long boat ride'' if she
talked to a grand jury investigating finances of Mecham's 1986
campaign.
   Watkins has denied threatening Ms. Carlson. Last week he refused
to testify when called as a prosecution witness.
   Ralph Milstead, director of the Department of Public Safety,
said he was told Nov. 15 by Mecham to refuse any request for
information by the attorney general. He has said he did cooperate,
however.
   Mecham has testified in House impeachment hearings that he may
have told Milstead not to cooperate with the attorney general.
   In other developments, a secretary to Peggy Griffith, the
official who first reported the alleged death threat, said that her
boss often exaggerated things and that she questioned Mrs.
Griffith's version of what occurred.
   But when senators asked her for examples of exaggerations, the
secretary, Terri Elaine Fields, paused and said, ``I can't even
think of any right now.''
   Under questioning by Mecham attorney Fred Craft, Burke said the
governor was ill-served by his subordinates because they did not
give him complete information on the alleged threat quickly enough.
   But on cross-examination, House prosecutor William French honed
in on Mecham's exact instructions to Milstead: ``Would you say
this: `Don't tell the attorney general anything?'''
   ``No,'' said Burke.
   ``Would you say this to Col. Milstead: `Never. Don't give him
any help?''
   ``No,'' said Burke.
   Burke, in apparent agreement with a number of prosecution
witnesses, said political loyalty impelled the governor to ignore
staff warnings and support Watkins.
   ``Why was Mr. Watkins not let go at an earlier date?'' asked
Democratic Sen. Lela Alston.
   Burke replied that Mecham ignored nearly unanimous advice from
his staff to fire Watkins.
   ``I think the governor felt a great deal of loyalty to Mr.
Watkins,'' said the witness, ``because Mr. Watkins hd been very
active and supportive of his campaign.''
   Prosecution witnesses have suggested Watkins won favor by
raising money for Mecham's campaign. They said Watkins told of
being rewarded with a state job and intimated he had information
which could bring down the Mecham administration.
   A two-thirds vote in the Senate is required to convict Mecham on
impeachment charges and remove him from office. Senators then could
take another vote and forbid him from holding state office again.
</TEXT>
