<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Meese,0349</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rappaport Attends Ceremony with Peres</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HAIFA, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Swiss tycoon involved in a plan to build
an Iraqi oil pipeline attended an event Thursday with Shimon Peres,
whom he allegedly tried to bribe into guaranteeing the line's
safety.
   Bruce Rappaport joined the foreign minister at a Haifa
University symposium on heart disease, which Rappaport financed. He
denied offering Peres a bribe and said he would ``tell all at the
appropriate time and place'' about the $1 billion pipeline project.
   Peres angrily brushed aside questions about the pipeline case,
which also has been linked to Edwin Meese III, the U.S. attorney
general.
   ``My name is not connected with anything and I don't want you to
connect it,'' Peres said, interrupting a reporter. ``Did anyone say
they gave me anything? Did anyone say they promised me anything?
Please, a little fairness.''
   Rappaport told reporters Israel lost $60-$70 million because the
project was not built _ the sum it was to receive for promising not
to bomb the line.
   He said Peres, then prime minister, gave the guarantee after
consulting Yitzhak Shamir, who then was foreign minister, and two
other Cabinet ministers.
   ``There was never a question of giving this sum to ministers or
a political party and the only one who would have benefited from
the deal would have been the Israeli treasury,'' the Israeli news
agency Itim quoted Rappaport as saying.
   In Washington, independent counsel James McKay is investigating
whether Meese violated a law that prohibits payment of bribes to
foreign officials by U.S. companies and authorizes the attorney
general to intervene to block them.
   The investigation stems from a 1985 memo to Meese from his
longime friend E. Robert Wallach, who had been hired as legal
counsel by Rappaport to help secure U.S. support for the pipeline
project.
   Wallach's memo says payments were planned to the Israeli Labor
Party, which Peres leads, in connection with the pipeline. Meese
has said he does not recall reading the portion that mentioned
payments to the party.
</TEXT>
