<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-88 2234EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-TerrorismPact     03-10 0415</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Terrorism Pact,0427</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Twenty-Three Nations Sign Treaty to Combat Terrorism at Sea</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERENA DOBNIK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A treaty requiring nations to prosecute or extradite
terrorists who commit acts of violence on the high seas was signed
by 23 countries Thursday, including the United States.
   Agreement comes more than two years after Palestinian terrorists
hijacked the Italian cruise ship Achille Lauro and killed an
American passenger.
   Representatives from 53 other nations, including the Soviet
Union, Israel, Egypt and Libya expressed approval of the document,
the first maritime convention against terrorism.
   ``I have a very vivid memory of the Achille Lauro and I can only
feel the deepest emotion today,'' said U.S. Ambassador Maxwell
Rabb, who signed for the United States. ``This document corrects a
tremendous void in the law of terrorism.''
   The treaty still must be formally ratified by the governments
that signed.
   A U.S. government official, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
said he expected most of the 53 other countries would sign within a
year. He said many representatives wanted their governments to
review the treaty before signing.
   The Palestine Liberation Organization sent observers to the
treaty conference.
   The treaty requires ratifying countries to make it a crime to
commit violent acts against ships or the people aboard them. It
also covers oil rigs or platforms anchored to the bottom of the sea
and the people aboard them.
   The countries agree to either prosecute or extradite terrorists
who commit violent acts at sea. A country whose citizens are
victims of an attack can seek extradition of the terrorists.
   The treaty was the final document of a 10-day conference of
diplomats and international law specialists convened by the
London-based International Maritime Organization, an agency of the
United Nations.
   Italy, Egypt and Austria requested the convening of such a
conference in 1986, following the Achille Lauro hijacking. The ship
was seized off Egypt and many passengers were Austrian.
   The U.S. government official said the treaty ``clarifies which
countries have the criminal jurisdiction to prosecute people who
commit acts of violence on vessels outside their territorial
waters.''
   He said it fills ``a gap in international anti-terrorist law.''
   In October 1985, four Palestinian terrorists hijacked the
Achille Lauro, killing Leon Klinghoffer, a 69-year-old passenger
from New York confined to a wheelchair. At the time, the United
States accused Italy of releasing Mohammed Abbas, the accused
mastermind of the hijacking who was later convicted in absentia by
an Italian court of the murder.
</TEXT>
