<HEAD>Reagan Talks of German Reunification</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Reagan-Interviews</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan said Thursday the
reunification of Germany could result from efforts to resolve
East-West differences over Berlin's divided status.
   Reagan spoke in an interview with the Washington correspondent
of ZDF television, which broadcast excerpts on its evening newscast.
   The U.S. president repeated a suggestion that the Olympic Games
be held in both halves of divided Berlin. He also said he hoped
Berlin could become an international meeting place and an air
traffic transportation center.
   Reagan was asked about the possibility of a future reunification
of the two Germanys as a consequence of improved East-West dialogue.
   ``Maybe out of these things (talks about Berlin's status)
reunification could grow,'' Reagan replied.
   The president said holding the Olympic Games in Berlin would be
an ``important contribution toward peaceful development between
East and West.''
   Reagan first suggested the Games be held in Berlin during a
visit to the city last year.
   Reagan said the Berlin Wall would continue to be an important
issue in talks with Soviet officials.
   The German state was divided into communist East Germany and
pro-Western West Germany following the defeat of Adolf Hitler's
Third Reich in World War II.
