<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Smoker'sSuit     03-10 0226</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Smoker's Suit,0232</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Smoker's Suit Probe Shows No Criminal Intent, DA Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LEXINGTON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tobacco-company representative who
telephoned jurors during a $17 million liability suit against the
makers of Pall Mall cigarettes did not break the law, a district
attorney said Thursday.
   ``We're not sure of the specifics of the calls but in essence it
was simply a case of trying to be friendly or trying to help _ even
being a bit nosy,'' Frank Carlton said in detailing the findings of
a state investigation.
   The investigation followed January's trial of a suit brought
against American Brands Inc. by the family of Nathan Henry Horton,
who died of lung cancer after smoking two packs a day of unfiltered
Pall Malls for more than 30 years.
   A mistrial was declared in the case when jurors couldn't agree
on a verdict.
   Allegations of attempted jury tampering later surfaced, and
Norman Clark, a jury consultant for the defense, said he had called
jurors at one point to inform them that the judge was sick and that
the day's session had been called off.
   ``What occurred was improper but being improper is not a
crime,'' Carlton said.
   ``The truth is there is not supposed to be contact with jurors
during trial for any reason. Even innocent contact can be
misconstrued, as it was in this case.''
</TEXT>
