<2ND_LINE>AM-Cave-In,0288</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gully Cave-In Kills Two Teens</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto AQ3</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dirt collapsed in a gully where three
boys were digging a hole, burying the youngsters and killing two
despite neighbors' efforts to save them, police said. The third boy
dug himself out.
   Joel Rogers and Damon Deakin, both 13, died Wednesday evening,
said police spokesman Tony Herrera.
   Residents of the trailer park where the three lived saw the
teen-agers digging in the gully then saw a cloud of dust, Herrera
said.
   Neighbors who heard screams pulled Joel out and were trying to
revive him when officers arrived, Herrera said. Paramedics pulled
Damon out about 15 minutes later, he said.
   Damon was pronounced dead at the scene and Joel was pronounced
dead at University of New Mexico Hospital.
   One of the boys, 14, whose name was withheld, dug out and went
for help, Herrera said.
   Dave Wild, a resident of the trailer park, said he had warned
the boys of the danger of digging in the dry gully, or arroyo, but
they continued to play, and moments later he saw a cloud of dust.
   ``I didn't think anything of it,'' he said. ``Then I remembered
the kids digging. I ran out and one of them was yelling that the
other two were trapped inside. I jumped into the arroyo and started
digging.
   ``I kept digging until I got to a foot, then I reached his
head,'' he said. ``I pulled him out and he wasn't breathing.''
   Trailer park manager Kaylin Morris said she heard the boys
talking earlier Wednesday about digging a tunnel. ``The three were
inseparable,'' she said. ``It was just like the Three Musketeers.''
</TEXT>
