<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf Rdp, 1stLd-Writethru, a0732,0734</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraq, Iran Hint at Cease-Fire, But Resume Attacks</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERT 3 grafs after 12th graf pvs, The statement ...
UPDATING with Iran's U.N. activity. Picks up 13th graf pvs, Iran's
Islamic ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SAMIR F. GHATTAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq and Iran said Thursday they would
stop rocketing each other's cities, but within hours both had
launched new missile attacks.
   Iraq fired three long-range missiles at Tehran on Thursday and
two into Qom. The Iraqi News Agency said the attacks brought to 51
the number of missiles fired at Tehran since Feb. 29.
   Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency said Iranian
Revolutionary Guards fired two missiles into Baghdad. Iran has
reported firing 27 missiles into the Iraqi capital since Feb 29.
   There was confusion over the timing of a possible cease-fire.
   An Iraqi statement broadcast over Baghdad Radio and monitored in
Nicosia said the bombardment of Tehran and other Iranian cities
would halt by 4 p.m. Friday if the Iranians stopped firing at
Iraq's cities.
   Iranian Prime Minister Hussein Musavi said that Iran would halt
attacks on Iraqi cities if Iraq stopped attacking Iranian cities,
Tehran radio reported.
   Musavi said he was responding to a call by Turkish Prime
Minister Turgut Ozal, who asked Iran and Iraq to stop the ``war of
the cities'' by Thursday at 5 p.m.
   Ozal sent messages to Iran and Iraq on Wednesday asking them to
end the bombardments on population centers.
   Twenty diplomats and their families drove to Turkey on Wednesday
night after evacuating Tehran, the independent Turkish Hurriyet
news agency reported. It said the group included diplomats from
Norway, Finland, the Netherlands, Denmark, West Germany and Syria.
   Iraq claimed that Tehran triggered the latest round of the ``war
of the cities'' by hitting Baghdad with two missiles Feb. 29.
   ``So the last bombardment should be Iraq's before the cessation
goes into effect,'' the statement said. ``If the enemy Iranian
regime attacks any of our cities ... in retaliation for the last
Iraqi bombardment, we will continue attacking.''
   The statement came after a meeting of top Iraqi officials
chaired by President Saddam Hussein.
   Iranian envoy Mohammad Ja'afar Mahallati told a news conference
at the United Nations that Iran would honor any unconditional truce
called for by Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar. He said
Iran would not fire back if Iraq got in the last shot before any
deadline set by Perez de Cuellar.
   ``We can respond to anyone _ but unconditionally,
unconditionally,'' he said.
   The U.N. chief did not respond to Mahallati's call. Sources
close to Perez de Cuellar said Iran also insisted he condemn Iraq
for starting the missile duel, something he was unwilling to do.
   Iran's Islamic Republic News Agency said scores of civilians
were killed or wounded in the latest Iraqi missile attacks.
   ``In the event of a complete halt to the air and missile attacks
by the Iraqi regime, we too will stop these attacks,'' Musavi told
the state-run radio.
   ``But if the rulers of Iraq refrain from accepting this request
by Turkey, we will strengthen the intensity of our retaliatory
measures,'' he said in the broadcast, monitored by the British
Broadcasting Corp.
   Musavi said his nation was eager to defeat Iraq on the ground
and to end attacks on civilians.
   ``We believe that the war must take place chivalrously on the
battlefields and that extending the hostilities to residential
areas to victimize women and children signifies only the impotence
of the party that started such a crime,'' he said.
   The all-Swiss International Committee of the Red Cross called
the missile exchange a ``very grave violation'' of international
humanitarian law. A statement issued in Geneva said the ICRC made a
``solemn appeal'' to end what it called ``this tragic escalation''
of the war.
   The official Iraq News Agency said ``a number of civilians''
were killed Thursday in Iranian shelling.
   Iran said its warplanes attacked Basra and Al-Amarah farther
north.
   Cities in western or central Iran reported hit by Iraqi
warplanes on Thursday included Isfahan, Hamadan, Arak, Dezful,
Shustar, Shahr-E Kord and Burujerd. A mosque and a school were hit
in Isfahan, and two schools and a hospital were destroyed in
Shahr-Kord, Tehran radio said. Iraq reported its planes also raided
Khorramabad, Guilan-E-Gharb, and Sar-E-Pol-Zahab.
</TEXT>
