<DOCNO> AP880310-0241 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-88 2137EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-DualTrial     03-10 0558</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dual Trial,0577</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>One Jury Convicts, Another Deliberates in Grisly Killing, Arson
Spree</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury Thursday convicted a man of murder
and arson in a grisly crime spree that left five people dead, a
verdict returned one day after a second jury in the rare ``dual
trial'' convicted a co-defendant.
   One jury was selected for each defendant at the trial to save
time and to prevent the possibility of publicity from one trial
tainting potential jurors for a second.
   Carl ``Butch'' Campbell, 28, and Robert Ahalt, 42, were accused
of beating three people to death in a bar in 1986 during a robbery,
then killing Campbell and Ahalt's girlfriends the next day in the
women's homes.
   One of the women, who was six months' pregnant, was sexually
mutilated and forced to eat glass before she and her fetus died.
The bar and the women's homes were set afire.
   It was only the second time in New York legal history that two
juries have been called on to listen to one case and give two
verdicts.
   During the trial, the defendants sat at the same table, but the
two juries sat on opposite sides of the courtroom, one in a
specially built jury box.
   The juries and evidence were color coded. The jury considering
Ahalt's case wore blue lapel tags, and Campbell's jury wore yellow
tags.
   Most testimony involved both cases, but when a witness was
providing information that involved only one defendant, the other
jury was taken from the room. The defendants testified in front of
their own jury only.
   Campbell, convicted Thursday, faces a sentence of 115 years to
life in prison. Ahalt could receive up to 125 years to life.
Sentencing was set for April 7.
   Each defendant was charged with three counts of arson, five of
intentional murder, five of murder during the commission of a
felony, in this case, robbery, and one of murder during a sexual
assault.
   Campbell was acquitted of a charge of murder during a robbery at
the home of one of the women and both murder counts in the slaying
of the woman at the other home. Ahalt was acquitted of murder
during a sexual assault.
   Attorneys for both men had objected to the dual juries and said
they would appeal the verdicts.
   State Supreme Court Justice Donald Mark had originally said that
the verdicts would have to be delivered at the same time.
   But four hours after the Ahalt jury reached its decision
Wednesday night, Campbell's attorney waived his client's right to
have the verdicts announced simultaneously.
   Killed at Dick's 43 Lounge were the bar's 75-year-old co-owner
Martha Gruttadauria; her sister-in-law Concetta Amatore, also 75,
and Colin Tuttle, 56, a patron.
   The next day, Dorreen Grachus, 28, and Evelyn Allen, 38, were
found slain in their homes a half-mile apart. Grachus, Campbell's
girlfriend, was pregnant. Allen, Ahalt's girlfriend, was beaten to
death, police said.
   Firefighters found all five bodies during fires.
   The first dual trial was held in 1984 in Nassau County and
involved two young men who were drag racing and were charged with
criminally negligent homicide when their cars slammed into another
car, killing the driver.
   That case has been appealed to the state's highest court,
largely because of the dual trial format, said Bruce Whitney, a
Nassau County assistant district attorney.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880310-0242 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-88 2337EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Railey 1stLd-Writethru a0705 03-10 0774</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Railey, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0705,0790</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prosecutors Release Phone Messages from Railey</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with three grafs to ADD wife's and children's ages;
PICKS UP 4th graf pvs, `Railey has ...'; SUBS 18th graf pvs, `Mrs.
Railey's ...' to CORRECT first name to Billie Jo sted Peggi; ADDS
one graf with details on Railey turning temporary custody over to
minister.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto DN2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF AWALT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former minister left two telephone messages for
his wife the night she was choked nearly to death, describing his
whereabouts in keen detail and giving times, and warning her to
lock the garage door, according to tapes released Thursday.
   Walker Railey told police he found 39-year-old Margaret
``Peggy'' Railey unconscious on the floor of the garage at their
Lake Highlands home shortly after midnight last April 22, choked
with a cord. She remains in a coma.
   Railey, 40, senior pastor of the prominent United Methodist
Church of Dallas at the time of the attack, claimed his family was
the victim of a racially motivated attack. After a suicide attempt
and reported refusal to testify before a grand jury, he resigned
and moved to San Francisco, leaving his children, ages 2 and 5, and
wife in Texas.
   Railey has denied attacking his wife and vows he is innocent. He
has not been charged but his lawyer said he was a prime suspect,
and police hope to have Railey answer more questions.
   Prosecutors released the answering-machine messages for the
first time Thursday.
   ``If you want to, go ahead and lock the garage door and I'll
park out front,'' Railey said on the tape. ``It really doesn't
matter to me at this point. My concern is that you're safe.''
   One of the biggest discrepancies with the tapes is the time
element. In the first message, Railey told his wife he didn't have
his watch on but thought it was about 10:30 p.m.
   Telephone company records, however, indicate he placed the call
at 12:04 a.m., Dallas County Assistant District Attorney Norman
Kinne said Thursday.
   In the first message, which lasted more than 1{ minutes, Railey
told his wife twice to lock the door and described his step-by-step
trail conducting research at two Southern Methodist University
libraries.
   He explained that he had to leave one library when it closed and
was on his way to another, and later called to explain that he was
on his way home.
   ``I'm not calling on the private line because I know you're
already asleep,' he said in the message saying he was on his way
home, ``but in case you get up with the kids, I just wanted you to
know that I'm on my way home. It's 12:30. I'll be home by about
12:45. Love you, dear. Bye Bye.''
   After waffling on the time in his first message, Railey noted
without hesitation in the second that the time was 12:29 a.m., a
figure Kinne said was confirmed to the minute by telephone company
records.
   He told police he arrived home at 12:40 a.m. and found his wife
unconscious.
   Kinne initially refused to release the tapes, prompting ABC News
to file suit. The network's suit failed but Kinne he decided to
release the material after an appeals court ruled it was up to
local officials to decide the issue.
   The attack occurred after Railey appeared at an Easter service
in a bullet-proof vest, claiming racially motivated death threats
had been made against him and his family because of his pro-civil
rights stands.
   He produced typed letters that threatened his life, but police
traced them to a typewriter in his church. The day police were
scheduled to question him further, he attempted to commit suicide
and left a note saying demons were torturing him.
   Railey became less cooperative, eventually appearing before a
grand jury last July when he reportedly cited his 5th Amendment
rights against self-incrimination 43 times.
   Mrs. Railey's mother and legal guardian, Billie Jo Nicolai,
filed a civil suit accusing Railey of the crime. He has not yet
responded to that lawsuit and must do so by Monday.
   Railey moved to San Francisco late last year and signed a year's
lease for an apartment with Dallas psychologist Lucy Papillon.
   That apartment's telephone number is unlisted, and The
Associated Press could not reach him for comment Thursday.
   Ms. Papillon has reportedly told grand jurors that she and
Railey were having an affair and that he was with her at her home
during part of the evening when Mrs. Railey was attacked.
   Railey gave temporary legal custody of his children to a
minister at the church where Railey served.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
