<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AbortionRuling     03-10 0284</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Abortion Ruling,0291</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Administration Appeals Ruling Striking Down Abortion Rules</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration Thursday appealed a
federal judge's order declaring unconstitutional regulations that
would have cut off federal funding to family planning clinics that
offer abortion counseling.
   The administration filed notice it was asking the 1st U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals to overturn the March 3 ruling. No date
was set for arguments.
   The ruling by U.S. District Judge Walter Jay Skinner was
announced the day the regulations were to take effect. In response,
the administration ordered Health and Human Services offices
nationwide not to enforce the regulations.
   The rules would have prevented federally funded family planning
programs from providing abortion counseling, abortion referrals,
and engaging in lobbying or legal action to increase availability
of abortions.
   If the clinic also performed abortions, it would have to
maintain separate facilities for those patients if it wanted to
continue to receive federal funding under a provision of the Public
Health Service Act of 1970.
   Skinner said the regulations violated a woman's rights to
privacy and to choose an abortion. ``Abortion referral and abortion
counseling are constitutionally protected speech under the First
Amendment,'' he said.
   About 5 million low- and moderate-income women receive services
at the 4,000 clinics nationwide that would have been affected by
the regulations announced in February by HHS Secretary Otis R.
Bowen.
   Federal judges in Colorado and New York had issued temporary
injunctions against the regulations but Skinner was the first to
rule on their constitutionality.
   He ruled on an injunction requested by the Massachusetts, the
National Family Planning and Reproductive Health Association and 13
other local and national family planning groups.
</TEXT>
