<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-88 2359EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Children-Health     03-10 0539</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Children-Health,0554</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Experts Optimistic On Increasing Child Survival</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SYDNEY RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLOIRES, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Diseases that now kill or cripple
millions of children probably will be wiped out by the end of the
century, a leading American health expert said Thursday.
   ``The news on child survival is very good,'' said Dr. William
Foege, head of the Task Force for Child Survival and former
director of the Centers for Disease Control in Atlanta.
   ``By the end of the century we hope that measles will be reduced
by 90 percent and that measle deaths, which are now over 2 million
a year, will be reduced by 95 percent.''
   Measles was just one aspect of the optimistic vision Foege
presented to some of the world's leading experts on children,
health and Third World development.
   Attending the meeting are Barber Conable, president of the World
Bank; James P. Grant, director of UNICEF, the U.N. Children's Fund;
Halfdan Mahler, head of the World Health Organization; leaders of
more than a dozen other international aid agencies, doctors and
health ministers from 11 developing countries.
   They will review a project that already is saving millions of
lives and plan other efforts for the remainder of the century.
   The three-day symposium, at a 16th-century former monastery on
the shores of Lake Annecy, is sponsored by the Task Force for Child
Survival, whose members are UNICEF, the World Health Organization,
the World Bank, the U.N. Development Program and the Rockefeller
Foundation.
   Since the early 1980s, the organizations have been working
together on an international campaign to immunize children against
polio, diphtheria, whooping cough, tuberculosis and tetanus. The
project, aimed particularly at developing countries, has been a
great success.
   Chinese officials said they believe 85 percent of China's 110
million children under age 7 will be vaccinated by the end of this
year.
   The number of the world's children vaccinated against the five
diseases has risen from 5 percent in 1974 to 50 percent today.
Experts attending the conference say predict virtually every child
in the world will be immunized by the early 1990s.
   ``In a little over a decade, a public health revolution has
quietly taken place,'' said Dr. Ralph H. Henderson, director of the
expanded WHO immunization program.
   He said the vaccination campaign against measles, neonatal
tetanus, tuberculosis and whooping cough is saving the lives of
more than 1 million children a year in poor countries. Another
200,000 children are being saved from the paralysis of polio,
Henderson said.
   Dr. Ken Warren of the Rockefeller Foundation called the project
``the single most remarkable example of international interagency
cooperation I've ever seen.''
   The Task Force took as its model a campaign against smallpox
begun in 1966. In October 1978, the world was declared free of the
disease.
   Henderson said eradication of polio in the Americas by 1990 is
achievable and Foege said experience gained in the next two years
in the Americas will allow the Task Force ``to set a reasonable
date for eliminating polio from the world.''
   Polio already has been overcome in the United States, although
cases sometimes are reported among immigrant groups.
   ``A world without polio would be a fitting gift from the 20th to
the 21st century,'' Henderson said.
</TEXT>
