<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dole-Campaign 4thLd-Writethru a0853 03-10 0706</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dole-Campaign, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0853,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dole Pulling Illinois Ads, Laying Off Staff</HEAD>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: New thruout with Dole statement</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Bob Dole said Thursday he would not drop
out of the Republican presidential race, but confirmed that he had
canceled all television advertising in advance of next Tuesday's
critical Illinois primary. He also ordered deep layoffs in his
campaign staff.
   Even as Dole issued a statement saying he was ``no dropout,''
campaign aides said Dole had discussed abandoning his presidential
bid. The Kansas senator's campaign was gravely weakened by Vice
President George Bush's sweep of 16 primaries on Super Tuesday.
   One aide, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Dole's
private polls showed Bush with a lead of between 15 and 20
percentage points in Illinois, reflecting a significant jump for
the vice president in the 48 hours since Bush's stunning showing in
this week's primries.
   An ABC News poll released Thursday night suggested Bush led Dole
in Illinois by a wide margin _ 58 percent to 31 percent.
   In his statement, Dole did not say explicitly whether he would
stay in the race if he lost Illinois next Tuesday. One aide said:
``I think it's clear to Dole that it's do or die.''
   Several campaign sources said Dole met with campaign manager
Bill Brock and other aides over the last few days in Illinois and
discussed the possibility of quitting the race in the wake of
Bush's commanding lead in the race for national convention
delegates.
   But Dole decided to stay in.
   In his statement, issued in Washington and Illinois, Dole
``categorically denied rumors'' that he would quit.
   ``Bob Dole's no dropout. I'm in this one to win,'' he said.
   In his statement, Dole confirmed the sweeping staff cutbacks,
but said they were sparked by the fact that the campaign no longer
needed to run in so many states at once.
   Dole said no cuts were involved in states with primaries after
next Tuesday.
   Dole's statement also confirmed he had ordered his television
ads shut down in Illinois. But one source said the campaign may air
a 30-minute paid broadcast in the closing hours of the Illinois
campaign.
   In the meantime, Dole took another shot at Bush.
   He said if the vice president still refuses to meet him in a
series of one-on-one debates, they should agree to back-to-back,
live one-hour press conferences staged before the Illinois primary.
   ``The people of Illinois and America have a right to see where
George Bush and Bob Dole stand on the issues,'' he said in his
statement.
   Bush, campaigning in Illinois, was asked about the reports of
Dole considering withdrawal.
   ``I just heard that. I don't know anything about it,'' he told
reporters in Champaign, Ill.
   Bush's chief of staff Craig Fuller said the vice president was
aware of the reports that Dole was talking with aides abut whether
to continue his campaign. He said Bush's reaction was: ``We'll go
about our business, do our job.''
   Earlier, campaign spokeswoman Dale Tate said more than half the
Dole campaign's 300 staffers were being laid off. Many were still
getting the word Thursday evening.
   Dole continued campaigning Thursday in Illinois. At one point he
obliquely addressed the possibility of dropping out, saying: ``I've
been in this business long enough to know that there comes a time
you have to say, well, maybe it would happen.''
   Tate declined to say who among the national staff was being let
go.
   ``It is significant _ it ranges from the top to the bottom in
every department,'' she said of the cutback.
   Some of the layoffs had been planned for the period following
Super Tuesday, regardless of its outcome, she said. She said the
key members of Dole's traveling staff would be unaffected by the
cutbacks, naming press secretary Mari Maseng, adviser Thomas Rath,
campaign chairman William Brock and consultant Kim Wells.
   Tate said the campaign would keep ``a full complement'' of staff
in Illinois.
   The developments came the same day that Rep. Jack Kemp abandoned
his presidential bid. Kemp, after a round of fourth-place finishes
on Tuesday, called it quits at a Washington news conference. He did
not endorse any of his rivals.
</TEXT>
