<1ST_LINE>a a AM-ReligionRdp Adv11   03-10 0581</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Religion Rdp, Adv 11,0604</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv11</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri AMs, March 11, and thereafter</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Representatives of major U.S. Protestant,
Eastern Orthodox and Roman Catholic bodies have declared their
solidarity with 18 organizations effectively silenced by South
Africa's government for opposing apartheid.
   Officials of the National Council of Churches, including
Protestant and Eastern Orthodox denominations, pledged continued
backing of the anti-apartheid efforts, and urged U.S. sanctions
against South Africa to spur ``peaceful change.''
   Archbishop John L. May of St. Louis, president of the National
Conference of Catholic Bishops, called the new repressive measures
an ``intolerable affront to the dignity'' of South Africans, and
voiced support of those working for ``a more just and democratic
society.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, CONN. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gideons International, which has supplied
Bibles to hotels, hospitals, prisons and schools since 1889, was
cited for ``outstanding achievements in Scripture distribution'' by
the Layman's National Bible Association.
   The interfaith association, which promotes Bible reading, said
the Gideons have distributed over 400 million Bibles in 137
countries. The 93,000-member organization currently places a
million Bibles every 15 days.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHAMBERSBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Presbyterians have ``got to figure out
how to respect each other and learn from each other in our
differences,'' says the moderator of the Presbyterian Church (USA).
   Isabel Rogers, who holds the top titular office in the
3-million-member denomination, a merger of Southern and Norther
branches, told a regional meeting:
   ``My yearning is to identify ways to enable people in
congrgations to talk to and listen to each other in trust.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Supreme Court has turned down a
two-year-old legal effort to overturn an action by a former
Southern Baptist president that voided a convention vote and helped
consolidate power of a fundamentalist wing.
   The disputed parliamentary procedure occured in 1985 when the
Rev. Charles Stanley of Atlanta headed the denomination, and a
group of opponents have fought it since through district and
appeals courts, which held they couldn't interfere in church
matters.
   The Supreme Court declined to review those lower-court decisions.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Southern Baptist home and foreign
mission boards report that contributions to their denomination's
program for world hunger relief in 1987 declined for the second
year in a row.
   Sums given fell to $8.9 million, a decline of 2.3 percent.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president of the Rabbinical Council of
America says reactions of Jewish groups to the riots in Israel's
occupied territories should be conveyed directly to Israel's
government and not made in the public media.
   Rabbi Milton H. Polin, head of the Orthodox body, said this
applied to ``all expressions of support or criticism of Israel.''
He said some advertised ``fringe'' Jewish reaction has been
``especially odious.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>COSTA MESA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Presidential Biblical Scoreboard
magazine, put out by right-wing evangelicals, has issued its 1988
survey ratings, scoring Republican contenders from 40 to 95 and
Democrats from 0 to 15.
   Comparing the candidates on a variety of what were termed
family-moral-freedom issues, the magazine said the higher the score
the more supportive the candidate is of Bible-based issues.
   Among the issues were abortion, abortion funding, capital
punishment, school prayer, pornography, homosexuality and national
security.
   The highest mark of 95 was given Republican Pat Robertson, and
the highest given a Democrat was 15 to Albert Gore Jr. Except for
Paul Simon, with a 5 score, the other Democrats were marked zero.
</TEXT>
