<DOCNO> AP880310-0256 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-88 1403EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a AM-TuitionPlans Adv14   03-10 0988</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tuition Plans, Adv 14,1014</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv14</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon AMs, March 14, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Economics and IRS May Undo Innovative Tuition Prepayment Plans</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE MITGANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Economics and the IRS may be undoing an idea
hailed as a possible antidote to rising college costs: tuition
prepayment plans.
   When Duquesne University in Pittsburgh pioneered such a plan in
1985, it seemed a natural. At a time of soaring tuitions, families
could buy higher education ``futures'' contracts. The idea was that
parents would pay a lump sum _ less if their child was young, more
if older _ and investments by the college would swell those funds
to cover tuition costs down the road.
   At Duquesne, for example, the family of a 1-year-old eligible
for college in the year 2005 could have paid a lump sum of $8,630
last fall to cover the projected four-year tuition of $102,604. But
a family of a 12-year-old hoping to enroll at Duquesne in 1994
would have had to put up $19,410 to cover the projected four-year
tuition of $48,747.
   So far so good. Parents purchase peace of mind at a discount,
knowing the plan guarantees four years of college as long as their
child is accepted. The school, in turn, gets a virtual lock on a
future student, hedging against future enrollment declines.
   But it hasn't worked smoothly for Duquesne or the several other
colleges that followed its example, nor for the five states that
have adopted tuition futures plans for public colleges since 1985.
   Duquesne announced last week it was recommending suspension of
its program because of higher-than-expected tuition increases and
lower-than-anticipated earnings on investments. The board of
directors is scheduled to make a final decision March 17.
   Similar programs at the University of Detroit and Canisius
College in Buffalo, N.Y., are likewise at a standstill and not
taking new applicants.
   Three of the five states that enacted tuition futures plans for
public colleges _ Tennessee, Indiana and Michigan _ are in limbo
because the Internal Revenue Service has yet to rule on the tax
status of investment earnings from those plans.
   Wilson Fadely, an IRS spokesman in Washington, refused to
comment on when such a ruling might be handed down.
   ``People contact me and say they are interested,'' said Lawrence
A. Jegen, chairman of the board setting up Indiana's program.
``They have a thirst for a regimented investment program so they
know that if they put their money on the table, their children's or
grandchildren's tuition will be guaranteed.''
   But Jergen said the plan might not be operating July 1 as
originally hoped because of difficulties in predicting future
tuition levels and because of the pending IRS ruling.
   A state-sponsored program that began last August at the
University of Wyoming is going strong and has signed up 332 future
students. Florida officials say they hope to start accepting
applicants next fall.
   Michigan officials remain confident they will eventually get
their program off the ground despite the questions raised by
Duquesne, and despite the fact that state law forbids them from
accepting a single student until the IRS rules.
   ``We'll have no problem at all paying for the program out of
public investments,'' said Richard Cole, higher education adviser
to Gov. James Blanchard.
   ``Duquesne's heart was in the right place, but it appears their
financial brains were in the wrong place,'' said Michigan Treasurer
Robert Bowman. ``They couldn't even gauge their own tuition.''
   But prepayment programs have been controversial from the start.
A number of colleges _ Fairleigh Dickinson University in New
Jersey, for one _ considered and rejected the idea because of the
built-in risks and unpredictability.
   Keith Briscoe, president of Buena Vista College in Storm Lake,
Iowa, called the idea a ``gimmick'' that ``overlooks students' best
interests'' because it deprives them of the chance to select a
school freely.
   The National Association of Independent Colleges and
Universities, which represents about 1,000 private institutions,
has likewise criticized them as inflexible.
   Even backers concede they are a high-risk gamble for both
parents and schools.
   A state or college offering the plan must accurately predict
future tuition and investment trends for years ahead _ or risk
losing money honoring its tuition guarantees.
   Parents, for their part, are gambling that their child will want
to attend a given college, and will qualify for admission. If for
any reaon the child doesn't attend the school in the prepayment
plan, refunds are often limited to the amount parents actually paid
in. That means parents stand to lose tens of thousands of dollars
in investment income.
   What happened at Duquesne was exactly what so many states and
private colleges had feared all along: bond markets weakened last
year and undercut the plan's investment income. Tuitions went up
more than anticipated: by 7.95 percent instead of the predicted 6
percent.
   The result was that the 622 alumni families who had signed up
found themselves with a far more generous bargain than Duquesne
ever intended, or could afford.
   ``Duquesne may be unique, or it may be the likely outcome for
many of these programs. There's just not enough history to
determine the real viability of programs like this,'' said Ron
Gambill, executive director of the Tennessee Student Assistance
Corp., the agency that will administer that state's program once
the IRS rules.
   Some, like Richard Anderson, director of the federally funded
Forum for College Financing at Columbia Teachers College, believe
Duquesne's program must have been, ``first and last, a marketing
tool,'' a premeditated financial giveaway aimed at attracting
future students.
   ``It's true we wanted to offer a program that was going to be
attractive,'' said Duquesne spokeswoman Ann Rago. ``However, the
changes in the economy were drastic. We never said our program was
forever. We started our program to help people, specifically alumni
families. It was not just a marketing a tool.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, March 14</NOTE>
