<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     03-10 0253</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0263</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crude Futures Rise, Refined Products Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crude oil futures have crept higher in
lackluster markets in the absence of any major influential
developments.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, contracts for April
delivery of West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark U.S. crude,
settled at $15.49 per barrel on Wednesday, up 4 cents from
Tuesday's close.
   Refined products traded on the exchange were mixed.
   Wholesale heating oil slipped .46 cent to 43.03 cents a gallon.
Some analysts attributed the decline in heating oil to milder
weather, which reduces demand.
   But an expected increase in demand for gasoline was credited for
a 0.29 cent rise, to 44.00 cents, in the April contract for
wholesale unleaded gas. Analysts said distributors have been
carrying low inventories, and demand is expected to pick up with
the imminent arrival of the spring and summer driving seasons.
   Crude oil trading was stalled by conflicting reports about Saudi
Arabia's support for a meeting of the OPEC pricing committee, said
John Azarow, senior trader for Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   Some members of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries have called for a meeting of the committee because the
price of OPEC oil has slipped to between $13 and $14 a barrel. At
their last meeting in December, OPEC oil ministers reaffirmed their
intention to maintain prices at $18 a barrel.
   Prices on world markets have fallen because of moderate demand
for oil, price discounting by OPEC members and an increase in
output by non-OPEC producers.
</TEXT>
