<1ST_LINE>r f PM-JulianStore Bjt   03-10 0457</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Julian Store, Bjt,0472</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Alexander Julian To Open Own Stores, First One In Charlotte</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL NOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York clothing designer Alexander
Julian plans a return to his native Tar Heel state this summer with
a new men's clothing store that he hopes will be the beginning of a
national chain.
   Julian, who also is designing uniforms for the Charlotte
Hornets, a new National Basketball Association entry, will open a
retail store here in July, said a spokesman for the designer.
   ``As a native North Carolinian, Alexander has a great affinity
for the state,'' Barry Miguel, creative director for Alexander
Julian Inc. of New York, said in a recent telephone interview. ``At
the same time, he feels Charlotte is a growing city and a growing
marketplace.''
   Julian was not available for an interview.
   The new stores will sell an upscale line of clothing and
accessories called the Alexander Julian Collection.
   ``We've expanded our men's collection,'' Miguel said. ``We have
more sportswear now than previously.''
   Julian, the 39-year-old son of a Chapel Hill haberdasher, is
considered one of the nation's top clothing designers. Although he
resides just outside New York, in Greenwich, Conn., he makes no
secret of his love for his native state.
   Julian also shares the state's passion for basketball. That's
why Hornets owner George Shinn approached Julian last year about
designing uniforms for the expansion team, which will begin play in
the 1988-89 NBA season.
   ``I felt like I wanted to lead the league in something the first
year,'' Shinn said at the time. ``I felt that being best dressed
was the way to go.''
   For his design work on the basketball team's uniforms, Julian is
being paid 10 pounds of North Carolina barbecue, delivered once a
month to his office on New York's East Side office.
   Julian's company is readying its 3,200-square-foot prototype
store for the July opening, said company president, Marty Staff.
The store's interior will be designed by Walker & Associates of New
York, which has done design work for Bloomingdale's and Calvin
Klein shops.
   A second store will open in late summer in Atlanta, followed by
another in the Northeast corridor, Miguel said.
   ``We hope to have 30 to 40 stores in the next five years,'' he
said.
   Cluett Peabody & Co. will continue to produce the Colours by
Alexander Julian line For Men and Levi Strauss & Co. will still
make the Colours by Alexander Julian for Women, Staff said.
   Julian, who is chairman and part-owner of the new company, plans
to visit the Charlotte store frequently, Miguel said. Several
venture capital firms also own stock in the company, including
Harvard Management Co. and New Enterprises Associates of San
Francisco, he said.
</TEXT>
