<DOCNO> AP880310-0267 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-88 0125EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Federated     03-10 0442</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Federated,0459</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Campeau Revives Fight Against Federated Poison Pill Defense</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Campeau Corp. is renewing its attempt to block
Federated Department Stores Inc.'s ``poison pill'' takeover
defense, contending the plan wrongly denies Federated shareholders
the chance to choose between rival buyout offers.
   Campeau, which is competing with R.H. Macy & Co. Inc. to acquire
Federated, filed a brief Tuesday in federal court to revive its
request for an injunction against the plan.
   The Toronto-based company called the rights plan a ``show
stopper'' that would block Campeau's $6.18 billion offer for
Federated.
   The plan makes a hostile takeover attempt more expensive by
allowing Federated shareholders to buy more of the company's stock
at a heavy discount.
   Campeau suspended its attack on the poison pill after the
company appeared to be close to an acquisition agreement with
Federated in late February. However, when the Federated board met
to consider accepting Campeau's offer on Feb. 29, it also began
reviewing the Macy bid.
   Macy, which last week signed a $6.1 billion definitive buyout
agreement with Federated, on Tuesday began a tender offer for
Federated's common stock. Under the offer, Macy will pay $74.50 per
share in cash for approximately 80 percent of Federated's stock.
Macy plans to swap shares in a new company, Macy's-Federated Inc.,
for the remaining 20 percent of Federated's shares.
   Analysts have valued the Macy bid at $6.1 billion.
   Campeau is offering $75 in cash per share for 80 percent of
Federated's stock and $44 in cash per share for the remaining 20
percent. The Campeau bid, which has an aggregate value of $68 per
share, totals $6.18 billion.
   Macy also went to federal court Tuesday, seeking an injunction
against the Campeau bid. Macy contended the Campeau offer, which
was amended from an earlier $68-a-share outright cash bid, actually
was a new offer and under federal law must remain open past its
March 15 scheduled expiration.
   If the Macy request is granted it effectively would put the
Campeau offer on a more equal footing with the Macy bid, which is
scheduled to expire April 4, by reducing pressure on Federated
shareholders to make a choice.
   Under federal law, a new offer would have to remain open for at
least 20 business days after publication or submission to
stockholders.
   Campeau's bid was announced March 2. If it is considered a new
offer, it could not legally expire on March 15 as scheduled.
   Federated, the nation's fifth-largest retailer, owns department
stores including Bloomingdale's, Lazarus, Rich's, Abraham & Straus,
Bullock's and Burdine's.
   Macy holdings include nearly 100 department and specialty stores
and Campeau, a real estate developer, owns Allied Stores Corp.
</TEXT>
