<1ST_LINE>r f PM-CableMerger Bjt   03-10 0564</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cable Merger, Bjt,0583</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>United Artists, United Cable Agree on Combination</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   United Artists Communications Inc. and United
Cable Television Corp. have agreed to combine their operations into
a $3.8 billion concern that would rank as one of nation's biggest
cable companies.
   The transaction, disclosed Wednesday and approved by the
directors of both Denver-based companies, would create United
Artists Entertainment Co., which would have interests in both cable
television and motion picture theaters.
   The two companies had agreed on an all-stock merger shortly
before the October stock market crash, but canceled the deal soon
after, citing disagreement over the terms and uncertain market
conditions.
   They announced in January that they had resumed their
discussions.
   The new deal is subject to approval of the companies'
shareholders and federal regulators and favorable tax rulings,
among other conditions, the companies said. They said they hoped to
complete the deal later this year.
   In trading on the New York Stock Exchange, United Cable rose
$2.87{ a share to $32.62{. In over-the-counter trading, United
Artists rose $2.25 a share to $29.75.
   The new company would have about 2.3 million cable subscribers
by the end of the year, said Stewart D. Blair, chairman and chief
executive of United Artists.
   That would place the new concern behind only the two industry
leaders in terms of subscribers, Tele-Communications Inc. and
American Television and Communications Inc., according to Paul
Kagan Associates, a media research and investment concern in
Carmel, Calif.
   Tele-Communications, which also is based in Denver, currently
owns 65 percent of United Artists and 23.7 percent of United Cable.
Its stake in the new company would be about 52 percent, the
announcement said.
   Under the new agreement, United Artists' stockholders would
receive one share of the new company for every share they currently
own of United Artists. United Cable shareholders would be eligible
to convert each of their shares into either $35 in cash or a share
of stock in the new company and the separable right to sell a share
of the new company's stock under special terms.
   The cash portion of the offer would be available on up to 49
percent of United Cable's 46.4 million fully diluted shares.
   William J. Elsner, senior vice president and chief financial
officer at United Cable, said the October agreement had been
criticized for failing to include a cash alternative.
   Sharon Armbrust, a senior analyst for Paul Kagan Associates,
estimated the new company was being capitalized at about $3.8
billion.
   That figure includes $2.4 billion in stock, $600 million in
existing debt and $800 million in new borrowing needed for the cash
portion of the deal.
   Blair would be chief executive and vice chairman of the new
company. United Cable's chairman, Gene W. Schneider, would be
chairman of the new company.
   United Artists has about 800,000 subscribers and recently agreed
to acquire the cable television division of Daniels & Associates,
which has about 380,000 subscribers. United Cable has about 1.1
million subscribers.
   United Artists also is one of the nation's biggest motion
picture operators with about 2,050 motion picture screens and plans
to boost that total by the end of the year to about 3,000 through
acquisitions and construction.
   The announcement said the new company would operate the cable
operations under the name United Cable and the theatrical
operations under the United Artists name.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880310-0269 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-88 0126EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-NewspaperAds Bjt   03-10 0546</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Newspaper Ads, Bjt,0565</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Several Newspapers Agree to Create Ad ``Island'' on Stock Pages</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Several major newspapers are hoping that putting
an ``island'' of advertising in their sea of stock tables will help
attract more national advertisers to the medium.
   The first ad buyer to participate in the unusual effort is
National Car Rental System Inc.
   The Minneapolis-based company said Wednesday it would spend $2
million through the end of the year to put quarter-page ads in what
is being called a new ``island'' position on the first page of the
stock table sections of 16 newspapers in the nation's 20 biggest
markets.
   The ads, which will be surrounded on four sides by stock
quotations, will appear a minimum of 26 times starting March 17 in
each newspaper, according to Lewis Carbone, a National marketing
executive.
   A committee of the National Advertising Bureau, a trade
organization, came up with the idea for the unusual ad position
and, along with National's ad agency, Chiat-Day Inc., persuaded the
16 newspapers to sell it.
   Michael Davies, head of the newspaper bureau panel and editor
and publisher of the Hartford Courant, said the committee looked at
a dozen proposals for displaying advertising more distinctively
before deciding on this approach.
   He said the committee wanted to find a way to help an ad message
stand out without disrupting normal reading patterns.
   Putting an ad in the stock tables seemed appropriate, he said,
because people usually look for individual stock prices rather than
reading through the entire section. ``This doesn't interrupt the
flow of reading a page,'' he said.
   But some big newspapers turned down the idea.
   The New York Times rejected it because ``it would make it too
hard for the reader to get through the stock tables,'' according to
spokeswoman Nancy Nielsen.
   The Wall Street Journal also balked. Bernard T. Flanagan, vice
president for marketing, said the placement would be ``an
inconvenience to the reader.'' ``In a sense, we want to make it as
easy as we can for readers to look up their stock quotes,'' he said.
   Flanagan said the ad placement also ``takes prestige away from
the page.''
   Newspapers have seen their share of national advertising
spending decline steadily in recent years as national advertisers
turned to television.
   Newspapers took in 15.9 percent of total national ad spending in
1950, but fell to below 6 percent in 1986.
   Last year, national advertisers spent $3.5 billion in
newspapers, or about 5.8 percent of their total spending of $60.6
billion, according to an estimate by the ad agency McCann-Erickson
Inc.
   But Robert Zach, media director for Chiat-Day, said the rising
cost of television time is making advertisers more receptive to
alternative ways to reach customers.
   Davies said he expected other advertisers would take an interest
in the new ad position and that other newspapers would embrace the
idea.
   The 16 newspapers that have sold the space to National include:
the Atlanta Journal and Constitution, Chicago Sun-Times, Dallas
Morning News, Detroit Free Press, Hartford Courant, Houston
Chronicle, Los Angeles Times, Miami Herald, Minneapolis Star and
Tribune, Phoenix Gazette, Rocky Mountain News, San Francisco
Chronicle and Examiner, Seattle Times, St. Louis Post-Dispatch, St.
Paul Pioneer Press and Dispatch and Tampa Tribune.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880310-0270 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-88 0129EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-SavingsInstitutions Bjt   03-10 0525</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Savings Institutions, Bjt,0538</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Black Monday Helping Boost In Savings Deposits, Decline in
Mortgage Rates</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Home mortgage rates fell at the quickest pace
since 1986 early this year, partly because of the broad decline in
interest rates in the wake of the October stock market crash,
according to the government.
   The stock market collapse also played a role in boosting net
deposits at the nation's savings institutions during January for
the fourth straight month, the Federal Home Loan Bank Board
reported Wednesday.
   Effective rates on typical 30-year, fixed-rate mortgages for
single-family homes dropped to 10.5 percent in early February from
10.97 percent in early January. Rates on the most popular type of
adjustable rate mortgages, those with caps on how much the rate can
change, fell to 8.74 percent from 8.98 percent over the same period.
   ``The decline in commitment rates is consistent with the
softening of mortgage demand that generally occurs during the
winter months,'' said James Barth, the bank board's chief economist.
   ``However, the recent declines were the sharpest since
1986...and appear to have reflected mainly large deposit
flows...after the stock market collapse...and an across-the-board
decline in interest rates,'' he said.
   Mortgage lending by S&Ls in January declined to the lowest level
since February 1985. Savings institutions lent $13.1 billion in
mortgages, down more than the usual seasonal dropoff from $21.7
billion in December.
   ``Contributing to the reduced lending volume was a lingering
skittishness on the part of potential home buyers following the
Oct. 19 collapse in stock prices,'' Barth said in a statement.
   The spread between fixed-rate and adjustable-rate mortgages
narrowed to 1.76 percent, the smallest difference since last
spring. The proportion of mortgages being closed with adjustable
rates edged down from 65 percent in December to 63 percent a month
later.
   But the popularity of adjustable-rate loans remains far higher
than last spring, when they represented 20 to 30 percent of the
market.
   A separate survey of mortgage rates by the Federal Home Loan
Mortgage Corp. indicated 30-year, fixed-rate mortgages averaged
9.85 percent last Friday, down slightly from 9.87 percent a week
earlier and sharply lower than 10.61 percent on Jan. 1. This survey
does not include add-on fees, known as points, which are included
in the bank board's averages.
   The bank board also said net new deposits at the nation's 3,135
federally insured S&Ls increased by $5.6 billion in January,
following a $2.6 billion increase in December. That compared with
net withdrawals of $2.1 billion in January a year ago.
   Barth said deposits normally increase from December to January,
but he added, ``Nearly half of the most recent improvement
represented non-seasonal factors. Undoubtedly, the precipitous
decline in the stock market remains one of these factors.''
   Nervous investors, seeking a safe haven for their money,
increased deposits by $6.2 billion in October and $3.2 billion in
November.
   The last four months represent a sharp reversal of the trend in
recent years, which has been described as a slow-motion run on
thrift institutions. There were net withdrawals of $3.3 billion in
1986 and $13.7 billion in the first nine months of 1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880310-0271 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-88 0130EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-SEC-Takeovers     03-10 0394</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SEC-Takeovers,0410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>SEC Opposes New York Takeover Law As Unconstitutional</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission says
New York's anti-takeover law is an unconstitutional impediment to
interstate commerce.
   The SEC also contended Wednesday that the statute conflicts with
the Williams Act, the 1968 federal law regulating corporate
takeovers.
   The agency made its arguments in a friend-of-the-court brief
filed in a suit brought by Salant Acquisition Corp. against
Manhattan Industries Inc., one of the nation's biggest makers of
men's shirts and sportswear.
   Proliferation of state anti-takeover laws since the Supreme
Court upheld Indiana's takeover statute last year has heightened
the issue of whether the federal or state governments should take
the lead in regulating corporate takeovers.
   The New York law prohibits a bidder who acquires more than 20
percent of a company's stock from completing a takeover or other
major business transaciton with the company for five years, unless
the bidder gets approval from the target's board of directors.
   ``The statute gives corporate management virtual veto power over
whether the company will be acquired,'' SEC General Counsel Daniel
L. Goelzer wrote in the brief.
   The law effectively preempts the Williams Act, he argued.
   Goelzer said ``the structure and the legislative history of the
(Williams) act make it clear that Congress believed that...it
should be the shareholders _ the owners of the corporation _ who
make the decision,'' not the management.
   The SEC, which regulates the nation's securities markets, is
intervening in the case in U.S. District Court in Manhattan on the
side of Salant.
   Salant, a unit of Salant Corp., another major apparel maker,
began a $95 million hostile takeover attempt of Manhattan
Industries in February.
   Manhattan Industries had sought to block the $16-a-share buyout
offer Salant launched on Feb. 2. U.S. District Judge Louis L.
Stanton last week denied Manhattan Industries' request for a court
order blocking the tender offer but did not rule on Salant's
constitutional challenge.
   Manhattan Industries said Wednesday it had entered into
negotiations about a possible merger with Salant.
   The SEC took a similar position when the Supreme Court
considered a challenge to Indiana's anti-takeover law last year,
but the court upheld the law.
   In another current battle, the SEC has indicated it was
considering whether to file briefs in suits challenging the newly
enacted Delaware anti-takeover law, which is structured somewhat
similarly to New York's law.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880310-0272 </DOCNO>
