<HEAD>Details Announced on Matsushita Plant</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TROY, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Matsushita Electric Industrial Co. Ltd. says
it may export to Japan some of the approximately 1 million
large-screen color television picture tubes it will make each year
in this western Ohio city.
   The $160 million Matsushita plant is to open in spring 1989 with
240 people and production of 400,000 tubes, company officials said
Wednesday.
   That will expand to about 400 jobs once full production is
reached in two or three years, said Fumio Kanazwa, president of the
subsidiary Matsushita Electronics Corp.
   The company announced it planned to build a plant in Troy last
December, but disclosed no details until Wednesday.
   Kanazawa declined to specify under what conditions Matsushita
would export tubes to Japan, where Matsushita already makes some
large-screen tubes, but said it would not depend just on the
yen-dollar exchange rate.
   The plant will make 29- and 33-inch tubes, although it could be
reconfigured to produce smaller picture tubes, said Yasuhiko
Yamaguchi, who will be president of American Matsushita Electronics
Corp.
   Production at Troy will represent slightly more than 10 percent
of the total picture tube production by Matsushita, which had total
1987 revenue of more than $36 billion.
   Matsushita, which makes Panasonic, Quasar, Technics and National
brand consumer electronics, began producing televisions in the
United States with acquisition of the Quasar plant from Motorola in
1974, spokesman Justin Camerlengo said.
   Matsushita has been buying about one-third of its picture tubes
in the United States, he said.
   Honda of America on Monday became the first Japanese automaker
to export to Japan when it shipped off 540 Accords made at its
Marysville plant.
   Honda, the fourth-largest automaker in the United States, plans
to export 4,000 Accords to Japan this year and 50,000 U.S.-built
cars to Japan annually by 1991.
</TEXT>
