<1ST_LINE>r f PM-USG Bjt   03-10 0521</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-USG, Bjt,0539</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>USG Urges Rejection of Desert Partners' Buyout Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officers of USG Corp. are urging the building
materials company's shareholders to reject a $1.9 billion hostile
takeover offer as inadequate and coercive, and say the company
might sell a major stake to a third party.
   USG Chairman Robert J. Day wrote shareholders Wednesday that
they should reject the unsolicited $42-a-share tender offer by
Desert Partners LP, a group led by Texas oilmen Jack E. Brown and
Cyril Wagner Jr.
   USG also disclosed in a Securities and Exchange Commission
filing that it may sell a substantial stake in USG to a third,
unidentified company.
   Placing a big block of shares in friendly hands, a maneuver
known as the ``white squire'' takeover defense, would make it more
difficult if not impossible for Desert Partners to acquire control
of the company.
   Desert Partners on March 1 launched a tender offer of $42 in
cash for each of 21.5 million shares of USG stock. The group also
offered to acquire the balance of USG's 50.8 million outstanding
shares with securities it valued at $42 a share. Desert Partners
already owns about 9.9 percent of USG stock.
   Day questioned the value of securities portion of Desert
Partners' offer, saying it consisted of junk bonds and warrants
``purportedly worth $42 per share.''
   Paul Colitti, a USG spokesman, said the company believed the
$42-per-share cash portion of the offer also did not reflect USG's
true value.
   USG stock fell $1.62{ to $36.50 a share Wednesday on the New
York Stock Exchange, indicating investor doubts about the
seriousness of Desert Partners' offer.
   Desert Partners responded to USG's decision late Wednesday with
a letter to the company's board saying it was prepared to negotiate
its tender offer.
   Desert Partners also chastised USG for considering selling a
chunk of the company to a third party, in what the Texas group
called an attempt to block its takeover bid.
   ``We are certain that your stockholders would much prefer your
entering into prompt good-faith negotiations with us rather than
your continuing to devote effort and expense to defensive tactics
that can only erode the value of USG shares,'' Desert Partners said
in its letter.
   Colitti said USG's discussions with another party did not
necessarily mean a deal was imminent.
   Desert Partners bought its USG shares last year for about $44.30
a share in a previous takeover attempt that fizzled when the Texas
group was unable to arrange the necessary financing.
   Desert Partners also is seeking shareholder purchase rights that
take effect Friday and that were triggered by the tender offer.
   The purchase rights, part of USG's ``poison-pill'' takeover
defense, would allow all shareholders except Desert Partners to buy
additional new USG stock, making completion of a takeover
prohibitively expensive.
   Desert Partners has filed a lawsuit in U.S. District Court in
Chicago challenging the legality of the poison pill and has said it
will seek to elect six directors to USG's 15-member board at the
company's annual meeting in May.
   USG, based in Chicago, is a leading producer of gypsum and
building materials, with about 100 plants nationwide.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
