<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Guinness,0295</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Merchant Banker Lord Spens Arrested in Guinness Affair</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former merchant banker Lord Patrick Spens was
arrested Thursday in connection with the case stemming from
Guinness PLC's 1986 takeover of Distillers Co. PLC.
   Fraud squad detectives arrested Spens, 45, a former managing
director of merchant bankers Henry Ansbacher and Co. Ltd., at his
home in the southeast England town of Gould and took him to a
London police station for questioning, Scotland Yard said.
   He was the fifth man to be arrested in the case.
   Scotland Yard said it is investigating the alleged purchase of
2.15 million Guinness shares for 7.6 million pounds, the equivalent
of $14 million, from Ansbacher clients during the Guinness takeover
of Distillers, a Scotch whiskey and gin maker.
   Spens resigned from his 100,000-pound-a-year post at Ansbacher
in January 1987 under pressure from the Bank of England, and told
reporters his alleged role in the Guinness affair was perceived as
an error of judgment.
   ``I acted properly and I don't think there was anything
inappropriate in what I did,'' he said.
   Police are investigating Guinness's tactics during its 2.6
billion-pound takeover of Distillers.
   Guinness, a major brewer, has admitted arranging for the illegal
repurchase of its stock in an apparent effort to boost its share
price and make its cash and stock offer for Distillers more
attractive than a rival bid from Argyll Group PLC, a supermarket
operator.
   At the center of the investigation is deposed Guinness chairman
Ernest Saunders, who remains free on 500,000 pounds bail after
being charged with 40 offenses.
   Others facing charges are former Morgan Grenfell merchant bank
director Roger Seelig and businessmen Sir Jack Lyons and Gerald
Ronson.
</TEXT>
