<HEAD>Stores, Taxis Begin 24-hour Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shopowners in the Greek capital pulled
down their shutters on Thursday to demand the return of the
traditional afternoon break abolished by the government last month
in favor of continuous working hours.
   Athens' 15,000 twxi drivers also locked up their taxis for a day
to protest anti-pollution measures. The ban restricts half of the
taxis from entering the center of the city on weekdays according to
license plates that end in odd or even numbers.
   Shopkeepers gathered at a downtown theater and later marched to
parliament to press their claim for a different set of work hours.
Large department stores and supermarket chains, however,
disregarded the strike call and remained open.
   The new store-hours, in effect from Feb. 1, replaced more than
40 different work-schedules for different kinds of shops, with a
continuous 50-hour work week.
</TEXT>
