<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market headed lower today, giving back
some of its recent gains.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials dropped 6.63 to 2,067.64
in the first half hour of trading.
   Losers slightly outnumbered gainers in the overall tally of New
York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 505 up, 524 down and 495
unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 24.11 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   Analysts said traders were disappointed by the Dow Jones
industrial average's inability to make a run at the 2,100 level
after reaching new early-1988 highs lately.
   Investors evidently are skeptical about the market's ability to
put together a sustained rally less than six months after the
October crash.
   Those traders who have been buying are quick to step in and take
profits when prices move up, brokers say.
   A good many market participants are already looking ahead to
next week's scheduled monthly report on the trade deficit, trying
to figure out whether the figures are likely to maintain the
favorable trend of the past couple of reports.
   Today Japan said its trade surplus fell in February from its
comparable level a year ago.
   Losers among the blue chips included International Business
Machines, down | at 116, and Ford Motor, down \ at 44~.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
slipped .10 to 151.38. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index was up .40 at 299.98.
   On Wednesday the Dow Jones industrial average dropped 6.80 to
2,074.27.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 4 to 3 on the
NYSE, with 871 up, 636 down and 459 unchanged. Big Board volume
totaled 210.90 million shares, against 237.68 million in the
previous session.
