<1ST_LINE>r f PM-US-China 1stLd-Writethru f0019 03-10 0794</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-China, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0019,0817</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 9th graf, The items ..., to include types of technology
that could be cleared. A version moving on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HENRY GOTTLIEB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The list of American high-technology goods
China is allowed to buy will start expanding again because the
Reagan administration has determined the Chinese are not selling
Silkworm missiles to Iran.
   China also says it wants a commodity the United States is
sending to 64 other countries: Peace Corps volunteers.
   Under an agreement announced Wednesday at the conclusion of a
three-day visit by Chinese Foreign Minister Wu Xueqian, the United
States will lift a five-month suspension on liberalization of
high-tech products China is permitted to buy from American
companies.
   The restriction was imposed in October to protest what the
United States said was sale of Chinese Silkworm missiles used by
Iran to attack neutral shipping in the Persian Gulf.
   During his visit, Wu continued to deny that such sales were ever
made directly by China. Without commenting on that assertion, the
administration said it was satisfied with what the Chinese are
doing now.
   ``We are encouraged by Chinese statements and actions regarding
Iran's acquisition of Chinese anti-ship missiles, Silkworms,''
State Department spokesman Charles E. Redman said.
   ``We have therefore decided to resume the export control
liberalization process for China,'' he said.
   This means experts from the state, commerce and defense
departments will resume reviewing the list of high-technology
products now banned for sale to China to see if any items can be
removed. Sales of high-technology products cleared for Chinese
purchase before last October have been continuing.
   Among the technologies that could be cleared for export to China
are computers, electronic components, communications gear and
metallurgical processes.
   The decision removed an irritant in the relationship. ``Clearly
they weren't happy about it, but we weren't happy about the
Silkworms,'' said a Reagan administration official, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   Wu also assured the United States that China would go along with
a United Nations resolution banning all arms sales to Iran, the
U.S. official said. According to U.S. estimates, China sold nearly
$1 billion worth of arms to Iran in 1987.
   Wu said at a National Press Club luncheon on Wednesday that U.S.
officials showed how upset they were about the Silkworms by raising
the issue 20 times during the three days of talks.
   He once again denied China ever sold weapons to Iran, but when
asked if Chinese weapons were getting to Iran through other
countries he said, ``We have no idea.''
   He gave an upbeat assessment of relations and called for more
trade and more people-to-people contacts between Chinese and
Americans. Then he revealed that after years of U.S. requests,
China had agreed in principle to accept Peace Corps volunteers.
   Since the program began in 1961 under President Kennedy, many
nations' feelings about Peace Corps projects have reflected their
overall view of relations with the United States.
   In India, for example, the largest country to have had Peace
Corps volunteers, the welcome mat was put out in 1962 when ties
were strong and was withdrawn in 1976, when relations soured. There
are now Peace Corps volunteers in 64 countries.
   The program in China is likely to concentrate on English
teaching, but further discussions will be needed to determine how
large the Peace Corps contingent will be and what it will do.
   ``It will be good news for our country and I believe for the
Chinese people if the Peace Corps can send its volunteers to the
most populous nation on earth,'' said Sen. Christopher Dodd,
D-Conn., who served as a volunteer in the Dominican Republic in the
1960s. ``We could learn much about each other.''
   Rep. Stephen J. Solarz, D-N.Y., chairman of the House Foreign
Affairs subcommittee on Asia called the Peace Corps agreement a
``potentially important step.''
   ``I feel confident that these ambassadors for the American way
of life will have a positive impact upon ties between the largest
nation in the East and the largest nation in the West,'' Solarz
said.
   Amid the good feeling they said was generated during the Wu
visit, U.S. officials had little comment on the issue of Tibet,
where Chinese authorities are clashing with groups seeking Tibetan
independence.
   Redman, the State Department spokesman, said Secretary of State
George P. Shultz raised the issue of human rights in Tibet, but
provided no details.
   In his press club remarks, Wu denounced a proposal by the Dalai
Lama, the religious leader of Tibetan Buddhists, who is living in
exile in India. The Dalai Lama's proposal includes a withdrawal of
Chinese troops from Tibet.
   Wu said of the Dalai Lama, ``He is an exile who attacks and
smears the People's Republic of China.''
</TEXT>
