<1ST_LINE>r f PM-UAWBillboard     03-10 0256</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UAW Billboard,0265</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wisconsin Union Local Appeals to Iacocca with Roadside Billboard</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HAMTRAMCK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   United Auto Workers union members in
Kenosha, Wis., have rented a billboard in this Detroit enclave to
ask Chrysler Corp. Chairman Lee Iacocca to keep their plant open
and save their jobs.
   Chrysler has announced it will close the former American Motors
Corp. car assembly plant in Kenosha at the end of the 1988 model
year, eliminating 5,500 jobs. Chrysler acquired the plant when it
bought AMC last year.
   The billboard, located along Interstate 75 in Hamtramck, says:
```Iacocca, keep your word to Kenosha!' UAW Local 72 Kenosha.''
   The UAW and Wisconsin officials contend Chrysler promised to
modernize the plant and keep it open for five years of making Dodge
Omni and Plymouth Horizon subcompacts. Chrysler denies it gave any
guarantees.
   ``We hope this will generate interest and motivate Iacocca to
change his mind,'' said Rudy Kuzel, spokesman for Local 72.
   The local paid $4,200 for one month's rent on the sign, which is
a few blocks from Chrysler headquarters in Highland Park.
   ``We will not crawl off in a corner,'' Kuzel said Wednesday.
``They want us to lie down, play dead and wait to see how we are
going to be buried.''
   Top Chrysler and UAW leaders met in Milwaukee on Wednesday to
discuss the Kenosha plant and benefits for workers should it close.
Unlike other Chrysler workers, those at Kenosha and other former
AMC plants aren't covered by the supplemental unemployment benefits
provision of the Chrysler-UAW contract.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
