<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Mulheren 1stLd-Writethru f0031 03-10 0335</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mulheren, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0031,0345</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS first two grafs with stay lifted; edits to conform
thruout</NOTE>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Removes Stays on Order to Release Mulheren From MCC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court today lifted a stay that
had prevented the arbitrageur accused of threatening to kill Ivan
Boesky from leaving federal detention and moving into a private
psychiatric hospital.
   The 2nd U.S. Court of Appeals denied the government's motion for
a continuation of a stay. The effect is to allow John Mulheren to
be moved to the private hospital.
   U.S. District Judge Whitman Knapp had ruled Wednesday that a
three-hour examination by a court-appointed psychiatrist indicated
that Mulheren presented no threat to either himself or the
community and released him from the Metropolitan Correctional
Center.
   But Assistant U.S. Attorney Robert Gage said he opposed
releasing Mulheren to the private hospital, and obtained a ruling
from the 2nd U.S. Court of Appeals staying the matter until today's
ruling.
   The government had argued that the private facility, the Carrier
Foundation in Montgomery Township, N.J., was not secure enough to
house Mulheren, the senior partner at Jamie Securities Co.
   However, Knapp said, ``He's no danger at the moment, and if he's
kept under proper surveillance there's no reason to believe he will
become dangerous.''
   Mulheren, carrying a loaded assault rifle, was arrested Feb. 18
by the police outside his Rumson, N.J., home.
   He is being held on a criminal complaint that he threatened to
kill admitted insider-trader Boesky and Michael Davidoff, Boesky's
former head trader. The men have reportedly implicated Mulheren in
possible securities law violations.
   Mulheren's lawyers argue that he is a manic depressive who had
failed to take his Lithium, a drug used to control impulses, the
day of his arrest.
   Knapp said he could not explain Mulheren's actions, but agreed
with the psychiatrist that they were an ``aberration.''
   One of his defense lawyers, Peter Bennett, said Wednesday that
Mulheren had not been getting the drug properly while in federal
custody.
</TEXT>
