<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street Noon,0311</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices sagged in quiet trading today,
giving back some of their recent gains.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials dropped 7.46 to 2,066.81
by noontime on Wall Street.
   Losers slightly outnumbered gainers in the overall tally of New
York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 648 up, 683 down and 471
unchanged.
   Analysts said traders were disappointed by the Dow Jones
industrial average's inability to make a run at the 2,100 level
after reaching new early-1988 highs lately.
   Investors evidently are skeptical about the market's ability to
put together a sustained rally less than six months after the
October crash.
   Those traders who have been buying are quick to step in and take
profits when prices move up, brokers say.
   A good many market participants are already looking ahead to
next week's scheduled monthly report on the trade deficit, trying
to figure out whether the figures are likely to maintain the
favorable trend of the past couple of reports.
   Today Japan said its trade surplus fell in February from its
comparable level a year ago.
   Colt Industries led the active list and jumped 5[ to 18]. The
company said it agreed to be acquired by a group including its top
executives for $17 a share.
   K mart gained { to 35]. The company reported earnings for its
fiscal fourth quarter ended Jan. 27 of $1.58 a share, up from $1.41
in the like period a year earlier.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks edged
up .02 to 151.50. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was down .87 at 298.71.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 80.39 million shares at
noontime, against 107.60 million at the same point Wednesday.
</TEXT>
