<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Open Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices opened mixed
today on the Chicago Board of Trade, with soybeans posting some
surprising gains in early trading.
   Market analysts had expected soybeans to open lower on ideas
that soybean plantings were on the rise and in response to an
increase in the Agriculture Department's estimate of this year's
ending stocks.
   Instead, soybean futures were as much as 3 cents a bushel higher
in early trading.
   ``It's a little bit of a surprise that some buying came into the
soybean market but I don't think it's anything too significant
because the market's starting to back off already,'' Ted Mao, grain
specialist for Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc., said about a half-hour
after the opening.
   Wheat futures were steady to slightly higher. Corn prices were
mostly lower.
   In early trading, wheat was \ cent to 1\ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in March at $2.96 a bushel; corn was { cent
lower to } cent higher with March at $1.99{ a bushel; oats were
unchanged to } cent higher with March at $1.85 a bushel; soybeans
were { cent to 3 cents higher with March at $6.08{ a bushel.
   Cattle futures were mixed while pork futures were mostly lower
in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were unchanged to .15 cent higher with April at
72.97 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .15 cent lower to .18 cent
higher with March at 81.20 cents a pound; hogs were .05 cent to .25
cent lower with April at 43.37 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were unchanged to .17 cent lower with March at 52.10 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures closed mostly lower on Wednesday.
</TEXT>
