<1ST_LINE>u f PM-LorimarBid     03-10 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lorimar Bid,0376</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lorimar Gets Unsolicited Bid from Marvin Davis</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CULVER CITY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Loss-plagued Lorimar Telepictures
Corp., which earlier this week said it was discussing a merger with
Warner Communications Inc., said today it has received an
unsolicited $780.3 million takeover bid from investor Marvin Davis.
   The $17-a-share price being offered by Davis is in the middle of
the $14 to $20 range that analysts have said Lorimar should be able
to fetch and was seen as triggering a bidding war for Lorimar.
   Lorimar stock jumped $1.37{ a share to $15.75 in early trading
after announcement of the offer from Davis. The company has 45.9
million shares outstanding.
   It hasn't been disclosed what sort of terms are being discussed
in talks between Lorimar and New York-based Warner. Those talks,
which began last weekend, have been described by both sides as
preliminary.
   Davis has been seeking to get back into the entertainment
business since selling 20th Century Fox Film Corp. to media magnate
Rupert Murdoch in 1985 for $575 million. Davis had owned Fox for
four years, but the company was beset by persistent losses.
   Last year, he made an unsuccessful $321.9 million bid for the
90.6 percent he didn't already own of Texas-based Spectradyne Inc.,
the nation's largest supplier of cable television and pay-per-view
movies for hotels.
   In a brief announcement, Lorimar noted that Davis' offer was
subject to a number of conditions and said it ``would bear Davis'
letter in mind.''
   Lorimar is a leading producer of original television
programming, but in recent years it has been troubled as its
ambitious plans to expand into other areas disintegrated and
sometimes caused the company to incur losses or heavy costs that
depressed earnings.
   For the first nine months of its current fiscal year, Lorimar
posted a loss of $82.6 million on revenue of $616.8 million. The
deficit included $45 million in writedowns on five movies and $22
million in reserves for possible future losses in its home-video
unit.
   Management of both the movie and home-video units have been
replaced.
   For fiscal 1987 ended last March 31, the company lost $58.6
million, mostly because of restructuring costs, on revenue of
$766.2 million.
</TEXT>
