<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-88 1322EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Japan-Trade Bjt   03-10 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Trade, Bjt,0405</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japan's Trade Surplus With United States Shrinks Declines 26.5
Percent In February</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan's unadjusted trade surplus with the United
States fell 14.4 percent in February as imports from the United
States reached record levels, the Finance Ministry said Thursday.
   The politically sensitive surplus was squeezed by the strong
Japanese yen, which makes it cheap for the Japanese to buy
foreign-made goods and inhibits sales of Japanese goods abroad.
   The Japanese-U.S. surplus fell to $3.40 billion from $3.97
billion in February 1987, unadjusted for seasonal fluctuations.
Exports to the United States rose 9.7 percent to $6.81 billion,
while imports from the United States soared by 51.9 percent to
$3.41 billion.
   The imports from the United States broke the previous one-month
record of $3.12 billion, set in June 1986.
   Japan's overall trade surplus declined 26.5 percent in February
as imports of foreign goods set another record, the ministry said.
   The overall surplus fell to $5.24 billion from $7.13 billion in
February 1987, the 10th consecutive month of year-to-year declines.
   The February surplus was up from $3.07 billion in January, but
the ministry said the scope of trade usually dwindles in January
because of Japan's long New Year holidays.
   Imports shot up 48.0 percent from a year ago to a record $15.0
billion in February, while exports rose 17.2 percent to $20.2
billion. The previous high for imports was $14.8 billion in
December 1987.
   Imports of U.S. aircraft in the month nearly tripled to $478
million.
   The ministry said the aircraft purchases were a special factor
in February, but over the last several months, export growth has
been held back and imports have been encouraged by the yen's sharp
rise against the U.S. dollar. The dollar was trading at 128 yen in
February, compared with 152 yen a year earlier.
   Meanwhile, machinery imports from the United States in February
grew by 77.9 percent to $1.26 billion and motor vehicle imports
rose 91.6 percent to $15.6 million.
   Japanese motor vehicle exports to the United States fell 5.4
percent to $1.71 billion.
   Japan ran a February trade surplus of $1.94 billion with the
European Economic Community, up by $4 million from a year earlier.
   Because of large oil imports, Japan's deficit in trade with the
Middle East rose to $1.20 billion from $844 million in February
1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880310-0290 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-88 1405EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Retail     03-10 0600</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Retail,0630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>K Mart Earnings Up; Dayton Hudson's Down</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   K mart Corp. reported Thursday its fourth-quarter earnings rose
nearly 13 percent while Dayton Hudson Corp. said its income fell
from a year earlier, when it had a one-time gain from the sale of
one of its divisions.
   K mart, the nation's second-largest retailer, said it earned
$321.2 million, or $1.58 a share, in the quarter ended Jan. 27,
compared with $285 million, or $1.41 a share, in the same period a
year earlier.
   Sales for the quarter totaled $7.75 billion, up from $7.23
billion in the year-earlier quarter.
   For all of fiscal 1987, K mart earned $692.2 million, or $3.40 a
share, up 19 percent from the $582.3 million, or $2.90 a share, the
company recorded in 1986.
   The retailer's full-year sales totaled $25.6 billion, up from
$23.8 billion the previous year.
   ``K mart had good, solid earnings improvement because of
effective control of their business,'' said Jeffrey B. Edelman, a
retail industry analyst for the investment firm Drexel Burnham
Lambert Inc. ``Markdowns were held to a minimum.''
   Dayton Hudson, the nation's sixth-largest retailer, said it
earned $133.7 million, or $1.54 a share, in the quarter ended Jan.
30, down 34 percent from $202.4 million, or $2.08 a share, in the
year-earlier period.
   However, the 1986 fourth quarter included an $85.2 million gain
from the sale of Dayton Hudson's B. Dalton Booksellers chain.
Excluding that gain, Dayton Hudson's earnings rose 11 percent in
the latest quarter.
   Dayton Hudson's fourth-quarter figures reflect ``some positive
earnings swings from a division that had been very depressed last
year,'' said Edelman.
   Edelman referred to the company's Mervyn's apparel stores, which
had helped pull Dayton Hudson's earnings into a decline in recent
quarters.
   Sales for the latest quarter totaled $3.68 billion, up from
$3.12 billion in the year-earlier quarter.
   For all of fiscal 1987, Dayton Hudson earned $228.4 million, or
$2.41 a share, down 26 percent from $310 million, or $3.19 a share,
in 1986.
   Excluding the fourth-quarter 1986 gain, the retailer's earnings
fell 10 percent.
   Full-year sales totaled $10.68 billion, up from $9.26 billion.
   Dayton Hudson said its Target discount stores division continued
to do well in 1987, but its department stores suffered from a drop
in sales.
   Edelman said both companies benefited from lower tax rates in
1987.
   Meanwhile, Charming Shoppes Inc. reported its fourth-quarter
income plummeted 46 percent as its sales declined along with those
of many other apparel retailers.
   Charming Shoppes said it earned $7.5 million, or 15 cents a
share, in the quarter ended Jan. 30, down from nearly $14 billion,
or 28 cents a share, in the year-earlier period.
   Sales rose to $182.9 million from $163.8 million.
   Many apparel retailers have seen their fourth-quarter profits
tumble because they were forced to slash prices in the face of
sluggish sales. Analysts said consumers were bored by the fall and
winter fashions in most stores.
   For the full year, Charming Shoppes said it earned $42.6
million, up 5 percent from $40.5 million in 1986. Sales totaled
$638.6 million in fiscal 1987, up from $521.2 million the year
before.
   Charming Shoppes operates 840 stores in 33 states under the
names Fashion Bug and Fashion Bug Plus.
   K mart, the nation's second-largest retailer, said it had 3,934
stores at the year's end, including K mart, Waldenbooks, Builders
Square and Pay Less Drug stores.
   Besides Mervyn's and Target, Dayton Hudson's divisions include
Dayton Hudson Department Stores and Lechmere's home electronics,
appliance and sporting goods stores.
   The company had a total of 577 stores at year's end.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
