<DOCNO> AP880310-0291 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-88 1426EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-JobOutlook     03-10 0446</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Job Outlook,0461</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Than 2.4 Million Jobs in 1988, Survey Predicts</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Embargoed for use after 6 p.m. EST; time set by source.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 2.4 million jobs are expected to be
created in the United States this year, fewer than in 1987 but
``still a very healthy number,'' a business research company said
Thursday.
   Manufacturers and companies with fewer than 20 employees will
again be leaders in creating jobs, according to Dun & Bradstreet
Corp., which announced the results of its annual survey of
employment expectations at 5,000 companies.
   Last year, the U.S. economy created about 3 million jobs. The
Labor Department announced last week that the nation's civilian
unemployment rate fell to 5.7 percent in February, its lowest point
since 1979.
   Dun & Bradstreet has predicted in a separate report that the
jobless rate will average 5.7 percent this year, down from an
average of 6.2 percent last year. The new jobs will be filled by
new entrants to the labor force.
   The goods-producing sector, aided by a cheaper dollar, is likely
to produce more than 610,000 jobs this year, the most since 1979,
Dun & Bradstreet said.
   In contrast, the goods-producing sector lost 180,000 jobs in
1986, and then added 210,000 last year as it began to recover, the
company said.
   ``This represents a significant departure from the pattern in
recent years, when job growth was driven largely by the services
sector,'' Joseph W. Duncan, the chief economist, said in a news
release.
   ``The hot spot, so to speak, in 1988 is going to be the
industrial Midwest,'' Reid Gearhart, a Dun & Bradstreet analyst,
said in an interview.
   Companies with fewer than 20 employees are expected to generate
35 percent of the new jobs in 1988, even though they make up less
than 19 percent of total employment, the company said.
   Similarly, it said, companies with fewer than 100 employees are
likely to generate just over half of the new jobs in spite of
making up only a third of the employment.
   Companies with over 25,000 employees are likely to lag again in
1988, contributing slightly less than 7 percent of new jobs in
spite of making up 20 percent of employment, Dun & Bradstreet said.
   Just over 32 percent of manufacturers in the survey said they
expected to increase employment, the highest of any sector. The
corresponding figures in other sectors were 12.8 percent in
agriculture, 27.8 percent in mining, 31.3 percent in construction,
27.5 percent in transportation and public utilities, 30.1 percent
in wholesale and retail trade, 25.7 percent in finance, insurance
and real estate, 31.5 percent in services and 25.5 percent in
government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880310-0292 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-88 1519EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet3pm     03-10 0320</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 3pm,0337</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market took a tumble today, giving
back some of its recent gains.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials dropped 22.05 to
2,052.22 by 3 p.m. on Wall Street.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by about 5 to 3 in the overall tally
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 556 up, 962 down and
441 unchanged.
   Analysts said traders were disappointed by the Dow Jones
industrial average's inability to make a run at the 2,100 level
after reaching new early-1988 highs lately.
   Investors evidently are skeptical about the market's ability to
put together a sustained rally less than six months after the
October crash.
   Those traders who have been buying are quick to step in and take
profits when prices move up, brokers say.
   A good many market participants are already looking ahead to
next week's scheduled monthly report on the trade deficit, trying
to figure out whether the figures are likely to maintain the
favorable trend of the past couple of reports.
   Today Japan said its trade surplus fell in February from its
comparable level a year ago.
   Colt Industries led the active list and jumped 4{ to 17}. The
company said it agreed to be acquired by a group including its top
executives for $17 a share.
   AFG Industries fell 5 to 31|. Forstmann Little & Co. said it had
decided after studying the matter not to make an offer to acquire
AFG.
   K mart gained ] to 35\. The company reported earnings for its
fiscal fourth quarter ended Jan. 27 of $1.58 a share, up from $1.41
in the like period a year earlier.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks fell
.97 to 150.51. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was down 1.99 at 297.59.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 148.47 million shares with an
hour to go.
