<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Decline In Price</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures closed moderately lower
Thursday on the Chicago Board of Trade as traders showed little
buying interest.
   Of overriding concern was an expectation that a March 31
government report on spring plantings will show a broad increase in
crop acreage, said Ted Mao, grain specialist with Shearson Lehman
Hutton Inc.
   Other maret pressures include the large soybean crop now being
harvested in South America, an increase in world vegetable-oil
production and the lackluster prospects for new grain export sales
to the Soviet Union in the near term, Mao said.
   ``It's a combination of all that in the atmosphere of a market
that's been kind of on the defensive and it's just feeding on
itself temporarily,'' Mao said.
   At the close, wheat was 3} cents to 6\ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in March at $2.91 a bushel; corn was 1\ cents
to 1} cents lower with March at $1.97{ a bushel; oats were 3\ cents
to 5} cents lower with March at $1.81 a bushel; soybeans were 4
cents to 5{ cents lower with March at $6.01{ a bushel.
