<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-88 1645EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Europe-Takeover     03-10 0470</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Europe-Takeover,0487</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>De Benedetti Calls for Societe Generale Shareholders Meeting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAF CASERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Italian investor Carlo De Benedetti,
who is vying for control of Belgium's biggest holding company,
Thursday called for an extraordinary meeting of the shareholders of
Societe Generale de Belgique S.A.
   De Benedetti said he would ask the meeting to consider himself
and two of his Belgian allies, Andre Leysen of Gevaert N.V and
Pierre Scohier of Copeba S.A, as company directors.
   De Benedetti and an array of Belgian and international partners
claim to control over 47 percent of the company's 28.2 million
shares.
   A Franco-Belgian alliance is fighting De Benedetti's bid to get
control of Societe Generale and claims a majority stake of 52
percent.
   The group formed around Belgium's biggest insurer, Group AG, and
the French investment firm Companie Financiere de Suez, has also
said it would like a shareholders meeting to discuss the company's
future but has not called for a specific date.
   In addition, it stressed it is willing to talk with De
Benedetti, but only on the condition that the Italian admits he
does not have control of the company.
   While the uncertainty on the corporate battle continued, Suez
president Renaud de la Geniere said the fight ``could take months
perhaps, but I hope I will not take years.''
   De la Geniere had talks with caretaker Prime Minister Wilfried
Martens on the takeover bid, but no details were available.
   In a statement released by his French investment company Cerus
S.A, de Benedetti said the shareholders meeting should discuss how
many directors should run the company, which controls a third of
the Belgian economy.
   Any shareholder with at least 20 percent of the share capital is
able to convene such a meeting according to Belgian commercial law.
   The stakes each side holds could change dramatically since a
Brussels court approved a capital increase of 12 million shares for
Societe Generale. Both camps claim they are entitled to the new
stock. A higher court still has to rule on the increase.
   To sidestep the issue, De Benedetti announced a request would be
made at the meeting that the company not make use of its recent
capital increase.
   Leysen said de la Geniere had made similar suggestions earlier
and said the two sides might agree to annul the capital increase.
   The shares were issued by Societe Generale immediately after it
was aware of De Benedetti's intentions, which it considers hostile.
The increase would dilute the stakes each side currently holds.
   De Benedetti wants to turn the 166-year-old company into a
holding company for enterprises across Europe, anticipating 1992,
when the movement of goods, capital and people should be free
throughout the 12-nation European Economic Community.
   The alliance fighting De Benedetti wants the company to remained
focused in Belgium.
</TEXT>
