<HEAD>Southdown Inc. Increases Tender Offer For Moore McCormack
Resources, Inc.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Southdown Inc., a cement and energy company, says
it is increasing its tender offer for Moore McCormack Resources
Inc. to $35 per share of common stock from its previous offer of
$31 per share.
   The increase was estimated to raise the total value of the
takeover to about $450 million from a previous estimate of roughly
$395 million, including offers for Moore McCormack preferred stock
and subordinated debt, Southdown officials said Thursday.
   ``We will consider this development in due course,'' said Tony
Doumlele, director of corporate relations for Moore McCormack.
   On March 23, Southdown announced its initial cash tender offer
for the Stamford, Conn.-based oil and gas and building materials
company. At the time, Moore McCormack officials called th offer
``totally unsolicited,'' but said they would study it.
   ``We haven't heard anything more (from Moore McCormack
management),'' said Ruth Pachman, spokeswoman for Southdown.
   Southdown said its tender offer is conditional upon the valid
tender of a majority of Moore McCormack common stock, the
invalidation of Moore McCormack's ``poison pill'' anti-takeover
defense and the acquisition of sufficient financing.
   Southdown said it was confident it could obtain the necessary
financing to cover the tender offer and related costs.
   Southdown produces and sells cement and ready-mixed concrete and
is active in oil and gas production. Moore McCormack produces
building materials and is involved in oil and gas exploration and
production, mainly in Texas and Louisiana.
