<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-88 1713EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-LastRoundup     03-10 0250</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Last Roundup,0257</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stockyards Sales Reports Headed For Last Roundup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After almost 70 years of tallying
livestock sales at the historic pens of the Fort Worth Stockyards,
the Livestock Market News Service said its reports are headed for
their last roundup.
   Government officials have issued daily or weekly reports on
sales at the pens since around 1920, but said Wednesday that so few
cattle and hogs are sold in the city still nicknamed Cowtown that
regular sales reports will be halted March 31.
   The oldest cattle pens in Fort Worth date to 1887. But as urban
growth has swallowed the stockyards, cattle raisers have turned
away from the maze of traffic lights and freeways to competing
auctions in small towns, said Rick Wahrmund, statewide director of
the Livestock Market News Service.
   Ronnie Steen, who has been reporting stockyard sales since 1976,
said sales have dropped to between 200 and 300 cattle a week for
months, from an average of about 5,000 weekly in 1976. Daily
auctions have long since been replaced with a weekly cattle auction
on Mondays.
   ``We don't have enough cattle to know what the market is,''
Steen said. Sales volumes of at least 500 are needed to establish
clear market trends for farmers, ranchers and others who use the
information.
   The U.S. Department of Agriculture began issuing daily livestock
reports from the Fort Worth Stockyards around 1920, when annual
sales regularly topped 6 million cattle, 1 million hogs and 400,000
sheep.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880310-0298 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-88 1856EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Belgium-Retailer     03-10 0208</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Belgium-Retailer,0215</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Biggest Retailer Makes Move to Thwart Corporate Raiders</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Retailing giant GB-INNO-BM S.A., one of
Belgium's biggest companies, proclaimed a ``poison pill'' takeover
defense Thursday to thwart potentially hostile acquirers.
   The company said it issued new bonds with warrants to five
friendly companies, which if fully exercised would create 6.1
million new shares, inflating the total shares outstanding by
nearly 20 percent to 37.1 million shares. This would make it
difficult for a hostile bidder to buy the retailer.
   Its stock value soared 51 percent last week on rumors that a
takeover bid might be imminent.
   Since Belgium does not have any disclosure rules for investors
in publicly traded companies, it was not clear whether a takeover
might be planned.
   The company said it knew of no parties interested in acquiring
it, but undertook the takeover defense in the interest of
protecting shareholder value and supporting management policies. It
said the unusual movement of the shares in recent days had
``created uncertainty.''
   The move by GB-INNO-BM came against a background of sudden
management uncertainty caused by a hostile takeover fight
surrounding Belgium's biggest company, Societe Generale de Belgique
S.A. Italian investor Carlo De Benedetti has been vying for control
of Societe Generale.
</TEXT>
