<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0035,0214</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Shares Close Sharply Higher</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: RECASTS throughout to UPDATE with market activity, closing
index; No pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices rose sharply on the London Stock
Exchange Thursday after Britain's top Treasury official, Chancellor
of the Exchequer Nigel Lawson, said a further steep rise in the
pound against the West German mark could not be sustained.
   Trading was heavy in selected stocks, with oil shares setting a
fast pace on good gains in crude oil prices.
   At the close, the Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index
was up 19.3 points at 1,834.6.
   The pound surged on world currency markets Monday and Tuesday
after the Bank of England stopped selling pounds to prevent the
British currency from rising too sharply. The pound retreated
Wednesday and Thursday when the central bank renewed its pound
sales.
   Lawson's comments in Parliament calmed fears that a strong
pound, which increases the price of exports, would make British
companies less competitive, dealers said.
   They said there was a general feeling in the market that the
British government will not let the pound go much above 3.10 marks
without taking steps to halt the rise.
   The pound fell in late trading to 3.06 marks from 3.08 marks
late Wednesday.
</TEXT>
