<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-88 1934EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-CommercialTalks     03-10 0562</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commercial Talks,0581</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Another Talent Strike Looms As Actors Vote Strike Authorization</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A joint board of directors for Hollywood's
two top acting unions voted to authorize a strike for March 21
against television and radio advertisers, with cable television
residuals a top sticking point.
   The vote by the directors for the Screen Actors Guild and the
American Federation of Radio and Television Artists came late
Wednesday, actors guild spokesman Mark Locher said Thursday.
   In 1987, actors were paid about $400 million for radio and
television commercials, according to advertisers. The unions said
the members earned $520 million.
   ``It's our bread-and-butter contract,'' said Locher. ``It
certainly means survival to most actors between jobs.''
   If actors strike it will be the second labor action by a
Hollywood talent union this month. The Writers Guild of America
struck studios and producers on Sunday.
   In New York, chief advertising group negotiator John McGuinn
warned Thursday that a strike could last as long as six months, and
urged advertisers to resist signing any interim agreements with the
unions. McGuinn made his comments at a television advertising
seminar.
   Talks between SAG-AFTRA and the Joint Policy Committee of the
American Association of Advertising Agencies and the Association of
National Advertisers have been held in Manhattan. The two
management agencies represent 400 advertisers and about 300
agencies, spokeswoman Dorothy Forget said.
   Negotiations for a new three-year contract began January 11,
with the old contract expiring on Feb. 6. The joint union
membership voted 93 percent for a strike authorization on March 2,
and talks broke off on March 7.
   The joint SAG-AFTRA membership is more than 100,000. The unions
negotiate jointly on the issue of commercials.
   Advertising negotiator McGuinn and guild national executive
secretary Ken Orsatti, the chief bargaining agent for the actors,
both cited the matter of residuals from commercials shown on cable
television as one unresolved point.
   Actors currently receive no residuals from cable television
showings of their commercials after they have earned their first
$1,000 in payments from showings on regular, prime-time television.
   Orsatti noted that virtually all commercials chosen for cable
television have met the $1,000 requirement.
   Orsatti also said advertisers want to take away the 10-year-old
cost of living clause in the commercial contract. He said a cost of
living raise has been the only kind of increase actors have had in
the last two contracts.
   Deteriorating viewership of network television over the past six
years has kept other commercial residual increases in check,
Orsatti said.
   ``Management has used the argument that the erosion in the
network area was caused by cable,'' Orsatti said, ``but they are
unwilling to consider any formula which restructures cable payments
so that the performer has an opportunity to somewhat make up for
those dollars lost on the network side.''
   Orsatti said the union wants to negotiate actors' payments for
commercials shown on cable TV based on subscribers, wit an actor
receiving a one-day session fee of $333 for the first 20 million
subscribers, and another session fee for each additional 30 million
subscribers thereafter.
   McGuinn said the advertisers offered to pay one session fee for
13 weeks of cable use, regardless of any previous use of the
commercial on broadcast newtorks. He said the union's proposal
would be too costly.
   Orsatti said several formulas have been discussed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880310-0306 </DOCNO>
