<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Eastern Bjt   03-10 0562</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Eastern, Bjt,0583</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>1,500 Attend Rally Critical Of Eastern Airlines Management</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID S. MARTIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Union members on Thursday accused Eastern
Airline's parent company of trying to financially cripple the air
carrier to win wage concessions.
   ``The primary focus of our new management seems to have strayed
from safety to cutting operating costs,'' Eastern pilot John
Knudson told a rally of 1,500 union members and supporters.
   Union representatives said Frank Lorenzo, chairman of Eastern's
parent Texas Air Corp., has stripped Eastern of valuable assets and
has hired Merrill Lynch to amass a $200 million strike fund.
   Under Lorenzo, Eastern management also has asked pilots to fly
in unsafe conditions and has harassed flight attendants, union
officials said.
   A three-year contract with the airline's 12,000 members of the
Machinists union expired at the end of December. Negotiations have
failed to produce a new agreement and the issues are now in federal
mediation.
   Lorenzo purchased the Miami-based airline in 1986. Giant Texas
Air also owns Continental Airlines, People Express, New York Air
and other aviation subsidiaries.
   ``These management practices of Frank Lorenzo are in direct
contrast to the policies of the other six major carriers, and they
will spread like a cancer to the rest of the industry if they are
ignored now,'' Knudson said.
   Paula Musto, a spokeswoman for Eastern, said the rally was a
union attempt to gain public support during contract negotiations.
   ``We feel that it's public grandstanding while we're in the
midst of contract negotiations with our largest union,'' Ms. Musto
said.
   Protesters, who rallied a block from the Philadelphia offices of
Eastern and Merrill Lynch, said they did not want boycotts of
either company but wanted to raise public awareness about what they
called union-busting practices.
   Demonstrations will be scheduled in other cities, including
Houston, Denver and Los Angeles, said Joseph B. Uehlein, an AFL-CIO
official who is coordinating a national campaign against Lorenzo
and Merrill Lynch.
   Eastern has sold the airline's most valuable assets, such as
wide-body planes and its computerized reservation system, to
subsidiaries for less than market value, Uehlein and other union
officials said.
   In complaining about the airline's safety concerns, Knudson, who
has been with Eastern for 21 years, said he was grounded for six
days in September 1987 after refusing to fly a plane with a broken
altitude alert.
   The warning device, which tells pilots when they have strayed
from a set altitude, is required on all civil passenger planes, he
said. Knudson said he was reinstated when Eastern failed to show
sufficient cause for his grounding.
   Knudson also said his co-pilot had been asked to fly more than
the 30 hours allowed during a seven-day period.
   Nancy Tauss, a flight attendant and vice president of the
Transport Workers Union, said Eastern management had searched
flight attendants and fired others for technicalities.
   ``Our people go to work each day not knowing if they're going to
be fired,'' she said.
   Ms. Musto said work rules, ignored for years, were being
enforced recently.
   Of Eastern's 32,000 employees, 7,000 belong to the Transport
Workers Union and 3,600 belong to the Air Line Pilots Association,
union officials said. Their contracts expire later this year.
   Eastern lost $182 million on total revenue of $4.4 billion in
1987 and has lost $500 million since airline deregulation in 1978,
Ms. Musto said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
