<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     03-10 0687</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0712</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gold Futures Rally As Oil Tops $16</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Gold and platinum futures prices made strong gains Thursday,
partly in response to a rise in the price of crude oil to $16 a
barrel for the first time this month, analysts said.
   On other markets, stock-index futures fell sharply; grain and
soybean prices retreated broadly; and livestock and meat futures
were mixed.
   The sharp increase in energy futures prices on a rumored
production cut by the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries
had inflationary implications that supported precious metals
futures, analysts said.
   ``There's a view in the market that inflation's going to be
picking up toward the end of the year and that inflation is going
to be more of a concern than recession at year end,'' said Fred
Demler, metals economist for Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. in New
York.
   In addition, talk of physical tightness developing in the cash
platinum market after two quarters of price weakness helped spur
buying of platinum futures, and some of that buying interest
spilled over into the gold market, Demler said.
   Demler said the gold and platinum markets were oversold and due
for an upside correction to bring futures prices more in line with
reality.
   Silver futures declined slightly.
   On New York's Commodity Exchange, gold settled $7 to $8.40
higher with the contract for delivery in April at $444.50 a troy
ounce; silver was 3.3 cents to 3.7 cents lower with March at $6.265
a troy ounce.
   Platinum settled $16.80 to $18.50 higher on the New York
Mercantile Exchange with April at $498.10.
   The rumors of OPEC production cuts that fueled the jump in
energy futures on the New York Mercantile Exchange were later
denied, but oil prices fell only slightly from their highs of the
day.
   Market players still expect OPEC nations to take measures aimed
at boosting prices, said Bob Baker, an analyst for Prudential-Bache
Securities Inc. in New York.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 44 cents to 51 cents
higher with April at $16 a barrel; heating oil was .72 cent to 1.07
cents higher with April at 43.93 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline
was .66 cent to 1.14 cents higher at 45.14 cents a gallon.
   Inflationary fears also contributed to a sharp drop in
stock-index futures on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, analysts
said.
   The Chicago Mercantile Exchange's contract for March delivery of
the Standard & Poor's 500 index settled 6.75 points lower at
262.90, nearly a full point below the spot index.
   Grain and soybean futures closed broadly lower on the Chicago
Board of Trade with little buying interest in the face of bearish
fundamentals.
   Traders expect a March 31 government report on spring plantings
will show a general increase in crop acreage, said Ted Mao, grain
specialist with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   Other market pressures include the large soybean crop now being
harvested in South America, an increase in world vegetable-oil
production and the lackluster prospects for new grain export sales
to the Soviet Union in the near term, Mao said.
   Wheat settled 4} cents to 9 cents lower with March at $2.90 a
bushel; corn was 1 cent to 2\ cents lower with March at $1.97} a
bushel; oats were 3 cents to 6 cents lower with March at $1.81\ a
bushel; soybeans were 2\ cents to 6 cents lower with March at
$6.03} a bushel.
   Live cattle futures finished slightly lower on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange on expectations of increased slaughters next
week, analysts said. Feeder cattle were mostly higher.
   Pork futures retreated on ideas that ham supplies were
sufficient to satisfy Eastertime demand, said Tom O'Hare, analyst
in New York with Smith Barney, Harris Upham & Co.
   Live cattle were .08 cent lower to .02 cent higher with April at
72.92 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .20 cent lower to .48 cent
higher with March at 81.55 cents a pound; hogs were .28 cent lower
to .05 cent higher with April at 43.32 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .50 cent to .75 cent lower with March at 51.65 cents a
pound.
</TEXT>
