<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     03-10 0601</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0626</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Mixed; Gold Rises</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was mixed Thursday as trading in the
other major currencies continued to dominate foreign-exchange
markets.
   Gold prices advanced sharply amid a confluence of factors.
Republic National Bank of New York quoted a bid price of $442.50
for a troy ounce of gold as of 4 p.m. EST, up $6.35 an ounce from
$436.15 late Wednesday.
   The British pound, which has soared in recent trading sessions,
gave up some ground to profit-taking after Britain's Chancellor of
the Exchequer Nigel Lawson said sterling would be unable to sustain
a further advance.
   In London, the pound fell to $1.8435 from $1.8460 late
Wednesday. In later New York trading, sterling slipped to $1.8462
from $1.8475 late Wednesday.
   With the slippage in the pound, traders turned not to the
dollar, but to other currencies, said James McGroarty, a vice
president at Discount Corp.
   The French franc fell and the West German mark gained following
rumors that French President Francois Mitterrand might not run for
re-election in May, McGroarty said.
   ``The dollar has been very much sidetracked by all this,'' he
said.
   He said trading in the dollar remained listless as the market
awaited the release of several economic reports from Washington:
retail sales and producer price figures on Friday, and balance of
trade numbers next week.
   In Europe, currency dealers said the mark gained against most
other major currencies in late trading after the Bank of France
withdrew its support for the franc against the mark.
   In Tokyo, the dollar rose to a closing 128.20 Japanese yen from
128.08 yen at Wednesday's close. Later, in London, the dollar fell
back to 127.85 yen, and in New York, it rose marginally to 127.955
yen from 127.95 yen late Wednesday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Wednesday's prices, included: 1.66345 West German marks, down from
1.66895; 1.3785 Swiss francs, down from 1.37905; 5.6665 French
francs, up from 5.6530; 1,236.625 Italian lire, up from 1,232.50;
and 1.25685 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2537.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Wednesday,
included: 1.6640 West German marks, down from 1.6685; 1.3785 Swiss
francs, unchanged; 5.6725 French francs, up from 5.6485; 1.8720
Dutch guilders, down from 1.8750; 1,236.625 Italian lire, up from
1,231.50; and 1.2564 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2532.
   Gold prices surged amid a variety of factors, said Stephen
Platt, an analyst with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in Chicago.
   There was nervousness in bullion markets about the upcoming
economic reports and about rising energy prices, Platt said.
   The benchmark U.S. crude oil jumped 51 cents to $16 a barrel on
the New York Mercantile Exchange after reports that officials of
the 13-nation Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries were
studying a plan to cut production.
   Rising energy prices are believed to be a harbinger of higher
inflation, and gold is considered a safe haven during inflationary
periods.
   Gold also rose because it may have been oversold recently, Platt
said.
   Bullion soared $7 on the Commodity Exchange in New York, closing
at $443.20 a troy ounce.
   In London, gold jumped to a late bid price of $443 a troy ounce,
up from $436.50 bid late Wednesday.
   In Zurich, Switzerland, it rose to $442.50 bid from $437 bid
late Wednesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold closed at $438.42 bid, up from
$438.01 bid at Wednesday's close.
   Silver bullion rose in London to a late bid price of $6.36 a
troy ounce, from $6.31 bid late Wednesday. But it fell on the
Commodity Exchange, slipping 3.3 cents to $6.265.
</TEXT>
