<1ST_LINE>u f AM-MoneySupply     03-10 0375</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Money Supply,0387</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Money Supply Fell In Late February</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The two broadest measures of the nation's money
supply fell in late February, the Federal Reserve Board reported
Thursday.
   The Fed said the measure known as M2 fell to a seasonally
adjusted $2,947.5 billion in the week ended Feb. 29 from $2,953.1
billion the previous week.
   An even broader measure, M3, fell to a seasonally adjusted
$3,722.4 billion from $3,724.4 billion.
   The narrowest measure of the money supply, M1, fell to a
seasonally adjusted $755.1 billion from a revised $762.1 billion.
   M1 includes cash in circulation, deposits in checking accounts
and non-bank travelers checks. M2 is M1 plus accounts like savings
deposits and money-market mutual funds. M3 is M2 plus less-liquid
accounts, such as certificates of deposit in minimum denominations
of $100,000.
   In judging its monetary policy, the Fed has indicated it is
monitoring the value of the dollar, commodity prices and the
difference between short- and long-term interest rates. It also has
shifted its attention from M1 to the two broader money supply
measures
   The Fed said in early 1988 that it would like annual growth for
M2 and M3 to be between 4 percent and 8 percent, which is slightly
lower than the 1987 target of 5.5 percent to 8.5 percent. The Fed
has not set a specific target range for M1 since early 1987.
   In other reports:
   _The Federal Reserve Bank of New York reported commercial and
industrial loans at major New York City banks rose $1.3 billion,
compared with a decline of $1.07 billion a week earlier.
   _The Federal Reserve said bank borrowings from the Federal
Reserve System at the discount window averaged $378 million a day
in the week ended Wednesday, up from $187 million a day in the
previous week.
   _The Federal Reserve said net free reserves averaged $615
million in the latest two-week period, down from a revised $879
million in the previous two-week period.
   _The Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis reported that the
monetary base, the seasonally adjusted total of member bank
reserves held at Federal Reserve banks and cash in bank vaults and
in circulation, was $271.2 billion in the two-week period ended
Wednesday, down from $272.4 billion two weeks earlier.
</TEXT>
