<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Britain-Rover     03-10 0209</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Rover,0218</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rover Announces Sharply Improved Results After Shedding Leyland</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state-owned Rover Group said it lost money in
1987, but far less than it lost in 1986.
   The latest shortfall totaled 26.8 million pounds, or $49.3
million _ a fraction of the record 892.1 million-pound net loss the
previous year, before it sold its Leyland bus and truck divisions.
   At the time the 1986 loss was the equivalent of $1.09 billion.
   The group achieved an operating profit of 27.9 million pounds,
or $51.3 million, in 1987, its best result for 19 years, the
company announcement said. Last year, the group posted an operating
loss of 355.6 million pounds.
   It's Land Rover division surged ahead last year, increasing
operating profits from 1.6 million pounds in 1986 to 22.5 million
pounds, or $41.4 million, in 1987.
   The group's largest company, Austin Rover, turned an operating
loss of 166.6 million pounds into a profit of 5.1 million pounds,
or $9.4 million, last year.
   The group, whose models include the popular Rover Sterling and
Range Rover, exported nearly 174,000 vehicles for just over 1
billion pounds, or $1.85 billion _ a 69 percent increase over 1986.
   Total sales at 513,000 vehicles were up 11 percent, the company
said.
</TEXT>
