<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Farmers-Batus     03-10 0256</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Farmers-Batus,0268</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Farmers Rejects Hostile Tender Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farmers Group Inc., a leading insurer, said
Thursday its board unanimously rejected an unsolicited $63 per
share, or $4.4 billion, tender offer from the U.S. susidiary of
British BAT Industries PLC.
   Farmers also said it was urging shareholders to reject the offer.
   The action by Farmers had been expected since the company has
consistently spurned BAT's overtures since the the British company
proposed a friendly $60-per-share merger in January.
   BAT's Louisville, Ky.-based unit, Batus Inc., launched the
sweetened hostile tender offer a week ago after Farmers' repeatedly
refused to meet and discuss a merger. The tender offer expires
March 30.
   Batus had no comment on the rejection by Farmers.
   The price being offered by Batus is still well below the $70 to
$80 per share that some analysts say Farmers should be able to
attract, although Batus officials have insisted their offer
represents a fair price.
   Farmers' stock was trading in the mid-$40 range before Batus
made it initial proposal. It closed Thursay at $60 per share, down
75 cents.
   Meantime, the companies in the past week have filed a flurry of
legal actions in the takeover fight.
   Farmers filed suit in federal court in Reno, Nev., where it is
incorporated, challenging Batus' efforts to place a proposal before
shareholders at the Farmer's May 20 annual meeting urging that
merger negotiations be held.
   Batus has filed suit in Nevada, Nebraska and South Carolina
seeking to block enforcement of laws restricting takeovers in those
states.
</TEXT>
