<FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-88 1920EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-NavalPetroleum     03-10 0507</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Naval Petroleum,0520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Whitten Says Plan to Sell Naval Oil Reserves `Doesn't Look Good'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A powerful House committee chairman told the
secretary of energy Thursday the Reagan administration's plan to
sell the naval petroleum reserves in California and Wyoming
``doesn't look good.''
   ``Privatization means let somebody have it so they can make some
money,'' Rep. Jamie Whitten, D-Miss., told Secretary John
Herrington, after recounting how he stopped the sale of the Elk
Hills oil reserve in California as a young member of Congress in
1943.
   ``I have a long memory,'' said Whitten, who is chairman of the
Appropriations Committee and as such, a member of the subcommittee
on energy and water development before which Herrington appeared.
According to his account, the potential 1943 buyer would have taken
oil from the field for immediate use and repaid the Navy at such a
slow rate that it would have taken 450 years to square accounts.
   Though still called Naval Petroleum Reserves, the two oil fields
have been controlled by the Energy Department in commercial
production since the mid-1970s.
   Whitten's objections were seconded by the ranking Republican on
the subcommittee, Rep. John T. Myers of Indiana, who said, ``I've
never understood why you wanted to sell that and pump in new oil''
into storage in the Strategic Petroleum Reserve in Lousiana and
Texas.
   The Elk Hills field, 22 percent owned by Chevron Corp. and the
rest by the government, is ``not a reserve, it's a cash cow'' being
milked for money by a revenue-hungry Congress, Herrington said.
   ``We had no business selling oil from there (Elk Hills) at $8
and $10 a barrel'' in the price collapse of 1986, said Herrington.
But the department did not have authority to suspend production as
a private owner would have done, he said.
   The administration's budget request assumes that sale of the two
oil fields will bring in $3.5 billion over the next two fiscal
years. The department's consultants said proceeds could be $4.3
billion, and Herrington told the subcommittee the amount ``could be
as high as $7 billion'' if Congress allows the sale.
   ``You're going to have to get 3 million barrels a day or 4
million barrels a day into the economy on an ASAP basis and you
can't do that at Elk Hills,'' said Herrington.
   Thus, he said, it makes sense to sell the naval reserves and use
the money to buy oil for the Louisiana-Texas stockpile because Elk
Hills can produce only about 115,000 barrels a day and the Teapot
Dome Reserve in Wyoming can produce only about 3,000 barrels a day.
   The salt domes of the Gulf Coast now hold 540 million barrels of
crude oil, roughly the equivalent of 90 days of imports, and can
pump oil to refineries at the rate of 3.5 million barrels a day.
   If the sale goes through, the department proposes to use the
money to increase additions to the strategic reserve from 50,000
barrels a day to 100,000 barrels a day.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
